<SLUG> BC-R-JAZZ-DIVIDE-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JAZZ SCHOOL MOVES WEST AND TRIPS ON THE BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (ADDS photo note.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT49 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are few people more identified with the soul
of jazz than the pianist Thelonious Monk, so it seemed a powerful
statement about this city's coming of age as a modern jazz center
when the prestigious education institute started by his heirs moved
from Boston to the University of Southern California last year.
</P>
<P>
   The university wore the arrival of the Thelonious Monk Institute
of Jazz Performance as a badge of honor, trumpeting it as a new
start for the program, which had been operating at the New England
Conservatory of Music. The best young jazz musicians, university
officials said, would now come to Los Angeles for instruction.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Monk program moves to the end of its first academic
year here, the picture has changed considerably. The entire first
crop of graduate fellows, eight unusually talented musicians who
began last fall, left the program within months _ a fact that the
university only reluctantly acknowledged. The institute frantically
recruited five new fellows in January and effectively started over.
</P>
<P>
   The students who left cited a range of problems, from
personality clashes to an emphasis on academic training over
performance. Some of the people who run the program said the
fellows were, for the most part, too young and inexperienced in the
ways of this sprawling city.
</P>
<P>
   But what people on both sides generally agree on is the gulf
that still separates the jazz cultures on the West Coast and the
East Coast, a divide that the move here had supposedly bridged.
</P>
<P>
   Because Los Angeles is the capital of the entertainment
industry, it gets top musicians and composers to work and perform
here, but the culture is far more geographically diffuse and
infused with a commercial sensibility than it is in the East, say
many of those involved. Most of the first group of fellows were
from the East Coast, or at least identified with the atmosphere
there, where life revolves around a vibrant and highly focused club
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how much I was into the East Coast vibe until
I started the program,'' said Damion Reid, a drummer in the first
group of fellows. He grew up in Los Angeles but had studied at the
New England Conservatory of Music. ``Because the program was so
prestigious and had a good rap, it seemed perfect,'' he said. ``But
when the institute moved, the agenda moved. It felt different.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Monk Institute has had to not only re-evaluate
the program's approach but also contemplate the persistently
nettlesome question of how subject matter relates to the
environment _ in this case, how the geography of Los Angeles
affects culture. This is particularly true of jazz, which has
always drawn its improvisational strength from the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do a good job of getting the students prepared for
the kind of work they'd be doing on the West Coast,'' conceded
Ronald C. McCurdy, a trumpeter who last fall became director of the
Monk Institute, which is technically separate from the university's
highly rated music school. ``It was pretty painful for a lot of
people. It was not the start we'd prepared for, I can tell you
that. We just hadn't really understood the extent of the adjustment
from one coast to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton Berg, a pianist and chairman of the jazz department at
USC's Thornton School of Music, said he was sympathetic about some
of the problems encountered by the first group of fellows, but said
he still felt the institute's move was wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all ripped out of one scene and brought to a
different one,'' Berg said of the first class. ``They hadn't been
well prepared for the differences. But the scenes each have their
advantages. L.A. has the whole entertainment industry and all those
opportunities.'' The East Coast, like Boston and New York, he
explained, has a more concentrated jazz scene and a deeper pool of
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Monk was a largely self-taught innovator whose imaginative
flights at the keyboard were credited with opening whole new areas
for musical exploration, including the bebop school, which he
helped originate in the early postwar years.
</P>
<P>
   After he died in 1982, his family and others in the music world
decided to hold a benefit concert to raise money for music
education. The benefit, held in 1986, was such a success that it
evolved into the idea of forming an institute, based in Washington,
that would focus on jazz education.
</P>
<P>
   The main offices of the institute are still in Washington, and
it has thrived with the support of President Clinton, as well as
that of Tipper Gore, who is a drummer. In addition to the
fellowship program, the institute runs programs in public schools
and a summer program in Aspen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Carter, the Monk Institute's president, said that it was
hard to find a home for the fellowship program. The University of
Southern California initially rejected the program because it
seemed an untested idea.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed. When the program ran into financial
problems recently in Boston and began looking for a new home, the
University of Southern California leaped at the idea, said the
music school's dean, Larry J. Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   The music school had been shifting toward a more pragmatic
approach, teaching its students not just about music but also about
how to survive and thrive in the music business. Moving the
institute here was a way to diversify the range of talented young
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Monk Institute wants to recenter jazz in the American
voice, and I think you can do that better here, where you have the
entertainment industry,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, many things are different in Los Angeles. For one, the
number of jazz clubs is modest, and they are spread out over the
city's vast geographical area, from the Jazz Spot near Hollywood,
where McCurdy and some of the fellows have regular jam sessions, to
Steamers Cafe, over an hour away in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here only three months, it was shocking at first,'' said
Bryan Lipps, a trumpeter and a current fellow at the institute.
``In New York you walk out the door and everything is right there.
The cats are all there. Maybe it's all here in L.A., but honestly I
kind of haven't figured the scene out.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Terry, one of jazz's most respected trumpeters, who gives
a master class at the institute, said the problem was not the
talent of the students but their fit with the program and the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they had problem with the faculty and I think they
felt far away from the scene,'' said Terry, who lives in New York.
</P>
<P>
   John Sullivan, a bass player who started last fall and then left
with the others, said another problem was that there were more
academic requirements after the program moved, and that left less
time for performance. The dearth of clubs only made that worse, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not as performance oriented,'' said Sullivan, whose
group, the John Sullivan Quintet, plays occasionally at the
Cornelia Street Cafe in New York. ``I wish I'd known what we were
in for. I think I'm a reasonable guy, and they treated us well. But
it looked kind of grim after a while. That's why we all split.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurdy said, ``I can say I'm a lot smarter now than I was eight
months ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
