<HEADLINE>
GEORGE PIERCY, PUBLIC TV EXECUTIVE, DIES AT 84  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Md. Wis., Minn. ) c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   George T. Piercy, a former senior vice president of Exxon Corp.
who, in the 1980s, was chairman of the Educational Broadcasting
Corp. of New York, now known as Channel 13/WNET, died March 30 at
his home in Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   He had been in declining health for two years, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Piercy was the chairman of the Educational Broadcasting Corp.
from 1981 to 1983. He joined the board in 1967, became vice
chairman in 1973 and remained on the board for a time after
stepping down as its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Piercy was a senior vice president at Exxon from 1970 until he
retired from that corporation in 1980. He was also a trustee of
Princeton Theological Seminary and on the boards of other nonprofit
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Eau Claire, Wisc., and received a bachelor's
degree in chemical engineering in 1938 from the University of
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   His wife of three decades, the former Virgina Mae Budrow, died
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by hiswife, Janet R. Piercy, whom he married in
1982; two daughters, Nancy P. Murray of Elkton, Md., and Susan P.
McCarthy of Arden Hills, Minn.; and five grandchildren
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
