the next grade. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
APRIL 9 -- EDLIFE-HARVARD-2 -- Almost three decades after Harvard
College fully integrated the women of Radcliffe into its
residential life, there are still places around campus where men
are always the hosts and women the guests. Many students here, male
and female, say the mere existence of the clubs engenders a male
dominance that reaches beyond the social scene and promotes an
old-boy culture. Sexism on campus, from left: The Phoenix Club; the
Fox Club; and the Spee Club. (Ed Quinn/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
APRIL 9 -- EDLIFE-HARVARD-1 -- Almost three decades after Harvard
College fully integrated the women of Radcliffe into its
residential life, there are still places around campus where men
are always the hosts and women the guests. Last spring, 19 women
decided to break down the final club monopoly, forming their own
single-sex club, the Seneca, named for the first women's rights
convention in Seneca Falls, N.Y., in 1848. Alexandra Seru, left,
and Julia M. Butler, co-presidents of the Seneca, on campus
recently. (Ed Quinn/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
EDLIFE-COLLEGE-CHOICE-2-B&AMP;W -- The members of ``Beverly Hills
90210,'' like their real-life counterparts, opted for a wide
variety of after-high-school options. 1. Andrea chose a local
university, C.U., to be with friends (and grandma was ill); 2.
Brandon also chose C.U. to with friends, rejecting a Rhodes
Scholarship in the process; 3. Brenda went out of state because
Dylan was dating her best friend; 4. Dylan became a C.U. dropout
due to a drug and alcohol problem; 5. Kelly dated Dylan, stayed
home and attended C.U. (Fox Broadcasting/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
EDLIFE-COLLEGE-CHOICE-1 -- Experts say that if you're scouting
colleges, listen to parents but do not allow them, as advisers,
advocates or adversaries, to be the prism for your perceptions. One
television teen-ager, Meadow Soprano, was lucky: her dad dropped
her off at Bates, Bowdoin and Colby because he had to track down
and murder a stool pigeon. (Anthony Neste/HBO)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) PUTNEY, Vt. -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9
-- EDLIFE-DISABILITY-2 -- According to a new study by the American
Council on Education, the number of college freshmen identifying
themselves as learning disabled almost tripled from 1988 to 1998,
to 58,000 freshmen - the fastest-growing category of all
disabilities. At Landmark College in Putney, Sahri Cohen, left, was
tutored by another student, Ashley Rondini. (Paul O. Boisvert/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) PUTNEY, Vt. -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9
-- EDLIFE-DISABILITY-1 -- Accommodations for those with learning
disabilities are making higher education a more viable choice than
ever before. At Landmark College in Putney, Ellen Engstrom used
Legos to teach Matthew Frieden sentence structure: red represent
the verb, blue the subject. (Paul O. Boisvert/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
BIZ-BOOKS -- In John Nathan's new book, ``Sony: The Private Life,''
the author treats the company's rise from a tiny radio repair shop
in a bomb-ravaged Tokyo after World War II to a $50 billion,
globe-straddling giant as a convoluted family saga. He sees the key
to Sony's triumphs and setbacks in the ``skein of personal
relationships'' at the company's pinnacle rather than in
hard-headed calculation of the bottom line. (The New York Times)
</P>
