<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- April 7, 2000 -- URBAN-FOLKLORE-B&AMP;W -- There
were two versions of the urban legend of Bozo the Clown circulating
in the '60s and '70s. The first is about a child contestant on a
local Bozo the Clown television program who misses a shot in a game
and utters a curse. When Bozo tries to comfort him, the child
responds with an angry, offensive outburst. In the second version,
Bozo utters the offensive words himself, causing the show to be
canceled. Both stories circulated for years but were never
confirmed. (Paradox Press/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LONG BEACH, Calif. -- April 7, 2000 --
TRUCKER-PROTESTS-2 -- The 40,000 truckers who work the nations
ports are so fed up, especially with high fuel prices and the long
lines that cut the number of paid trips they make each day, that
thousands of them have joined recent demonstrations or strikes at
all the major ports, including Long Beach. Demetrio Beltran, a
Mexican immigrant who has been a port trucker for 17 of his 42
years, next to his vehicle waits for a shipment with dozens of
other trucks at the Evergreen Terminal earlier this week. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LONG BEACH, Calif. -- April 7, 2000 --
TRUCKER-PROTESTS-1 -- The 40,000 truckers who work the nations
