ISRAEL-WAGNER-B&AMP;W --Is Israel finally ready to abandon its
zealously sustained taboo against public performances of music by
Richard Wagner, the Nazis' favorite composer and a symbol of
unreconstructed anti-Semitism? The Israel Symphony Orchestra of
Rishon Lezion is planning to include Wagner's ``Siegfried Idyll''
in a chamber music series in the fall. Wagner is shown at his villa
in Switzerland in 1868. He wrote ``Siegfried'' for his son's birth.
(The New York Times)
