<P>
   (NYT43) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 7, 2000 -- OBIT-RUGE-2-B&AMP;W --
Arthur C. Ruge, who invented a fingernail-sized gauge that helped
the United States win World War II and revolutionized the way
things are weighed and tested for stress, died Monday at his home
in Lexington, Mass., according to his daughter, Claire Bertucci. He
was 94. In 1936, Ruge, foreground, worked in a laboratory at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology to study the effects of
earthquakes. He created the SR-4 strain gauge to help a student
complete a thesis. (The New York Times)
