<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
BIZ-BOOKS -- In John Nathan's new book, ``Sony: The Private Life,''
the author treats the company's rise from a tiny radio repair shop
in a bomb-ravaged Tokyo after World War II to a $50 billion,
globe-straddling giant as a convoluted family saga. He sees the key
to Sony's triumphs and setbacks in the ``skein of personal
relationships'' at the company's pinnacle rather than in
hard-headed calculation of the bottom line. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) LONDON -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL-3 -- Stephen Peak of Ivy European
Opportunities, who has bought both technology and other European
stocks, said mainline businesses should gain from the technology
boom. ``What we like to do is be different, but different and
right,'' he said. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) PRINCETON, N.J. -- April 7, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL
9 -- MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL-2 -- The solid performers in the
international stock fund category last quarter were ones that,
rather than riding the market tide, proved adept at the arduous
task of spotting gems in the raw. ``It's almost like looking for
antiques,'' said Ken Chiang, the fund manager for Merrill Lynch
Global SmallCap, a strong performer last quarter. (Nancy Wegard/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
