<HEADLINE>
BOTTENFIELD FOCUSED, NOT FAZED BY BIG-TIME FOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Kent Bottenfield is at the getting-to-know-you
stage with his new Anaheim Angels teammates, having joined the team
just a few days before it broke camp in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, acquired with Adam Kennedy from the Cardinals in
the trade for Jim Edmonds, also is getting to know the American
League, having spent his entire career before the trade in the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   One perception of the AL is that there is little pitching. But
don't tell that to Bottenfield. In his first start last Tuesday, he
was matched up against the Yankees' Roger Clemens. On Sunday he
goes up against the Red Sox's Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' Bottenfield said about facing Clemens and
Martinez to start his Angels career. ``I'm not pitching against
them, I'm pitching against that team's lineup. And our team can
score runs off anybody. My job is to keep the team in the game.
Those kinds of variables (the opposing pitcher) I've learned to
eliminate from my thinking so as not to affect me on game day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield admits he knew almost nothing about the Angels
before the trade, other than what he heard through the media _ no
pitching, projected for last place, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team has gotten a lot of bad press,'' he said.
``You can't go on what happened last year because of all the
injuries they had. I see a lot of good things. There's no reason
this team can't compete for the division.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ortiz ready: One day after going six innings and throwing 91
pitches in a rehab start at Lake Elsinore, Ramon Ortiz pronounced
himself fit and ready to go. Ortiz, who was diagnosed with a small
tear in his right shoulder on March 14, will start Tuesday's game
against the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy, my arm feels great,'' Ortiz said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz gave up two runs and eight hits against Single-A Rancho
Cucamonga. Why all the hits? ``Those guys swing at every pitch,''
Ortiz said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Old ties: It's been more than a year since Mo Vaughn left his
hometown Boston Red Sox to sign with the Angels, but he still gets
a certain feeling playing against his old teammates. During batting
practice Friday, Vaughn got a hug from Red Sox shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra and the two chatted and joked with each other.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-area writers waited for Vaughn in the Angels
clubhouse to talk to him before the game. One of their questions
was: ``Is this home now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Home is) all over, wherever the flow is,'' said Vaughn, who
owns houses in North Easton, Mass., and Newport Beach. ``In Boston,
I have too many ties there, too many things going on. I definitely
have to be in Boston for Thanksgiving, and in Virginia (where his
parents now live) for Christmas. After that, who knows? As long as
I arrive in Arizona by February (for spring training).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Also: Edgard Clemente, acquired in a trade from the Rockies
for two minor-leaguers March 29, got his first start Friday as the
DH. . . . Friday was GM Bill Stoneman's 56th birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
