<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0798 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-08 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
C'MON, DAVID, LIGHTEN UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ We wondered aloud what David Duval, a taciturn
guy and terrific golfer, found more difficult: staring down a
vipery Augusta National Golf Course or facing the meddlesome media
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The question seemed innocuous enough. Obvious, even. Duval
appeared to have barely broken a sweat Friday on his way to a
second-round 65 at the Masters. He blistered the back nine in a
six-under-par 30 to take a one shot lead over an illustrious field,
looking for all the world like a champion in transit.
</P>
<P>
   But a few minutes later, as he sat in front of some three dozen
reporters, Duval had the wary air of someone looking down a
pitch-black alley.
</P>
<P>
   Then came our question. The way Duval stared at us, you would
have thought we had asked if it was his child Madonna is carrying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand that question,'' he asked, his posture
stiffening until he was sitting dagger straight. ``What do you
mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Between his body language and his balky reaction, Duval had let
slip his answer well before the supercilious Augusta National
member acting as the moderator rephrased our question and the
golfer spit out, ``I'm sorry I don't give you a highlight reel all
the time. It's my job to give you an answer, not a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the highlight reel, we'd settle for a snippet of
civility. What Duval is too bullheaded to see is an answer and a
story become one and the same when a golfer of his talent and
determination refuses to look beyond his own discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   That Duval, 28, is an introverted person who carefully guards
his privacy is neither a shortcoming nor a big deal. Not everybody
is armed with a personality that can commandeer a room like a Tiger
Woods, an Arnold Palmer or a Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Nicklaus, 60, had nearly as fine a front nine as Duval
did a final nine. The six-time Masters champion made the turn in a
3-under 33, pulling along with him a crowd so sweeping and sonorous
it must have scared Nicklaus's putter.
</P>
<P>
   Over the final nine holes, Nicklaus, by his own accounting,
missed seven makeable birdie or par putts and had to settle for a
36-hole score of even par.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus preceded Duval into the interview room and garrulously
recounted the good (four birdies), the bad (two bogeys) and the
ugly (a handful of missed putts inside five feet) of his round.
</P>
<P>
   The man who remains _ remarkably, almost incomprehensibly _ in
the hunt for his 19th professional major gave thoughtful answers to
routine questions.
</P>
<P>
   When his time was up, Nicklaus continued the interview session
out in the hallway, regaling reporters while Duval sat on the other
side of the double doors, serving up one clipped response after
another.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forget, but in Duval's defense we must remember
Nicklaus wasn't always so glib. Before he joined Arnold Palmer and
Gary Player as the game's greatest ambassadors, Nicklaus was a
serious, insular 20-something locked in on greatness.
</P>
<P>
   He was not unlike Duval, warily circling a press corps that,
mirroring the public, took a while to warm to the chunky, self-
contained, supremely skilled challenger to Palmer's throne.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus wore the first of his Masters jackets, in 1963, more
comfortably than he did the spotlight that came along as an
accessory. It took time, Nicklaus said, to grow into his public
persona. ``And there wasn't as much media then as there is today,''
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus was known early in his career for giving curt responses
to questions he deemed stupid. The relaxed riffs with reporters
would come later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was cooperative,'' said Ron Green Sr., who covered Nicklaus
in the 1960s for The Charlotte Observer, ``but he didn't go on and
on and on. You can't hush him up now.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what transcendent athletes do: They lure you to their
sport with their performance, then hook you with their
personalities. Or they lure you to their sport with their
personalities, then hook you with their performance.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it works.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we should have to explain this to Duval. After all, he
is an avid fisherman. He said so after recovering from our
question. Fishing ``tends to relax'' him, he revealed in what was
intended, we suppose, to be an olive branch of insight.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, Duval is deeper than that. He must be. Because if
he was shallow, he'd pretend to be personable and we'd be none the
wiser. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
