<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN'S REUNION WITH FATHER COULD COME NEXT WEEK, RENO SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FIRST LEDE WRITE-THRU (to correct number of people on boat with
Elian's mother) By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno announced Friday that
Elian Gonzalez would be reunited with his father as early as next
week as she sought to put an end to a four-month political and
custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting for more than an hour with Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
Reno ordered that a letter be sent to Gonzalez's Miami relatives
revoking their temporary custody of Elian. The Justice Department
would also instruct them to meet on Monday with a team of medical
experts to determine how to transfer Elian to his father's keeping
with as little disruption as possible.
</P>
<P>
   She said the meeting with two psychiatrists and a psychologist
in Miami would help determine where and when the custody transfer
would take place. But Reno indicated that she wants to see Elian in
the arms of his father within a few days of the Monday meeting,
adding that the two have been kept apart long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for this little boy, who has been through so much,
to be with his father,'' Reno declared at a news conference. She
stressed that she is confident that Juan Miguel Gonzalez is a good
father who ``obviously loves this little boy'' and is not acting as
a pawn of Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general acknowledged that once the reunion takes
place, Gonzalez will be free to take his son home to Cuba
immediately if he chooses. But she indicated that she might try to
persuade him to remain in the United States until a court appeals
process launched in the case by his Miami family has run its
course.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez has captured national
and international attention since he was rescued at sea last
November. The boat he and his mother were on sank during a crossing
from Cuba to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Elisabeth Brotons, who was divorced from his father,
drowned along with 10 others.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief hospital stay, Elian was placed in the temporary
custody of his Miami relatives at his father's request. But a
battle over his custody erupted when Gonzalez told immigration
officials that he wanted his son returned to him as soon as
possible. His Miami family refused to comply with immigration laws
requiring that they give him up and have since sought through
negotiations and court appeals to retain custody.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like the case might drag on for months more, but
things changed dramatically on Thursday when Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
accompanied by his second wife, Nercy, and their 6-month-old baby
boy, Hianny, flew from Havana to Washington to reclaim his son.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from his meeting Friday with Reno and Doris Meissner,
commissioner of the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
Gonzalez looked relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that I will soon have my son with me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, the Washington attorney representing Gonzalez,
said his client was at times very emotional in the meeting as he
sought to ``convey ... the depth of his pain and his feelings, and
his love for the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she was touched by Gonzalez's emotional plea, and she
sought to dispel any notion the Miami relatives may harbor that
Gonzalez can be persuaded to remain in the United States with his
son. Noting that no Cuban officials were present at the meeting,
she said Gonzalez was emphatic about his desire to return to his
homeland and bring up his family there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand and respect with all my heart the deep-seated
beliefs which the Cuban exile community feels on this subject,''
she said, referring to Castro's repressive regime. ``I
wholeheartedly reject Cuba's system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general called on the Miami relatives to end their
resistance to the transfer and cooperate voluntarily and
peacefully. But she made it clear that the government would act to
enforce the immigration laws if they refuse, possibly by seeking a
federal court order to facilitate the return.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A federal court ruled last month that Lazaro Gonzalez, the
great-uncle who has been taking care of Elian, must relinquish
custody. But the uncle is appealing that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his attorneys signaled Friday that he would likely comply
if he is ordered to turn over Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Linda Osberg-Braun, however, said the Miami family is
still hoping that a face-to-face meeting can be arranged with Juan
Miguel Gonzalez in ``a natural setting'' free of lawyers,
government officials and politicians so they can discuss what is in
the best interest of the child. She said Lazaro Gonzalez is not
opposed to reuniting Elian with his father; he simply wants to make
sure it is handled with as little trauma to the boy as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be done right, not fast,'' Osberg-Braun said on
NBC's ``Today'' program.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of establishing some sort of familial contact, two of
Juan Miguel Gonzalez's Florida relatives flew to Washington Friday
in an effort to talk with him. But they were turned away outside
the Bethesda, Md., home where Gonzalez is staying.
</P>
<P>
   Delphin Gonzalez, an uncle, told reporters through an
interpreter that he couldn't understand ``why Juan won't meet with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The two relatives said they also planned to lobby members of
Congress in hopes of getting legislation passed that would grant
Elian and his father permanent residency in the United States. The
bill would in effect give the boy and his father political asylum
and prevent their return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
