<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE SECOND STRAIGHT NIGHT, EWING IS THE KNICKS' LIFELINE
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ All around him, Patrick Ewing's younger
teammates were fraying beneath the chaos caused by the Orlando
Magic's intensity. Although it did not seem fair to the
37-year-old, the New York Knicks grabbed onto him for the second
time in two nights.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, Ewing may have looked as tattered and drenched as a
survivor crawling on the shore, but he was the perfect life
preserver for the Knicks. He held up for another 24 hours. A night
after scoring 30 points, Ewing delivered 28 points and 18 rebounds
_ including a key 3-point play with 22.3 seconds left _ to give the
Knicks an impressive road victory, 96-89.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like that Patrick was mentally tough when things were
going wrong in the fourth quarter,'' said coach Jeff Van Gundy,
whose team had 21 turnovers. ``This is one of the best wins we've
had all year.''
</P>
<P>
   It came against an intense Magic team that had won seven in a
row and 11 straight at the Orlando Arena. The Knicks were able to
stay two games behind the Miami Heat, whom they will face on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing put the Knicks in position to threaten the Heat with a
10-point fourth quarter. With the Magic within 89-86, Ewing
pump-faked Pat Garrity, leaned in for a 6-foot jumper and drew the
foul.
</P>
<P>
   The instant the whistle blew, Ewing swaggered over in the
direction of Orlando coach Doc Rivers. The Knicks' center knew he
had just put an end to the Magic's fourth-quarter comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just messing with him,'' said Ewing, who was given a
long break in the third quarter to rest for the fourth-quarter
push. ``Jeff took me out. I was missing shots I wouldn't normally
miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was not the only one who was struggling. In foul trouble
and out of sync, Allan Houston was 2 for 10 until the fourth
quarter, when he came up with two jumpers to help the Knicks gain a
nine-point cushion.
</P>
<P>
   That lead quickly evaporated under a 10-4 run by the Magic.
Orlando was as close as 87-86 when Latrell Sprewell, who also
struggled under relentless double teams, came up with two free
throws with 46 seconds left. Ewing did the rest. Houston finished
with 10 points and Sprewell also scored 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great admiration and respect for the way the Magic
play with heart and desire,'' Van Gundy said. ``They have good
players who play extremely hard. We knew how well we had to play to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' energy threshold for back-to-back games this season
has been dreadfully low. Just the thought of a playing the second
night in a row has been exhausting for the Knicks, who began the
night 5-11 in this situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, it has grown to epic proportions,'' Van Gundy said.
``Just the words `back to back' means you can't practice, can't
move, can't speak and can barely breathe. Mentally, everyone is
convinced that it's harder than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiastic Magic was the last team the Knicks wanted to
face under the circumstances. Rivers has his band of league misfits
believing that relentless effort can trump a team of complacent
superstars on any night.
</P>
<P>
   For teams that handle the ball as carelessly as the Knicks _
with the turnover-prone Houston, Sprewell and Ewing _ the Magic's
ability to swarm the ball can be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic came out just as expected. It double-teamed and
pressed and harassed the Knicks into 12 first-half turnovers.
Darrell Armstrong irritated Charlie Ward and players like Monty
Williams and Corey Maggette shut down Sprewell and Houston.
Flustered, the Knicks' star duo combined to score just seven
first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   With their guards getting nowhere, the Knicks had no choice but
to turn to their big men. Just 24 hours after scoring 30 points to
bail the Knicks out against the Wizards, Ewing dragged his old
bones out on the floor to save his team again.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 14 first-half points, while Kurt Thomas added 10 to
give the Knicks a 47-39 halftime lead. That lead was brief. Under
the Magic's pressure, the Knicks could not get off a clean shot and
were beaten badly down the floor on the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   After surviving a 7-0 run by the Magic, the Knicks' inability to
recover in transition resulted in a lead change with 5:09 left in
the third quarter. After a miss by Ewing, the Magic pushed the ball
down the floor and Armstrong pulled up for an open 3-pointer to
give his team a 56-55 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and Marcus Camby came through in the last three minutes of
the third to put the Knicks ahead, 66-63, entering the fourth
quarter. Left alone by a Magic defense focused on the Knicks'
scorers, Ward stepped up to provide some calm by hitting a
3-pointer with 2:35 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   After Ward missed on a 3-pointer the next time down the floor,
Camby popped up in the middle of a hoard of white jerseys with a
tip-in and then delivered on a runner to put the Knicks back up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
