<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' FRUSTRATION CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Darren Dreifort walked eight, Shawn Green had the
Shea Stadium wind play him and it led to both Mets runs, and Devon
White was ejected for arguing a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Mets righty Rick Reed struck out seven in 7 innings in a
2-1 win against the Dodgers on Friday despite nearly missing the
start with a stiff neck, then pitching in pain from the fifth
inning on after he aggravated it during an at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Shall we continue? Dreifort and two relievers allowed just two
hits: Mike Piazza's windblown double and a fourth-inning single by
Reed.
</P>
<P>
   More? OK, there's the game's last play in which Dodgers catcher
Todd Hundley, still a hero in these parts, dribbled a 2-0 sinker
from Armando Benitez down the first-base line. Hundley thought the
ball crossed into foul territory before first baseman Todd Zeile
fielded it, but home-plate umpire Mike Everett thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Third out. Game over. Three-game losing streak for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it foul,'' Hundley said. ``Reed pitched a good game, but
man, it's frustrating. He just frustrates you, and then at the end
of the game (Everett) calls it fair. . . . Frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   So after two wins, 20 runs and rays of optimism everywhere,
again the Dodgers' clubhouse is solemn.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, they have dropped three in a row, and the need for
Kevin Brown to drag the Dodgers out of this minislide today is
important if they are to survive this 10-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   And Hundley, who admitted to being surprised at the quality of
Benitez's sinker, leads the frustration march.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even tried to move at the last minute in case I was blocking
him (from seeing the ball),'' Hundley said. ``That ball was foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Dreifort allowed just the two runs on two hits, the
walks took their toll. He was nearly untouchable when he got the
ball near the plate, but his lack of control forced him to throw 92
pitches in five innings and chased him before Matt Herges and Terry
Adams added solid relief.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort walked three batters in the first, two of whom scored,
walked a pair in the third and hit Derek Bell, walked two more in
the fourth and one in the fifth. He got out of a bases-loaded jam
in the fourth when Edgardo Alfonzo lined into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything seemed to be out of whack and every adjustment I
made was an overadjustment,'' said Dreifort, who walked nine in a
game against Atlanta last season. ``I don't know how many guys they
had on base, but I was lucky to get out of it. It's called timely
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   This one was strange from the start for the Dodgers. Dreifort
didn't have have control problems in the spring, but he walked Jon
Nunnally to lead off the game and Alfonzo with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza hit a high fly to the warning track in right field. Green
ran parallel in front of the fence but never caught up to it. One
run scored and Robin Ventura followed with a run-scoring grounder
to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like (the wind) was blowing left to right, and the ball
went the other way,'' Green said. ``I went to where I thought it
was going to end up and it kept floating. I couldn't get to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' lone run came on Gary Sheffield's homer in the
fourth, two batters after White was ejected by Everett. It was the
first of four hits for the Dodgers. Green followed with a double,
but Eric Karros, 0 for his last 14, grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, the Dodgers had another chance with back-to-back
singles from Adrian Beltre and Jose Vizcaino, but Dreifort and Todd
Hollandsworth flew out to end the inning. Reed (1-0) left the game
by retiring 10 of the last 11 guys he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Reed) hit his spots. He's crafty,'' Green said. ``We couldn't
get any rallies going. Nothing. Not that we had that many hits. But
every time we got somebody on, it was with two outs. The situations
weren't ideal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
