<HEADLINE>
JAILED VIETNAM PROTESTER
 HOWARD MECHANIC MAIN
 TAINS INNOCENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY DENNIS WAGNER 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Florence, Ariz.) - In the first news paper interview since he
surrendered to federal agents in February, con victed Vietnam war
protester How ard Mechanic maintained his innocence and said he
does not regret spending the past 28 years as a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be let loose,'' Mechanic said today. ``There's no
doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in prison khakis, the 51-year-old inmate spoke with two
reporters at a private prison in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   He asked forgiveness from friends and political allies he
deceived in Scottsdale. He discussed a book he's writing on his
life as Gary Tredway, the Phoenix area political activist and
entrepreneur. He talked about a possible presidential pardon, and
what he'll do once he's free again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to stop working for causes I believe in,'' he
promised.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic was convicted in connec tion of hurling a cherry bomb
at firefighters during a a May 5, 1970, anti-war demonstration at
Washing ton University, in St. Louis, Mo. When appeals failed in
1972, he was ordered to surrender for a five-year prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mechanic says he boarded a bus in a small Missouri town
and headed for the Southwest. He stopped in Albuquerque, but it was
so cold he climbed on another bus and continued on to Tempe, where
he began building a new life as Gary Tredway.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic worked in a Tempe natural foods store, developed a
health food business of his own, founded an automotive recycling
business and operated an apartment-motel in Scottsdale. He also
married and had a son.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic says he avoided police officers and was hounded by bad
dreams during his 28 years of hiding: ``The nightmares never really
stopped. Being hunted down and caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those fears, Mechanic said, he could not resist his
compulsion for environmentalism and political activism. Over the
years, he emerged as a leader in Scottsdale, fighting development
plans at Los Arcos Mall, writing op-ed pieces for the local
newspaper, spearheading a ``Clean Elections'' organization.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, last year, Mechanic decided to run for City Council.
</P>
<P>
   He admits it was a huge mistake seeking public office, and
issued an apology to those who supported him: ``I'm sorry I let
those people down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Mechanic said he feels bad about claiming he had
leukemia as an excuse for backing out of the council campaign when
he began to fear his identity would be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a definite mistake,'' he said. ``But I was in a corner
at that time, and felt I had to withdraw from the race. . . . I'm
sorry. I wasn't looking to get sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic said his fraudulent identity and background did not
amount to a life of lies: Instead, he portrayed himself as a
principled idealist caught in a tangled web. He begged those who
judge him to keep in mind the times and circumstances of his
criminal conviction.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1,000 people joined the 1970 protest at Washington
Univer sity after National Guard troops killed four students at
Kent State University, and U.S. warplanes began bombing Cambodia.
Someone set fire to the ROTC building. Rocks and at least one
cherry bomb were hurled at firefighters who arrived to fight the
blaze.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, a single witness claimed that he had seen a
cherry bomb fly from Mechanic's direction, and later observed
Mechanic loading a cherry bomb into a slingshot.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic, a student at Washington University, said he attended
the demonstration but did not see or touch any explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been involved in violence at all,'' he added. ``The
government perpetrated all the violence, drop ping those 500-pound
bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic was convicted anyway, and sentenced to five years in
prison. Another defendant received a sen tence of just three
months. Mechanic says he was given an ``outrageous'' punishment
because authorities wanted to use him as an example. In the
process, Mechanic said, he be came ``another victim'' of the Viet
nam war.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he regrets running from the law, Mechanic said,
``Never did. Still don't.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he admitted there is a sense of relief now
that his charade has ended: ``That's the silver lining behind this:
I'm not going to have to tell anymore lies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
