<SLUG> BC-TOURISM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURISTS BOOST ARIZONA RE
 TAILERS' BOTTOM LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 BY PETER CORBETT  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Scottsdale, Ariz.) - A yellow bill board near Hermosillo,
Sonora, beckons motorists to cross the bor der and 250 miles of
desert to shop at Scottsdale Fashion Square.
</P>
<P>
   Mall owner Westcor pays $200 a month for the sign, but it's
money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   Well-heeled Mexican shoppers are a retailer's dream, according
to Dana Christensen, Westcor tourism direc tor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pay in cash, and they don't return things,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Westcor, Arizona Mills outlet mall and Biltmore Fashion Park all
are cashing in on across-the-border shopping trips. Like other U.S.
retail ers, they're recognizing the boost tourists bring to the
bottom line and are marketing their malls to foreign and domestic
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist revenue not only keeps retail ers in business but also
broadens the choices of stores for local shoppers, said Stacy
Strombeck, Arizona Mills tourism director.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempe outlet mall, Biltmore and Westcor have marketing
specialists whose sole job is to lure tourists. The reason is
clear.
</P>
<P>
   When a nation of shoppers goes on vacation, it shops.
</P>
<P>
   A third of domestic travelers list shopping as their top
vacation activ ity, according to a Travel Industry Association of
America survey. That's nearly double outdoor activi ties, which is
the next highest cate gory at 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retail is starting to understand that tourism is a big part of
their business,'' Christensen said.
</P>
<P>
   A LEISURE EXPERIENCE
</P>
<P>
   Retailers know travelers have more time and shopping has become
a universal leisure experience, said Da vid Fick, a retail analyst
with Legg Mason in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Mall of America in Minnesota is the most visited destination for
U.S. travelers, according to a study by the National Park Service
and ``Road Smart'' magazine. About 40 percent of its 42.5 million
annual visitors are travelers who live 150 miles or more from the
4.2 million-square-foot mall.
</P>
<P>
   Is anybody sightseeing or reading a good book on their vacation?
</P>
<P>
   Mall tourism directors say that for most tourists, shopping is a
second ary travel activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little scared of seeing this happen,'' Fick said of the
shopping craze. ``When I'm on vacation, I want to be cruising the
Mediterra nean in a sailboat.''
</P>
<P>
   But others are content cruising mall aisles and crashing through
waves of shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   `EAT, SHOP, LIE IN SUN'
</P>
<P>
   Carol Morin, a high school secretary from Norwich, Conn., came
to Phoe nix ``to eat and shop and lie in the sun,'' she said after
five hours of shopping at Arizona Mills on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Within less than 24 hours, she had lightened her wallet by about
$400 on five pairs of shoes, some shorts and Krispy Kreme
doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the time of year, Arizona Mills retailers estimate
that tourists account for 30 percent to 60 percent of their
business, Strombeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty percent of the Fashion Park's business is from tourists,
said Bonny Ruscetti, the center's tourism market ing specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Biltmore's research shows that 84 percent of its tourist
shoppers make at least one purchase and 66 percent eat at a
restaurant, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Mills gets mosts of its non-resident visitors from
Tucson, Flagstaff and Yuma. Big out-of-state markets include
California, New York, Texas and Illinois, Strombeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Other foreign visitors flock to the Phoenix area from Canada,
Britain, Germany and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican shoppers include those driv ing from Sonora and others
flying from Mexico City on America West and Aeromexico. Many of the
Sono ran visitors shop in Tucson, but some come to the Phoenix area
for its broader offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy travelers from southern Mexico who used to fly to
Houston and San Antonio to shop are coming to Phoenix, said Larry
Martin, sales director at Scottsdale Quality Inn &AMP; Suites.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel joined with Scottsdale Fashion Square and Arizona
Mills for a fashion show in Hermosillo in October. Shopping and
travel pack ages generated hotel business almost immediately, and
it has continued for the past seven months, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The mall tourism directors work closely with Phoenix area hotels
and resorts. They also do business with travel agents and tour
operators to offer incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are offered coupon books, mall brochures _ available in
seven languages _ and gifts like carry-on travel bags, luggage tags
and per fume samples.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAMS FOR SPOUSES
</P>
<P>
   The malls offer spouse programs for convention travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Women traveling with their hus bands can shop while their spouse
attends a conference or plays golf. Few men show up for the
shopping excursions, Westcor's Christensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Westcor operates Fashion Square, Paradise Valley, Superstition
Springs, Desert Sky, Arrowhead Towne Cen ter and Flagstaff malls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prime customer is female in a target age of 35 to 54,''
Christensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion Square's shoppers overall spend an average of 1 hour, 40
minutes in the mall, visit 2.4 stores and spend an average of $81,
accord ing to Christensen.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite tourist package is a spa treatment at Nordstrom or
Dillards' day spas, lunch and shopping, she added. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
