<HEADER>
A0810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SOCSEC-1STLD-     04-08 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOCSEC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS LAW LIMITING EARNINGS ALLOWED WITH SOCIAL SECURITY
BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (DELETES ``and their dependents'' in 2nd to last graf)  
(ART ADV: Photo, NYT3, has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Friday signed into law a measure
eliminating Depression-era limits on the amount of money some
elderly workers may earn without having their Social Security
benefits reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which Congress passed last month without a single
dissenting vote, repeals federal rules covering how much money
workers age 65 to 69 may receive in Social Security benefits. Under
current law these beneficiaries had their Social Security benefits
reduced by $1 for every $3 they earned over $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   In signing the measure, Clinton said that the limit placed on
earnings ``made some sense in the Great Depression when the nation
was desperate to find jobs for young workers with families and the
unemployment rate in our nation was 25 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions today could hardly be more different,'' Clinton
said. ``The economy is booming, the unemployment rate is at its
lowest point in 30 years, companies desperately need more workers.
Older Americans have the skills and the experience that businesses
need.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law is retroactive to Jan. 1. It will affect some
800,000 elderly workers or beneficiaries of elderly workers this
year.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, these workers would have forfeited more than $6
billion in benefits this year. Eliminating the ceiling on earnings
will allow beneficiaries to receive an additional $6,700 on average
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Social Security Administration said that
about 415,000 of these workers have each already earned more than
$17,000 or had officially said that they intended to earn more than
that this year.
</P>
<P>
   People who have said they expected to earn more than the $17,000
ceiling this year have already had their monthly Social Security
benefit checks reduced. Under the new law, they will have their
full benefits restored in June, and they will be sent a check in
May paying them their retroactive benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
