<HEADER>
A0812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DOCTORS-NYT &LR;      04-08 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DOCTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CARTEL FOR DOCTORS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 8:
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The House is preparing to vote on a bill that would permit
independent physicians to bargain collectively with health plans _
in effect to form a union _ even though they do not work for a
common employer or work together in any other way. This is a
terrible idea.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would invite doctors to form cartels, jack up prices,
boycott health plans and exploit consumers in ways that are
permitted to no other independent businessmen in the economy. The
legislation may induce physicians to pour contributions into the
campaign chests of politicians during an election year, but
patients would suffer the nasty consequences. That is why the
Consumer Federation of America, the Department of Justice, the
Federal Trade Commission and many leading antitrust authorities
oppose the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, proposed by Tom Campbell, a California
Republican, has already sailed through the Judiciary Committee. It
would permit independent doctors to bargain collectively to
negotiate fees and working conditions with health plans. The
purpose of the bill, says Campbell, is to put doctors in a better
position to negotiate better deals when they go up against huge
health insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors do not need the artificial help. Individual health plans
rarely dominate regional markets. In urban areas, a single health
plan typically accounts for less than 10 percent of patients.
Doctors can avoid doing business with a plan they do not like.
</P>
<P>
   Salaried physicians are already allowed to form unions, and tens
of thousands have already done so. What is new, and dangerous,
about the Campbell bill is that it would extend this right to
independent doctors. That would give doctors the ability to
conspire to fix prices and engage in other types of
anti-competitive behavior, such as collectively refusing to provide
services to a health plan that tries to drive a hard bargain. That
could force the health plan to succumb and guarantee that patients
would pay substantially higher prices for medical services.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious consequence will be to raise insurance premiums.
Physician unions could also be used to stymie health plans that try
to weed out doctors who practice bad medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Current laws already permit physicians to act cooperatively when
it benefits patients. Doctors can, for example, coordinate efforts
to raise standards of medical care and form networks to improve
care. By contrast, the cartels envisioned by Campbell would
victimize consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
