u k BC-EDIT-PAKISTAN-NYT &LR;      04-08 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PAKISTAN'S QUESTIONABLE VERDICT  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 8:
</P>
<P>
   Ousted from power in a military coup last October, former Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan has now been convicted of
hijacking a commercial airliner and sentenced to life imprisonment.
Apparently recognizing the dubious nature of the charges, a
Pakistani judge has at least spared Sharif the death penalty. His
leniency may also have been a response to President Clinton's
appeal last month to Gen. Pervez Musharraf, the coup leader, not to
execute the former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   But the trial of Sharif was itself of dubious legitimacy. It
only underscores the need for Pakistan to move more quickly to
restore democracy and rescue the integrity of its justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The trial did nothing to clear up the sequence of events leading
to the coup. Sharif was charged with barring Musharraf's plane from
landing in Pakistan when it was low on fuel, jeopardizing his life
and the lives of other passengers. But the former prime minister
denied direct involvement in the order. He also argued that, far
from trying to hurt the general, he was simply trying to block him
from plotting a military takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Although the trial judge was a civilian, he was required to take
an oath of allegiance to the military authorities before handling
the case. An earlier judge withdrew, charging that security agents
in the courtroom were trying to intimidate him. In addition, one of
the defense lawyers was mysteriously shot and killed in the streets
while the trial was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf has promised an eventual restoration of democracy, but
his steps have been slow. His aim seems to be to allow elections
only after he has destroyed the leadership of Pakistan's two major
political parties. Sharif's party, the Pakistan Muslim League, is
in disarray after the coup, and the Pakistan People's Party of
former Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto is also in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   This is a moment of extreme volatility in Pakistan. A potential
of nuclear confrontation with India is aggravated by doubts about
the Pakistani military's relationship with terrorist groups and
insurgents in the disputed Indian state of Kashmir. Musharraf must
recognize that Pakistan's grievances against India are undercut by
continued military rule and ill-advised actions like the
prosecution of Sharif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
