<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BABY-RECOVERED-1ST     04-08 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BABY-RECOVERED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWBORN ABDUCTED FROM HOSPITAL ROOM IS RESCUED HOURS LATER
</HEADLINE>
  (UPDATES thruout with motive and details; CHANGES byline.) 
By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 2-day-old baby girl was abducted from a bassinet in
her mother's room at University Hospital at the Downstate Medical
Center in Brooklyn Friday afternoon, but was found hours later
after an intense search by the police, who said the infant had been
taken by a 17-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   The police identified the teen-ager as Angelica Lawrence, and
said that charges of kidnapping and endangerment were being
considered.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, who is severely overweight, had told friends she was
going into the hospital to have a baby. In fact, she went to the
hospital for surgery, to have her ovaries removed.
</P>
<P>
   After her surgery, she grabbed the infant and carried her out of
the hospital in a box, the police said, and displayed the baby as
her own to neighbors and friends.
</P>
<P>
   The baby was reported missing from the mother's room shortly
before noon. The room was semiprivate, but the other bed was
unoccupied, and the mother left the infant alone while she took a
shower. When she returned, the baby was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's parents, Mitchelle Shaw Knight, 28, and her husband,
Eric Knight, 32, were distraught, said Inspector James Albert, as
the police conducted a room-to-room search through the hospital, at
445 Lenox Avenue in East New York. The police flooded the area with
officers, using bloodhounds and helicopters to aid in the search.
But it was a tip that someone wearing leopard-print leggings had
been seen carrying a baby from the hospital that led to Lawrence's
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   At approximately 6:40 p.m., Lawrence returned to the hospital to
get medication she needed for her own recovery, still wearing the
leggings and her patient identification bracelet. Detective Vincent
Didonato recognized her and made the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence then directed the police to an apartment at 282 E. 35th
Street in East Flatbush, where they found the baby, Melanie. She
was taken to Kings County Hospital in Brooklyn for evaluation. The
police said she was in good health, and returned her to her mother.
</P>
<P>
   At an emotional news conference at 10 p.m. outside the pediatric
emergency room of Kings County Hospital Center, the Shaws _ who
also have a 3-year-old son _ cradled Melanie and thanked God and
the police for her safe return. ``We're basically emotionally
drained right now,'' said the father. ``We're just happy that we
have our Melanie back.'' Didonato said, ``It's a nice story with a
happy ending.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the child capped a frantic day that saw the
police and hospital officials mobilizing scores of people to carry
out the search. The baby was described as weighing 6 pounds 8
ounces and measuring 23 inches at her birth on Wednesday. She was
wearing a white diaper and a white long-sleeved shirt with buttons
and was wrapped in a blue and turquoise blanket. The parents had
not yet had a picture taken of her.
</P>
<P>
   When the mother discovered the baby was missing shortly before
noon, she notified the nurses' station. At the same time, an alarm
device activated by a sensor attached to the infant's umbilical
cord went off, sending a signal to the nurses' station on the
maternity ward and the hospital's main security office, said Brian
Kell, a spokesman for SUNY Downstate Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital guards at the building's four primary exits were
notified by radio around noon, Kell said, and hospital officers
began searching the building, and nurses on the floor checked to
see if the baby had been taken for a bath or treatment by a
pediatrician. Then, at 12:30 p.m., a telephone call was placed to
911.
</P>
<P>
   Kell could not explain how someone had gotten out of the
hospital with the baby, even though the guards had been immediately
notified and were supposed to check all people leaving the building
with an infant.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, a woman abducted a newborn from another Brooklyn
hospital and was arrested two days later as she walked down a
street carrying the 3-day-old boy. In that case, the woman
convinced a nurse in the eighth-floor nursery of St. John's
Episcopal Hospital that she was the baby's mother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
