<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     04-08 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKSON GIVES CRITICS PAUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The residents of Chatham, New Brunswick,
Canada have little access to news on the Anaheim Angels. Anaheim
pitcher Jason Dickson was one of those in the dark. And even when
he was able to find something written about the team, he never saw
his name. Talk about the team's possible starting rotation centered
on washed-up veterans and unproven rookies, but not him.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, in his first start since Aug. 8, 1998, Dickson let
his pitching speak for him.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander gave up two runs and four hits in 6 innings to
earn the win as the Angels beat the Red Sox 7-3 before 30,412 at
Edison Field. It was Dickson's first major-league win since July
12, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson was supported by an offense that included a three-run
homer by Garret Anderson, a two-run double by Gary DiSarcina and a
solo homer by Troy Glaus. Heck, even Mo Vaughn stole a base, his
second steal of the season, which equals the most he's had in any
season since he got 11 in his 1995 MVP season.
</P>
<P>
   For Dickson, the win justified manager Mike Scioscia's decision
to put him in the starting rotation. But before Dickson could win
that spot, he had to show Scioscia that he had recovered from the
shoulder surgery that put him out for all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a forgotten man,'' Dickson said during spring training.
``There were a lot of articles this winter and it was like I was
nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   By no means was Dickson dominating Friday, but he made pitches
when he needed to and got the Red Sox to hit the ball at people.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson walked Trot Nixon in the first inning, but Carl Everett
hit into a double play. Troy O'Leary doubled with one out in the
second inning, but was stranded. And after Nixon led off the fourth
with a double, Dickson retired nine consecutive hitters, taking him
into the seventh with a two-hit shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson gave up a homer to Carl Everett leading off the seventh,
then two outs later gave up a double to Mike Stanley and was
replaced by Kent Mercker.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hit .303 last season, but when he batted with two out
and runners in scoring position, he was hitting only .217. In the
first inning Friday, he got his first chance to hit in such a
situation and delivered with a three-run homer to right-center
field on the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Anderson had one three-run homer (Aug. 30 at
Cleveland) all season. His 21 homers in 1999 were a career-high,
and he feels he can hit more as his career advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it comes with maturity,'' Anderson said. ``I'm
reacting to things instead of thinking about 'em. I'm not trying to
muscle the ball out, my technique has to be there. I have a
line-drive swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm getting stronger, I don't have warning-track power
anymore. The ball is carrying.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had another chance to do some damage in the fifth
inning after the Angels mounted a rally. The Angels had runners on
second and third with one out, but Mo Vaughn was caught looking at
a third strike for the second out. After an intentional walk to Tim
Salmon, Anderson stepped to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who did not have a hit with the bases loaded all last
season, popped out to left field to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added to their lead in the sixth inning when Gary
DiSarcina doubled in two runs. Later in the inning, the Angels had
runners on second and third with Adam Kennedy up, and the Red Sox
decided to walk the rookie to face Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who had struck twice already, fell behind in the count
0-2 before grounding out to second and driving in the third run of
the inning for a 6-0 Angels lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
