<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS HIT PETTITTE HARD,   THEN HOLD OFF YANKS' RALLY
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At his best, Andy Pettitte has tunnel vision, his cap
lowered to block out any glimpse of the stands, his concentration
fixed on rapidly and instinctively making his next pitch, without
reflection or review.
</P>
<P>
   When he is pitching badly, as he was Friday night, Pettitte will
seem distracted by the decisions he must make, like a tourist
debating which way to turn at an intersection. The only way
Pettitte could have appeared more confused was if he had worn a
flowered shirt and brown socks and carried a tattered map.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners, who lost 9 of 10 against the Yankees last
year, won the game, 7-5. But this year they have a patient and
efficient lineup, with good starting pitching and a good bullpen;
they are, in a sense, a poorer market's version of the Yankees, and
they played and ran aggressively Friday night, pressuring Pettitte,
who allowed seven hits, four walks and five runs in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (3-1) has not missed Ken Griffey Jr. yet. His
replacement in center field, Mike Cameron, scaled and reached over
the wall to take a home run away from Derek Jeter in the eighth
inning. The play, so reminiscent of Griffey, earned Cameron a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer's ninth-inning two-run homer _ his third home run
in four games _ made the final score respectable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, has lauded Jorge Posada for his
improved communication with the pitchers, but it was obvious Friday
night that the Yankees' catcher is not fully trusted by Pettitte,
who possesses perhaps the most delicate psyche of any starter on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte would sometimes pitch entire games to Joe Girardi
without shaking off any signs, nodding robotically to anything
Girardi suggested. But Pettitte struggled with his command from the
outset, and as he prepared to throw to David Bell with the count at
no balls and two strikes in the first inning, he shook off Posada
five times.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte shook off more signs and began stepping off the mound,
slowing the pace of his work; he had increased his tempo in spring
training dramatically and felt this was an important part of his
success. At one point while pitching to John Olerud in the second
inning, Pettitte shook off a sign, then stepped away from the
rubber to meet with Posada in front of the mound. When the catcher
returned to his position and signaled again, Pettitte shook him off
again. The left-hander threw 12 pitches in the third inning, and
shook off signs before nine of those.
</P>
<P>
   His control problems, and not his problems with Posada, had a
more direct effect on his performance. Placing his left fist
against his mouth for warmth before each pitch on this chilly
evening, Pettitte needed 53 pitches to get through the first two
innings, throwing about half of his pitches for strikes. Alex
Rodriguez mashed an opposite-field home run in the first inning,
and Pettitte balked home a run in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's labors, however, appeared to have an unintended
impact on John Halama, the Seattle starter. Halama threw expertly
in the first two innings, his breaking ball sharp and his control
uncanny as he fired first-pitch strikes to seven of eight batters.
</P>
<P>
   But Halama had to wait through Pettitte's miserable 28-pitch
second inning, and when he came out for the third, the crispness in
his work had disappeared. Halama threw a first-pitch ball to the
next 10 hitters. Chuck Knoblauch doubled with one out and Jeter
unloaded a two-run home run to left-center, Jeter's first home run
of the year to tie the score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Bellinger, replacing the injured Scott Brosius at third,
led off the fifth by pulling a line drive into the left-field
corner for a double. Knoblauch grounded to shortstop for the first
out, failing to advance Bellinger to third, and when Jeter lined to
deep right, Bellinger tagged up and moved to third. But Bell, the
Seattle second baseman, nonchalantly took the throw from right
field and dropped the ball, and Bellinger scampered homeward and
scored with a headfirst slide, giving the Yankees a 3-2 edge.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte collapsed in the bottom half of the inning, walking
Rodriguez and surrendering a run-scoring double to Jay Buhner. Two
batters later, Joe Oliver walloped a two-run homer to right-center.
Rodriguez drove in Seattle's sixth run with sacrifice fly, against
reliever Ramiro Mendoza.
</P>
</TEXT>
