<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS KEEP KILLER INSTINCT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dallas Stars played it loose Friday night, but
the Los Angeles Kings had no such luxury.
</P>
<P>
   There still was the matter of a playoff opponent to determine,
even if winning means playing the mighty Detroit Red Wings in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings know maintaining momentum from an impressive
regular season might be just as important, so they took nothing for
granted in beating the Dallas Stars 3-2 in front of a sellout crowd
of 18,118 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by their first victory in 25 games against the Stars
in their last meeting, the Kings did not show the effects of
playing without Rob Blake and Ziggy Palffy, who hope to return for
Sunday's regular-season finale in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   That game also could have meant a lot since the Kings entered
Friday's action just one point ahead of Phoenix (90-89) for the
fifth spot in the Western Conference. But the Coyotes lost to San
Jose, meaning they will play Colorado in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Ducks won 5-1 in Nashville on Friday, they were
eliminated when No. 8 Edmonton tied Vancouver. Now the Kings know
they are going to Anaheim with a date Thursday night in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's game sounded closer than it was. The Stars pulled their
goaltender with 1:55 left in the third period and Kirk Muller
scored his second goal of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kings coach Andy Murray had a premonition. The fiery
first-year coach allowed Fox television to put a microphone on him
during the game. In this one, there was little need for profanity.
</P>
<P>
   Murray also rested starting goaltender Stephane Fiset, who has
been spectacular in the past two weeks since returning from a groin
injury. Jamie Storr took over, but didn't get much work. He faced
just 13 shots in the first period and did not allow a goal until
Muller scored on the power play in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Murray even got the chance to use Pierre Boucher for the first
time this season. Boucher has been sidelined all year after two
foot operations. He had played the past few weeks for minor league
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings actually made it look kind of easy against the Stars,
who are winless in their last four while tuning up for their
defense of the Stanley Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jaroslav Modry, playing in place of the injured
Blake, opened the scoring with his second goal in two games. He
also had the Kings' only goal in Thursday's 1-1 tie against
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The goal came on the power play at 7:08 of the first period on a
pass to the slot by Glen Murray with Richard Matvichuk off for
holding.
</P>
<P>
   Modry beat Stars backup goaltender Manny Fernandez, who was
playing in place of starter Ed Belfour, low to the stick side for
his fifth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings made it 2-0 at the 17:13 mark of the first when Ian
Laperriere scored his ninth. Laperriere, who was elevated to the
second line when Bryan Smolinski went down with a knee injury
Monday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Laperriere, usually an enforcer with the Kings' third unit, was
parked in front when Luc Robitaille intercepted a pass from the
Stars Jamie Pushor. Robitaille fired on net and Laperriere poked it
in.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four minutes into the second period, the Kings made it
a three-goal lead with their second power-play goal of the night.
Grant Marshall was off for roughing when Karalahti scored on a
rebound shot from Jozef Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first time in 17 games the Kings had two power
play goals, dating back to Feb. 23 at Calgary.
</P>
</TEXT>
