<HEADLINE>
DUVAL (65) MASTERS AUGUSTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ This was billed as a major golf championship,
which the scalpers confirmed. Still, some were wondering how we
ended up with a Hooters event, then the U.S. Senior Open.
</P>
<P>
   But after two rounds, this Masters finally makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Someone cut off Dennis Paulson's bar tab. Someone else asked to
see Jack Nicklaus' ID.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this chaos Friday, David Duval and a star-studded
leaderboard emerged, promising a stimulating weekend of golf. Of
the 57 players who made the cut, 20 have won majors, including six
of the final eight.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is not one of those with all the hardware, but he could be
soon. He knows how to spot an opening when he sees one. Friday, the
Florida native snuck into the lead while the rest of Augusta
National was watching Nicklaus, 60, attempt to recapture his youth.
</P>
<P>
   Closing hard and fast, Duval had four birdies and an eagle over
his final seven holes. He shot the tournament's low round, a
7-under-par 65, giving him a 138 total and one-stroke lead over
three players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting more comfortable,'' Duval warned.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh, Ernie Els and Phil Mickelson were one stroke back,
and Tom Lehman and Steve Jones just three behind. Of that quintet,
only Mickelson hasn't won a major, but he's an 11-time tour winner
and a considerable threat.
</P>
<P>
   Before teeing it up this week, the taciturn Duval practically
guaranteed he would be there at the end. He wasn't kidding. He was
sixth last year, runner-up the year before. He wears earth-tone
colors, but green would agree with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody seems to be asking players what their goals are, so
I just told everybody that tournament champion is what mine is,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the group playing ahead of Duval was the 60-year-old
Nicklaus, who pulled within two shots of the lead midway through
the round. People scrambled to watch the Golden Bear play the back
nine, remembering his unlikely Masters title run in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Had his putter been more kind _ he missed what he said were
seven makeable putts over the final eight holes _ Nicklaus would
have had retirement homes emptying across the nation. Still, he
finished with a 70, good for a 144 total, leaving him six behind
Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Some players might be chortling about Nicklaus' chances at
winning a seventh Masters, but not all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can beat anybody right now,'' said Jeff Sluman, who
is four shots behind Duval. ``Any time you underestimate your
opponents, that's a terrible thing to do. You can never
underestimate Jack Nicklaus.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lehman, ``That's pretty spectacular. It really shows,
besides the talent of the man, he just knows how to play this golf
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Still getting acquainted with Augusta National is Paulson, who
went from first-round leader to tied with Nicklaus and five others.
</P>
<P>
   The former career mini-tour player, long-drive champion and
self-professed wild man shot 76 Friday, eight strokes higher than
his first round. He bogeyed his first two holes, finding a bunker
and hitting a tree. At least he kept his anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   With a million stories to tell while reveling in the first-day
Masters spotlight, Paulson was cautioned that he might become
famous _ or at least interrupted during dinner, something his PGA
Tour peers routinely battle. By his own choosing, nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go anywhere,'' he said. ``I had a pizza and a few
beers and a bath day with my kids. I just had a regular day at the
golf course and regular night at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulson probably has nothing to worry about during the rest of
his Augusta stay.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tiger Woods is still hanging around. The Masters did its
best to run him off, but he shot 72, leaving him at 147, nine
strokes behind Duval.
</P>
<P>
   He can't get his putter working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to try and play solid, and if it happens, it
happens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a sprint to the finish, bet on Duval. He's become such a
fitness freak, he jogged 6{ miles after a practice round the other
day. Friday, he planned to hit the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   Duval sees an advantage to this exercise overload.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come Sunday afternoon, the fact I believe I'm in good shape
can pay off,'' he said. ``I'll be more refreshed than other people,
and my strength will still be high. That's the focus of why I'm
doing this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   So, it's not the Hooters Tour or Senior circuit. How does the
Masters Ironman Triathlon sound?
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 0210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
