<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORIOUS DUCKS LEFT WITH HOLLOW FEELING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Knowing full well they had backed themselves
into a corner, the Mighty Ducks took out some of their frustrations
on the Nashville Predators. Anaheim ruined the second-year
franchise's ``Fangtastic'' celebration with a 5-1 victory Friday
night that kept its slim playoff hopes alive _ but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   While the Ducks were flying back to Southern California, the
Vancouver Canucks outducked the Ducks. The Canucks needed a victory
in regulation to extend the suspense for themselves and the Ducks
but blew a 3-1 third- period lead and lost to Edmonton 5-4 in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   In a season that has seen the Ducks blow their share of leads,
it seemed a fitting way for the Oilers to clinch a playoff spot and
turn Anaheim's season finale against the Kings on Sunday into a
meaningless exhibition for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had departed the Gaylord Entertainment Center with
hope, but at the same time they seemed to be realistic about their
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good feeling to sit around and wait for somebody
else to do your job for you,'' said Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg,
who knows the Ducks have nobody else to blame but themselves for
being in such a position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 81 games to control our own destiny,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nobody's fault but our own if we don't get in,'' said
Paul Kariya, who registered his third 40-goal season by scoring his
40th and 41st goals in a four-point performance that turned out to
be too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya almost seemed resigned to what was going to happen, even
moments after the game had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time we showed our true colors,'' he said of a game
in which the Ducks outshot the Predators 39-29 and easily could
have scored nine or 10 times if not for some spectacular saves by
Mike Dunham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real frustrating because you know the talent level is
there to do some good things in this league,'' Kariya added. ``But
the work effort and commitment wasn't consistently there. The scary
thing is that when it was, we beat a lot of good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, they also lost to a lot of bad teams, games that
came back to haunt them Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   After losing 5-2 in Chicago on Wednesday, the only way the Ducks
could even give themselves a glimmer of hope was to defeat
Nashville for the fourth consecutive time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't look good in the first 10 minutes, when the
Predators, playing their last game of the season, came out strong
and scored when Greg Johnson skated 1 laps around the Ducks'
defense before shoving a centering pass to Tom Fitzgerald, who
scored at 6:03.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly the Ducks' money players took over. Steve Rucchin
tied the game with the first of his two goals _ a one-timer on the
power at 11:33.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen seconds into the second, Kariya turned the game around
for good by scoring a shorthanded breakaway to give the Ducks a 2-1
lead. Antti Aalto gave Anaheim a 3-1 lead at 6:16 before Rucchin
scored again at 11:41. Kariya finished off the scoring with a goal
at 2:57 of the third period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0837 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RAMPART-GARCETTI-LADN     04-08 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-GARCETTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR DENIES STALLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG GITTRICH AND BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The prosecutor handpicked by L.A. District
Attorney Gil Garcetti to lead the LAPD corruption probe has denied
that he stalled efforts to indict rogue cops to benefit Garcetti
politically.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a Daily News article, Head Deputy District
Attorney Dan Murphy said Friday that the decision not to indict at
least four officers in February as prosecutors had urged was his,
and not Garcetti's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the head of the prosecution team ... I will determine
when cases are ready to prosecute,'' Murphy said when questioned by
reporters after a luncheon at a downtown hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti, who has refused repeated requests for interviews for
more than a month on how his office has handled early warnings of
police corruption and prosecution against officers, walked past the
reporters and would not respond to questions.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Daily News reported comments made by Deputy
District Attorney George Rosenstock that he and at least one other
prosecutor were thwarted in efforts to indict Rampart Division
officers after Garcetti put Murphy in charge of the task force.
Rosenstock said, when he objected, Murphy kicked him off the team
and he was assigned a lesser post in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer came a month before Garcetti was forced into a
November runoff in the primary election. Rosenstock accused Murphy
of being ``a political operative with one agenda -- to avoid any
action which might damage Mr. Garcetti's re-election chances -- not
as a professional prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview, Murphy said indictments will be handled
``in a professional, timely manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy insisted there is no truth to allegations that politics
resulted in Rosenstock's removal from the task force or were
factored into the timing of indictments.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to explain why Rosenstock's charges echo recent
complaints from LAPD Chief Bernard C. Parks, the Public Defender's
Office, and other deputy district attorneys, Murphy said he would
not comment on the task force's prosecutorial strategies. He also
refused to predict when indictments may come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to be rushed by the police chief or the Daily
News,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy added that his decision to transfer Rosenstock off the
team was based upon ``sound management decisions,'' nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy made his comments in a hallway of the Wilshire Grand
Hotel downtown where Garcetti was appearing at an awards ceremony
honoring citizen heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Following the ceremony, a spokeswoman for Garcetti indicated he
would speak to reporters after he posed for pictures with some of
the honorees.
</P>
<P>
   But when the camera shots were finished, Garcetti huddled
briefly with Murphy and Victoria Pipkin, the spokeswoman. With
Pipkin at his side and Murphy nearby, Garcetti walked by reporters,
ignoring repeated questions.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rosenstock and other sources, Garcetti's political
ambitions led to a policy to delay filing charges against ``dirty
cops'' until this summer. The time was designed to allow Garcetti
to gain credit for the indictments without running the risk that
the cases would reach trial before the November election against
Head Deputy District Attorney Steve Cooley.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley, who narrowly beat Garcetti in the March 7 primary, said
Rosenstock's allegations raised serious questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garcetti, with a reputation as a passive prosecutor, tends to
see the criminal justice system through a political prism for his
own advantage,'' Cooley said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any perceived attempt to obstruct the speedy administration of
justice through political manipulation, given the worst police
corruption scandal in the city's history, will backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   No officers, other than dirty-cop-turned-key-informant Rafael
Perez, have been indicted. Perez was sentenced to five years in
prison Feb. 25 for stealing about $1 million worth of cocaine from
an LAPD evidence room.
</P>
<P>
