r a BC-BABYDOL-MADAM-LADN     04-08 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABYDOL-MADAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MADAM CONVICTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE CARNEY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jody ``Babydol'' Gibson, accused of running a
call-girl ring that catered to entertainers, star athletes and
politicians, was convicted Friday on three counts of pimping, but a
jury deadlocked on four pandering charges.
</P>
<P>
   Bailiffs immediately took a visibly surprised Gibson into
custody after the judge set bail at $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Nuys Superior Court jury deadlocked 11-1 for conviction
on three pandering counts and 10-2 on the fourth. Prosecutors
expect to announce at Gibson's sentencing on April 28 whether they
will retry her on the charges of procuring women to work for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for something strong, showing she was coercing,
convincing,'' said Ronnie Berkovics, 42, of North Hollywood, a
juror who voted for acquittal on the four pandering counts. ``I
didn't see her manipulating or encouraging anything other than what
would be normal business practices in other careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, 41, faces a minimum three-year prison sentence. The
maximum is eight years, four months.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors said they think the penalty is harsh, and some even
questioned whether prostitution should be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would have been contributing a lot of money to the Board
of Equalization if what she had been doing was legalized,''
Berkovics said.
</P>
<P>
   But jury foreman Russell Breeding, 43, of Mission Hills, said
jurors based their deliberations on the law and the evidence before
them, not their feelings about prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the books and evidence. They sent her money. We agreed
they were all prostitutes,'' said Breeding. ``The harshness of the
penalty -- we didn't really consider that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the jury might have considered conviction on a lesser
offense if it had had that option.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's partial verdict came after nearly eight days of
deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson had been free on bail during the four weeks of trial and
jury deliberation, but Superior Court Judge Lloyd Nash ordered her
remanded to custody after the verdict and set bail at $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard nothing regarding any community ties. She has
every opportunity to flee the jurisdiction,'' Nash said. He also
cited the mandatory prison sentence as a reason for not letting her
go home.
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting the verdicts, Gibson joked with her attorney,
Gerald Scotti, then licked her red, lipsticked lips and sat
impassively in a blue blazer, crisp white blouse and slacks while
they were read.
</P>
<P>
   She and Scotti showed no emotion, although she looked surprised
when she realized she was being taken to jail. Bailiffs handed her
watch and hair barrettes to supporters outside; they had no
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Scotti lashed out at the laws against
prostitution and said he might appeal the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no real crime here,'' Scotti said. ``Everybody got
what they wanted. Everybody went away happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are draconian laws. You're putting that in the category
of serious, heinous crimes,'' he said of the verdicts and the
impending sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed dismay that none of Gibson's clients, whose
names jurors said included entertainers, political figures and at
least one professional athlete, were called to testify or have been
charged with anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a railroad case. Those customers should have been
brought in. But they can sit back safely now,'' he said. ``Why do
they all get free passes?''
</P>
<P>
   Because soliciting prostitution is a misdemeanor, Los Angeles
County Deputy District Attorney Richard Walmark said it would be up
to the City Attorney's Office to charge the men.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Gibson, an aspiring pop singer, at the Century
Plaza Hotel on June 8. They said she ran a prostitution ring by
telephone and the Internet from her home in Palo Verde near the
California-Arizona border, and also from a Van Nuys hotel, charging
up to $3,000 per encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the 10-month police investigation included Officer
Cynthia Neff posing as a woman named Taylor seeking to work for
Gibson as a prostitute. She surreptitiously recorded several
conversations with Gibson over several months. The other hold-out
juror, Tony Holguin, 54, of Studio City, said he didn't believe
Neff's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In building his case, Walmark also offered testimony from three
women who said they worked for Gibson as prostitutes. They were
given immunity for their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the jury reached verdicts on three counts of
pimping, saying Gibson was employing prostitutes. But Nash sealed
those verdicts while jurors continued deliberating on the four
charges of pandering -- that she was influencing people to be
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
