<SLUG> BC-MATTHEWS-BANKRUPTCY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTHEWS STUDIO GROUP IN CHAPTER 11
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Matthews Studio Equipment Group, the once-high
flying entertainment equipment supplier, has announced that it
filed for Chapter11 bankruptcy reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court late Thursday, the
Burbank-based firm said it has assets of $55 million and debts of
$80.3 million. Other subsidiaries of the company also filed for
Chapter 11 protection Thursday, including Matthews Studio Group
Centers Inc. and Hollywood Rental Company, LLC.
</P>
<P>
   The Chapter 11 filing follows a series of blows to the firm,
including losses at its Duke City Video unit and its March 29
delisting from the Nasdaq Small-Cap Market.
</P>
<P>
   But company officials, while admitting they made mistakes in
recent months, said they remain optimistic about the company's
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great company, which is very strong on cash flow and
earning potential, but our balance sheet was a little off and we
had too much debt,'' said Carlos D. DeMattos, the company's
chairman and chief executive officer. ``Through reorganization, we
hope to get those things solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews Studio stock is frozen at 94 cents a share; less than a
year ago, the stock hit an all-time high of $10.88 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old firm specializes in renting lighting, cameras
and other equipment to the entertainment industry. It went public
in 1989 and began purchasing rival firms, eventually emerging as
one of the giants in the theatrical equipment rental industry. The
company's stock rose quickly in late 1998 and early 1999, driven
largely by its launch of the ShowbizMart.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But officials say losses and heavy capital investment at Duke
City Video, a unit that Matthews Group purchased for its broadcast
equipment rental operations, has hurt the company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   On March 29, the company announced it was having liquidity
problems and was considering a Chapter 11 filing.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Peter Cardillo, director of research for New York-based
Westfalia Investments, said the company still has strong assets and
could do well after a reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect they're going to try and survive and there's a shot
at that happening,'' Cardillo said. ``Obviously, management needs
to be changed, and I think that will come about.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardillo -- who last year estimated Matthews Studio stock could
rise as high as $18 a share -- blamed the company's troubles on its
rapid expansion beyond equipment leasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lost sight of their core business, which was a good
business,'' he said. ``They got in over their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bret Weeks, the company's investor relations spokesman, said
the firm should recover soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a hiccup in the company's history,'' he said.
``Right now we expect to come out of Chapter 11 relatively
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
