<SLUG> BC-HKN-NEWKING-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS BEAT STARS
</HEADLINE>
 ... WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sometime in the third period Friday night, the
playoff tumblers started to click and the Los Angeles Kings' 3-2
victory over the Dallas Stars no longer seemed so important.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Kings still had a game to play, but they also learned
they will open the postseason Thursday night in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   And the Stars, the defending Stanley Cup champions who now are
winless in four consecutive, finally got out of their lounge chairs
to make it close after pulling their goaltender with less than two
minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we were watching what was happening on the scoreboard,''
Glen Murray said. ``The game kind of lost its importance out there.
Even after the first goal, they seemed to let up. It's good to
finally know where we stand.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Kings (38-31-12), won and Phoenix lost to San Jose, the
fifth seed was secured no matter what happens Sunday in the
regular-season finale against the Mighty Ducks in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the Ducks won in Nashville, they were
eliminated, as were the Vancouver Canucks, who blew a two-goal lead
and lost in overtime to Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Kings, who could finish the season with 94 points,
this was an important game vs. a team that had a five-year unbeaten
streak against them until their last meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also scored two goals on the power play for the first
time in 17 games. And they maintained their momentum, which might
be just as important, even though most think they have little
chance against the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   When the Kings made the playoffs two years ago, they struggled
at the end of the regular season and were swept in four games by
St. Louis in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Now, playing well and getting players healthy is big. Captain
Rob Blake, out the past three games with a bruised left knee, and
Ziggy Palffy, sidelined three weeks with a right shoulder sprain,
will play Sunday against the Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also think the play of our goaltenders is a big
difference between now and two years ago,'' Luc Robitaille said.
``(Stephane Fiset) had the night off and Jamie (Storr) stepped in
and gave us a great game. There is no substitute for hot
goaltending in the playoffs. It can change everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr's only two mistakes came on goals by Kirk Muller. The
first came on the power play, the second with a six-on-five
situation after Dallas pulled its goaltender in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw what Jamie did out there,'' said Kings coach Andy
Murray, who will start Fiset on Sunday and in the playoffs. ``I
think this is the first time since the beginning of the season that
we've had both guys healthy. You never know what can happen in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray might have had a premonition about Friday when the fiery
first-year coach allowed Fox television to put a microphone on him
during the game. In this one, there was little need for profanity.
</P>
<P>
   Murray even got the chance to use Pierre Boucher for the first
time this season. Boucher has been sidelined all year after two
foot operations. He had played the past few weeks for minor-league
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings actually made it look kind of easy against the Stars,
who are winless in their last four while tuning up for their
defense of the Stanley Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jaroslav Modry, playing in place of the injured
Blake, opened the scoring with his second goal in two games. He
also had the Kings' only goal in Thursday's 1-1 tie against
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings made it 2-0 at the 17:13 mark of the first when Ian
Laperriere scored his ninth. Laperriere, who was elevated to the
second line when Bryan Smolinski went down with a knee injury
Monday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure feels good,'' Laperriere said. ``We're ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
