<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0841 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-08 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SHOW YANKEES ALL WITH CLUTCH HITS, PLAYS, PITCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The times, they are a-changing.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe it, then you haven't watched the Seattle
Mariners during the first week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners dusted off the Boston Red Sox twice in three games
to begin the season, then came back and opened a set with New York
with a powerful performance in a 7-5 victory Friday night that
showed the breadth of the M's ability to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new year and a new season,'' winning pitcher John
Halama said. ``We're anxious to get on a roll and get some sense of
ourselves as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to realize what everybody's capable of, and
we're starting to jell.''
</P>
<P>
   The win, the third in a row for the M's, contained some of the
key elements of the two earlier wins.
</P>
<P>
   There was the usual classically inspired relief pitching from
Kazuhiro Sasaki _ when's the last time a Mariners team could take
that as a given? _ and one seriously clutch tie-breaking homer from
Joe Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a homer-stealing catch from center fielder Mike
Cameron in the eighth inning that helped blunt the Yankees'
comeback effort. The leaping catch was such a winner that much of
the crowd of 40,827 gave Cameron a standing ovation in the bottom
of the eighth inning _ after he'd struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, these aren't the
lay-down-and-lose-when-the-Beasts-of-the-East-come-calling
Mariners. Seattle lost 16 of 20 games to the Red Sox and Yankees
last year, but you can consider it a done deal that two of the best
teams in baseball have had all they can handle from the Safeco
samurai.
</P>
<P>
   And the fans have been voting with their voices, making an
impact with the sheer volume of their cheering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are into it,'' manager Lou Piniella said, simply.
``It's just four games, but they've been into the four games. It's
been electric, and when you're playing New York it's always going
to be a little more electric.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver provided the biggest offensive infusion of energy with a
first-pitch, two-run homer that came moments after a game-tying
fifth-inning double by Jay Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's cannonade into the right-field seats broke the backs of
the Yankees, who had erased an early 2-0 Seattle lead to take a 3-2
lead in the top of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver is a take-it-as-it-comes guy, but he showed real emotion
while the crowd was doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hoping for a double,'' Oliver said. ``When it went
over the fence, that was special. I don't think I've ever shown
that kind of emotion on a homer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Oliver, it was vindication of a long winter of work that got
him back to the major leagues after an agonizing season at Triple-A
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mariners, the night was vindication of the moves that
the club made to shore up the 1999 product.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the holdover Mariners didn't have their
moments on center stage Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez hit his 150th career homer, tying the Mickey
Mantle for the fourth-youngest player to get to 150 home runs.
Halama pitched six strong innings, didn't walk anyone and allowed
three runs, just two of them earned. Jose Paniagua and Paul Abbott
each threw a strong inning of relief.
</P>
<P>
   But the new kids on the block, led by Oliver, stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Mark McLemore entered the game late and engineered two
rallies that pushed the lead to four runs at one point, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki took over after a Shane Spencer homer in the ninth cut
the Yankees' deficit to 7-5 and got three quick outs for his second
consecutive save.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Cameron who made what he called ``maybe my
best catch ever'' to take away Derek Jeter's bid for a homer.
</P>
<P>
   The center fielder, who has heard so much about how Ken Griffey
Jr. played center, dropped a defensive bomb on the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron did an Sir Edmund Hillary vs. Mount Everest thing to
bring back Jeter's blast, scaling the wall to pull the ball back
into play for the inning's second out, showing a little snowcone as
he held up evidence of his handiwork for the umpire's _ and the
crowd's _ inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made it the best was the standing ovation,'' Cameron
said. ``It was so loud I couldn't hear myself think.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre said Cameron's catch was
``Junior-esque stuff out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still the catch didn't end the game. Spencer's homer showed the
Yankees' determination to get back in the game. But not this time.
The Mariners are playing the final few innings of games with a
confidence unknown to recent Seattle clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The glue has been Sasaki, who was pitching for the third time in
three nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to have to use him again,'' Piniella said. ``But
he came in and did the same thing he's done every time we've used
him. He gets outs.''
</P>
<P>
   The last one, a swinging strike by Ricky Ledee, moved the
Mariners to 3-1, the best record in the West less than a week into
the season.
</P>
<P>
   That may not seem like much, but that record has been carved out
against teams that victimized the Mariners repeatedly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
