<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FORUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH REJECTS GOV. WILSON'S POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Reaching out for California's growing Latino vote,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush repudiated Proposition 187 and the wedge
politics of former Republican Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the National Hispanic Women's Conference in Los
Angeles &UR;  &LR; on Friday, Bush never mentioned Wilson by name but said
issues such as Proposition 187, which would have curtailed most of
California's social services for illegal immigrants and their
children, were divisive and destructive.
</P>
<P>
   '`It's so important to have leadership that tears down barriers,
leadership that offers a future hopeful for everybody, leaders who
reject the politics of pitting one group of people against each
other,'' Bush told the meeting at the Biltmore Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not use our children, the children of immigrants, as a
political issue. There are no second-rate children in my vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was unavailable for comment, but his spokesman, Sean
Walsh, said the former governor has much in common with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Wilson shares Gov. Bush's sentiments and agrees with the
comment about why illegal aliens come to this country,'' Walsh
said. ``But we make no apologies for seeking to have the federal
government reimburse California for the costs of illegal aliens.
There, we have a legitimate policy disagreement with Gov. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive GOP presidential nominee to face Democrat
Vice President Al Gore, spent most of his speech emphasizing the
need for accountability in education through testing and for
national reforms to make the educational system respond to the
needs of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of government is not to create wealth, it's to create
opportunity,'' Bush said, occasionally addressing the crowd of some
1,000 women in Spanish. ``We don't want people to feel left behind
... in the pursuit of the American dream. This country belongs to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made it clear he intends to campaign vigorously in
California and believes he has a chance to carry the state in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Critical to his strategy is the mending of GOP's relations with
Latino voters and others who saw Wilson's support for Proposition
187 in 1994 as a direct attack on the state's large immigrant
population.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 187, which won 60 percent of the vote in 1994, was
intended to limit public education, welfare and health services to
illegal immigrants. U.S. District Judge Mariana R. Pfaelzer ruled
most of the initiative was unconstitutional, in part because it
entered the jurisdiction of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Gov. Gray Davis abandoned the legal battle in
negotiating a settlement with opponents that left in little more
than provisions that had become federal law.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bush talked briefly about immigration issues,
saying the United States has to work to promote the economy of
Mexico and other Latin American countries to reduce people's need
to cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family values do not stop at the Rio Grande River,'' Bush
said. ``If you're a mother or dad and you're worried about feeding
your children and you can't find work close to home and you hear of
opportunities somewhere else and you're worth your salt, you're
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Texas governor's second major address to Latinos in
California. Earlier in his campaign, Bush made his first major
policy address before a Latino business group.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference and in a meeting with California political
reporters, Bush said he intends to win the state and its 54
electoral votes by attracting new voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a rumor going around that somehow I'm not going
to compete in California,'' Bush said. ``That's wishful thinking on
the part of Al Gore. I plan to campaign in California, and I think
we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will return to the state in May and June and plans
an extensive campaign in the state during the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be making the mistakes of 1992 or 1996,'' Bush
said, referring to the lackluster campaigns in the state by his
father, former President Bush, and by former Sen. Robert Dole, the
GOP's '96 nominee.
</P>
<P>
   California has gone Democratic in the past eight years, a trend
capped last year by a near sweep of statewide offices. President
Clinton and Gore have spent a great deal of their time in the state
to try to solidify Democratic support. The party will hold its
national convention in Los Angeles in August.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged his party's problems in the state, thanks to
its positions on such divisive issues as illegal immigration,
affirmative action and bilingual education, as well as the
difficulty of convincing GOP regulars of the need to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in politics, you have to alienate people to
expand,'' Bush said. ``If some people are alienated by me reaching
out to new voters, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   While not rejecting the support of Wilson -- ``I welcome
everyone's support,'' Bush said -- he indicated he would be taking
a different approach to California politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Republican Party has somehow gotten the image we
are not mindful of the concerns of new Americans,'' Bush said.
``We've got to do a better job. Our party -- our candidate, me --
has to do a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has been running an independent advertising campaign for
Bush, which the likely nominee said he has not seen and is not sure
is helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had someone in Texas running some independent ads and I
think they hurt more than they helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, Bush continued to say that the case of Elian
Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy who has been the subject of
international attention, should be decided in family court in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Such an approach angers many in the Mexican-American community
who have seen their own families deported or the issuance of green
cards delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he understood the difficulty, but that the Gonzalez
case was a unique situation and needed to be handled differently.
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
<P>
   X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
