<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAIT-AND-SEE MARINERS FANS ARE SEEING VICTORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When you think of the most famous play in the most
intense Mariners-Yankees contest, when a runner scored all the way
from first base on a smash double, what do you think of?
</P>
<P>
   Right: Ken Griffey Jr. hitting the afterburners on Edgar
Martinez's double into the left-field corner in Game 5 of the
American League Division Series in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to history buffs, but that doesn't quite cut it
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   A new era is being built at Safeco Field during this already
heady opening homestand week. Four games in, and the Mariners are
putting a new spin on things.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to start a new tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Mariners downloaded a 2000 version of the old
Yankee killer.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the fifth, Jay Buhner rapped a double down the
left-field line, and a new Mariner king _ Alex Rodriguez _ went
flying around the bases to score, tying the game at 3.
</P>
<P>
   The good ol' Mighty Mariner karma was up and running. Joe Oliver
followed Buhner's RBI double with a two-run homer, giving the
Mariners a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the strangest thing in Mariner history took place.
</P>
<P>
   All across the Puget Sound, all across the state of Washington,
up into Alaska and over into Idaho and down past the Columbia River
into Oregon, Mariner fans started looking forward to seeing
Seattle's bullpen get into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Please bring back Arthur Rhodes and Kazuhiro Sasaki. Pretty
please?
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Lou Piniella called on Sasaki, after Paul Abbott
gave up a two-run homer in the ninth, and all was saved in the 7-5
win as Sasaki's Daimajin ``evil spirit-killer'' aura was elevated
yet another level.
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't even touched upon the snow-cone grab by Mike
Cameron _ the one that pulled back a Derek Jeter bomb over the
center-field wall and gave Cameron the ear-ringing welcome he
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Did that play look familiar or what? A speed demon getting on
his horse, racing to the warning track and scaling the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' Cameron said after the game, pointing down to his
cleats. ``Those are Ken Griffey Jr. ``Swingman'' shoes I was
wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The number on Cameron's back is different, 44 instead of 24, but
the heart, the desire and the athletic ability can't be
second-guessed.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' whopping opening homestand was supposed to be a
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to start off with the heavy hitters from Boston and
New York. Bring in the fans. Give Safeco Field a
center-of-the-universe feel.
</P>
<P>
   But something funny happened at the ballpark Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz created by two impressive victories over the Red Sox
has already jump-started those wait-and-see fans to stand up and
take notice of these 2000 Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance Friday was 40,827, with about 3,000 of those walk-up
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if the Sonics would have liked that kind of last-minute
interest?
</P>
<P>
   The odd consequence of this encouraging start is that it seems
less important that this is a Mariners-Yankees series.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a case could be made that a Mariners-Yankees series at
Safeco would have been better in May or early June, so that by
then, if these winning Mariners continue in this fashion, Seattle
fans will be drooling in anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   As of now, Marinerville is playing catch-up. It's getting a
crash course in how the new Howard Lincoln/Pat Gillick,
win-in-Safeco with pitching, defense and hit-and-runs team really
works.
</P>
<P>
   More important than renewing the Yankee rivalry is the work that
citizens of Marinerville have to do to crystallize this team in our
collective baseball consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   People are catching on. Players are making an impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't hear myself thinking,'' Cameron said after the
standing ovation continued through his at-bat in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a few goosebumps, but I'll tell you what, it's nice to
be rewarded for something you work hard on every day. I just tried
to get up as high as I can and get it. I knew it was coming down
into the tip of my glove, and I tried to snatch it before it went
back over the fence,'' Cameron said.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that a team with so many new parts can come
together so quickly?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why not,'' Mark McLemore said. ``Why wait until
June?''
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, who was 0-for-4 in his first game as a Mariner, has
now reached base in nine of his past 11 at-bats. That included a
walk and a single Friday after McLemore replaced Charles Gipson in
the sixth. McLemore scored both times, proving he knows how to find
home plate.
</P>
<P>
   This is why McLemore is a catalyst. This is why McLemore is
here. This is why Gillick took a plane ride to talk to the former
Texas Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore won three AL West Division titles with Texas, or should
we say: McLemore was a big reason why the Rangers won, since he was
on base for all those Juan Gonzalez RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come to a team that had a chance to win,''
McLemore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to win. That's what this team is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about winning _ and winning back the wait-and-see citizens
of Marinerville, who don't have much reason to wait any longer.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
