<HEADLINE>
THE BEATINGS GO ON FOR CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ?????  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Michael Vega
</P>
<P>
   Globe Staff
</P>
<P>
   It was only fitting that, in game No. 76 of this torture test of
a season, the Celtics ran their losing streak to 10 with an
abominable 102-97 loss to the Philadelphia 76ers Friday. Maybe
Celtics fans should start calling the NBA team from Philly the
``Deep Sixers'' for the myriad ways it has buried Boston this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Before a FleetCenter crowd of 18,342, the playoff-bound Sixers _
er, Deep Sixers _ allowed Boston to get off to a sizzling start. In
the first half, the Celtics scored 60 points on 24-for-48 shooting
from the field, 4 of 7 from 3-point range, while holding Allen
Iverson to just 7 points on 3-for-5 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But, like in so many other games the Celtics have lost during
this skein, Boston's hopes for a victory were dashed in the second
half, particularly the fourth quarter. The Celtics led by as many
as 11 in the second quarter before settling for a 60-55 halftime
lead. Thrice in the third they increased that margin to 9 (74-65,
76-67, and 78-69) before squandering it by scoring just 37 points
on a putrid 14-for-44 shooting performance in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   As the final seconds ticked away, a pair of loud fans tried to
take out their frustration on coach Rick Pitino with derisive
taunts of ``We love you, Rick! We hope you come back, Rick!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's very frustrating,'' Pitino surmised. ``There are
a lot of things that I like that I see, so I can look at the
negative or I can look at the postive. And, at times like these,
you have to look at the positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Celtic fans, you knew he would say that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only salvation you have,'' Pitino said. ``I do want
to thank the fans again. The fans have been wonderful to us. As you
look around the league, you don't see the support we are getting
for a team that's not winning. And that's wonderful from the
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, the Celtics failed to send their fans home feeling
warm and fuzzy, instead subjecting them to another numbing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson, though, did his best to put a halt to the
mounting losses. He scored a game-high 28 points on 8-for-16
shooting from the field and 8 of 8 from the foul line. He also had
6 assists, 5 rebounds, and 3 steals. Paul Pierce added 18 (6 for
13) and Antoine Walker had 16 points, 9 rebounds, 6 assists, and 3
blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the losing has begun to wear on the team, Walker said,
``To be honest, it does wear on us. It wears on you mentally as
well as physically, because it's very hard to get your body ready
to play each game emotionally and to understand the game plan. You
play good for three quarters and things don't work out, that's part
of being a professional. You've got to somehow find a way to get a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite hitting just 8 of 24 field goals in the third, the
Celtics still managed to control an 80-78 lead. Matt Geiger, who
came off the bench to lead the Sixers with 20 points, shaved a
6-point Boston lead to 2 with a 4-point tear in the final 55.3
seconds of the third when he threw down a slam dunk and hit a
7-foot lane jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geiger has hurt us in two games,'' Pitino said. ``We do a very
good job on Iverson (who had been held to a mere 2 points on
1-for-5 shooting through three quarters), but you get hurt a bit in
the frontcourt.''
</P>
<P>
   Geiger hit a foul-line jumper to tie it, 80-80, with 11:43 left,
but Dana Barros answered with a jumper and Danny Fortson followed
with a strong layup in the lane to make it 84-80. Philly came back
to tie it on an Aaron McKie jumper and a pair of free throws by
Toni Kukoc.
</P>
<P>
   McKie then gave the Sixers their first lead since 10-9 when he
scored a foul-inducing basket underneath to make it 86-84, but
missed the accompanying free throw. Kukoc missed a technical called
against Walker, but McKie atoned when he hit a jumper to make it a
4-point game. Walker responded with a timely trey that pulled the
Celtics within 1, 88-87, with 6:54 left.
</P>
<P>
   That's as close as Boston got. The Sixers twice went on to lead
by 9, the last time at 100-91. And referee Ken Mauer teed up his
fourth player of the game when he got Anderson with 3:20 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   By then, though, it was apparent the Celtics had been deep-sixed
again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
