<HEADLINE>
THIRD RED SOX LOSS BRINGS THOUGHTS OF PEDRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angels 7 Red Sox 3
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Nation no doubt is restless. Four games into this
season of great expectation, the Red Sox are wounded, wobbling, and
waiting for Pedro Martinez to provide some emotional rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox dropped their third straight Friday, a 7-3 decision to
the Anaheim Angels. It's way too early to worry, but that won't
stop the Nation from wondering when someone other than Pedro will
win a game for the wild-card wonders of 1999. Brian Rose gets the
ball Saturday. Pedro Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going to get better, gentlemen,'' Sox manager Jimy
Williams promised after the game. ``They really are.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran first baseman Mike Stanley said, ``A hundred and
fifty-eight to go. We need to get our game back on track. You can't
keep saying it's a long season forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra, who's struggling at .188, said, ``We're just
not in synch. We've got to go out and get some runs so pitchers
feel more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is all about the long haul, and it's nutty to draw
conclusions from four games, but the Sox find themselves in search
of better pitching (21 runs, 21 walks, and 7 homers yielded in the
last three games), more timely hitting, and tighter defense than
they've shown since Pedro's impressive opener.
</P>
<P>
   Boston got homers from Carl Everett and Brian Daubach in Game 4,
but it couldn't offset the two-homer, nine-hit barrage off Pete
Schourek and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek gave the Sox five serviceable innings, yielding three
runs on four hits and four walks while striking out four. He threw
74 pitches, 45 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I threw all right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Schourek's first Sox start since the infamous fourth game
of the 1998 Division Series when Red Sox manager Jimy Williams
defied logic and went with the journeyman lefty over Pedro (who
would have been working on three days rest) when the Sox were on
the brink of elimination. Schourek made Jimy look good that night,
spinning 5.1 innings of two-hit, shutout ball, but the Red Sox lost
anyway and Pedro went home mad.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Schourek surrendered a first-inning, one-out double to
Adam Kennedy, then walked cleanup man Tim Salmon after fanning Mo
Vaughn for the second out. Center fielder Garret Anderson turned on
the next pitch and drove it over the wall in right-center for a 3-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'd like to have that pitch back,'' said Schourek.
``After that I felt I threw better. I didn't throw poorly in the
first, I just made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek settled down after the three-run bomb, but it was
pretty clear he needs work on his slide step. Kennedy stole third
without drawing a throw in the first, and Vaughn stole second in
the same manner in the third. It was Vaughn's second steal of the
season. He did not steal a base in 1998 or 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, meanwhile, continued to struggle at the plate.
Boston scored only seven runs in three games in Seattle (four on
solo homers), and the immortal Jason Dickson had them in knots
early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had Trot Nixon batting second in place of John Valentin
(sore left knee). Stanley was designated hitter, Daubach played
first, Scott Hatteberg made his first start behind the plate, and
Jeff Frye started at third in place of Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' first good chance to score came when Nixon led with a
double in the fifth and went to third on a right-side ground out by
Everett. With Nixon on third and one out, Garciaparra popped up,
failing to get the run home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy on third, one out, that's not our team,'' said a disgusted
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary flied out to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   It got a little ugly in the bottom of the sixth. Rich Garces
came on for Schourek and quickly surrendered two singles and a
two-run double to Billerica's Gary DiSarcina. The Sox infield
continued to struggle and a Vaughn grounder to Jose Offerman drove
home the third run of the inning to make it 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox fought back with three in the seventh. Everett started
the rally with a solo homer on an 0-and-2 pitch to start the
inning. After a double by Stanley, old friend Kent Mercker relieved
Dickson, and Daubach greeted Mercker with a long homer to right to
cut the lead to 6-3. It was Daubach's third homer of the young
season.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield came on to pitch the bottom of the seventh and
surrendered a solo homer to Troy Glaus on a 1-and-2 pitch. That was
the end of the scoring for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be OK,'' said Garciaparra. ``We've just got to create
more opportunities and capitalize on 'em.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
