<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0849 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-FRANCE-REVIEW     04-08 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-FRANCE-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZUT ALORS! A NATIONAL TREASURE FLIRTS WITH HERESY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ On both sides of the English channel the treachery made
the front pages.
</P>
<P>
   Barely six months after she was chosen as the model for the bust
of Marianne, France's curvaceous national symbol, Laetitia Casta
was rhapsodizing about the benefits of living in London.
</P>
<P>
   The young supermodel talked of a diverse, lively city. But
everyone else suspected tax benefits, setting off a political
fistfight among French politicians and a cross-channel flow of
snide remarks that are so often the stuff of French-British
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The British press made sure to mention that Casta was only one
of 150,000 French citizens who had moved to Britain since 1995 _
presumably lured by less red tape and a tax rate that at 37.6
percent is the lowest in the European Union after Spain and
Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   The French, however, let it be known that the London subway was
crowded and dirty, apartment rents were high, and should the
21-year-old Casta fall ill, British hospitals would not be nearly
as fine as the French ones.
</P>
<P>
   The French newspaper Le Monde wondered why _ apart from money _
any sensible French person would ever move to England. The health
system is a disaster, the trains are barely any better, the unions
cannot protect their workers, and the poor are paid peanuts.
England is an exquisite paradise indeed, huffed the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could one doubt the fury of the Association of French
Mayors, which choose Casta to be Marianne, facing down a barrage of
criticism that the mostly male group was simply running a beauty
contest. Some critics had suggested that a more accomplished woman
should be chosen to represent the modern Marianne, a figure that
emerged from the French Revolution to symbolize the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Marianne _ a kind of Uncle Sam figure _ has
evolved from a 1794 version in which she is helmeted like a Greek
goddess to the flag-waving, rifle-toting revolutionary of 1830
depicted in Delacroix's ``Liberty Leading the People,'' to busts
modeled on Catherine Deneuve and Brigitte Bardot.
</P>
<P>
   Only last month, Casta appeared at the unveiling of the bust
based on her pouty good looks. But the news of her flirtation with
London had some French mayors swearing that her statue would never
appear in their city halls.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Paul Delevoye, the president of the 36,000-member mayors'
association, lashed out at her defection. ``All we can say is that
we hope everyone who has been formed in France, supported by
France, educated in France, will also decide to pay their taxes in
France,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With tax reform an issue before Parliament now, Casta's rented
apartment near Covent Gardens offered a soap box opposition
politicians could not resist. ``This symbolizes magnificently the
failure of socialism, which succeeds in chasing away all talented
people,'' proclaimed Patrick Devedjian, the spokesman for France's
Rally for the Republic party. ``The tax burden in France is
suffocating.''
</P>
<P>
   After several days of silence, Casta on Tuesday denied that she
was making London her primary residence, though tax experts
estimated that she could cut her tax bill by 30 percent to 40
percent by doing so. France taxes models much more than other
countries because they are classified as salaried employees of
modeling agencies rather than freelancers.
</P>
<P>
   Her agent issued a statement saying: ``In reply to the false
information that has appeared in certain European media this
weekend, we are keen to re-establish the truth over a certain
number of errors.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement added that Casta ``does not plan to buy an
apartment in London'' and ``has not decided to settle there for tax
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 0944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
