<HEADER>
A5845 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTA     04-08 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: JOEL BRINKLEY  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATO Finally Catches One
</P>
<P>
   The accused war criminal Momcilo Krajisnik was arrested at his
parents' Bosnian home by French NATO troops and flown to the
international tribunal in The Hague, where he pleaded not guilty to
war crimes for his role in Serbia's ethnic cleansing campaign in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik, a close ally of the Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic, is considered the most important war crimes suspect yet
captured by NATO, which has been criticized for not pursuing more
aggressively those responsible for the atrocities committed in the
Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
said of Krajisnik's capture, ``This is possibly the most important
day since the Dayton agreement on Bosnia,'' which ended the war in
1995. Krajisnik, 55, faces a maximum sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Incredible Is Testable, But in Another Dimension
</P>
<P>
   Superstring theorists have a problem: You can't test a theory
that posits that all matter consists of ``notes'' produced by tiny
strings vibrating in nine-dimensional space. We aware of only three
dimensions because the rest are curled up into extremely tiny
balls, a hundred million trillion times smaller than a proton.
</P>
<P>
   But Lisa Randall of Princeton University, Raman Sundrum of
Stanford University and Joseph Lykken of the Fermi National
Accelerator Laboratory have proposed that at least one of the extra
dimensions is actually a four-dimensional megaverse inside which
the universe floats like a bubble. They believe that energy might
occasionally leak into the fourth dimension _ and that idea might
be testable.
</P>
<P>
   When two particles are slammed together in an accelerator, the
amount of energy going into the reaction should equal the amount
coming out.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, energy could be leaking into the fourth
dimension. Scientists are searching records of past accelerator
experiments for signs of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe a discovery of extra dimensions is already sitting on a
tape in some data bank,'' Lykken said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By GEORGE JOHNSON
</P>
<P>
   A Friend of Ours Writes
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker magazine was renowned for attempting to verify
every fact it published. In a recent book on the magazine, however,
onetime staff writer Renata Adler announced without proof that the
late Judge John Sirica was ``corrupt,'' ``dishonest'' and had
``clear ties to organized crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Sirica, who presided over the Watergate burglary trial, which
ultimately led to the resignation of President Richard Nixon in
1974, was widely regarded as a scrupulously honest jurist.
</P>
<P>
   Adler told a New York Times reporter that she would publish
proof of her charge when she pleased. Meanwhile, John Dean, former
Nixon counsel, suggested Adler might have been misled by G. Gordon
Liddy, whom Sirica sentenced to prison for his role in Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Goods
</P>
<P>
   Border guards in the former Soviet republic of Uzbekistan seized
a radioactive cargo on an Iranian truck bound for Pakistan, said
State Department officials. The material, found in 10 lead
containers about the size of a thick briefcase, was being tested by
officials in neighboring Kazakhstan, where it originated, to see if
it could have been used to make a nuclear weapon. Pakistan has a
history of smuggling nuclear components, and is believed to have
built about a dozen warheads.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TIM WEINER
</P>
<P>
   Whose Life Is It, Anyway?
</P>
<P>
   No one should be forced to be a parent, according to a ruling by
the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court concerning the fate of
frozen embryos created by a couple with fertility problems. After
the couple divorced, the 44-year-old former wife wanted to use the
embryos for one last try at getting pregnant, but the ex-husband
objected, though he had earlier signed consent forms saying she
could have the embryos.
</P>
<P>
   In the third such dispute over embryos to reach a state supreme
court _ and likely not the last, given the estimated 150,000 frozen
embryos nationwide _ the Massachusetts court said that, despite the
contract, it would be bad public policy to coerce parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   The Coup That Fell to Earth
</P>
<P>
   Nawaz Sharif, ousted by a military coup last October from his
position as Pakistan's prime minister, was convicted of hijacking a
commercial airliner. He was sentenced to life imprisonment and
ordered to forfeit all his personal property. Six co-defendants
were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's hijacking was a peculiar one in that he didn't take
over an airplane. Rather, he ordered that a Karachi-bound plane be
refused permission to land, even though it was running low on fuel.
The plane carried 198 passengers, including Gen. Pervez Musharraf,
who would depose Sharif later in the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Red Faces in High Places
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army, already battered in recent years by sexual
misconduct scandals, was jolted again with the disclosure that a
general accused of sexual harassment by the Army's highest-ranking
woman was appointed last August to be the service's deputy
inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the officer, Maj. Gen. Larry G. Smith,
prompted Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy, the Army's first woman to earn
three stars, to lodge a formal complaint against him.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said she was concerned that he would be responsible
for investigating accusations of wrongdoing, including sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
</TEXT>
