<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A CYBER FINAL FOUR MIGHT SETTLE EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that our forum is off and running at the mouth, just a click
away on your e-mail dial (TheLipsite(AT)aol.com), your only excuse
for not participating is the continuing confusion over college
sports: Is it professional, semiprofessional, amateur? Are these
labels without meaning? Why should we care?
</P>
<P>
   As more colleges go online with their courses, the ultimate
Final Four may be played among great cyberuniversities, several of
which will probably be spun out of the Microsoft breakup. When a
kid from Gates Tech who grew up in a home without a laptop wins
most valuable player, we'll know that the old-school values held.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Fogel Yeager, who was one of TheLipsite's first
respondents, is definitely old school. By e-mail, she says: ``In my
dreamworld students would go to college and then try out for the
team. Many high school students I know don't even know that Duke or
Georgetown are colleges _ they think that's just a team name.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeager identifies herself as ``an avid sports fan (except when
Dick Vitale is broadcasting),'' who thinks ``greedy players,
coaches, TV, sporting goods manufacturers, etc., are dominating the
system'' and the ``NCAA, NFL, NBA, NHL, etc., need to take back the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   You're right, Ms. Y, but aren't those groups the ones who gave
(at least part of) the game away during their greedy snarfle at the
trough?
</P>
<P>
   A mailer called Pagresti writes: ``All the stories I read over
the past four weeks mentioned how good the basketball players were
and how exciting the games were, but I never read about how the
student-athletes keep up with their studies when they are on the
road playing basketball for several weeks at a time. Do they get
tutoring? When do they go to school to keep up with the other
students? Or do they even go to classes? What do the college
presidents say about going to school, or is schooling just another
annoyance that the basketball players have to tolerate when they
are playing these games?''
</P>
<P>
   This should encourage the Drake Group, that band of tenured
desperadoes who met in Des Moines last October in a remarkable
conference organized by Professor Jon Ericson of Drake University.
Among the many notable academics in attendance were William
Dowling, a founder of the Rutgers 1000, which is devoted to
de-emphasizing sports at the university; Andrew Zimbalist of Smith
College, the noted demystifier of sports economics; and Murray
Sperber, Indiana University's antidote to Coach Bob Knight.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest manifesto from the prairie, the Drake Group calls
for the end of athletic scholarships and the term
``student-athlete'' (it's one or the other). The group wants sports
controlled by the faculty senate rather than the athletic
department. It is demanding full disclosure of all academic aspects
_ tutors, course load, choice of major, graduation rates _ of a
team and of athletes, except for individual grades.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the Drakes (they are mostly males, after all)
is in their bold challenge to a corrupt system run by their bosses,
the college presidents. Coaches may make the headlines and the
shoe-contract money, but they are ultimately dependent on the
talents of teen-agers; meanwhile, the presidents perk on, whether
or not the athletes win, whether or not the students learn. The
Drakes are also bucking the sad complicity of their colleagues. Too
many teachers roll over for coaches. Some are intimidated, others
are fans, many just love to rub around in the testosterone pools of
the jock culture.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of testosterone, the social, cultural, political and
physical powers of that manly hormone were celebrated in an
absorbing article in The New York Times Magazine last Sunday by
Andrew Sullivan, who also poses questions for sports. How can women
consider competing in most games with men when that most profound
distinction, testosterone production, can never be equalized
without making women into men? Sullivan adds, ``Even more
unsettling is the racial gap in testosterone.'' He cites scientific
studies that show black men have 3 to 19 percent more testosterone
than white men. He wonders if that could be the reason black men
dominate certain sports.
</P>
<P>
   If white men can't jump, they can do androstenedione, a legal
supplement that boosts the hormone pumpers. Mark McGwire set the
home run record on andro in 1998, although he says he has stopped.
Lately, feeling righteous, McGwire criticized Major League Baseball
for opening the season in Japan. He said it was a money-grubbing
tactic not in the best interests of the pastime.
</P>
<P>
   A reader, Jothar, comments to TheLipsite: ``For Mark McGwire to
turn down a trip to Japan because it was just about money is
absurd. Since its inception, professional baseball was all about
money. This Japan trip is merely a new twist in the sport's
relentless pursuit of Mammon. Fifty years from now, we'll be waxing
nostalgic about the very first advertising patches to be featured
on major league uniforms, and it will involve our very own Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
