<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE OLD MASTERS ASSESS TIGER WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ If the old masters of art include Michelangelo,
da Vinci, Raphael, Rembrandt, Rubens and Van Dyck, the old masters
of the Masters include Nicklaus, Palmer, Player, Snead, Nelson and
Watson. And as those old masters wandered Augusta National this
weekend, each was asked the same question:
</P>
<P>
   What is the one most impressive factor in the success of golf's
young master, Tiger Woods? ``His ability to make himself do
something when he needs to; that's the mark of a champion,'' Jack
Nicklaus said, alluding to Woods' flair for the theatrical. ``When
you have to do something, he does it.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Saturday's third round of this Masters began, the
24-year-old Woods had to do something different, for him: get in
contention.
</P>
<P>
   With a three-over-par 147 for 36 holes, the world's No. 1 player
was nine strokes off the lead, the most he has trailed at the
halfway mark of a PGA Tour event this year. At the Nissan Open in
Los Angeles he was five strokes behind at the halfway mark before
finishing tied for 18th. In his six other tournaments, he won three
and finished second in three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way Tiger has played the last eight months is
better than I've ever played in a particular period,'' Nicklaus
said. ``If he continues to do what he's doing, he'll break all my
records; sure he will. But there's an awful lot of things that need
to happen that that depends on. His health. His desire to want to
play. And who else is going to come along.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a couple more Tiger Woods that are about 15 years
old right now. You just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Player also warned that Woods' eventual rivals might be
mere youngsters somewhere now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're building bionic men,'' Player said. ``You'll find a
man like Michael Jordan who comes out with the same flair Tiger has
and hits it 50 yards past Tiger. We haven't seen the start of it.
There's never been a man out here built like Michael Jordan who has
a flair for the game. Watch out when that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But that man might not possess what Player describes as the
``passion'' Woods has for golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of guys have Tiger's ability, like Ernie Els,'' Player
said, referring to his fellow South African who has won two U.S.
Open titles. ``But they don't have that passion that Tiger has. And
if you watch Tiger playing these finesse shots over traps and out
of the rough, he's scoring because of his great short game and his
great putting, not just his long game.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer had a different perspective. ``I'll take Tiger's
length,'' Palmer said. ``What impresses me the most about Tiger is
his strength as he applies it to his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods applies that strength with a swing that's not much
different from the swing that Sam Snead, now 87, saw when he was
playing an exhibition in the Los Angeles area in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up walks Tiger, he was 6, and his dad, who asked if Tiger
could play two holes with me,'' Snead said. ``He had that swing
then. He gets that thing through there. When he first came out on
the tour, he had only one fault. From 135, 145, he'd hit it over
the green sometimes. Now he hits a knockdown shot there. He's by
far the best player today. And you watch him swing. That right arm
stays straight down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   But what's the one most impressive thing?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't deny him any putt,'' Snead said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson preferred to cite an intangible aspect of Woods'
success in already winning 18 times on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``His desire to be the best ever,'' Watson said. ``That's there
and he backs it up.''
</P>
<P>
   With six consecutive victories on the PGA Tour recently, Woods
was linked to Byron Nelson's record 11 straight in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the champions dinner here every year, I'm the emcee,'' the
88-year-old Nelson said. ``When I got up to start it Tuesday night,
I said, `I want to thank Tiger Woods for making today's young
people know what I did 55 years ago.' He just looked up at me and
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to answer your question, what impresses me the most about
him is the fact that, as good as he is as the golfer who's
considered the best player in the world and maybe the best ever,
yet he's still not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all his wealth, he still has the drive, he still has the
desire to play golf as well as he can. I just admire the way he
carries himself, but in a way, I feel sorry for him. Back when I
played well, I had about one-thousandth of the attention he's
getting.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if he doesn't win here this year, Tiger Woods will
still be getting that attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one Tiger Woods,'' Jack Nicklaus said. ``Not only
what he's done by his record but how he has handled himself and how
he's played and the way he overpowers a golf course. He has no
weaknesses in his golf game. He's an amazing young man.''
</P>
<P>
   As the old masters of the Masters agree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
