<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      04-08 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Redskins Control Future of the NFL East
</P>
<P>
   When the Washington Redskins officials and scouts gather for
their draft meetings, there is almost a giddy feeling in the room.
That is because they know what every other team knows: The Redskins
will control the direction of the National Football League draft
next Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins own the second and third overall picks, which
almost guarantees that they will get a good player unless they make
a trade. The draft is an imprecise science, and it is possible the
Redskins could make a bad pick with one of those early selections.
But the chances of the Redskins _ especially with a skilled talent
evaluator like Vinny Cerrato running their draft _ picking two
consecutive busts are extremely low.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Redskins are in an enviable position. They already
have a team loaded with talent, and now they have the opportunity
to draft at least one of the Penn State stars in defensive lineman
Courtney Brown and linebacker LaVar Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   There are some in the league who believe that the Cleveland
Browns, who have the first pick, might still draft wide receiver
Peter Warrick of Florida State, despite their somewhat public
souring on the player. That would leave Washington the chance to
pick Arrington and Brown, a coup of major proportions and one that
could change the balance of power in the National Football
Conference East for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Washington does, whether they trade one of their picks,
or use both of them, will determine what the rest of us do in the
first round on draft day,'' one NFC general manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is flirting with the idea of trading its third pick
to the Jets as part of a deal for wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson.
Several personnel executives say that would be a mistake for the
Redskins because Johnson could potentially ruin their salary-cap
situation, and also because the team has a chance to get two
players who could help turn around the team's poor defense.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington has been compared to Lawrence Taylor, an overblown
parallel to be certain, but not completely outrageous since
Arrington has displayed the same kind of athleticism that Taylor
did. Brown might be the next Bruce Smith.
</P>
<P>
   If the Redskins could somehow get both players, which is a
possibility, they would improve their defense dramatically. Johnson
could help an already explosive Redskins offense only so much.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not an easy decision. The Redskins definitely have
some tough choices to make. Surely, however, every team wishes they
had Washington's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Way a Giants' Concern
</P>
<P>
   Giants fullback Charles Way, one of the most professional
players in football, continues to have serious problems with his
injured right knee. In fact, the difficulties are so serious that
they could affect his career.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the Giants are almost certain to draft a running
back.
</P>
<P>
   Way recently had cartilage from a cadaver transplanted into his
knee to make it sturdier. While amateur athletes and nonathletes
have undergone this procedure, it has rarely been attempted with
professional football players.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery was considered a success, but Way has been
experienced some difficulty, and he was scheduled to have
arthroscopic surgery this month to clean up other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Way is entering only his sixth NFL season, but according to a
league official he has been told by the team's medical staff that
his knee problems could significantly shorten his career. The
Giants are so concerned about Way that Coach Jim Fassel has been
told he must use Way sparingly in training camp and maybe during
the season. There is a small chance that Way could be forced to
retire after this coming season.
</P>
<P>
   If his knee does not hold up, the team will look to his backup,
Greg Comella.
</P>
<P>
   Blank Seeks New Pact
</P>
<P>
   Brad Blank, the agent for Giants guard Ron Stone, has contacted
the team about renegotiating the lineman's contract. Blank and
General Manager Ernie Accorsi will most likely speak after the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Stone has two years remaining on his contract, but he wants to
become the highest-paid guard in the league. That would mean that
the team would have to pay him around $4 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   Stone will not hold out if he does not get a new deal before the
season because his agent and the Giants have a friendly
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Burress Upsets Eagles
</P>
<P>
   Teams are attempting to screen bad apples from their draft
boards and will continue to do so in the days leading to the draft.
The Denver Broncos have removed more than 10 players with troubled
pasts from their board, and other teams are believed to have done
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Yet teams can go too far in this pursuit of the flawless athlete
_ there is no better example of this than what is happening to wide
receiver Plaxico Burress of Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Burress' stock has quietly, but rapidly, fallen in recent days.
Just last month he was projected by many teams as a top-10 pick.
Now, he could fall into the middle of the first round, or lower,
because of rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Burress claims the problem started with the Philadelphia Eagles.
He rescheduled a visit with the team once Michigan State made it to
the National Collegiate Athletic Association men's basketball
championship game; Burress wanted to attend the game since some of
his close friends are on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Other NFL teams Burress was scheduled to visit around the same
time, including the Jets, simply made another appointment with
Burress. The Eagles, however, remained upset, and canceled the
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Burress claims, soon after that, a whispering campaign
began that he possessed a bad attitude. Other rumors followed _
which Burress claims are not true. In fact, one team executive
said, as far as he can tell, Burress has no documented off-field
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have I done to people for them to say this type of stuff
about me?'' Burress said. ``I have never had any on-the-field or
off-the-field problems. I don't hang around people that are
troublemakers.''
</P>
<P>
   His situation shows there may be some innocent victims who are
swept up in the league's attempt to clean up its image.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is telling the difference between a player like
Burress, and someone who is guilty of serious indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler Working Out
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hostetler, the former Oakland Raiders and Giants
quarterback, continues to work out in West Virginia awaiting
another chance to play professional football. Hostetler is still
good enough to play backup for a team, maybe even start, which
makes one wonder why teams pass on him, but continue to go for
longtime busts like Rick Mirer ... The XFL _ the World Wrestling
Federation's new league _ is successfully recruiting players from
the Canadian Football League and the Arena Football League. But
what will the quality of football be like? ... Look for Kent
Graham, the former Giants quarterback who is with Pittsburgh
backing up Kordell Stewart, to be starting by the fourth or fifth
game if Stewart has a slow start. The Steelers plan to have a quick
hook ... The National Football League Players Association continues
to build its strike war chest, just in case the amicable
relationship that exists between the owners and the players breaks
down when the collective-bargaining agreement expires four years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
