<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Caruso, Javier Valentin and Brett Tomko spent the past two
seasons in the major leagues. All have started this season in the
minor leagues. So have Joe McEwing, Jason Johnson, Chad Allen and
Doug Mientkiewicz. All thought they had left the minors behind, but
it is back to buses and fast-food dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a very humbling game,'' McEwing said. ``It can come
up and bite you any time.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwing, who can play nearly anywhere on the field, spent seven
seasons all over the minors, then finally won a job with St. Louis
last season. He played 152 games and batted a respectable .275.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Cardinals traded him to the Mets during spring
training, it was a setback. The Mets needed a backup shortstop, and
they felt he was Kurt Abbott, not McEwing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things you can't control,'' McEwing said, speaking
on the telephone in the Norfolk Tides' clubhouse. The trade and the
results for him were among those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to worry about it because it's only negative
thoughts,'' the 27-year-old McEwing added. ``I was shocked in the
beginning, but that's because I spent nine years in the Cardinal
organization. But I'm happy to be a Met. Sometime during the year,
I want to be a piece of the puzzle and help that team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Caruso was the Chicago White Sox' starting shortstop for two
years, vaulting to the majors from Class A at the age of 20. But he
played poorly defensively, and his offensive production plummeted
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple years ago, Ozzie Guillen had slipped and we didn't
have a shortstop ready,'' Ron Schueler, the White Sox general
manager, said. ``Mike played very well in spring training. We
pushed him and he responded and had a heck of a year. Like any
other 20-year-old kid, he went home and didn't do anything, didn't
get stronger. When he came back, he wasn't ready. He had a bad
year, and we had to go out and get someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Valentin, Javier's older brother, is the White Sox
shortstop now. Caruso is playing for the Charlotte Knights in Class
AAA, a level where Caruso had never played.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was a little angry, because I was told I had a
chance to compete for the spot,'' Caruso said. ``I prepared myself
for that during the winter. I felt I had a good spring. I did the
things I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Caruso said he initially felt he was taking a step backward but
decided, ``I don't have time to think about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to work hard here not just to get back to the big
leagues but to prove to myself that I can have a good year,'' he
said. ``I have to work on my skills and hope they get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Schueler hopes for a rapid return. ``If he went down with the
attitude he had this spring, he'll be back real quick,'' the
general manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was in Baltimore's pitching rotation for 21 starts
last season (8-7, 5.46 earned run average), could also be back in
the majors before long.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a typical young pitcher,'' Syd Thrift, the Orioles' chief
of baseball operations, said of the 26-year-old right-hander. ``I'm
not sure if he was trying too hard or what he was really doing, but
he had one real good outing against the Mets and the rest of the
time he was erratic with his command.''
</P>
<P>
   What Johnson was doing in spring training was ``working on
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told I had a job as one of the starters so I was working
on stuff,'' he said from Scranton, Pa., where Rochester opened the
International League season. ``I was competing, but not as
intensely. I just took it too lightly. I plan on doing well my
first three or four starts and getting out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomko, who went to Seattle when Ken Griffey Jr. moved to
Cincinnati, had already had experience returning to the minors. The
Reds sent him there for the first half of last year. He arrived in
camp this spring with an Achilles problem, could not get in enough
innings and wound up No. 6 in a five-man rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners very likely will bring him back if one of their
starters encounters a problem or they want to bolster their
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling when, or if, the Minnesota Twins' trio of
Allen, Mientkiewicz and Valentin will be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some things happen here last year that looked like we
were progressing,'' Terry Ryan, the Twins' general manager, said.
``Then things fell apart in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen was the team's starting left fielder last season,
Mientkiewicz the primary first baseman and Valentin a platooned
catcher who was in line to replace the retired Terry Steinbach as
the regular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I announced the first day of spring training that most of the
positions are open here,'' Manager Tom Kelly said. ``Out of
necessity last year a number of young players were given an
opportunity. That doesn't mean that same opportunity is there, that
we're going to hand you a job. Ryan brought in people to compete
for the positions. That's what it ended up, a pretty good
competition for us where we had to do some picking instead of
handing. I think a few of the fellows thought they were locked in
despite the warnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said Allen had a poor spring and was outplayed ``by every
outfielder we had in camp.'' Valentin and Mientkiewicz, he said,
probably should have been given more learning time in the minors
before being brought to the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably did those fellows a disservice,'' Kelly said.
``But out of necessity, we did what we had to do. You feel a little
bad about it, but that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Homer Happy
</P>
<P>
   Looking for early signs of the season? How about the new trend
in home runs? In the first days of the season, hitters have not
been content with hitting one home run in a game; two seems to be a
better number.
</P>
<P>
   In the first five days of the season (not counting the two days
in Japan), 15 players hit a pair of home runs in a game. In the
corresponding period last season, only four players whacked two in
the same game.
</P>
<P>
   Those four players all did it in the National League; five
hitters performed the feat last week in the NL. The American League
last year had none in that time; this year 10 (through Friday
night) players have deposited the ball over the fence twice,
including two pairs of teammates, each pair doing it in the same
game and both pairs doing it on opening day: Tony Batista and
Shannon Stewart of Toronto and Ivan Rodriguez and Gabe Kapler of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to make realistic projections, but if hitters
keep lighting it up, the home run total will rise again this
season. Last year, home runs increased 9 percent _ from 5,064 to
5,528 _ over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   You Can Call Them Johnson
</P>
<P>
   The development will not make any record books, but for the
first time in major league history, three catchers named Johnson
started on opening day last week: Charles Johnson for Baltimore,
Brian Johnson for Kansas City and Mark Johnson for the Chicago
White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   As common a name as Johnson is, very few Johnsons have been
major league catchers. Other than this season's three, baseball
encyclopedias show only six others who caught in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   One was Elmer, who caught in 11 games for the New York Giants in
1914; that was the extent of his major league career. Another was
Ron, who caught two games for Kansas City in 1983; he played in
only 20 other games over three seasons. Larry caught in nine games
for three teams in a 12-game career over five seasons in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby was a catcher in 81 games of his 98-game career in three
seasons with Texas in the early '80s. Darrell, who would manage the
Boston Red Sox to the 1975 World Series, played for seven teams in
six seasons in the '50s and '60s and caught in 124 games of his
134-game career.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Cliff, whose 179 games behind the plate were the
most any Johnson caught before Charles arrived in the majors. Cliff
is noteworthy this season for another reason.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yankees try to become the first team since the 1972-74
Oakland A's to win three successive World Series, it is recalled
that a major reason the Yankees did not get a chance for their
third straight 21 years ago was the clubhouse fight in April
between Johnson and Rich Gossage. Gossage, the Yankees'
irreplaceable closer, tore a ligament in his right thumb in the
fight and missed 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A Vote for Bagwell
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio, Houston's second baseman, bristles when he hears
people talk about how the National League Central has three great
home run hitters, Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one,'' Biggio said. ``His name's Bagwell. Except his
name doesn't get mentioned with those guys because he hasn't hit 50
home runs. That's really the sad thing about it. People have this
criteria when you hit 50 home runs you're a power hitter. What
people don't understand or don't care about is the Astrodome is the
biggest ballpark in the league. Baggy would be hitting 55, 60 a
year if he played in some of the other parks. If Baggy had played
in Seattle, he'd have as many home runs as Junior. I've seen him
hit so many long balls that fell short at the Astrodome.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell hit 115 home runs the past three years compared
with 193 for McGwire, 165 for Sosa and 160 for Griffey. But Bagwell
no longer has to contend with the Astrodome. This weekend the
Astros began playing in Enron Field, which promises to be
friendlier to hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how many home runs he hits this year in the new
park,'' Biggio said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
