<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0866 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CENSUS-REVIEW-APATHY-     04-08 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-REVIEW-APATHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN ABOUT THE COUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He had hoped it would be different. But as the
forms roll in _ or, more accurately, do not roll in _ Kenneth
Prewitt, director of the Census Bureau, is beginning to doubt that
he will meet his twin goals for the 2000 census: persuading 70
percent of Americans to return their forms, and sparking a new wave
of American civic engagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we end up at 61 percent, I would give a very good grade to
the Census Bureau,'' Prewitt said last week. ``But not a good grade
_ maybe a C _ for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But is the census a fair measure of the country turning inward?
Or are there other explanations for what appears to be public
apathy toward the decennial head count?
</P>
<P>
   The plummeting response rate to the census over the years _ from
83 percent in 1970, the first year that forms were sent by mail, to
65 percent in 1990 _ parallels a well-documented trend of voter
apathy.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, the purposes and procedures of voting are more clear;
the once-a-decade census is hardly habit-forming. Focus groups
conducted by the Census Bureau found that for most people, the
census is an obscure governmental function that they don't
understand. Nor do they have any sense that it benefits them.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Internet age, when the country is awash in anxiety
about the vulnerability of personal information, the census has
been caught in a web of privacy concerns. A vocal, mostly
conservative contingent has put forth sometimes Orwellian visions
of a government that cannot be trusted with any personal data.
</P>
<P>
   The main target of the criticism is the long form, with its 53
questions covering everything from income to plumbing, although
questions have arisen about the short form as well. About 48
percent of long forms have been returned so far this year, compared
with 57 percent by this time a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Senate passed a resolution sponsored by Robert
Smith of New Hampshire, a conservative Republican, that vowed
``that no American will be prosecuted, fined or in any way harassed
by the federal government or its agents for failure to respond to
any census questions which refer to an individual's race, national
origin, living conditions, personal habits or mental and/or
physical condition.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that citizens would be hauled into court in any
case. Still, the conservative Southeastern Legal Foundation has
offered to defend anyone prosecuted for such civil disobedience.
Its president, Matt Glavin, does not see the lack of participation
as a civic problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rise of concerns over privacy issues'' over the Internet
``and hackers getting into government and private databases _ that
in and of itself is an indication of civic involvement,'' Glavin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the census were taking place in a more conducive
environment, some scholars of American culture say the bureau would
still have trouble gaining the participation of the public. After
all, return rates for the census had been declining for three
decades, well before concerns about the Internet and privacy had
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Putnam, a professor of public policy at the John F.
Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University, places the
unwillingness to fill out census forms alongside the decline in
community bowling leagues, neighborhood bars and, of course, voting
_ all signs that Americans have become more alienated from, and
less caring about, one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big story is not political alienation or worries about
privacy,'' said Putnam, author of the forthcoming book ``Bowling
Alone: The Collapse and Revival of American Community'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster). ``We attend 60 percent fewer club meetings than we did a
generation ago. We go on 60 percent fewer picnics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that kind of community connectedness that is the
strongest predictor of how people respond to the census,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, officials estimated that 61 percent of households
would return the forms this year. But Prewitt had hoped the the
Census Bureau's $102 million advertising campaign would push the
response rate up to 70 percent. Now that seems unlikely. Given the
trends in American civic life, and the news, it may be more
surprising that the response rate is as high as it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
