<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, April 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-AMERICANISM (Paris) _ In Europe, experts say, there is a
growing backlash of anti-Americanism. More and more often,
Europeans talk about America as a menacing, even dangerous force
intent on remaking the world in its image. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-AFTERSHOCKS (Rozaje, Yugoslavia) _ A year ago, the
people of this little town took in tens of thousands of refugees
from the Serbian rampage through Kosovo. Today, the folk of Rozaje
have received little thanks for their open-armed welcome of Kosovo
Albanians. In fact, at least 10 inhabitants _ who, though mostly
Muslim, are Slavs _ have lost their lives in revenge attacks by
Albanians in Kosovo just because they spoke Serbian, instead of
Albanian. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECTION (Lima, Peru) _ For a decade, President Alberto
Fujimori has been Latin America's master of crisis management,
defeating terrorist insurrections, hyperinflation and drug
traffickers. But as 14 million voters decide on Sunday whether
these successes should translate into five more years in office,
Fujimori faces his most serious political crisis since he shut down
the Congress and Supreme Court at the height of the guerrilla war
in 1992. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-POLITICS (Maracaibo, Venezuela) _ For the second time
in two years, a former military officer vowing to dismantle a
corrupt and incompetent status quo has emerged to challenge
Venezuela's political establishment. This time, though, Hugo Chavez
is not the leader of the insurgency, but its main target _ and it
is one of his closest comrades in arms who is trying to drive him
from the presidency he has held for just 14 months. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA-OIL (Luanda, Angola) _ For decades, reality in Angola has
been ruled by the paradox of plenty. Angola's oil wealth has helped
to pay for an endless war between President Eduardo dos Santos and
his bitter foe, Jonas Savimbi, leader of the Unita rebels. That, in
turn, has meant poverty for almost all Angolans. If the paradox
holds, Angola is ripe for even more misery. Recent offshore
discoveries have made it one of the hottest oil-producing countries
in the world. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration is opposing
a proposal that would boost exports from the world's poorest and
most indebted nations, for fear that it would inflame sentiments
against imports in Congress and threaten some of President
Clinton's other international economic initiatives. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BANK-PROTESTS (Washington) _ Many of the people who
disrupted the Seattle meeting of the World Trade Organization are
reassembling in Washington this week, where they have identified as
their targets two older, richer and savvier agents of the global
economy: the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
Students, church groups, environmentalists, and labor unions, a few
of them planning to scale buildings and block traffic to make their
point, say they want to disrupt the spring meetings at the bank and
the fund. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-TECHNOLOGY (Berlin) _ Underfunded, state-run German
universities have been very slow to adapt their traditional
curricula to reflect the explosive growth of Internet-related
industries. As a result, in a country with more than 4 million
unemployed, there are an estimated 75,000 to 100,000 jobs vacant in
the booming Internet sector, with few Germans apparently qualified
to fill them. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE-ELECTION (Athens, Greece) _ For Greeks, their economy,
their standing in Europe, and even their tense relationship with
Turkey are better now than at any time since World War II. And it
is this new confidence that could form Socialist Prime Minister
Costas Simitis' biggest liability in what has shaped up to be an
extremely close race for re-election on Sunday against his
challenger, Costas Karamanlis, leader of the center-right New
Democracy Party. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS (Undated) _ They are not drunk or high on drugs.
They are not racists or Satanists. Most are white men, but a
surprising number are women, Asians and blacks. Many have college
degrees, but most are unemployed. Many are military veterans. That
is the profile of the 102 killers in 100 rampage attacks examined
by The New York Times in a computer-assisted study looking back
more than 50 years. First in a four-part series. By Ford Fessenden.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-INFO (Undated) _ A growing number of companies are
making medical information services available to their employees to
help them navigate through the mass of medical information
available today. These companies believe that their employees will
get better care, and they hope their workers will be less inclined
to proceed with treatments deemed not appropriate. Many companies
also view the added services as a way to attract and retain
employees. But in the longer run, many employers that offer the
added advice are also trying to prepare their employees for a shift
the companies hope to make toward a system of vouchers for medical
care. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-JANITORS-STRIKE (Los Angeles) _ In the 15 years Maria
Santania has worked as a janitor here, her pay has increased $2 an
hour, to $6.50. But her rent amounts to more than two weeks of her
salary before taxes. So on Friday, she joined thousands of striking
janitors _ police and union officials estimated a crowd of 3,000 _
marching down Wilshire Boulevard in search of a larger pay
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ADMISSIONS-POLICIES (Undated) _ The U.S. Commission on Civil
Rights plans this week to issue a harsh critique of policies in
Florida, Texas and California that have replaced affirmative action
with admission to public universities for the top graduates in
every high school in the state. A draft of the 10-page statement
notes that the programs' successes in bringing minorities to
campuses relies on the segregation of high schools, and that they
do nothing to diversify graduate and professional schools. By Jodi
Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   EARTH-DAY (Seattle) _ With 4,500 organizations planning events
in more than 180 countries, the 30th Earth Day is living up to its
name in a way that was not true for the first Earth Day, which was
largely a domestic affair. But if much has changed over the years
about Earth Day, one thing about this year's event is strikingly
similar to the original: Denis Hayes is leading the effort. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Developments in the Elian Gonzalez
case. By John Broder.
</P>
<P>
   SEQUOIA-PROTECT (Los Angeles) _ Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman has recommended that 355,000 acres of national forest be
given monument status to safeguard about half the giant sequoia
groves remaining in the United States. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SPRING-BREAK (Port Aransas, Texas) _ Out on the back porch
of Woody's bait stand, off the Gulf of Mexico, Johnny Mathews, a
fishing guide, flicks the foam from a cold beer and weighs in on
the topic of students on spring break: ``It's not that they're bad
people. They just don't know how to act like normal people.'' By
Ross E. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) _ This past winter, the Democratic
National Convention looked like a disaster in the making.
Fund-raising was behind schedule. The billionaire moguls who helped
lure the convention appeared to be bickering among themselves.
Finally, Mayor Richard J. Riordan ousted the head of the local host
committee and replaced her with a trusted deputy, then got on the
telephone and began dialing for dollars himself. Now, local and
Democratic Party officials say they are confident the convention
will be a worthy successor to the one that nominated John F.
Kennedy in 1960. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Another big year for women;
Crossing party lines and making enemies; A poll finds voters less
than excited; High gasoline prices as a campaign issue; Walking all
the way to the nomination. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REPUBS (Washington) _ A year after House Republicans spoke
glowingly of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas as a life raft who would
carry them to victory, congressional leaders and Bush aides have
scotched talk of a common legislative agenda and are pursuing
distinct electoral strategies of their own. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ American Beauty. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Rights of Bill Gates. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
