<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT     04-08 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTES AND NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pitino Promises to Revive Celtics
</P>
<P>
   He shot back at venomous fans earlier this season, reminding the
Boston Celtics faithful that neither Larry Bird nor Kevin McHale
would be soon walking through the arena door, that those days live
only in memory. Some of his players openly feuded in front of him
during a game late last month, and he strongly considered
suspending them before deciding against the move.
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight year, Rick Pitino maintains his passion
about returning a hallowed franchise to its former glory. And for
the third straight year, the Celtics are still a reclamation
project. They are not going to the playoffs again, fueling
speculation that Pitino will soon be working elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've found out anything, it's that the Celtics are the
Yankees of basketball,'' he said in a phone interview last
Thursday. ``The fans are not used to this. They should be unhappy.
I shouldn't be that surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, I look back, I had eight years in Kentucky where I
was treated better than most princes. I was coaching the Knicks and
we started selling out the Garden. In this business sometimes, you
just have to take the good with the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were making somewhat of a playoff push before
dropping nine straight games, a succession of last-second and
mostly competitive losses that took their toll.
</P>
<P>
   As the team president with final say on personnel matters,
Pitino insists he is not going anywhere until at least after next
season. Much of the reason stems from a belief that the team's
owner, Paul Gaston, refuses to buy out part of the $29 million
remaining on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three weeks ago, Pitino drove to Gaston's home and gave
him an alternative. ``I said, `Paul, if you feel at any point you
don't like the job we're doing, I'll go my own way and won't expect
to take your money with me,''' Pitino said he told Gaston.
``Instead of being negative, he was the direct opposite. Paul was
very excited about our future.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Celtics continue to falter next season, Pitino told
Gaston, he will surrender the balance of his seven-year, $50
million deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not turning the corner, I'd go to Paul and say, `You
have two choices,''' Pitino said. ```Blow up the team or you can
make a coaching change.'''
</P>
<P>
   Boston has done little but lose in the three weeks since his
meeting with Gaston. And while it appears Pitino will indeed remain
in charge, it would not be shocking if the Nets and other
franchises asked the Celtics for permission to speak with Pitino in
the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino attributes many of Boston's problems to an unlucky 1997
draft, in which the Celtics were nudged out for the first and
second picks in the lottery. Instead of Tim Duncan and Keith Van
Horn, they settled for Antoine Walker and Chauncey Billups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, unfortunately, the Ping-Pong balls determined my fate in
a way,'' Pitino said. ``You had a shot at 1-2. And you get 3 and 6.
But that's in the past. We've just had some unbelievably tough
losses lately. Buzzer-beater, buzzer-beater, double overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Pitino said he had no plans to return to
college, where he resurrected programs at Providence and Kentucky.
``I'm not packing in pro basketball,'' he said. ``If I'm done in
Boston, if it doesn't work out, I'll coach somewhere else. I have
not given up on the pro game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there are things I'm jaded about on the collegiate level.
The idea that kids are only staying for one and two years is
depressing. There are no stars at the collegiate level. They've all
gone to professional basketball. And the agents and AAU people are
infiltrating college ranks like you wouldn't believe.'' (The AAU is
the Amateur Athletic Union.)
</P>
<P>
   Pitino, 47, said he hoped to coach another six or seven years
and insisted that procuring another long-term multimillion-dollar
deal had nothing to do with his desire to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' he said, ``whoever said money can't buy you happiness
was a very wealthy man. But as coaches, winning is where we derive
our happiness. It's why most of us coach. This is not the way I
want to leave the Celtics, winning less than 40 games. We've still
got work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas in Demand to Coach
</P>
<P>
   Isiah Thomas is at least several weeks away from becoming a
National Basketball Association coach. The former Pistons great,
who has been mentioned as a possible candidate for jobs in Atlanta,
Indiana and Dallas, is one of the most sought-after commodities on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC analyst since giving up his stake in the Toronto Raptors,
Thomas has been itching to get back in the league. But a potential
conflict of interest may derail his plans. Before he works for an
NBA team, league officials want him to sell the Continental
Basketball Association, which Thomas bought last year. They cite a
provision of NBA bylaws prohibiting an employee from owning any
portion of another basketball league.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine. But you wonder why no similar fuss was made when
Michael Jordan decided to take over the Washington Wizards and cut
a deal for part ownership. Jordan's footwear and apparel company,
the Jordan Brand, employs players like Ray Allen, Eddie Jones and
Vin Baker, who appear in television and print advertising for the
products and have endorsement deals through the company, a Nike
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Were Allen a free agent and the Wizards had salary-cap room,
wouldn't he consider signing on with a person with whom he already
has a business relationship?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not even comparable,'' Russ Granik, the league's
deputy commissioner, said. ``There is a clear provision regarding
employees owning pieces of other leagues. I just don't see a
connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is staying mum on the issue, saying only, ``I think the
time is right for the NBA, the players association, the NCAA and
the CBA _ as the leaders in the basketball community _ come
together and help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the Pacers and the Hawks seem more interested
than the Mavericks. Thomas bought property in Atlanta last year to
build a house, but said the decision had ``nothing to do with the
Atlanta Hawks or anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think half the NBA lives in Atlanta,'' he said. ``Damon
Stoudamire just told me he was buying a place down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's Role
</P>
<P>
   It is not only Rasheed Wallace's fault. Many of his Portland
teammates are also to blame for the late-season meltdown of the
Trail Blazers, the league's most highly compensated and talented
team.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, as the Trail Blazers' lone All-Star, Wallace
inherits a leadership role. And on a relatively leaderless team,
you can't afford one of your most talented players to be the most
combustible.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Wallace earned two technical fouls milliseconds
apart, setting a record for technical fouls in a season with 34,
and an automatic ejection. Wallace surpassed the mark of 32
technicals by Charles Barkley in 1992-93 and 1994-95 with Phoenix
and tied by Dennis Rodman in 1993-94 with San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who has been ejected six times this season, earned his
35th technical on Thursday night in a dismal loss to Vancouver. He
has told teammates he will not lose his composure in the playoffs.
But he told some of them more than a month ago he would tone down
his incessant complaining.
</P>
<P>
   As the probable third-seeded team in the Western Conference,
Portland is looking at a first-round matchup with Minnesota or
perhaps San Antonio. On talent alone, the Blazers could get past
the Timberwolves and maybe the Spurs, wear down a possible
second-round opponent like Utah with their depth and meet the
Lakers in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   That would take mental toughness, a quality neither Wallace nor
his teammates possess at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
