<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Sunday, April 9. The N.Y. Times News Service supervisor is
Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ The Clinton Administration is opposing
a proposal that would boost exports from the world's poorest and
most indebted nations, for fear that it would inflame sentiments
against imports in Congress and threaten some of President
Clinton's other international economic initiatives. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-AMERICANISM (Paris) _ In Europe, experts say, there is a
growing backlash of anti-Americanism. More and more often,
Europeans talk about America as a menacing, even dangerous force
intent on remaking the world in its image. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS (Undated) _ They are not drunk or high on drugs.
They are not racists or Satanists. Most are white men, but a
surprising number are women, Asians and blacks. Many have college
degrees, but most are unemployed. Many are military veterans. That
is the profile of the 102 killers in 100 rampage attacks examined
by The New York Times in a computer-assisted study looking back
more than 50 years. First in a four-part series. By Ford Fessenden.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-INFO (Undated) _ A growing number of companies are
making medical information services available to their employees to
help them navigate through the mass of medical information
available today. These companies believe that their employees will
get better care, and they hope their workers will be less inclined
to proceed with treatments deemed not appropriate. Many companies
also view the added services as a way to attract and retain
employees. But in the longer run, many employers that offer the
added advice are also trying to prepare their employees for a shift
the companies hope to make toward a system of vouchers for medical
care. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REPUBS (Washington) _ A year after House Republicans spoke
glowingly of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas as a life raft who would
carry them to victory, congressional leaders and Bush aides have
scotched talk of a common legislative agenda and are pursuing
distinct electoral strategies of their own. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-AFTERSHOCKS (Rozaje, Yugoslavia) _ A year ago, the
people of this little town took in tens of thousands of refugees
from the Serbian rampage through Kosovo. Today, the folk of Rozaje
have received little thanks for their open-armed welcome of Kosovo
Albanians. In fact, at least 10 inhabitants _ who, though mostly
Muslim, are Slavs _ have lost their lives in revenge attacks by
Albanians in Kosovo just because they spoke Serbian, instead of
Albanian. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-ABORTION-ANNIVERSARY (Albany, N.Y.) _ To one side, it was an
epochal breakthrough. To the other, it felt like the end of
civilization. It stunned nearly everyone, and its tiniest details
remain etched in the players' memories. Thirty years ago this week,
New York state legalized abortion, adopting what was the most
liberal law in the country, three years before the Supreme Court
made abortion legal nationwide. By Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
