<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 9, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-PSYCHODRUGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Are toddlers being plied
with Prozac, Ritalin and other powerful drugs for minor behavioral
problems? A recent study that documented an acute increase in the
prescription of psychiatric medications for preschoolers would
suggest that. Some mental health professionals have painted young
children as the latest victims of a culture obsessed with syndromes
and disorders. And politicians have seized the opportunity to
condemn the ``overmedicating'' of the nation's youngest citizens.
By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-REVIEW (Undated) _ Since 1995, when the
government chronicle of Microsoft's predatory war on Internet
innovators begins, PCs have become less expensive and more
sophisticated. The industry has generated growth, jobs and wealth.
So why was this costly and sweeping antitrust suit filed against
Microsoft? To enforce the law and to support innovation. And the
latter reason marks what may be an important step in how government
and courts deal with the Internet economy in the future. By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-APATHY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Does the American public's
growing lack of responsiveness to census questionnaires, which
parallels the falling rate of voting, represent a decline in a
sense of community or civic engagement? Is it a sign that Americans
have become more alienated from and less caring about each other?
Is it a fair measure of the a country turning inward? And to what
extent is the privacy issue, in this first census of the Internet
age, a factor? By Steven Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-CUBANS-REVIEW (Miami) _ A look at the Cuban diaspora: this
city of exiles has never been known for restraint and moderation;
there are too many people drinking too much Cuban coffee, too many
conspiracies to untangle, too much frustration bottled up for too
many years. Ever since the Cuban exodus started 40 years ago, Miami
has been a place apart, a city floating in some sort of ether,
removed from the rest of the country. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   GENEALOGY-DNA-REVIEW (Undated) _ Oxford Ancestors has applied
for a patent on the idea of deriving surnames from DNA. The
company's founder, Dr. Bryan Sykes, is a geneticist who has made an
intriguing discovery about English surnames: Many of them once had
a single bearer. Sykes, who analyzes DNA to track ancient
population changes, tries to trace the origins of his own surname.
By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   MARGIN-MANIA-REVIEW (New York) _ A comparison of stock market in
the 1920s and the present shows some similarities and some
differences. Now, as then, the Fed has been trying to tighten
credit by raising interest rates but has seen stock prices soar as
more and more money has been borrowed to buy shares. Margin debt is
now rising faster than it ever did in the 1920s. By Floyd Norris.
WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   DICAPRIO-CLINTON-REVIEW (Washington) _ What Leonardo DiCaprio's
interview with President Clinton about global warming might be
like. By John. B. Kenney.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-IMAGE-REVIEW (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Uganda has been groping
for explanations for the mass killings, and alongside
sensationalism in the press there has been a remarkably frank
discussion of the roots of the problem and a tracing of the current
religiosity and mysticism associated with cults to the despair left
by years of dictatorship, poverty, AIDS and other diseases. The
press discussion reveals much about how far Uganda has come in its
four tortured decades of independence, through a brutal
dictatorship and at last toward a society where open expression is
recognized as a tool for solving the nation's problems. By Ian
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS-REVIEW (Tokyo) _ For all the attention
surrounding the stroke that toppled Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi,
the change at the nominal helm of the country has little real
import. The Japanese people have long been aware of a reality that
the rest of the world has yet to realize: Political leadership has
always been more irrelevant in Japan than in other countries. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-FRANCE-REVIEW (Paris) _ On both sides of the English
Channel, the treachery made the front pages. After she was chosen
as the model for the bust of Marianne, France's curvaceous national
symbol, Laetitia Casta rhapsodized about the benefits of living in
London. The young supermodel spoke of a diverse, lively city. But
everyone else suspected tax benefits, setting off a political
fistfight among French politicians and a cross-channel flow of
snide remarks that are so often the stuff of French-British
relations. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
