<HEADLINE>
SPRING 2000 IS MARRYING SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER HAMM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The busiest, most jam-packed wedding season began
this weekend, and renewed interest in tying the knot _ coupled with
a desire to marry in the first year of the millennium _ could make
this a record-breaking wedding year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is crazy. It's nuts. So many people are getting
married,'' said Kelli Koerner, an event planner who delayed her own
wedding until next year to avoid the rush. ``If people want to get
married this year, they are going to have a hard time coordinating
things.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, the prospect of being a millennial bride has proved
irresistible. Brides say they like they way 2000 looks on the
invitations and napkins, while bridegrooms say it will just be
easier to remember the number of anniversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get married in 2000,'' said Mindy Herrera, a
20-year-old Burbank, Calif., resident. ``It sounded good. There's a
lot of stuff you can buy that says 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers aren't in yet, but experts like Antonia Van der
Meer, executive editor at Modern Bride magazine, are predicting a
record year for nuptials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big year both for getting engaged and getting married
because it's the year 2000,'' said Van der Meer. ``It has a nice
ring to it. It makes a wonderful date to have on your wedding
invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wedding boutiques, reception halls, bakers and ministers
throughout the suburban San Fernando Valley are feeling the
pressure. They've been slammed with calls since the first week of
January. And, with the unpredictable weather of January through
March over, the season of love begins now.
</P>
<P>
   At the Church of the Valley in suburban Van Nuys, the schedule
for Minister Steve Borgard has gotten so crowded, he performed one
wedding last week on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been busy,'' said Borgard. ``There's no doubt about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Herrera is busy with last-minute details now that her wedding is
just two weeks away. She and her fiance, Chad Tewksbury, also 20,
started planning the ceremony seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was smart to plan before the major rush began, say wedding
planners at the Pickwick Center for events in Burbank. They can
schedule up to four weddings on Saturdays and are booked solid
until early October, said Koerner, who plans events at Pickwick
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Romero, who will have her reception at Pickwick in June,
started planning last summer, but it quickly turned into a
headache, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every place I looked was already booked,'' said Romero, 27.
``I thought maybe it had to do with the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Margie Ann Taylor-Black, minister at the
nondenominational Encino Community Church says marriage is just
``back in vogue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone the full cycle and now it's back in,'' she said.
``It seems as though the new millennium is embracing some of the
old virtues.''
</P>
<P>
   It will, however, take more than a one-year surge to reverse the
declining marriage rate. Nationwide, marriage was at its lowest
point in recorded history last year, according to a 1999 Rutgers
University study. The National Marriage Project found that over the
last 40 years, marriage rates have dropped 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Young people who grew up in a ``divorce revolution era'' have
become pessimistic about marriage, said David Popenoe, professor of
sociology at Rutgers University and co-director of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men are stalling. The women can't wait,'' Popenoe said.
``You have this bad dating scene in the 20s.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of those surveyed for the study said a happy,
healthy marriage is a priority. This could indicate marriage rates
could increase, the study concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger generations may decide that they want to have more of
a marriage culture than the baby boomers did,'' said Popenoe.
``There are some signs in the data that things are improving.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles County, the number of marriage licenses issued
was down in the first two months of this year compared with 1999.
But officials believe many of this season's brides haven't picked
up their marriage license yet because the documents are only valid
for 90 days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Taylor-Black said more people are interested in a deeper
commitment than couples of years past. Men are more involved with
the wedding plans, many want to write their own vows and they are
serious about having children, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the guys who've been pushing to the weddings,'' said
Taylor-Black. ``There is a new breed of man who is at the marrying
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Men like Loren Thall, who was scheduled to be married by
Taylor-Black. The 29-year-old Los Angeles resident said he's always
looked for a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Thall and his bride, Holly Mociler, met nearly a decade ago on
Catalina Island. After dating briefly and breaking up, the couple
got back together a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found someone. I figured, here it is, right in front of me.
I've got to go for it,'' said Thall, a mortgage banker. ``She was a
friend and a lover. There was no reason to look any further.''
</P>
<P>
   After Helen Romero hoped for years that she would marry high
school sweetheart Lupe Sandoval, he finally proposed. Sandoval
surprised her with an evening at the Biltmore Hotel, where Romero
had always dreamed of staying.
</P>
<P>
   Sandoval guided a blindfolded Romero into a room, where she was
immediately overwhelmed by the smell of fresh flowers. He told her
everything he loved about her while she remained blindfolded.
</P>
<P>
   As he was talking, Romero thought, ``This is it. This is the one
thing I've been waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sandoval removed the blindfold, Romero found herself
surrounded by scores of white flowers. She looked at the glass
table in front of her, where Sandoval had written, ``Marry Me
Helen'' in white rose pedals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just cried,'' said Romero. ``I was in disbelief. That was
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
