<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-REPUBS-ART-970(2     04-08 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REPUBS-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BUSH AURA DIMS, HOUSE REPUBLICANS RUN ON THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year after House Republicans spoke glowingly of
Gov. George W. Bush as a life raft who would carry them to victory,
congressional leaders and Bush aides have scotched talk of a common
legislative agenda and are pursuing distinct electoral strategies
of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans who once flocked to endorse the Texas
governor, sometimes sight unseen, now say that after the bitter
primary fight they have come to realize that Bush is a weaker
candidate than they once had hoped for. And they recognize that
they will have to run on their own accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the overwhelming 15 to 16 points ahead that he was,''
said Rep. Brian Bilbray, R-Calif., who holds one of the most
historically competitive House seats.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bilbray added that Bush, who is running neck and neck in
the polls with Vice President Al Gore, was far better at the top of
the ticket than recent Republican presidential contenders. ``Just
being able to break even is a great advantage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas M. Davis, III of Virginia, the chairman of the
National Republican Congressional Committee, said: ``Our guys are
not afraid to run with Governor Bush. He's going to be far stronger
than Dole was and his dad was. Even if the polls are equal, that's
8 points better than Bob Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is hardly the kind of praise that Bush was hearing last
June when he journeyed to Washington to meet about 100 Republican
lawmakers. ``He's really got the magic,'' Rep. Jennifer Dunn of
Washington said then.
</P>
<P>
   Just as House Republicans are charting their own course, the
Bush campaign has made a tactical decision that it does not want to
march in lock step with the Republican-run Congress, trying to push
through a common legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers say that this is partly because yoking Bush to
Congress would hamper his efforts to present himself as a different
kind of Republican. They also say it would be a recipe for failure,
since any Bush proposal that Republicans tried to enact as
legislation would become an inviting political target for
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``To take Bush's education plan and introduce it into Congress
today is simply an invitation for every Democrat to vote no,'' said
an aide to Bush. ``Our focus is on developing an agenda that is
capable of being passed by the Congress on Jan. 1, 2001 because of
the mandate in the election.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is that the Bush campaign and congressional
Republicans have settled into an information-sharing relationship,
with each running on generally harmonious yet distinct platforms.
For instance, in contrast to Bush's sweeping tax-cut proposal,
Congress' tax cuts would be bite-sized and designed to be provide
popular relief for particular problems.
</P>
<P>
   There is frequent contact between senior Bush advisers and
senior Republicans. Bush's policy team often reaches out to
congressional experts. And the Republican National Committee has
recently started a weekly conference call between Bush aides and
Republican press secretaries across Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But this is far from the kind of direction and coordination that
many House Republicans, in particular, once envisioned when they
thought that their agenda would be shaped in Austin, Texas. ``We
are not coordinating,'' said Rep. Roy Blunt of Missouri, the chief
deputy House whip who is Bush's liaison in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's job for the next few months is to let
Americans know who he is as a person, the success he's had as the
governor of Texas and most importantly cast a vision of what he'd
like to do as president,'' Blunt said. ``Our job is to get our work
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans say they are comfortable with the evolving
relationship, arguing that there is broad enough agreement on
general themes to allow Republicans to meld their messages come
autumn, when Congress is no longer in session.
</P>
<P>
   They say they also understand the advantage to keeping Bush free
from every controversy in Congress, particularly as the annual
battle over spending and tax cuts reaches its peak in September.
``A lot of what we have to deal with would be total baggage for
anybody running for president of the United States,'' said Sen.
Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., who is Bush's chief liaison in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But others say they are deeply troubled by the lack of stronger
coordination and consider the Austin-based Bush campaign too
insular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is pulling together what needs to be pulled together,''
said one Republican senator who spoke on condition that he not be
identified. ``The presidential and Republican congressional agendas
have to be bolted together here, and every day that goes by is a
squandered day.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``You can't have a Republican nominee, a Republican
House, a Republican Senate and a Republican National Committee not
moving in the same way at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats, too, have their own points of
divergence with their nominee. Gore drew the ire of numerous
Democrats when he broke with President Clinton on the case of Elian
Gonzalez. And whether to grant China normal trade relations sharply
divides the party, with many House Democrats opposed to Gore's free
trade stance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in contrast to the Republicans, House and Senate
Democrats have been working closely with Gore on a common agenda
and strategy for more than a year, ever since Rep. Dick Gephardt,
the minority leader from Missouri, dropped his own presidential bid
to fight for control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats have rarely missed an opportunity to try to
highlight differences between congressional Republicans and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday they forced a vote in the Senate on whether to enact
Bush's tax-cut plan as part of this budget cycle. The vote was 99-0
against it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0919 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-REPUBS-ART-NYT &LR;      04-08 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REPUBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: against it.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the Bush campaign has had a delicate balancing
act to follow in its relations with the Congress. Last year Bush
aggressively sought to lock up endorsements from House and Senate
members as a way of diminishing primary challengers and adding to
his aura of the inevitable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he tried to maintain some distance, since his
theme of compassionate conservatism is implicitly a contrast to the
sharp-edged kind of conservatism practiced by former Speaker Newt
Gingrich. When Bush made his visit to Congress last June, he
managed to sidestep any picture with the House Republican
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   And he drew the ire of some Republicans last fall when he
criticized a Republican proposal to reduce tax credits for the
working poor as an example of balancing the budget ``on the backs
of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of the anger that caused, one Bush adviser recently
noted that the governor's highest standing in the opinion polls
came just after that blowup. The adviser said it was better for
Bush to ``float above the fray'' in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger turnabout in attitude has come in Congress,
particularly in the House. The degree of coattails a presidential
candidate will carry is often overstated. But the early expectation
among House Republicans that they could rely on Bush underscores
how much they had pinned their hopes on his candidacy and how
uncertain they were about their own abilities to function with a
razor-thin majority.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Republicans say, they have more self-confidence, more faith
in their own leadership and they are more realistic about Bush's
ability to carry them into office.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, chairman of the House
Republican conference, showed colleagues a poll indicating that
Bush would not carry coattails for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of the House have woken up to the fact that we have to
win these races on our own,'' said Rep. Rob Portman, an Ohio
Republican close to the Bush campaign. He called this a ``positive
evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate Republicans say that they decided on their own
agenda over the winter, even before the bitter primary battle
between Bush and Sen. John McCain was in full swing. They agreed to
focus their campaign on a series of smaller tax cuts, on shoring up
the Social Security system, improving national security, supporting
more local control of education and fighting crime and drugs. In
addition, lawmakers up for re-election are being urged to run
localized races, not to hope for a national wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coattail elections are pretty rare,'' said Sen. Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky, the chairman of the National Republican
Senatorial Committee. He said that even when Bush's poll numbers
were ``unrealistically high'' he had been telling candidates ``that
this didn't smell like any kind of coattail year to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been counseling our candidates that races were going to
be won or lost state by state,'' McConnell said. ``Senators who win
will be ones who custom craft their races the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Blunt, Bush's House liaison, was dismissive of some of the
Republican nervousness about how strongly their nominee will run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people in Washington spent all of last year
overestimating George W. Bush, and today they are underestimating
him as a candidate,'' Blunt said. ``In politics, it's always better
to be underestimated than overestimated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
