<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0932 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MEDICAL-INFO-ART-2TAK     04-08 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-INFO-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS SEEK NEW ROUTE TO CUTTING HEALTH COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ariz., Calif., Mich. S.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a 15-minute office visit in February 1999, a cardiologist
told the parents of Dominic Fernandez, 3, that he needed open heart
surgery and a possible heart transplant _ ``right now, or he will
not survive through the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just overwhelmed,'' said Beverly Fernandez, a
warehouse manager for Honeywell. Her son was still recovering from
surgery he had undergone nine months earlier for congenital heart
problems. ``I wanted to know more about transplants'' and the
alternatives, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She called Consumer's Medical Resource Inc. in Duxbury, Mass., a
medical information service available through her employer. A
physician and a researcher listened to her account for an hour.
Within the week, she received packets of medical journal articles
and books on heart transplants, including success and failure
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved because she felt better informed, she got a second
opinion from another cardiologist who recommended monitoring
Dominic for six months. After additional repair surgery _ no
transplant _ eight weeks ago, her son, now 4, is ``doing
wonderfully,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of companies are adding specialized services
like Honeywell's to help their employees navigate through the mass
of medical information available today, from advertisements for
prescription medicine to pitches for doctors and hospitals in
magazines, books, television and online.
</P>
<P>
   These companies believe that their employees will get better
care, and they hope their workers will be less inclined to proceed
with treatments deemed not appropriate. Employers hope to save
money at a time when health costs are rising 9 percent or more a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies also view the added services as a way to attract
and retain employees at a time when workers are scarce. The new
services may reduce absenteeism as well. ``It is clear to us that
productivity is linked to good health,'' said Sue Nelson, a senior
benefits executive at Texas Instruments.
</P>
<P>
   But in the longer run, many employers that offer the added
advice are also trying to prepare their employees for a shift the
companies hope to make toward a system of vouchers for medical
care. In such a system, employees would receive a set amount of
money, rather than a promise of benefits, to cover their health
care needs, and they would need advice on selecting the best care
in order to manage for themselves. The new offerings are partly
designed to accustom employees to seeking out medical information
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The firms that provide information are careful to direct
questioners to consult their own doctors on new information they
obtain, thus avoiding legal liability. But health care legal
experts said lawsuits were always at least a remote possibility for
the companies _ and for the employers paying for their services.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William M. Sage, a health law expert at the Columbia
University law school, said that providing information ``would be
pretty safe from a liability perspective'' in most cases. But he
said lawyers might try to pin liability on ``an employer or other
purveyor of information that has a financial interest in what the
recipient does with the information.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Altman, director of the Schneider Health Policy Institute
at Brandeis University, said: ``It can't be bad to provide more
information to people. Ultimately, most people would just ask their
doctors more intelligent and tougher questions.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added: ``What it will do for the quality and cost of
health care is an open question. I think it will raise costs but
improve the quality by directing people to better quality providers
of care.''
</P>
<P>
   Some workers can get information from prestigious medical
centers. Employees of a dozen big companies can get feedback _
often advice to ``see your doctor'' or ``go immediately to a
hospital emergency room'' _ 24 hours a day, from doctors and nurses
at the Mayo Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   At Consumer's Medical Resource, the company working with
Honeywell, the doctors, like many in the Boston area, are
affiliated with Harvard Medical School. ``We don't give advice, we
listen and summarize and send the most up-to-date medical and
practical information,'' said Dr. Maureen Tierney, the company's
medical director.
</P>
<P>
   Employers pay about $1.35 per employee per month to sign up with
Consumer's Medical Resource.
</P>
<P>
   But Brian Marcotte, vice president of benefits at Honeywell,
said the company had saved $2.80 for every $1 it spent on the
program. He said that of 41 Honeywell employees who had called
Consumer's Medical Resource, 10 had changed doctors; three had
identified incorrect diagnoses, including one misdiagnosis of
Parkinson's disease; three had halted questionable treatments; and
12 had eliminated or reduced side effects by changing a treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies offer rewards to employees who answer questions
about their health status in questionnaires that are processed by
outside firms. Companies like Staywell Inc., recently acquired by
Havas MediMedia, and Optum, a unit of the UnitedHealth Group, then
follow up by offering recommendations and reminders for those with
chronic conditions like diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mayo Clinic is testing the effectiveness of such
recommendations with 4,000 employees of Lucent, Texas Instruments
and Intel. Mayo also publishes an offshoot of its widely circulated
health newsletter for employees at these companies as well as
Dow-Corning and General Mills.
</P>
<P>
   In part, employers are contending with a managed care system
designed to hold down costs, in which many doctors see more
patients for shorter consultations. ``There doesn't appear to be
enough time in that office visit,'' said Nelson of Texas
Instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the patient more involved is so critical right now,''
added Dr. Lawrence G. Shoner, vice president of health services at
Lucent. ``Physicians are running so hard and so fast now, that to
give the patient more information is a way to assure the best
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Many companies that are offering the extra advice are also
planning for harder times ahead when employees may no longer be in
short supply. That is when these companies hope to introduce
``defined contributions,'' or vouchers, that employees would use to
purchase their own health care. The companies would like to stop
providing relatively open-ended coverage, which keeps getting more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Employees ``need to have more financial stake in it,'' Marcotte
of Honeywell said. ``If we can give employees the information,
tools'' and money, he said, ``they will make the right decisions''
about obtaining care.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Benefits managers at big companies like Honeywell and Lucent say
they would still provide employees with information to help them
select an appropriate health plan, and continue company-paid
insurance against the huge expenses of a catastrophic illness.
</P>
<P>
   But defined health benefits, or vouchers, are controversial.
When a Xerox executive seemed to be endorsing the idea last year,
irate employees and health care economists attacked it as a retreat
from employer-provided health care. Xerox quickly backed off. Many
large employers are ``champing at the bit to make the transition to
defined contributions, but reticent to move first,'' said Gary
Ahlquist, senior vice president of the Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton
consulting firm. ``The risk of alienating employees in a high
employment economy is just too high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even those amenable to health care vouchers argue that consumers
need to be properly equipped for such a system. ``Who is going to
help consumers so they don't get raped and pillaged in the
process?'' asked Regina Herzlinger, a Harvard Business School
professor who studies the role of consumers in shaping health care.
She argues that government should require health care providers to
disclose information on their competency. Companies like Honeywell
are providing the added access to medical information themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are offering more than just simple information.
HealthAllies, based in Scottsdale, Ariz., negotiates discounts for
individuals for procedures like plastic surgery, fertility programs
and laser eye surgery that are often not covered by health plans.
CareCounsel, based in San Rafael, Calif., helps consumers clear up
administrative problems with their health plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees are suspicious and mistrustful of managed care and
the health insurance industry,'' said Larry Gelb, president of
CareCounsel.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``People say to themselves, `Why would the insurance company
really care whether I make the best decision?' when the bottom line
is profit or cost containment,'' said David Hines, president of
Consumer's Medical Resource. (Services like his typically promise
confidentiality, so that employers do not know which employees are
seeking help.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry is well aware of such problems. A
number of HMOs are now adding programs to help consumers understand
their choices, said Susan Pisano, a spokeswoman for the American
Association of Health Plans, a managed care trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put the consumer at the center of the system and
empower her with information and access,'' said Dr. David Lawrence,
chief executive of Kaiser Permanente, the California-based
nonprofit HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser plans to spend $2 billion by 2003 on computerized and
Internet services for its 8 million members. Soon, they will be
able to sit next to their doctors in front of a computer display of
their personal health records and discuss them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Blue Cross plans in Michigan, New Jersey and South Carolina are
testing an Internet service that will include medical advice and
support forums with health care experts. The project is being
developed by Franklin Health Inc. with collaboration from IBM and
units of Intel and Reuters. ``We know we need to do business
differently,'' said Maureen Sullivan, a senior vice president of
national Blue Cross and Blue Shield.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers appear to be hungry for added medical advice. They are
eagerly responding to drug company advertising. And at least 60
million people visit Internet health sites each year, according to
Harris Interactive, a research firm. But ``many Web sites are a
mile wide and an inch deep,'' Herzlinger said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, anyone can get a few facts about a doctor or health
plan on thehealthpages.com.
</P>
<P>
   But some 45 companies offer an enhanced version of what is
publicly available, providing information like the credentials of
doctors and hospitals in their networks.
</P>
<P>
   For a fee, consumers can also look for doctors' names on
BestDoctors.com, or on Guidetotopdoctors.org.
</P>
<P>
   A few employers pay so that their employees can have access to
those sites without charge. But such lists of recommended doctors
can be incomplete or biased by the physicians who help compile
them, said Dr. Jerome Groopman, a professor at the Harvard Medical
School.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
