<HEADER>
A0959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GREECE-ELECTION-NYT &LR;      04-08 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREECE-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIMES COULD BURDEN INCUMBENT PREMIER IN GREEK VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ For Greeks, their economy, their standing in
Europe and even their tense relationship with Turkey are better now
than at any time since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   And it is this new confidence that could be the biggest
liability for Costas Simitis, the Socialist prime minister, in what
has shaped up to be an extremely close race for re-election Sunday
against his challenger, Costas Karamanlis, leader of the
center-right New Democracy Party.
</P>
<P>
   While Greek voters may be more or less satisfied with Simitis
and his party, Pasok, those who are weary of the Socialists' long
lock on power and secure enough now to look for change, may be
tempted to take a risk and select a fresh, if untested, face,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters are making up their minds on something that is not
discussed in public and cannot actually be done at the polls,''
said Thanos Veremis, a political analyst who heads a foreign policy
research group in Athens. ``How to change the government without
getting rid of Simitis? Greeks are happy with him, but they are
tired of the Pasok party's rule and the corruption that comes with
longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice is made more tempting still by the closeness of the
candidates economic and foreign policy platforms. Both espouse the
same fundamental choices for Greece _ cooperation with the United
States and other NATO allies, and cautious rapprochement with
Turkey and fiscal restraint to meet prerequisites for membership in
the European Union's joint currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign itself has focused on unemployment, health care,
schools and the feverishly volatile Greek stock market, which
boomed last year but has since plummeted, enraging small-time
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Pasok has held power since 1981, except for 1990-1993. Elected
in 1996, Simitis, 64, quickly shed the welfare state policies and
passionately anti-American rhetoric of his flamboyant predecessor,
Andreas Papandreou.
</P>
<P>
   Like Prime Minister Tony Blair in Britain, he moved his party
toward the center. Two years ago, the Greek economy fell
embarrassingly short of the minimum standards for the euro. Greece
has since caught up, cutting inflation, public debt and interest
rates and stabilizing the drachma, and it is almost certain to be
included to use the euro next January.
</P>
<P>
   That success could work against Simitis, since he called early
elections on the grounds that Greece needed a stable, experienced
government to lead it to the euro. Greeks already believe that has
been done.
</P>
<P>
   Karamanlis, 43, a lawyer who studied foreign policy in the
United States and is fluent in English, does not suggest he would
do differently, just better. ``We are the authentic expression of a
European orientation,'' he said at a campaign rally at the Olympic
Stadium in Athens on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He complained when Greece supported Turkey's effort to be
considered for membership in the European Union, saying the
government had failed to wring enough concessions from Turkey. But
those nationalist sentiments seem mainly aimed at garnering votes.
He assured American academics at a private lunch last year at his
alma mater, the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy in Boston,
that Turkey belonged in Europe, using the same pragmatic language
as the Greek foreign minister, George Papandreou.
</P>
<P>
   During the NATO bombing campaign in Kosovo, which was fiercely
opposed by almost all Greeks, New Democracy again sought to tap
into popular sentiment by fiercely denouncing the United States and
its allies, at times echoing the rhetoric of Greece's small,
hard-line Communist party. But few in Greece believe that if
Karamanlis were elected, he would reverse the current government's
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Karamanlis, who has spent his career in New Democracy party
politics, is mostly counting on voters' thirst for change. But his
chief credential is his lineage as the nephew and namesake of
Konstantinos Karamanlis, the founder of New Democracy and a
legendary former president and prime minister who coaxed the
European Union to accept Greek membership in 1981, six years ahead
of Spain or Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of polarizing policy disputes has forced a curious
reversal of roles _ Simitis campaigned as a capitalist while
Karamanlis moved left, portraying himself as the champion of labor
unions, farmers and other constituencies usually claimed by
Socialist parties. But his chances mainly rest on whether voters
will trust him to competently execute policies Simitis pushed
through.
</P>
<P>
   Many have not yet made up their minds. ``I will decide at the
last minute,'' Maria Christodulakou, 36, a schoolteacher in Sparta,
said Saturday. ``They do not really differ,'' she explained. ``I
don't think there is a big risk if either man is elected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
