<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0961 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-ABORTION-ANNIVERSA     04-08 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-ANNIVERSARY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30 YEARS AFTER NEW YORK LEGALIZED ABORTION, POLITICIANS OF THE TIME
REFLECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y _ To one side, it was an epochal breakthrough for
women's rights. To the other, it felt like the end of civilization.
A defining political and cultural event, it stunned nearly
everyone, and its tiniest details remain etched in the players'
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago this week, New York state legalized abortion,
adopting what was the most liberal law in the country, three years
before the Supreme Court made abortion legal nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The state's decision turned on dramatic, hard-to-predict
legislative votes and tactical errors by abortion opponents. It was
decided by the last-minute change of a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   New York had a Republican governor then, Nelson Rockefeller, and
Republicans controlled both houses of the Legislature. Of the 207
legislators, just four were women.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving supporters of that 1970 bill will celebrate the
anniversary on Tuesday at the Yale Club in New York City, at a
reception sponsored by the National Abortion and Reproductive
Rights Action League, known as NARAL. Their adversaries plan no
gathering, but are acutely aware of the date.
</P>
<P>
   By 1970, a few states had carved limited exceptions out of what
was essentially a nationwide ban on abortion. A few weeks before
New York's Legislature acted, Hawaii approved the nation's first
broad legalization, but it applied only to Hawaii residents.
</P>
<P>
   New York was second, and its law went farther since it imposed
no residency requirement. In the first two years, 60 percent of
women having abortions in New York were from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, Assemblyman Percy Sutton of Manhattan
introduced New York's first bill to loosen the prohibition. In
1967, 1968 and 1969, the Assembly defeated bills by Assemblyman
Albert Blumenthal of Manhattan to permit abortion under very
limited circumstances. The third vote was the closest, 78-69.
</P>
<P>
   But before 1970, the Republican Senate majority leader, Earl
Brydges of Niagara Falls, a staunch abortion opponent, would not
allow a vote in his house.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews this week, some of the surviving participants
shared their memories of the legalization debate:
</P>
<P>
   John J. Marchi, a Republican state senator from Staten Island:
</P>
<P>
   ``Abortion had barely entered into the public dialogue. I
remember attending the (New York state) Constitutional Convention
of 1967, and there wasn't a single bill on the subject, nor was
there any advocacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Manfred Ohrenstein, a former Democratic state senator from
Manhattan:
</P>
<P>
   ``We were living in a time of enormous change. There was the
war. There was the women's movement, which was really bringing the
abortion issue to a crescendo. It was the end of the civil rights
era, and we viewed this as a civil right. In '65, we had repealed
the death penalty, which people thought was impossible. There was a
sense that extraordinary things were possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lader, then chairman of what was then called the
National Association for Repeal of Abortion Laws:
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just formed NARAL, in February 1969 at a meeting in
Chicago. We decided at that first meeting to concentrate on New
York state as our breakthrough state. We felt that New York
represented our best opportunity, and we knew that other states
often looked to New York as setting an example. So we set up tables
and gathered petitions in key districts in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Shack, then an organizer with the New York Civil
Liberties Union, now president of the board of NARAL:
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign to change the law was largely run by men, which
really tells you about that time. And people forget that back then,
a big part of the argument was about economics. Women with money
could get abortions. They could pay doctors to do them, or they
could go to Puerto Rico or to another country. Poor women, on the
other hand, were dying in droves from unsafe abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael R. Long, chairman of the New York State Conservative
Party:
</P>
<P>
   ``Abortion was a nonissue up until then. The party wasn't even
united on it then, because nobody had given it much thought. We
first put a pro-life plank in the party platform in 1968, and we
had a big internal fight about it. Nobody _ and I mean nobody _
expected this to become a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Constance Cook, a former Republican assemblywoman from Ithaca:
</P>
<P>
   ``I followed Al Blumenthal's bills with great interest, but a
Democrat really couldn't get a bill passed in those days, with the
Republicans in control. So in '69, Franz Leichter and I sponsored a
bill for a full-fledged repeal, and we did it again in 1970.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Clinton Dominick III, a former Republican state senator from
Newburgh:
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Blumenthal and Fred Ohrenstein came up with the strategy of
doing it first in the Senate. The Senate was perceived to be the
more conservative house, and they thought if the Senate passed it,
that would improve the chances in the Assembly. So Fred Ohrenstein
came to me and said, `Would you be a sponsor?' I told Fred, `Only
if you get a bunch of other Republicans to be co-sponsors.' A
couple of days later, he came back to me and said the only other
Republican who would be a sponsor was Roy Goodman. But I said OK,
anyway. And then Fred said they decided that it would be best to
have a Republican as the prime sponsor. So without my doing much of
anything, I became the prime sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren M. Anderson, a former Republican state senator from
Binghamton, later the majority leader:
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't all that much lobbying on it, and especially not
against it. The big groups that have formed around this issue over
the last 30 years barely even existed then.''
</P>
<P>
   Long:
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really gear up over it because we didn't think it
would pass. It came rather fast, and it even took the church by
surprise, because their main concern was the aid for schools. I
remember a lot of us being kind of angry at the cardinal (Cardinal
Terence Cooke) and the bishops for not doing more, that if they had
all gone to Albany, it would have changed the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Lader:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic Church was caught off guard. They didn't think we
had a chance, so they were really not that loud on the subject
until the end. The church was really focused on a bill for state
aid to parochial schools. The other strategic error was by Earl
Brydges, in letting it come to a vote. There were bills to create
limited allowances for abortion, but Brydges made sure that what
came to a vote was a bill for out-and-out pure repeal, full
legalization, no restrictions. A lot of his colleagues said it was
a ploy on his part, because he thought the more liberal the bill,
the more likely it would be defeated, and that would put an end to
it. He just miscalculated.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson:
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I don't know why Earl allowed a vote. Generally,
he was pretty forthright about what he was up to, but this was one
he kept to himself. I was as close to him as anyone in the
Legislature, and I don't know what he was thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy M. Goodman, a Republican state senator from Manhattan:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most fascinating debate we've ever had in the
Senate, because the outcome was really unclear, and furthermore it
struck me as likely that some minds might change. It was a very
tense thing. I remember I studied for literally days, looking into
the embryology of the fetus, preparing for the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchi:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a cliffhanger, and a number of people unexpectedly
voted in favor of it. I wasn't persuaded that we had lost until we
had the roll-call vote. I was in disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 18, 1970, the Senate was packed. The debate took more
than five hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``From those of us opposing this bill, I hear a buoyancy and a
luminous debate,'' Marchi said in the floor debate. ``But from
those on the other side I hear plaintiveness and anguish. And it
must be this way, for we are for life and they are against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said: ``The present abortion law encourages butchery. We
torture the fetus and we allow them to be born in stunted and
twisted form. This law presses down unmercifully on the poor. Is
this equality under God?''
</P>
<P>
   Several senators had refused to say in advance how they would
vote, and even as the roll call began, the result was unclear.
Brydges spoke last, his voice gravelly and slow. ``I have a deep,
real, abiding conviction that this is the wrong way for the state
to go,'' he said, ``because we are a bellwether state, and many
other states will follow our lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The tally was 31 for, 26 against. Thirteen Republicans and 18
Democrats voted for the bill; 20 Republicans and 6 Democrats voted
against.
</P>
<P>
   Ohrenstein:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was the majority leader of the Senate, a very powerful
man, a respected man, Earl Brydges, a very orthodox Catholic, and
he got up and made a speech, practically in tears, and he was
heartsick. He could have stopped it, but he said that he wasn't
going to stand in the way of the majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman:
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt him tremendously that the vote worked out the way it
did. When it was over he slumped into his chair and just dissolved
in tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Lader:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate vote set the Catholic Church off, and then they
really started to put pressure on the Assembly members. They had
children at parochial schools write letters to Assembly members.
Cardinal Cooke had a pastoral letter read in every church. When it
came to a vote, there were nuns and priests walking the floor of
the Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook:
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Senate vote, we amended the bill in the Assembly
because it had no restrictions at all, and we didn't think that had
a very good chance of passing. So we made it unrestricted abortion
up to 24 weeks, and after that only for the life of the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Franz S. Leichter, a former state senator who was then a
Democratic Assemblyman from Manhattan:
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the first vote (on March 30) and it was 73 for to 70
against. But we needed 76 votes, an absolute majority of the house,
for it to pass. That certainly cast a pall and made us very
apprehensive, but we agreed to table it and try to bring it up a
second time (on April 9) ... People were really torn, as a matter
of conscience and as a matter of politics. People who had voted yes
the first time voted no, and people who had voted no the first time
voted yes. I spent 30 years in the Legislature, and it was one of
maybe 20 times that I saw a bill come to floor where you really
just didn't know what was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through an agonizing roll call, Assemblyman George M.
Michaels, a Democrat from a conservative, heavily Catholic, central
New York district, quietly voted no.
</P>
<P>
   The count ended at 74-74. One Assembly member was absent.
Speaker Perry B. Duryea Jr., a Long Island Republican, did not
vote, in keeping with tradition that the speaker votes only if it
would affect the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Before the clerk could say ``record the vote'' and bring it to a
close, Michaels stood and asked to be recognized. At first he
rambled, his voice thick and trembling, and it was unclear where he
was headed. But heads turned when he said his constituents would
``condemn me for what I am about to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my sons just called me a whore for the vote I cast
against this,'' he said. Another son had told him, ``Dad, for God's
sake, don't let your vote be the vote that defeats this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully appreciate that this is the termination of my
political career,'' Michaels said. ``But Mr. Speaker, I must have
some peace in my family. And I therefore request you, Mr. Speaker,
to change my negative vote to an affirmative vote.''
</P>
<P>
   He crumpled into his seat and buried his face in his hands, as
bedlam swallowed the chamber. Supporters of the bill whooped,
opponents shouted ``No!'' and people on both sides wept. An
adversary screamed epithets at Michaels. Blumenthal kissed his
forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Duryea cast the final ``aye'' vote, making it 76-73. Voting yes
were 46 Democrats and 30 Republicans. Voting no were 24 Democrats
and 49 Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the Senate passed the Assembly version of the
bill, 31-26. The day after that, April 11, Rockefeller signed it
into law. ``The wives of the Senate and the Assembly put this bill
through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In that year's elections, Michaels, Dominick and a handful of
others who supported the bill lost to anti-abortion challengers.
Michaels died in 1992 at age 80.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, the Legislature voted to repeal the 1970 law, but
Rockefeller vetoed it. In January 1973, the Supreme Court made its
landmark ruling in Roe vs. Wade, patterned in part on the New York
law.
</P>
<P>
   Cook:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really have a sense at that time that we had done
something momentous, though it was long overdue. Looking back now,
it seems like a bigger deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Long:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to look back and see how the New York
Republicans have tended to remain a moderate party, while the
national Republicans have moved to the right on abortion and other
issues. Look at George Pataki and Rudy Giuliani, who are both on
the opposite side from us on this issue. The Republicans in New
York actually have a pro-choice plank in their platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchi:
</P>
<P>
   ``Abortion has become fairly automatic. It's a tragedy. I don't
think you're going to have total elimination of it, but I think you
will see a gradual evolution of measures against it. I would say
this and capital punishment are the worst things the Legislature
has done in my time here.''
</P>
<P>
   Shack:
</P>
<P>
   ``This was absolutely the most important thing I ever did. We
knew that nothing would ever be the same again. We knew that we
were changing the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
