<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0982 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RAMPAGE-KILLERS-ABRID     04-08 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMPAGE-KILLERS-ABRIDGED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY THREATEN, SEETHE AND UNHINGE , THEN THEY KILL IN QUANTITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Calif., Mass., Texas, Md., Hawaii, Ga.)  (Eds.: With RAMPAGE-KILLERS-STUDENTS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FORD FESSENDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are not drunk or high on drugs. They are not racists or
Satanists, or addicted to violent video games, movies or music.
</P>
<P>
   Most are white men, but a surprising number are women, Asians
and blacks. Many have college degrees, but most are unemployed.
Many are military veterans.
</P>
<P>
   They give lots of warning and even tell people explicitly what
they plan to do. They carry semiautomatic weapons they have
obtained easily and, in most cases, legally.
</P>
<P>
   They do not try to get away. In the end, half turn their guns on
themselves or are shot dead by others. They not only want to kill,
they also want to die.
</P>
<P>
   That is the profile of the 102 killers in 100 rampage attacks
examined by The New York Times in a computer-assisted study looking
back more than 50 years and including the shootings in 1999 at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. Four hundred twenty-five
people were killed and 510 people were injured in the attacks. The
database, which primarily focused on cases in the last decade, is
believed to be the largest ever compiled on this phenomenon in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Though the attacks are rare when compared with other American
murders, they have provoked an intense national discussion about
crime, education and American culture. The Times found, however,
that the debate may have largely overlooked a critical issue: At
least half of the killers showed signs of serious mental health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was most intense last year, which began with echoes
of gunfire in a Salt Lake City television station in January and
ended with seven Honolulu office workers dead in November. In
between there was a berserk rampage by an Atlanta day trader that
left 12 dead and 13 injured. A self-styled fascist attacked a Los
Angeles day care center. Seven people died as a hymn ended in a
Fort Worth church.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most shocking were the shootings by two Columbine
High students who burst into classrooms and killed 13 and wounded
23.
 &UR;  &LR; While many possible causes have been cited, including violent
video games, a decline in moral values and the easy availability of
guns, there has been little serious study of this explosive
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Times analysis included only rampage homicides _
multiple-victim killings that were not primarily domestic or
connected to a robbery or gang. Serial killers were not included.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ While the killings have caused many people to point to violent
aspects of culture, there is little evidence that video games,
movies or television encouraged many attacks. In only six of the
100 cases did the killers have a known interest in violent video
games. Seven others were interested in violent movies.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a decade that had a sharp decrease in homicides, the
incidence of rampage killings appears to have increased, FBI data
show. Still, these killings remain extremely rare, much less than 1
percent of all homicides.
</P>
<P>
   _ Society has turned to law enforcement to resolve the rampage
killings. But the analysis shows that these cases may have more to
do with society's lack of knowledge of mental health issues than a
lack of security.
</P>
<P>
   The rage that boiled over into homicide was clearly building in
many. Of the cases reviewed, 63 involved people threatened violence
before the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not impulsive acts,'' said J. Reid Meloy, a forensic
psychologist at the University of California at San Diego. ``They
are not acts of affective violence, where they drink a lot and go
kill someone. There's a planning and purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was often a precipitating event _ a spark that set off
the tinder, and gave the crime the appearance of being at the same
time deliberate and impulsive.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most common precipitator was the loss of a job, which
was mentioned as a potential cause in 47 cases. A romantic issue _
a divorce or breakup _ was present in 22 cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some men see the loss of a job, or the loss of a mate, as
irrevocable and catastrophic,'' said David Buss, author of ``The
Dangerous Passion: Why Jealousy Is as Necessary as Love and Sex''
and a psychology professor at the University of Texas. ``They set
out on a course to inflict the maximum cost on their rivals.''
</P>
<P>
   Other recurring element were found, including some that
surprised the experts.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: Regular criminals try to get away. More than a third
of regular homicides went unsolved in 1997. But among the 102
killers in the Times database, not one got away. Eighty-nine never
even left the scene of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three offenders killed themselves after their crimes.
Nine tried or wanted to, and four killed themselves later. Nine
were killed by the police or others, perhaps committing what some
call ``suicide by cop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The link between suicide and homicide is a very real one, and
it hasn't been studied nearly enough,'' said Kay Redfield Jamison,
a professor of psychiatry at Johns Hopkins School of Medicine and
author of ``Night Falls Fast: Understanding Suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Rampage killers also differ by demographics.
</P>
<P>
   Half of all murderers in this country are black. Eighty percent
went to high school, and no further. Most of them killed someone
they knew, or while committing another crime.
</P>
<P>
   Rampage killers were white, by far, though 18 of the 102 were
black, and seven Asian. The racial profile of the rampage killers
is close to that of the entire population.
</P>
<P>
   And rampage killers were far more likely to have military
backgrounds, and to kill strangers. And, rampage killers were older
than regular murderers, with more in their 40s and 50s and fewer in
their 20s, compared with the typical killer.
</P>
<P>
   Of rampage killers over 25, a third had college degrees. Another
third had some college education. Only nine had less than a high
school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   And there seemed to be no urban bias for these crimes, as there
is for other violent crimes; 31 were in suburban areas, 25 were in
small towns or rural areas. Forty-two committed their crimes in
urban areas.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-47     04-08 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDEN DEFECTION IN VENEZUELA SCRAMBLES AN ELECTION SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARACAIBO, Venezuela _ For the second time in two years, a
former military officer vowing to dismantle a corrupt and
incompetent status quo has emerged to challenge Venezuela's
political establishment. This time, though, Hugo Chavez is not the
leader of the insurgency, but its main target _ and it is one of
his closest comrades in arms who is trying to drive him from the
presidency he has held for just 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Arias Cardenas broke with Chavez and declared himself
a candidate barely a month ago. The challenge, which coincides with
signs of military discontent with Chavez, appears to have caught
the president by surprise and has resulted both in prominent
defections and increased squabbling within the government
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all political experts here are still predicting that
Chavez will triumph in the May 28 ``mega-election'' in which
virtually every elective office in this country of 23 million
people is up for grabs, as required by a new constitution made to
measure for the president. But at the very least, Arias' candidacy
has transformed what the Chavez camp envisioned as a leisurely
canter into a horse race whose outcome is no longer guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of his first year in office, Chavez, a
45-year-old left-leaning populist and nationalist, enjoyed an
approval rating of nearly 80 percent, a figure that was expected to
hold if Venezuela's two discredited traditional political parties
were foolish enough to offer an opponent. But many of the numerous
polls that have recently been published show him with a lead of
merely 10 to 12 points over Arias.
</P>
<P>
   Arias has been able to appeal to Chavez supporters precisely
because ``he comes from the same ranks'' as Chavez, said Teodoro
Petkoff, a former guerrilla leader and planning minister who is now
editor of a new newspaper called Tal Cual.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Arias' reformist credentials are such that
Chavez sympathizers can vote for him without feeling that they have
betrayed their ideals.
</P>
<P>
   Like the president, Arias, 49, was one of the leaders of a
military coup attempt that failed in February 1992, was stripped of
his colonel's rank and served two years in prison. Since then, the
former seminary student has twice been elected governor of the
important oil-rich western state of Zulia while preaching a gospel
of probity and personal sacrifice in public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the electorate sees is a man who cannot be identified
either with the past or the present, but articulates a very
different message than Chavez, and in a very different way,'' said
Anibal Romero, author of ``Decadence and the Crisis of Democracy''
and other books on Venezuelan politics. ``And for the middle class
that never liked Chavez, Arias is their new champion by default,
because there is nothing else.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In what was seen as an effort to brake Arias' momentum and
deprive him of opportunities to get his message across, the
Chavez-dominated national electoral council has forbidden formal
campaigning until May 1.
</P>
<P>
   But a ``caravan of support'' here in Arias' home state had all
the hallmarks of a stump rally, suggesting the tone of his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dignity, decency and good management!'' and ``No more empty
talk!'' were among the slogans blaring from loudspeakers as a
procession of more than 150 vehicles wound its way through the
streets of a working class neighborhood near a large oil refinery.
Earlier, in a speech at the airport, Arias sounded essentially the
same themes before a largely middle class audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time of words that deceive and simply encourage hatred and
vengeance should give way to better living conditions for all
Venezuelans,'' he said, rejecting what he described as
``demagogic'' calls for class struggle. ``This country is not poor
because someone has a nice house or car, but because of a lack of
proper, competent administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Arias, whose oratory is more restrained and manner less
exuberant than the still popular Chavez, has also hammered away at
what he describes as massive corruption, singling out Chavez's
closest adviser, Luis Miquilena. In response, Miquilena has called
Arias ``a Judas,'' but since polls show Miquilena is one of the
country's least popular public figures, his attacks may actually
have worked to the challenger's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the independent comptroller general whom Chavez
forces ousted in December delivered an annual report last week that
said the current government is no less corrupt than previous
administrations and pointed to ``a deplorable situation'' in a
military-run civic assistance program that is one of Chavez's
favorites. That has fed popular disillusionment and concerns about
the more prominent role Chavez wants for the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez promised us a social and economic revolution, but all
he has done is concentrate power in his own hands and give us the
old-style politics with a different cast of characters,'' said
Cesar Guevara, 40, whose last job was as a door-to-door survey
taker for a marketing company. ``Unemployment and crime are way up,
so we are worse off now than when he took over. No, we need to go
back to the true ideals of this movement so that we can have a real
change.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent manifesto, a group of more than 100 retired officers
led by Fernando Ochoa, a former minister of defense, warned that
under Chavez the armed forces ``have begun to be seen as an
organization at the service of a political project and not the
nation.'' Chavez, they said, has ``politicized the armed forces and
fractured their internal unity'' by using military events to
``batter and insult his political adversaries and vast sectors of
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Chavez is also having to contend with divisions
within his left-wing Patriotic Pole coalition. As the result of
squabbles over the spoils of power, the 23-party grouping has been
unable to agree on a unified slate and has strengthened the chances
of anti-Chavez forces by running two or even three candidates for
some state and legislative posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a month ago, we were all wondering whether Chavez was
going to have any organized opposition at all after May 28,'' a
Latin American diplomat here said. ``Now not only has it taken
shape, but it comes from within Chavez's own movement, in the form
of Arias Cardenas and other dissidents, rather than from outside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-765&AMP;ADD-NYT     04-08 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. STEPPING UP PRESSURE FOR HANDOVER OF CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration is inexorably increasing
the pressure on the Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez to reunite
him with his father _ and hoping it happens without resistance.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has reason to be chary of the lingering
Cold War passions that divide the United States and Cuba, has tried
to moderate the tensions set off by the case of the Cuban boy. But
the Justice Department, with the White House's concurrence, has
nonetheless made ever more clear that the government's patience is
nearing its end.
</P>
<P>
   The major question facing administration officials at this point
is whether persuasion alone will bring about a peaceful transfer of
the boy this week, or whether it will take the force of law to
overcome defiance among the Miami relatives and their crowds of
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said Saturday that a number of plans had
been prepared for the handover of Elian to his father, including
his removal from the home of Miami relatives by armed federal
marshals.
</P>
<P>
   The official added that everyone in the government hoped the
return of Elian to his father's custody would be accomplished
voluntarily and peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   The official said: ``Are we capable of enforcing this action by
force? Yes. Does anybody want to see that happen? No.''
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, the Cuban issue has been a problem for two decades.
Clinton links his 1980 re-election defeat as governor of Arkansas
in part to rioting among 20,000 Cuban refugees temporarily
resettled at Fort Chaffee, Ark., by the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Clinton has walked a careful line on relations
with Cuba, offering modest steps to increase cooperation and travel
between the two countries while maintaining the strict 38-year-old
economic embargo on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on cue from the president, officials from the White
House, State Department and Justice Department all expressed hope
in public and private last week that the boy's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, who arrived here on Thursday from Cuba, can work out an
amicable custody deal with his Miami relatives, who have kept Elian
since he was rescued at sea last Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's mother, Elizabet Brotons, died when their boat sank as
they fled Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The administration does not relish the idea of Cuban-American
Miami rebelling over the repatriation of Elian. But neither does it
want to jeopardize the slow and delicate diplomatic opening to
Havana begun last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even as other agencies are handling the emotional issue of the
shipwrecked boy, the State Department is trying to manage an
incremental opening to Havana. Last year the administration
announced that it would permit additional charter flights to Cuba
from the United States and would approve significantly more visas
for researchers, athletes, journalists, artists and students to
travel to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles played an exhibition game against the
Cuban national team last spring, and other sports events are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is also quietly seeking broader cooperation
with Cuba on immigration, drug smuggling, the environment and
human-rights matters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has repeatedly said that the case will be handled under
existing immigration law, which would most likely result in Elian's
return to Cuba with his father and his stepmother, Nercy Carmenate.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official said that administration officials
were of one mind on the matter _ with the exception of Vice
President Al Gore, who broke with the president and announced that
he wanted the case moved into Florida family court, where Elian's
relatives in Miami might have a better chance of winning permanent
custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no split in the administration over what we hope
happens,'' the official said. ``There is great concern if the
family in Miami seeks a confrontation; there's no telling what
direction this could go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pastor, who handled Latin American policy at the National
Security Council under President Carter, said that Clinton should
harbor little hope of separating the Gonzalez case from 40 years of
pained history between the United States and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor also noted that Cuban-American tensions always seemed to
rise in election years and that this case was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no U.S.-Cuban issue that is not politicized,'' said
Pastor, now a professor of political science at Emory University in
Atlanta. ``The United States and Cuba have been contesting a
divorce for 41 years, so it's not surprising that this would be the
mother of all custody fights.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pastor said that the riots at Fort Chaffee in June 1980, which
left more than 40 Cubans and Arkansas law-enforcement officers
injured, caused a strain in relations between Clinton and Carter
that took years to heal. Clinton blamed Carter for sending
thousands of Cubans to Arkansas without adequate provision for
their security.
</P>
<P>
   A diplomat monitoring the case at the State Department said that
officials there were ``happily out of the picture.'' He expressed
hope that Justice Department and immigration officers can persuade
the families to agree to a peaceful transfer of Elian to his
father's care.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials have said that while they believe
the department has authority to order the boy's immediate handover
to his father, officials are trying to handle the case in a
``sensitive'' manner and would be willing to accept a few days'
delay to accommodate the wishes of Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But they have now set a schedule for meetings on Monday to
discuss the methods of the handover, with the boy's return to his
father coming shortly after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has to handle this very delicately because
of the intensity of feelings, and it's not going to be easy,''
Pastor said. ``It's not going to be easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
