</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSE _ WASHINGTON _ Almost every day, an explosion of
unimaginable cataclysm occurs somewhere in the universe and a burst
of gamma rays lasting only a few seconds reaches the Earth.
Discovered in the 1960s by military satellites deployed to watch
for nuclear explosions, the gamma ray bursts are over before
telescopes on the Earth or in orbit can detect anything more than a
faint afterglow. Yet, for a few seconds they seem to represent a
flash of energy greater than that of an entire galaxy. NASA is
building a satellite that will be able to detect the flashes from
``the corner of its eye'' and wheel around in a few seconds to take
a closer look. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Logo, a sketch of the planned ``Swift'' satellite and a
schematic showing how a collapsing star could burn off the Earth's
ozone layer if it were to happen as near as 5,000 light years from
here.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Second in the occasional ``Windows on the Universe''
series.
