<P>
   PLAINTIFF-DAVIDIANS _ Who's in/who's out in the various lawsuits
against the government. Lead plaintiffs attorney Mike Caddell has
moved to drop some of the plaintiffs and has picked up criticism
from Davidians represented by Ramsey Clark. (England, Waco
Tribune-Herald). FILE MUGS ARE AVAILABLE.
</P>
<P>
   GA-FLAG _ ATLANTA _ The SCLC's announcement this week of plans
for a boycott next year if Georgia's flag isn't changed adds a new
wrinkle for state officials who were already trying to come up with
a way to do just that when the Legislature convenes in January. The
strong push in South Carolina has demonstrated to Georgia lawmakers
that they can't postpone the flag debate forever. But some
Democratic leaders were hoping to have the summer and fall to try
to build a coalition to push legislation in January to remove the
confederate battle emblem. With Marty King's pronouncement this
week that the state would be under a boycott if the change doesn't
occur next year, leaders have to try to figure out how to smooth
over the flag controversy, keep it from flaring into an election
year issue that entrenches all sides and still work quietly to
build votes _ which they say there aren't enough of now _ to change
the flag. (Pruitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK _ ATLANTA _ Some version of Freaknik rolls into town
later this week. But it looks like Freaknik '00 will be just that:
a double zero. Crowds have steadily dwindled since 1994's peak.
Last year, the crowd was mostly local, and the cops seemed to
outnumber the partygoers. We're going to check with Atlanta police,
historically black colleges, city of Atlanta officials and others
to try to get a handle on this year's event? Police planning should
say a lot about what they expect. (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PERRY-TEXAS _ Lt. Gov. Rick Perry expects to be Gov. Rick Perry
when Texas lawmakers convene in January. That would make him the
state's first Aggie governor, and it could come as the Legislature
debates whether to allow familes of Aggie bonfire victims to sue
the state. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WEALTH _ SAN JOSE, Calif. _ After a turbulent, unsettling
week on Wall Street, once again Silicon Valley leads the rest of
the nation into a new era. This time, it's the age of high anxiety.
In a space of three hours last Tuesday, high-tech firms in the
Silicon Valley lost, and then regained, an estimated $200 billion
in value as the Here, at the affluent epicenter of the New Economy,
the gyrations were one more sign that toughr times could be ahead.
(Holmes, Cox News Service). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
