<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0408: A SEASON ON THE LAND -- More flue-cured
tobacco is grown in Pitt County, North Carolina, than anywhere else
in the nation. The culture and the economy are rooted in tending
the leaf, and in the self-reliant way of life such labor demands.
Yet as court rulings, public opinion and pressure from Washington
alter the fortunes of tobacco, change has made its way into the
fields. There will be fewer and fewer lives like the ones Betty and
W.C. Moore of Bethel live, shaped and bound by the rituals of
passing seasons on the farm. (Schulken, The Daily Reflector) Art
includes a 5-column color photo of a farmer tending his fields, a
2-column color photo of a farm, a 2-column color photo of a farmer
eating lunch with his family and a 1-column color photo of a
farmer's wife ringing the dinner bell.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TOBACCO PRIMER -- In their infancy tobacco plants look
like tiny shamrocks. As many as a million plants have taken root in
the warmth of W.C. Moore's greenhouse, snug in Styrofoam seed
crates, resting on a bed of water. They were sowed in mid-March,
and in April, when the threat of a hard freeze is past, they will
be transplanted in the field, the first crop of a new century. The
green fuzz sprouting in the seed crates doesn't look like much. But
with an average price, the half-million pounds of leaf it will grow
into could net $850,000. (Schulken, The Daily Reflector) Art
includes a 1-column color photo of tobacco seedlings awaiting to be
planted.
</P>
