<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ANTHEM LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Thank goodness the Czechs won a match and
have a sense of humor. They apparently understand that when you
come to America, you take the gaffes with the good.
</P>
<P>
   ``To bring this Laker Girls and all this stuff, this is what we
like,'' Jan Kukal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls, especially,'' said Slava Dosedel after the Czech
Republic's Davis Cup team got a healthy helping of Hollywood, in
all its glitzy, vacuous splendor.
</P>
<P>
   The Czechs love the hotel at Marina del Rey, but the freeway
traffic they could do without. They are enjoying the sights of Los
Angeles, but don't always appreciate the sounds.
</P>
<P>
   They heard the wrong national anthem Friday afternoon before
splitting the opening-day singles matches at the Great Western
Forum. Somebody worked very hard on a souped-up introduction
ceremony but forgot to consult an updated map. The Czech anthem
that was played was an old version _ the Slovakian march in
addition to the symphonic Czech part _ from before the peaceful
split.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is divided seven years, you know?'' said Kukal,
the Czech team captain, who ought to know because he is married to
a Slovak and lives in Bratislava, Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   When we last saw the U.S. team, triumphant in Zimbabwe, Captain
John McEnroe was referring to the quarterfinal opponent as
``Czechoslovakia,'' so maybe the organizers of
Davis-Cup-does-David-Stern didn't know. Or it could be there just
wasn't time to worry about diplomacy, with more pressing priorities
such as fireworks and Laker Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be lucky if they don't play the Russian anthem,''
McEnroe, a veteran Hollywood guy, joked earlier in the week, when
Kukal proactively raised the issue.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Kukal pointed out that the Slovak part
was played at a more accurate pace than the Czech part. No problem.
Patty Smyth McEnroe's rendition of our anthem and Lenny Kravitz's
``American Women'' sounded just right.
</P>
<P>
   Someone might have assured Kukal that this was no big deal in a
town where historical events are regularly interpreted loosely for
the benefit of dramatic effect. If McEnroe's team should go on to
win the Cup, they'll make a movie and we should expect the fans to
be serenading the Czechs with ``Commies, go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Our lines between entertainment and sports continue to blur.
Yes, those were the Laker Girls prancing between sets (not matches,
sets!) in tennis wear to Kravitz's remake of the old Guess Who hit.
The player introductions were vintage Charlotte Hornets vs. Miami
Heat. The noncorporate simplicity that made the first round in
Zimbabwe so refreshing just two months ago was as ancient as Bill
Tilden here once the Forum lights dimmed and the fireworks smoked
up the joint.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, we like our events dressed up and revved up, with
energy and attitude, the reason this round was awarded to Los
Angeles in the first place. It was the perfect script, the
sure-fire way of guaranteeing that reticent local boy Pete Sampras
would make the commute. McEnroe would have his dream team, Andre
Agassi and Sampras; we would beat up on the overmatched Czechs, and
the American Davis Cup cause would get a major marketing boost.
</P>
<P>
   As McEnroe says, ``Weird things happen in Davis Cup.'' Maybe the
anthem slight had nothing to do with Jiri Novak's three-set
demolition of Sampras, but that was Kukal's story and he was
sticking with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something like this can happen, maybe it, you know, help
Jiri,'' Kukal said. ``Novak played without respect. He got really
angry, and he woke up in dressing room after match. ``
</P>
<P>
   Meaning he forgot he was supposed to lose and played in a
possessed, nationalistic fervor. Unfortunately for the Czechs, by
the time Dosedel got on against Agassi, he was distracted _
presumably by Guess Who? _ and was dispatched in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Czechs' goal of surviving for the reverse singles Monday
was reached. Kukal was even wondering if the old anthem could be
played again Saturday, before Novak and David Rikl took on the
American team of Alex O'Brien and Jared Palmer in the doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do it, poor O'Brien and Palmer,'' Kukal said.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't starting any international incidents. Europeans tend
to be bewildered and amused by our sports pageantry excess, our
need to decorate every event like it is the Super Bowl halftime
show. As far as Kukal was concerned, it was just another case of
Americans awash in the wonderfulness of being No. 1 _ or in the
case of Agassi and Sampras, No. 1 and No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Kukal was a good sport; he even applauded one of the few winners
Sampras hit. With all due respect to Lenny Kravitz, we still should
have got the Czech anthem right.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I think in Europe this might not happen,'' Kukal said.
``It can't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Dosedel said, just wait, when the Americans next come to Prague,
they can expect to hear the Mexican anthem. Then someone asked him
what he was thinking when the anthem kept going after it reached
the Slovak border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to whistle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say why, or at whom. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
