<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WORKING-COWBOYS09-COX     04-08 2114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COWBOYS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ranch work may be seasonal, but cowboy mystique is timeless
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ There's a certain way a cow sounds when
she has pneumonia, a cough that rumbles through her wide chest and
comes out her mouth in a heaving hack.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a certain way she dodges a lasso, feinting left and
right and moving much faster than she should be able to. There's
the way the waist-high mountain brush snags the lasso again and
again before it reaches the running cow, the way she struggles as,
finally caught, she's wrestled to the ground and bellows when the
jumbo-sized vaccination shoots through the needle plunged into her
hide.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the way that sometimes happens in the rain,
weeklong periods of drizzle like those last summer when moisture
darkens brown leather chaps and dampens the jeans underneath them
and the saddle underneath the jeans and the horse underneath the
saddle, and it's late afternoon and the horse is unhappy and the
cow is unhappy and the lasso is wet and there are 2,300 other cows
spread over 50,000 acres of high summer pasture that possibly could
have pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Louis L'Amour might say, in such a situation, that it's time to
cowboy up: time to suck it in and do what needs doing. Cowboy up,
he'd say.
</P>
<P>
   If the concept exists outside the pages of romanticized Western
fiction, Jerry King knows a little about it. He's a cowboy, and
he's got work to do.
</P>
<P>
   It starts in spring with more than 40 miles of fence to tend,
then continues in June when 12 ranchers send their cattle up to
summer pasture in King's care, and lasts through fall when the
cattle come back to the lower valleys for winter or transport to
processing plants. During winter he trains horses.
</P>
<P>
   He's a cowboy, and the work never ends.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WINDS OF THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to get misty-eyed and romantic about cowboys. They
were and are integral to the allure of the West, the Real Men who
helped tame the wild prairies and mountains into prime grazing land
for enormous herds of cattle, then herded those cattle in mythic
drives that covered land to each horizon in a moving sea of beef.
</P>
<P>
   They were immortalized in dime novels about the West, the
steely-eyed, leather-skinned, Indian-fighting men's men who said
little, worked hard and liked their fancy women and liquor when
they finally got to town after months on the trail. They embodied
all that was free and mysterious and strong about the great
American West.
</P>
<P>
   Since the glory days of the West after the Civil War and through
the turn of the century, the role of cowboys has changed. Cowboys
started having to get off their horses to do things like fix fences
and administer inoculations to cattle and help with branding. They
began relying less on their guns and more on log books.
</P>
<P>
   The cowboy job is mythicized and glorified in thousands of books
and movies, but some of it is accurate, King said. There's
something about strapping on a pair of spurs before mounting a
high-spirited horse, something about swinging a rope lasso and
watching it land perfectly over an unruly cow's head, something
about sitting in the saddle on a ridgeline overlooking a herd of
cattle, surveying the horizon and understanding something about
life.
</P>
<P>
   King, 35, and his wife, Chrissy, 33, have two sons: 6-year-old
Cody and 5-year-old Clay. They are a cowboy family.
</P>
<P>
   It's a seasonal lifestyle that guarantees the family never will
be rich. Cowboy salaries are small, cowboy quarters humble. That's
not important, Chrissy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving can be good,'' she said. ``You learn about your
priorities. Living at cow camp in the summer with no electricity,
you learn what a waste of time TV is.''
</P>
<P>
   They've criss-crossed the West, with King driving his tough,
old, primer-gray Chevy truck pulling the trailer they sometimes
live in and Chrissy driving the beige Jeep Cherokee with the boys
and most of their things.
</P>
<P>
   Because most cowboy jobs are seasonal, they've moved from
Montana to Colorado to Wyoming to New Mexico. They've been in
western Colorado several years and tentatively plan to stay,
depending on what kind of work King gets this winter training
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Now they live in a small bunkhouse about 16 miles from the lower
cow camp where they'll spend most of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many cowboy jobs around these days. With less than
2 percent of the U.S. population employed in agriculture, according
to the 1990 U.S. census, cowboys compete for fewer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The texture of the lifestyle is changing, too. King remembers
how, when he first became a cowboy in Wyoming, ranchers shared and
pooled the work on things like branding and vaccinating and
winter-range work. Now ranchers have to struggle to survive and
that preoccupation has dented in small ways the sense of community.
Cowboys are affected the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's no money in it,'' King said. ``These young guys
know they can go into mining, carpentry, high-paying jobs where
they can drive around in new trucks. There's not a lot of younger
guys in it. There's a lot of wannabes, but as far as cowboying,
it's dying.''
</P>
<P>
   To supplement the family income, King sells drawings and
paintings. He's been an artist for as long as he can remember,
though he has no formal training. His western landscapes of
cowboys, horses, wildlife and scenery are becoming well-known for
quality and accuracy in depicting the cowboy lifestyle. One of his
drawings was used on the official poster for the 1994 College
National Finals Rodeo, and some of his work is in the Cowboys
Artists of America display in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tells me I ought to go do my art full-time, but
nah,'' he said. ``I'd rather do what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now that's getting his six horses in shape for the rigors
of summer cow camp, when they will pack in salt licks and carry
King all day as he rides through the pool of 2,350 cattle that 12
ranchers contracted with him to manage this summer. He gets up
early, before Chrissy and the boys begin a day of home schooling,
makes his coffee and goes outside before the sun is up to don chaps
and get all the equipment he'll need from the tack trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Through the winter he trained other people's horses, but now he
has to get his own in shape, so he takes them to the arena across
the road and gets them used to answering to him and being ridden.
Chrissy doesn't ride and the boys are just learning. The pace of
life is relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING THE ROPES
</P>
<P>
   A very little boy at some point in childhood dreams of being a
cowboy. King did. Growing up in southeast Ohio in the Appalachian
foothills of Wayne National Forest, he got his first horse,
Brownie, at age 9. His dad paid $100 for the horse and saddle, and
King paid his dad back with money he made from trapping.
</P>
<P>
   He always was self-sufficient like that, the black sheep of his
family who preferred going off alone into the woods to hunt and
trap, rather than play sports like his two younger brothers or have
sleep-overs with friends like his two younger sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The King family lived on a large farm run by King's paternal
grandfather. King helped plow fields and feed the hogs and cows.
Mostly, though, when he wasn't in school or doing homework, he was
in the woods running coon dogs and trapping foxes, muskrats,
raccoons, opossums, whatever critters he saw. He used the money
from the animals he sold to buy more traps _ at one time he had 125
traps going that he checked every day.
</P>
<P>
   And he learned from old-timers, men familiar with the woods and
animals who taught him what they'd learned from experience.
</P>
<P>
   When he got Brownie, though, he spent a little less time in the
woods and a little more time in the corral. His grandma bought him
a black cowboy hat and he used trapping money to buy his first pair
of boots. He's rarely been out of boots since then.
</P>
<P>
   He subscribed to Western Horseman, reading it voraciously every
month and getting ideas about what he wanted to do. He wanted to be
a cowboy. He wanted to live in the West. He wanted to ride into the
open range and see for miles in any direction and live his life
outside the confines of a 9-to-5 rat race. When he graduated from
high school in 1983, he pooled the money he'd saved, $500, and
several weeks later packed his stuff in his Chevy Corsica, said
goodbye to his family and drove west.
</P>
<P>
   On that first trip, he slept in his car and ate at gas stations
and tried to envision, as he saw the plains flash past on
Interstate 80, what waited for him in the West. He watched the land
grow browner, the space get bigger, the sky bluer. He crossed into
Wyoming and knew he'd entered cowboy country. Instinctively, he
knew the way cowboys get jobs: stop at ranches and ask if they need
help.
</P>
<P>
   On his third try, the ZN Ranch near Saratoga, Wyo., owned by
George Williams, King got a job making $400 a month. His references
were good and he'd grown up working hard, so he got hired despite
his inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   His title was cowboy and he rode open range herding cattle, soon
learning that modern cowboys do a lot more. He helped brand cattle,
dig post holes, irrigate, spread poison out for prairie dogs, work
in the shop and run a swather. It was different from what he'd
envisioned, but he still found himself when he became a cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a job for whiners,'' he explained. ``It's a job for
people who like to be self-sufficient, who don't like being told
what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He lived in a bunkhouse with a sagging roof. At night he and
another cowboy lay in bed and with a .22 shot at the mice running
through the ceiling. They got up before dawn most mornings and
gauged that day's work based on the season. In summer and fall they
were at cow camp and spent their days on horseback. During those
three summers, King learned to brand, deliver calves, take care of
equipment, give vaccines, use a lasso, diagnose bovine illness,
ride better and harder than he ever had. He learned to break up
clumps of cattle so they wouldn't trample a portion of pasture,
learned their quirks and idiosyncracies and how to work with
intense bovine stubbornness.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, Williams kept him on and he did more ranch work,
which is common. Most cowboys take winter jobs like carpentry or
construction or work as ranch hands.
</P>
<P>
   Being a cowboy, though, was the job King loved.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he enlisted on a whim in the U.S. Air Force in 1986
while he was in Ohio visiting his family. He stayed in until 1990,
first loading cargo airplanes then working on heavy equipment. His
unit went to Fort Leonardwood, Mo., in late 1989 to train to
rebuild runways in preparation for Desert Storm, but he got out
before going to Saudi Arabia ``because I was tired of all those
rules and regulations,'' he said. ``I don't like being told what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   That winter he spent a few weeks with his family in Ohio, but
knew he'd head west in spring, when ranchers were hiring cowboys.
When eating at a Bob Evans restaurant in Kettering, Ohio, he met a
waitress named Chrissy. He sat at the counter drinking black coffee
and she teased him about his cowboy duds, the ``howdy, pardner''
stuff he got a lot back then. He asked for her phone number and she
said no, so he gave her his and asked her to call him. She did two
days later and that April they went to Montana.
</P>
<P>
   That was 10 years and two sons ago.
</P>
<P>
   A COWBOY TILL THE END
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the whole family will go to cow camp, alternating
between lower and upper camps. There will be another cowboy up
helping King, and they will spend the majority of their days on
horseback, overseeing the cattle. Chrissy and the kids will explore
the woods, take pictures, play, ride ATVs and keep the cabin tidy
and, when King gets back, mess around with horses and take care of
equipment and kick back.
</P>
<P>
   When the cattle come down to the valleys this fall, the Kings
would like to find a house near Loma. They have friends who will
help them if they need it because, though the cowboy lifestyle is
shrinking, what remains of it is strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good people,'' Chrissy said, ``We've made some
really good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   If everything works out, they'll spend the winter in the Grand
Valley, where Jerry will train horses and create artwork and get
ready for the spring, when cowboys go to work. King said he'll be a
cowboy until he can't get on a horse anymore, but even then he'll
keep working with horses until he's so old he creaks like a leather
saddle.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it is with cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
