<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-THEWEST-COWBOYS09-COX     04-08 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEWEST-COWBOYS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking West, to the cowboy
 &HT;    By Marla Pierson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ On the big screen, a cowboy rides tall in the
saddle, moving rhythmically against a background of scenic vistas
and towering rock.
</P>
<P>
   A lone Texas Ranger, desperately outnumbered, chases bandits on
horseback through canyon and plain. A girl flirts with a cowboy in
a saloon.
</P>
<P>
   This is Hollywood's Old West _ a creation of film and novels
sometimes as far from the true West as it is from today's world.
</P>
<P>
   Even as early as the 1800s, legend colored the grueling life of
cowboys and other Western icons.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy now sells everything from cologne to cigarettes.
Television cowboys herd cats during a Super Bowl commercial break.
``Star Wars''' Han Solo is the quintessential good guy in what one
historian calls the modern morphing of a classic Western.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still identify in a positive way with the notion that
there are cowboys. You want to know there's some guy out there in
the middle of nowhere under the stars dealing with simple things,''
said Byron Price, executive director of the Buffalo Bill Historical
Center in Cody, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   The more complex the world becomes, Price said, ``the more we
need to experience that and believe that kind of thing can continue
to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which has little do with the realities of the cow
business today.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that carefree rider on horseback, said cattle aficionado
Bill Bond of Groesbeck. Real life is much more grimy.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a gooseneck trailer hooked to a worn-out pickup. The
trailer has a flat. A man's feet are sticking out from underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Bond said, ``is the modern cattle industry.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend Richard Morrison, a rare-book dealer, publishes an
annual price guide of Western Americana and Texana material. He is
familiar with thousands of books written on the West. He knows how
their tales differ from reality.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Bond heads to the pasture to brand cattle, Morrison
wants to come along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everything in the books and movies is fictionalized _
here I am college educated, graduate school _ and I just love the
hell out of going out and helping him and H.C. (another friend)
work cows,'' Morrison said. ``It's a life that hasn't been
mechanized out of existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, who owns a Western book store and art gallery, said the
average individual cowherd in Texas is about 20 mother cows. He
said he considers his cattle operation small, but he's adamant he
doesn't want to be without a cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just tradition with my family. I've just got to have
them. I don't know why,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has noticed city folk moving to the country and acquiring
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting in Texas, maybe Oklahoma and the Western
states, it's very, very common for the working person when they
acquire affluence, when somebody makes some money, the first thing
they want to do is buy a ranch,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   To Don Reeves, curator of cowboy collections at the National
Cowboy Hall of Fame in Oklahoma City, part of the fascination is
the freedom to choose and live out this lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independence, however you cut it, has a lot to do with it.
Self-reliance,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Price, executive director of the Buffalo Bill Historical
Center in Cody, Wyo., said cowboys ``represent our aspirations, at
least of white Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep canyons, tall mountains and broad vistas _ the notion the
West offered unfettered freedom where a person could control their
own destiny. That's really appealing imagery. The part of the myth
that's true is the deep canyons, tall mountains,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   It offered freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very quickly,'' Price said, ``people tried to replicate what
they had left and changed the face of the landscape. But the myth
remained.''
</P>
<P>
   There were cowboys driving cattle to market by the 1850s, living
out what Reeves calls ``a pretty mundane existence.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1870s, as life settled after the Civil War, the
cattle business heated up. Drives became a profitable venture
instead of an occasional necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper and magazine reporters looking for adventure after the
war turned their attention west, creating an image that holds even
into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys weren't quite their own bosses. They were hired hands
who sometimes didn't even have a claim to the horse they rode.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves remembers how the National Cowboy Hall of Fame had
trouble contacting the widow of a well-known rancher. She later let
them know she didn't want her husband connected with any cowboy
hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a cattleman. He hired cowboys,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   The term cowboy ``was used more in press and in dime novels than
it was on the range,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vaquero'' _ which referred to both Caucasian and Mexican
workers _ or ``cowhand'' was more comman in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the fantasy of the cowboy in fiction and film that
caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the 19th century, dime novels glorified cowboy life.
Young men in the East read them, some heading out to the range
seeking their own adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Price noted early depictions of the cowboy were not kind. ``The
popular press thought they were sort of ruffians and uncouth and
unrestrained,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then those publications, striving to show America as a
civilized, maturing nation, started playing up the heroic taming of
the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cowboys became part of the taming group instead of those that
needed taming,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh winters in the late 1880s devastated herds. People looking
for capital investments in cattle turned away from the open range.
Feed lots began developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the fencing of the ranges and the hay feeding,
there was less work for some of the itinerant cowboys or
cowhands,'' Reeves said. ``In the teens, a great many cowhands all
fled to Hollywood for jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The movies they would help make, however, hardly ever showed
cowboys working with cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's with them chasing each other or being chased by Indians
or in a barfight,'' Reeves said. ``The cowboys, the cowgirls, their
life revolved around the land and the cattle and their horses and
the ability of the horses to work cattle. And that's never
portrayed.'' The real cowboys were young.
</P>
<P>
   Some were 14 or 15. Most were 17 to 25 years old ``much like
professional athletes at the top of their game,'' Price said. ``You
couldn't take the day-to-day rigor of that after you got much
older.''
</P>
<P>
   They lived alone or in pairs in a line shack, a makeshift
dwelling sometimes dug out of the side of a hill. ``Just a place to
get in out of the weather,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the classic image of the cowboy is the trail drive,
even big outfits drove cattle only a short time out of the year
when there would be enough grass for the cattle to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many cattlemen who spent most of their life working
cattle, but they only went on one trail drive,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   All those gunfights, too, were created for the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Texas passed pistol laws in the mid-1880s outlawing the carrying
of pistols and side arms. Ranch owners forbade it on their
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very early on, Texas cowboys were shorn of their firearms,''
Price said.
</P>
<P>
   In Waco resident W.A. (Bill) Poage's account of an 1874 cattle
drive along the Chisolm Trail, he writes that card-playing was not
tolerated. One boss, Poage wrote, frequently told him that ``a deck
of cards and a tent only caused boys to fuss and waste time.''
</P>
<P>
   The cowboy's footloose image is not entirely made up, however.
It was a transient life. Few of the ranch hands were kept on over
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys were independent sorts, apt to take their saddles off
the company horses and head for another ranch if they ran into
problems with their employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear people from larger cities back East scoff at
self-reliance, individualism. But that is the tradition,'' Reeves
said.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the work fostered those traits. This is not a job
with sick days and substitutes who can be called in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out there alone. Whatever they found they dealt
with, whether stolen cattle or a steer stuck up to the neck in
mud,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of a cowboy's character was a quiet pride in the
work. Complaints and superlatives were not part of life on the
range. Loyalty was. Newcomers learned early not to gripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's thirsty. Everybody's hot,'' Bond said. ``So
there's some real good lessons to be learned.''
</P>
<P>
   The definition of cowboy today is slippery.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has heard plenty of old-timers say there aren't any more
cowboys like there were half a century ago. He's met people in
their 20s and 30s who would call themselves nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an identity and an occupation all rolled into one,''
Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   To Price, part of the lingering appeal of this icon is that it's
participatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can adopt the stance and the look and the attitude and
they don't have to have a single cow,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   These are jobs that people fill daily on large ranches and in
family operations. There are men and women competing in rodeos or
maybe just living out the cowboy ideals of self-reliance and hard
work in suburban settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't see 'em from the highway, as Baxter Black the
cowboy poet says,'' Price said of today's cowboys. ``The thing to
know about myth like this is it endures so long as people can
participate in it and believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The frontier is space. Han Solo wears his ray gun slung low. The
Millennium Falcon is a glorified horse that can outrun all the bad
guys' horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cowboys are finding a way to get into the next generation,''
Price said. ``That's why the myth will continue to be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
