<HEADER>
A1005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-2TAKE     04-08 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNITTING THE RAVELED THREADS OF THE DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was supposed to be a wonderful party, Los
Angeles' best chance in years to show off to 15,000 journalists and
the watching world its recovery from its early 1990s diet of fire,
riot and earthquake. But by this winter, the Democratic National
Convention, to be held here in August for the first time in 40
years, seemed to be shaping up as another disaster in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising was behind schedule. The billionaire moguls who
helped lure the convention were portrayed as bickering among
themselves. And if that were not enough, the worst police
corruption scandal in decades erupted in ugly headlines that sent
the city's public officials into a kind of collective meltdown, and
unions facing contract negotiations warned of possible labor
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mayor Richard Riordan, still smarting from the
collective raspberry that greeted the city's soggy New Year's
celebration, realized he would be blamed for any problems, ousted
the head of the local host committee and replaced her with a
trusted deputy, then got on the telephone and began dialing for
dollars himself. Now, local and Democratic Party officials say,
fund raising is back on track, planning is moving forward and they
are confident the convention will be a worthy successor to the one
that nominated John F. Kennedy in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things weren't happening,'' Riordan, a Republican who worked
to win the convention, acknowledged in a recent interview.
``Questions weren't being answered. If you had to say one thing
caught my attention, it was when Dianne Feinstein cornered me and
said, `You know, even if you aren't technically part of it, you're
going to be held accountable, so you'd better get involved.'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, part of the problem was that unlike past conventions,
including the 1984 gathering in San Francisco when Feinstein was
mayor there, this gala was to be privately sponsored. Working on
the model of the 1984 Olympics, Los Angeles' $35.3 million bid for
the convention was to be backed not by the city itself but by a
committee of prominent local citizens, including a trio of
billionaires: the entertainment mogul David Geffen, the insurance
and construction entrepreneur and philanthropist Eli Broad and the
supermarket magnate Ron Burkle, who agreed to raise most of the
money privately.
</P>
<P>
   That arrangement posed challenges in a city celebrated for civic
entropy. At the same time, the Democratic National Committee, which
is responsible for planning details of the convention program,
along with logistics, was dogged by delays in selecting a chief
executive for the convention, and unsettled by what was still a
struggle for the nomination between Vice President Al Gore and
former Sen. Bill Bradley. Complaints rumbled from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   For about the first six weeks of the year, officials concede,
the host committee was virtually paralyzed. Decisions were deferred
on everything from where to hold the media party kicking off the
convention week of Aug. 14 to how to design an official logo for
posters and banners. In mid-February, Riordan ousted Lucy McCoy, a
veteran fund-raiser who had been in charge of the committee and
replaced her with his own deputy mayor and press secretary, Noelia
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   In her first day on the job, Rodriguez chose the Los Angeles
Music Center for the press party and within days hired a contractor
to design a logo, which features not only the usual
red-white-and-blue but other bright primary colors in a tableau of
stylized political placards proclaiming Los Angeles the ``Capital
City of the 21st Century.'' She also forced Riordan to spend two or
three hours a day, two days a week, raising tax-exempt
contributions from individuals and corporations, a task he called
``a pain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a foundation established, but we really needed to
take it to the next level,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Broad, perhaps the most influential private-sector player behind
the scenes in civic affairs, had been McCoy's patron, and confessed
he initially doubted Riordan's decision to replace her. ``I did not
totally favor it at the time, but I've come around to believe he
did the right thing,'' Broad said. ``I think Noelia's very
talented, and the mayor is spending a lot of time at this,
including fund-raising, and we are hopeful of getting the job done
in the next several months.''
</P>
<P>
   As of this week, officials said the host committee had raised
$27.6 million of its goal, bolstered by a $1 million contribution
from Broad himself and a second $1 million in collective
contributions taken in over the last week. That figure includes a
pledge of about $7 million by the city toward the cost of police
and transportation for the delegates, but officials say that plan,
apparently based on what was needed in 1996 in Chicago, will now be
more costly, given the geographic sprawl of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one senior planning official said, the agreement
with the Democrats called for the city to provide up to 150 buses,
each with a police officer aboard, to shuttle the delegates to and
from their hotels. In fact, the official said, more than 300 buses
will now be needed, at a cost of $4 million more, at least some of
which they hope to get from the state, whose governor, Gray Davis,
a Democrat, is Gore's campaign chief here.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Democrats were wary about signing an agreement not
backed by the full faith and credit of the host city, the host
committee's agreement called for it to provide letters of credit
totaling $10 million, as a guarantee against unpaid bills. Riordan
and Broad signed such letters, as did two other people, but neither
Burkle nor Geffen did so, and a spokesman for each said it was
never envisioned that they would.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly never agreed to that letter of credit,'' said
Andy Spahn, head of corporate affairs for Geffen's studio,
DreamWorks SKG. ``We agreed to do what we could to help Los Angeles
secure the convention, period, and we made it clear that at that
point, we would segue into helping elect the Democratic nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Absent a hierarchy, Broad took on the most prominent public
role, which by turns amused and ruffled the feathers of some of his
colleagues. For his part Broad insisted he had no wish to be top
dog and added, ``I wish some of the co-chairs would do more than
they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   After a rocky start last fall, the Democrats' convention chief
executive, Lydia Camarillo, a former executive director of the
Southwest Voter Education Project, a Hispanic voter rights group in
San Antonio, Texas, has geared up her staff here, and Gore's
national campaign chief, former Rep. Tony Coelho, has taken a more
active role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not feel like we're behind at all,'' said Rod O'Connor,
the convention's chief of staff, who noted that the party Web site
would broadcast all convention proceedings, including delegation
meetings, while a special network would allow delegates to book
accommodations and coordinate schedules online. ``There's a lot of
work to do, but this is where we want to be.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One remaining hazard: concession workers and engineers at the
new Staples Center arena, where the convention will be held, are
working without collective bargaining agreements. For months,
officials planning the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia have had written assurances from unions there that
would essentially rule out strikes or picket lines at convention
sites. But with roughly 300,000 workers in fields from film to
schools facing contract renewals by this summer, union officials
here say no such agreement will be forthcoming, at least until the
negotiations at the arena are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very optimistic we can work it out,'' said Miguel
Contreras, executive secretary-treasurer of the Los Angeles County
Federation of Labor, AFL-CIO. ``We've told that to the DNC and
we're willing to negotiate ay and night. But people shouldn't be
pointing their fingers at the unions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-08 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Minn., N.D., Calif., Fla., W.Va., Ohio, Texas, Va.)  By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another Big Year For the Women
</P>
<P>
   In the lexicon of American politics, 1992 is known as the Year
of the Woman because that was the year women won four seats in the
United States Senate and 24 in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   This year's congressional elections are not likely to top that.
But 2000 is shaping up, nonetheless, as another important year for
women, especially when it comes to women running in highly
competitive races _ including many for open seats _ whose results
could weigh heavily in determining party control on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Of the dozen or so Senate contests rated most competitive, women
are running in four, with the New York contest being the most
prominent since it pits Hillary Rodham Clinton against Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani. On the House side, women are solid contenders in
at least six of the 20 or so top races, among them the contest in
Pennsylvania's Fourth Congressional District as well as contests in
California, Florida, Minnesota, Ohio and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, there are about a dozen women running for the Senate
and about 140 for the House _ some of them already nominated,
others still angling to get nominated.
</P>
<P>
   As some political experts see Election 2000 unfolding, women may
get an extra lift at the polls this year because a number of top
election issues are of special importance to women. Among them:
abortion, education, gun control, health care and the Medicare and
Social Security programs.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is a far cry from the women-in-politics situation 42
years ago, when Rep. Coya Knutson, D-Minn., the only woman ever
sent to the House from that state, was running for re-election. She
lost after her opponents circulated a letter they had obtained in
which her husband plaintively urged her to abandon legislating in
Washington and return home to him.
</P>
<P>
   This year, five of the 12 candidates running in Minnesota's
Fourth District are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's surely proof the Coya Knutson days are long gone,''
said Ellen Malcolm, the president of Emily's List, an organization
that raises money for Democratic women running for office who
support abortion rights. ``We think this year's election could very
well turn out to be the biggest for women candidates since the 1992
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossing Party Lines And Making Enemies
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Carlos Ramirez of El Paso, Texas, is the kind of supporter
Gov. George W. Bush just loves.
</P>
<P>
   He's a Democrat. He's a Latino. He runs a city that is heavily
Democratic and heavily Latino. And he loves to travel about the
country telling Latinos, whose political strength is growing but
who still lean Democratic, that he loves the governor and they
should too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the values that we share,'' Ramirez says.
</P>
<P>
   He was with the governor in the days leading up to the New
Hampshire primary. He was with him in the days leading up to the
California primary. And he was with him in 1998 when Bush became
the first Republican candidate for governor ever to carry El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez calls himself a conservative Democrat. But to other El
Paso Democrats he is a political pariah. And last weekend they all
but read him out of their ranks at a local party convention.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, they said, he can call himself anything he wants
and support whomever he pleases. But, they declared, he cannot
speak for them or the party and he cannot hold any party posts.
</P>
<P>
   A Poll Finds Voters Less Than Excited
</P>
<P>
   It is indeed a long, long way to November. And here is what the
latest Vanishing Voter Project poll by the Shorenstein Center at
Harvard found when voters were asked if they were paying any
attention this far from Election Day, and, if so, what conclusions
they had reached:
</P>
<P>
   One in five said they were paying ``quite a bit'' to ``a great
deal'' of attention to the candidates and issues. But all the rest
said they were paying ``just some'' attention to none at all.
</P>
<P>
   Final conclusion?
</P>
<P>
   ``Boring,'' said three of every four.
</P>
<P>
   High Gasoline Prices As a Campaign Issue
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department says gasoline prices should decline a bit
before next fall. But the way Rep. Thomas M. Davis III of Virginia
sees it, unless the decline is significant, the cost of fuel will
be a good Republican issue on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, chairman of the National Republican Congressional
Committee, sent out a memorandum recently in which he urged
Republican House candidates to make special efforts to pin the
blame for high pump prices on Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Act now to let voters know that the Clinton-Gore
administration has been asleep at the wheel and has done nothing to
combat this crisis,'' he wrote. ``We cannot allow foreign countries
to gouge American consumers. Republicans are stepping forward to
address the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional candidates _ Democrats and Republicans, House
members and senators _ were talking up the issue on the campaign
trail even before the Davis memorandum went out. But the memorandum
calls for more than just trail talk.
</P>
<P>
   Davis suggests that Republican candidates also initiate
letter-writing campaigns, that they seek out appearances on talk
shows and that they hold protests and press events at gas stations
and truck stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that hits home with every voter in your
district,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Walking All the Way To the Nomination
</P>
<P>
   Remember Duane Sand, the Navy man who retired, went home to
Fargo, N.D., and took off on a 346-mile trek across the state in
January to call attention to his novice campaign for the U.S.
Senate?
</P>
<P>
   He made it. Neither snow, nor minus 50-degree temperatures, nor
derisive laughter, nor ...
</P>
<P>
   What is more, at last weekend's Republican state convention in
Fargo, he managed to get himself nominated, defeating the favorite,
state Rep. Al Carlson of Fargo, by a solid 2-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in the hall was more surprised by the win than Sand. He
had no victory speech prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously demonstrated that he can attract attention,''
said Curly Haugland, the state's Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But come the fall, can Sand attract enough attention to beat the
veteran, well-entrenched Democratic incumbent, Kent Conrad?  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
