u i BC-WORLD-BANK-PROTEST-60     04-08 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BANK-PROTEST-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE PROTESTORS ARE BACK, WITH A NEW TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Beka Economopoulos, a 25-year-old environmental
campaigner with a premature streak of gray in her long black hair,
the drive to shut down the world's financial institutions began in
Seattle's King County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   She and about 250 other woman spent five days there shortly
after Thanksgiving last year, most of them arrested for refusing to
disperse when the Seattle police told them to move on. Inside the
cells, they planned an encore.
</P>
<P>
   ``For five days they only thing we talked about was how to take
this to the next level,'' said Economopoulos, a Washington native
who now spends full time on this mix of environmental and economic
causes. ``You go through that, you know, and you're hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people who disrupted the Seattle meeting of the
World Trade Organization are reassembling in Washington this week,
where they have identified as their targets two older, richer and
savvier agents of the global economy: the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund. Students, church groups,
environmentalists, and labor unions, a few of them planning to
scale buildings and block traffic to make their point, say they
want to disrupt the spring meetings at both groups.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters contend that the institutions have destroyed rain
forests, left poor countries in debt, and protected Nike, Disney
and Monsanto instead of workers in the Third World. They estimate
that between 10,000 and 30,000 people will join the week-long
demonstrations beginning on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That would add a street dimension to a growing political and
academic fracas over how to change the two financial institutions
and, more broadly, whether globalization is hurting more people
than it helps.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months the bank and the fund, which lend tens of
billions of dollars each year to poor and middle-income nations,
have come under strong pressure to slim down, pay more attention to
the side effects of their policies, and open up to public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Clinton administration has not reacted officially to
the protests, the United States, the largest donor to both
agencies, has a great deal at stake. At a time when America is
relying increasingly on the bank and the fund to manage the world
economy and spread American influence abroad, both agencies have
come under attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. government has long done whatever it wants with these
institutions without anybody saying anything,'' says Jeffrey Sachs,
a Harvard economist who has become a leading critic of the sister
institutions. ``The tradition that allows the U.S. to create any
mission it wants for these institutions is being challenged _ and
it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the World Bank and IMF say that most of the
protesters and many political and academic critics have scant
knowledge of what these institutions do, and that the relative
health of the global economy these days proves that they are
effective. But the attacks have left the bank, the fund and the
Clinton administration on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that globalization has cut into a nerve _ many
people want more say and they should get it,'' said James D.
Wolfensohn, the World Bank president. But he adds that protesters
tend to extrapolate from a few past mistakes to condemn the whole
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``On some of the issues they raise, there will just have to be
differences of opinion,'' said Wolfensohn, a former investment
banker who in recent years has championed poverty relief projects.
``But people should also know that the bank is a very different
place than it was five years ago.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Washington protests may not mirror the unrest in Seattle,
where a rare alchemy of violence and vandalism by a small group of
anarchists botched crowd control by the police and dissolution
among world trade ministers gave opposition groups a notable
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But they do seem likely to show the ability of diverse
nongovernment organizations to mount a coordinated campaign against
a common enemy: globalization as envisioned by traditional,
free-market-oriented government economists. Communicating via the
Internet, about 450 groups are sponsoring the Washington
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   At a local planning session this week organized by the
Mobilization for Global Justice, veterans of Vietnam War-era
protests mingled with college students in T-shirts. A guitarist
sang in protest mode, paraphrasing a song by Leonard Cohen, ``First
we take Seattle, then we take D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting had little of the visceral anger and fear of Vietnam
War protests or the passion of anti-apartheid demonstrations in the
1980s. Although one goal of the movement against globalization is
to turn the focus away from corporations to the poor nations of the
world, there were only a handful of people from what the
participants call the global South, or developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   One was Njoki Njoroge Njehu, a Kenyan who serves as one of the
movement's key ``facilitators.'' (Participants say there are no
generals, only lieutenants and ground troops.) She said the
coalition has managed to bridge different purposes because it
operates strictly by consensus. The process is mapped on a flow
chart on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are emulating the kind of world we are seeking, with total
transparency and without hierarchy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington protests will last for a week, beginning with a
march for debt relief organized by Jubilee 2000 Sunday and
culminating in rally-cum-civil-disobedience events on April 16 and
17, when the IMF and World Bank are scheduled to hold their spring
meetings and world finance ministers are to descend on the city.
</P>
<P>
   Police, wary of violence orchestrated by some 200 anarchists in
Seattle, have prepared for months in ensure that the meetings are
not disrupted. The main protest groups have pledged to demonstrate
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the protesters view the World Bank and the IMF as global
loan sharks, hooking lower-income nations on cheap debt and then
insisting that they adopt free markets, unlimited investment,
privatization, restrained government spending, or risk a cut-off in
new aid.
</P>
<P>
   They are armed with research that they say shows some of the
poorest countries that get World Bank and IMF assistance,
particularly in sub-Saharan Africa, have become dependent on loans.
They cite statistics that they say show that some African client
countries have experienced declining per capita income over the
last two decades, while other nations that shunned official aid
performed better.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the policies work, they often come at the expense of
the environment, others argue. The bank and the fund sometimes
require aid recipients to curtail fiscal spending and increase
exports to earn hard currency. To meet those targets, governments
often slash environmental protection budgets, they contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot conceive of policies more diametrically opposed to
sound management of resources'' than those preached by the bank and
the fund, said Brent Blackwelder, president of Friends of the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters have treated Sachs and Joseph E. Stiglitz, the
recently departed chief economist of the World Bank, as
intellectual leaders. Stiglitz's scathing insider critiques have
contributed to a raging debate in universities and in Congress
about the effectiveness of the agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the protesters have implicit allies on the right. A
commission appointed by the Republican-controlled Congress to
recommend changes at the fund and bank last month called for an end
to long-term loans of the type criticized by environmentalists. The
commission also said the bank should act less like a bank and make
more grants, rather than loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underneath it all is a feeling that globalization has not
brought the benefits to the poor as promised,'' Stiglitz said.
``The architecture of the world financial system is decided by
finance ministers behind closed doors, but farmers and small
businessmen are the ones who get hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
