<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-PRESIDENT0409-COX     04-08 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRESIDENT0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Documentary provides an interesting look at our presidents
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Philip B. Kunhardt III is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American President,'' the 10-hour PBS documentary he
produced, wrote and directed, does what no series has ever done: It
profiles all 41 presidents. Every commander-in-chief from the
obscure Rutherford B. Hayes to the legendary Franklin Delano
Roosevelt is featured in the series, which begins today and will
air over the next four nights in two-hour installments.
</P>
<P>
   But even Kunhardt, who produced the documentary with his father
and brother, wonders how many viewers will actually watch what
could be perceived as a dry-as-dirt history lesson. ``It does worry
me a little bit that the average person's attention span will be
taxed,'' he admits. ``But despite all the cynicism, people still
care about the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep viewers from switching channels _ or not watching at all
_ Kunhardt wisely chose to group the presidents' stories into a
common theme each night. For instance, ``Family Ties'' examines how
power and influence are handed down from generation to generation.
In that segment, John Quincy Adams, Benjamin Harrison, Franklin D.
Roosevelt and John F. Kennedy are profiled. Many viewers may be
surprised to learn, for example, that Adams was miserable during
his term and would often take long walks by himself or swim in the
Potomac River. Meanwhile, ``Happenstance'' explores the careers of
five presidents _ John Tyler, Millard Fillmore, Andrew Johnson,
Chester Alan Arthur and Harry Truman _ who were vice presidents,
but moved to the White House after the death of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would've been awfully deadly if we walked through history
in lockstep,'' Kunhardt notes. ``That would've been too
predictable. Each hour takes a different swipe at history, so we
could juxtapose an early president with a more recent one.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the profiles, ``The American President,'' which
took five years to make, also features interviews with President
Clinton and every living former president except Ronald Reagan.
Hugh Sidey, Time magazine's White House correspondent for four
decades, conducted the interviews and narrated the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Sidey to narrate other PBS documentaries in the
near future. ``That's the one and only time I'll do that,'' he
says, chuckling. ``It took three years and every other month I was
in the sound booth all day. That's hard work. Gosh, I don't know
how those narrators do it, and stand there agonizing over every
phrase and sentence. I'd just blow my brains out.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the veteran Sidey learn anything about a president he didn't
know?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that Andrew Johnson was a drunk and was hooched up at
Lincoln's inauguration,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of most historical documentaries seek A-list
celebrities to provide the voices for long-dead political figures.
``The American President'' producers, however, opted to sign up
politicians and well-known journalists. Among those lending their
voices include columnist George Will (John Quincy Adams); Gen.
Colin Powell (William H. Taft); talk show host Charlie Rose (John
Tyler); former CBS News anchor Walter Cronkite (George Washington)
and radio personality Don Imus (Andrew Johnson).
</P>
<P>
   The raunchy Don Imus ... on PBS?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was our last choice,'' Kunhardt acknowledges. ``We couldn't
get anyone else to do that part. Johnson was a racist,
segregationist and a stubborn kind of character. No one wanted to
touch it. When Don heard everybody said, 'No,' he said that made it
more attractive to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kunhardt points out that the idea to not hire trained actors
wasn't attractive to him. He says his brother Peter convinced him
to use a diverse group of individuals. ``You know actors will bring
a tremendous ability of range and will bring a huge amount to the
project,'' Kunhardt says. ``But over the last 10 years, so many
documentaries have turned to the same actors. It was getting
boring, so we wanted to break the mold in a new way.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge, however, was gathering the volume of
material needed. ``We wanted this to be largely driven by the words
of the presidents themselves,'' says Kunhardt, who wrote the ABC
miniseries ``Lincoln.'' ``That meant reading huge volumes of their
writings, sometimes in unpublished form. We wanted intimate
writings and letters, and that meant going to the Library of
Congress and then deciphering their miserable handwriting.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will viewers walk away with?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there's a renewed faith in the president,'' Sidey says.
``It's a remarkable institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
