<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SPRING-BREAK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS REASSESSING SPRING RITE OF STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Fla.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ARANSAS, Texas _ Out on the back porch of Woody's bait
stand, in a salt-thick breeze off the Gulf of Mexico, Johnny
Mathews, a fishing guide, flicks the foam from a cold beer and
weighs in on the topic of students on spring break: ``It's not that
they're bad people. They just don't know how to act like normal
people.''
</P>
<P>
   By normal, he means like native Texans.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 300,000 college students or families celebrating
spring vacations have come and gone from the sandy Gulf beaches
that stretch 100 miles from here to South Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   And left behind are mounds of trash, some alcohol casualties
recovering in emergency rooms, and a debate rekindled every year by
residents of the Texas coast: Is the annual raucous, crowded rite
of spring really worth the money, and the aggravation?
</P>
<P>
   Because towns like Port Aransas and South Padre thrive primarily
on the tourist trade, one would think that any visitor with a
credit card would be highly prized.
</P>
<P>
   But with the economy in full blossom and with the residents
increasingly restless about rapid growth in their once-small
communities, the value of crowds is being debated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cities that once fought over the spring break crowd are now
becoming a lot more selective, particularly when it comes to the
college kids,'' said Ann Vaughan, a Chamber of Commerce executive
in this weather-beaten fishing village of 2,100 that had 100,000
visitors last month.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with traffic, lewdness and general rowdiness,
particularly among college students, have prompted Port Aransas to
change the focus of its marketing away from students, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can come if they want to, but they have to play by our
rules,'' Vaughan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us the families, and let the students go to South
Padre,'' says Larry Stimson, captain of a bay fishing vessel called
the Island Queen, who has lived in both cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The families will come with a set amount of money and spend
every bit on beer, hotels, restaurants, fishing trips and other
tourist stuff,'' Stimson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the students bring their own beer, sleep on the beach, and
just might buy a loaf of bread and some bologna. They don't have
any money, so you can't get any out of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities have come to this conclusion. Fort Lauderdale,
Fla., once attracted as many as 350,000 students on spring break.
But Nicki Grossman, president of the Convention and Visitor's
Bureau, says, ``Now, we don't even like to see Fort Lauderdale and
the `s' word used in the same sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Fort Lauderdale attracted only 15,000 students out of
550,000 visitors in March, she said. ``We got rid of MTV and got
rid of the wet T-shirt volleyball games,'' she added. ``When MTV
went, the lemmings went with it. We felt that if the kids could
graduate, so could we.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said open container laws, police visibility, and a
half-billion dollars in beach clean-up programs and community
investments made it possible to discourage the student crowd and
attract the more lucrative family vacation business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The college student business was worth about $110 million a
year at its peak, but the current family market we cater to brings
in between $450 and $500 million,'' Grossman said. ``If the weather
stays good and the kids stay away, everything's fine for us.''
</P>
<P>
   South Padre Island has become known as a vacation destination
among students, and the resident population of 2,000 swells to
nearly 200,000 during spring break, says Jennifer Beck of the
Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Vern Vincent of the University of Texas Pan American at Edinburg
says last year's crowd resulted in $700,000 in sales and hotel tax
revenues to South Padre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring break comes during the off-season and it really helps
the local businesses,'' he said. Everyone benefits from having the
spring breakers there.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are problems.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Morrison of the South Padre police department said his
office arrested 530 people during this year's spring break, up from
the normal 15 to 20 monthly arrests at other times of year. ``Most
of those are driving while intoxicated arrests, and virtually all
of those are students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the porch at Woody's, Mathews, who has lived his entire
life in Port Aransas, said that even though he found the spring
visitors' habits peculiar, particularly their driving, the economic
benefit of their presence was worth the inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes the college students. ``You just have to learn
to go where they're not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for some residents, any visitors are too many. A popular
bumper sticker asks: ``If it's called tourist season, why can't we
just shoot them?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
