<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-JANITOR-STRIKE-     04-08 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-JANITOR-STRIKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANITORS RALLY IN LOS ANGELES AFTER VOTING TO STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the 15 years Maria Santania has worked as a
janitor here, her pay has increased $2 an hour, to $6.50. To earn
it, she vacuums, dusts and scrubs two floors of an office building
on South Hope Street in downtown Los Angeles _ 100 law offices and
consulates filled with thick carpeting and cherry wood desks that
she is regularly warned not to damage.
</P>
<P>
   At night Santania, who came to the United States from El
Salvador 18 years ago, goes home to a one-bedroom apartment in the
Koreatown section of mid-Los Angeles that she shares with her two
children; she separated from her husband six years ago. The rent,
$550, amounts to more than two weeks of her salary before taxes. So
on Friday, she joined thousands of striking janitors _ police and
union officials estimated a crowd of 3,000 _ marching down Wilshire
Boulevard in search of a larger pay increase.
</P>
<P>
   Multi-year janitorial contracts are lapsing in several major
American cities this year, including San Francisco, San Jose and
Chicago, but Los Angeles' was the first to expire with no agreement
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The strike came after janitors voted to reject a pay plan put
forward by a group of building maintenance companies that would
have offered a 50-cent raise the first year and 40-cent raises the
next two years. The workers are seeking a $3 increase in their
hourly pay over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be here,'' Santania said. ``I'd like to be
working. But I can't accept 50 cents.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse L. Jackson and other civil rights leaders and
political figures led marchers Thursday and Friday. And leaders of
the union, the Service Employees International Union, which
represents nearly 10,000 janitors in Los Angeles, said workers
would not go back until they got a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a dramatic increase in order for them to
move above the federal poverty line,'' about $15,000 annually for a
family of four, said Blanca Gallegos, a union leader. ``They're not
going back until the contractors come back with an offer they can
accept, that would be a livable wage.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Davis, the chief negotiator for the maintenance companies,
did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders said wages for janitorial workers in Los Angeles
have declined in real terms from the equivalent of $13 an hour in
the early 1980s to an average of $6.80 today, as the face of
janitorial labor here has changed in the past two decades from
largely American-born blacks to foreign-born Hispanics. Union
leaders say the shift is a result of Los Angeles' status as a
magnet for immigrant labor. Union leaders said janitors in Los
Angeles earned less than unionized janitors in any other major
city.
</P>
<P>
   American Building Maintenance, one of the largest janitorial
services companies with more than 39,000 janitorial employees, and
the only one whose figures are publicly available, earned $49.5
million in profits last year on $933 million in revenues, according
to its annual report.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Stang, a lawyer advising American Building Maintenance on
the negotiations, said the maintenance companies offered wage and
benefit increases better than the industry average, but union
members walked out on talks without responding to the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Stang said, companies that use union labor have to keep
costs down to compete with nonunion firms.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Fernandez, a 39-year-old mother of seven, marched on
Friday with her daughter, Sylvia, 10, and her niece, Patricia, 9.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez estimated that she cleaned more than 100 toilets each
night at the Trans-America building downtown, earning $7.80 an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of work for what I earn,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      04-08 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SENATE BID, MRS. CLINTON CLAIMS TO HAVE GOP SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OWEGO, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, apparently bolstered by an
uptick in support from upstate voters, said Saturday at two
small-town campaign stops that she saw evidence that many
Republicans would cross party lines to back her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had more and more Republicans coming up to me,'' Clinton
told 50 Democrats who had gathered for a brief stopover at an
Italian restaurant in this Tioga County village. ``They came, both
men and women, and said they would support my campaign both because
they really want to continue the policies of the president, and
because they want somebody in the Senate who will work with
everyone in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton made almost identical remarks at the
annual Broome County Democratic Party Breakfast in Endwell, a
suburb of Binghamton. Responding to reporters here, she said her
evidence of growing Republican support was ``just anecdotal.'' She
said supporters she had met on this two-day road trip from
Rochester to the Binghamton area ``identified themselves as
Republicans, and that is gratifying to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In other remarks, Clinton sought to ally herself with moderates
and fiscal conservatives within her own party. At one point in her
Binghamton speech, in which she pointed to the success of the White
House in reducing the federal deficit, she said she advocated a
``rendezvous with responsibility'' in fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also took several occasions during her campaign stops
Friday and Saturday to portray herself as someone with long
experience in upstate New York. In describing her advocacy of more
stringent gun control, she said she had spent ``every summer'' of
her youth at a cottage on a lake near Scranton, Pa., and had
frequently visited Binghamton. ``I was taught how to shoot, not
well I admit,'' she said, adding that she had ``nothing against gun
ownership, and nothing against hunting or sport shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's breakfast meeting with Broome County Democrats, a
fund-raising event that attracted 400 people at $50 a plate, also
attracted a group of 20 opponents, who greeted her arrival outside
an Endwell restaurant with placards.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was one depicting a witch on a broomstick under the
phrase ``Westchester Witch.'' Another read: ``Hillary, if we elect
you, do we get him?''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hoskins, an Endwell computer programmer who was carrying a
sign, said the group was composed of friends who opposed Clinton's
positions on abortion rights and other social issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
