<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EARTH-DAY-ART-NYT &LR;      04-08 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH-DAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTH DAY GOES GLOBAL AS IT TURNS 30 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With 4,500 organizations planning events in more than
180 countries, the 30th Earth Day is living up to its name in a way
that was not true for the first Earth Day, which was largely a
domestic affair and which provided a major spark for two landmark
pieces of federal environmental legislation, the Clean Air Act and
the Clean Water Act.
</P>
<P>
   But if much has changed over the years about Earth Day, one
thing about this year's event on Saturday, April 22, is strikingly
similar to the original: Denis Hayes is leading the effort.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, just a few years out of Stanford University, where he
was student body president, Hayes dropped out of the Kennedy School
at Harvard to serve as national coordinator for the first Earth
Day, which was the brainchild of Sen. Gaylord Nelson, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   There was more than a bit of the angry young man in Hayes'
approach to galvanizing public ire over air and water pollution.
This time around, as the chairman of the international Earth Day
Network, Hayes, 55, says ecological crises, especially global
warming, are no less severe. But the lawyer and environmental
advocate says the ``clean energy agenda'' at the heart of this
year's rallies is ``almost Reaganesque in its robust optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   The earth ``is confronting some extremely difficult problems,''
said Hayes. ``How do you deal with racism, how do you deal with
ethnic tensions that have existed for thousands of years? We don't
have any clever ideas. Global warming is an enormous threat to the
well-being of the planet, but it's one where we honest to God do
know what to do, and it's a matter of summoning the necessary
political will.''
</P>
<P>
   Summoning the will to confront global warming is thus the chief
goal of the Seattle-based Earth Day Network, which says the biggest
rally in this country on April 22 will be on the Mall in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Much as earlier Earth Days led to a push on such causes as
recycling, organizers hope this year's energy agenda will lead
consumers, government agencies and businesses to expand
conservation efforts and the use of cleaner forms of energy, such
as solar and wind power. The agenda also includes tougher pollution
standards for cars, appliances and factories.
</P>
<P>
   All of these are achievable and even affordable goals, Hayes
insisted last week at Earth Day offices in downtown Seattle, where
a giant world map flags the locations of Earth Day events across
the planet and where energetic staff members and volunteers appear
to be in touch, via the Internet anyway, with groups around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   To cite a smattering of events, there are workshops for youth in
Burkina Faso on solar cooking; a children's clean-air bicycle rally
in New Delhi; rallies to curb global warming in at least five
cities in Bangladesh; a car-free event in Seoul, South Korea, that
will close major streets to automobile traffic; and a huge
``eco-festival'' at London's Millennium Dome. A clean-air rally in
Mexico City may draw more people than the one in Washington, say
Earth Day organizers.
</P>
<P>
   But in all cases, Hayes said, these groups are focusing on a
``single, unifying global problem that has a local dimension to it:
Groups that are fighting tanker traffic through Puget Sound, groups
trying to protect the rain forests of Nigeria or the Arctic
Wildlife Refuge, Bangladeshis scared to death of an ocean rise that
will take out their country, all of them are really mobilized to
get engaged in a clean-energy agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Hayes said he has been struck in international travels
by how many political leaders, not just ordinary citizens, cite
pollution as a dominant problem. ``That was certainly true in
China,'' he said, where heavy use of coal has contributed to
tremendous air pollution. ``Seven of the 10 most polluted cities in
the world are in China, and that's a source of some real
embarrassment for a nation that wants to hold itself up as a model
for an alternative form of development.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25th anniversary of Earth Day in 1995 was not without
controversy, as some environmentalists complained that the event
had taken on a nebulous feel-good air and a degree of corporate
sponsorship that led some to say Earth Day had been ``greenwashed''
out of significance.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, even as organizers have emphasized more teach-ins
and grass-roots events, Earth Day organizers had to stand by with
some pain as a recent dispute unfolded over a decision by ABC News
to have one of the event's celebrity leaders, Leonardo DiCaprio,
interview President Clinton about global warming. (Hayes said the
movie star had helped galvanize youth interest in the environment
and, he added, ``Leo is a fine, articulate spokesman, and we're
proud to have him.'')
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if environmental advocates have sometimes
been accused of lacking a sense of humor, that does not seem to be
an issue at Earth Day headquarters or on the Web site,
www.earthday.net. One of the network's projects is a daily online
compendium of environmental news called the Daily Grist, billed as
``gloom and doom with a sense of humor'' and marked by puns and
tongue-in-cheek headlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Grist even offered an April Fool's edition reporting,
among other things, that a coalition of New Mexico environmental
groups was backing a massive shopping complex ``in the sprawling
suburbs of Albuquerque,'' which grateful developers were thinking
of naming Muir Valley. ``It's just a bunch of scrub brush,'' one
environmentalist was quoted as saying. Another said, ``All the
species on this land can be found in at least two or three other
places, so I don't see a real problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes said a little such humor is a good thing, but he hopes
this year's event will spur a serious commitment to energy
efficiency. His ire has clearly been raised by sport utility
vehicles and large cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit took the most environmentally irresponsible vehicle
that is made in the world, found a loophole for it in the
standards, and then sold it to the greenest cohort of American
consumers,'' he said. ``Most of the SUV decision-makers among
consumers are young urban females, who are the strongest
environmentalists in the country. They sold it on the basis of
urban safety, and all these photographs of them in the Serengeti,
as though you're going to drive your SUV through the hills of East
Africa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
