u k BC-EDIT-NY-SENATE-NYT &LR;      04-08 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW TWISTS IN NEW YORK SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, April 9:
</P>
<P>
   Two startling developments are changing the dynamics of the
Senate campaign in New York state. In a surprising shift, the
latest opinion polls show New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
losing ground to Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a New York Times/CBS News survey last week, Clinton surged
from 2 percentage points behind to 8 points ahead of the mayor,
gaining not only in the city but also upstate, where Republicans
are traditionally strong. But in an unexpected counter trend, the
latest fund-raising reports show that the mayor has raised far more
money than the first lady. His campaign has a balance of $19
million compared with her $12 million. With seven months to go,
this race could devour as much as $70 million or $80 million for a
single Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind these two countervailing forces seem clear.
The latest polls are registering the mayor's mishandling of the
Patrick Dorismond shooting, including his unwarranted release of
Dorismond's juvenile records. The surveys also signal Giuliani's
failure to focus on a statewide message, especially to potential
voters outside the city. The unanswered question is whether the
Dorismond case has caused only a momentary blip in the polls, as
the mayor's campaign believes, or will solidify misgivings raised
by the first lady that he is a divisive and authoritarian figure
unsuitable for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, the candidates are spending their considerable
funds to minimize their own weaknesses and amplify their
opponent's. After a shaky start, Clinton has gained in the upstate
areas by energetically working the rural coffee shops and courting
the hometown television stations. For her effort, she has pulled
even with the mayor upstate, a position that could be difficult to
maintain. Still, her support in Republican territory has clearly
terrified local Republican leaders, who already fear that if Al
Gore wins the presidential vote in a generally Democratic state it
will trickle down to the rest of the ballot. Undoubtedly shaken by
these latest polls, the mayor's campaign has scheduled more visits
outside the city to calm these Republican nerves and shore up
Giuliani's support.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor remains strong in the suburbs, where the first lady,
despite her move to a comfortable enclave in Westchester County,
has failed to energize voters or lure enough white professional
women into her army. The suburbs will be particularly hard-fought
territory, and the mayor launched his latest advertising campaign
to target them. Giuliani's new instant commercial features him
campaigning last week with Sen. John McCain, who appeals to crucial
swing voters, especially on Long Island. The ads not only allow the
mayor to ride on McCain's residual popularity, but also make it
clear that not all U.S. senators are soft and malleable.
</P>
<P>
   If each candidate stirs intense dislike among the opposition, a
political given in this high-powered duel, Giuliani's campaign is
using this antipathy to great financial advantage. An Associated
Press story in February cited donors around the country who could
not pronounce Giuliani's name but contributed to him because, as
one $100 donor in Dallas explained, ``I hate Hillary, plain and
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The massive flow of regular campaign funds to both campaigns
makes it all the more distressing that each side is now also
raising largely unregulated donations or soft money. Two advocacy
groups _ Common Cause and Democracy 21 _ have asked the Federal
Election Commission and Justice Department to investigate these
donations that are not independent of the campaigns as required by
law. A swift ruling to stop these new ``joint committees'' would
help end a bad scheme before it becomes a political tradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1446EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
