<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEQUOIA-PROJECT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAN TO PRESERVE GIANT SEQUOIAS, WORLD'S BIGGEST TREES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Colo., Wyo.)   By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman has recommended
that 355,000 acres of national forest be given monument status to
safeguard about half the giant sequoia groves remaining in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are really precious jewels of the American geography,''
Glickman said Friday. Monument status would give them ``a
long-term, even permanent protection for the benefit of the
American people to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation will now go to President Clinton, who is
expected to approve it under the 1906 Antiquities Act.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year of his presidency, Clinton has been
increasingly using the act, which allows him to create national
monuments on federal lands without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   He has protected more land using the act in the lower 48 states
than any other president.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts in Sequoia National Forest, part of which is used
for logging, have met with opposition. In an effort to block
Clinton, three members of Congress from California have drafted
legislation that would require an 18-month study by the National
Academy of Science on how best to protect the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, a Republican sponsor of the bill, has said
that the president is ``declaring war'' on communities closest to
the forests. During debate on the measure last month, supporters of
the legislation acknowledged that it was unlikely to pass before
Clinton acted.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas could not immediately be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   While the legislators agree that the trees should be protected,
they argue that cutbacks on logging in the national forest would
cost millions of dollars in lost jobs and would also be
shortsighted.
</P>
<P>
   They say timber operations protect the sequoias by thinning out
the undergrowth and smaller trees surrounding them and protecting
them from fire and pest infestation.
</P>
<P>
   Under Glickman's proposal, any future arrangements for logging
within the boundaries of the monument would be outlawed, but
logging deals already negotiated would continue while logging is
phased out over the next 2{ years.
</P>
<P>
   In his recommendation, Glickman outlined a plan that he said was
intended to safeguard the trees well into the future. He suggested
that a science advisory panel be created to help develop a
management plan for the trees. The plan would be used to draft
guidelines on issues like controlled burning, which could replace
the clearing by timber operations.
</P>
<P>
   Grazing operations and other uses that are already permitted
would remain in effect, and all existing rights of private property
owners within the forest would be preserved under the secretary's
recommendations. Recreational access would also continue. Existing
camps, like Camp Whittsett Boy Scout Camp and Pyles Boys Camp,
would probably remain, Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that overall, there will be a special management
effort to protect the trees over and above your normal forest
management,'' he said. ``Despite their tremendous size, giant
sequoias are vulnerable. They are very much affected by what
happens in the surrounding forest.''
</P>
<P>
   Forestry officials said that the area chosen for the monument
included 75 groves. The area was selected primarily because of
underground water supplies and its history of fires. The Sequoia
National Forest is close to a million acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ancestors of the giant sequoia once grew as far east as
Colorado and Wyoming,'' Glickman noted. ``Now these precious trees
are only found on the west slope of the Sierra Nevada. To ensure
the permanent survival of these ancient giants, we must provide
them with permanent protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Although California's redwoods are the tallest trees in the
world, sequoias are the largest overall, measuring up to 30 feet in
diameter and weighing as much as 600 tons. In 1992, President Bush
signed a proclamation prohibiting logging within 1,000 feet of a
sequoia.
</P>
<P>
   Several other groves are already protected because they are in
national parks, not national forests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has used the antiquities act to establish four monuments
and expand another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CORZINE-ROOTS-2TAKES-     04-08 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORZINE-ROOTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CORZINE COUNTRY, IDEA OF ETHNIC IDENTITY DIDN'T TAKE ROOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ill.)   By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAYLORVILLE, Ill. _ The name is Dutch. Probably.
</P>
<P>
   When Jon S. Corzine, the former chairman of Goldman Sachs and
now a Democratic candidate for the U.S. Senate from New Jersey,
waded into the thicket of ethnic politics recently, he made it
quite clear that he regretted his ill-considered humor about
Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his repeated expressions of regret, one thing
remained thoroughly unclear _ his own ethnic background, an issue
that he treated with a mixture of ignorance and indifference. Asked
about his background, in a state where such things tend not to be
treated casually, he said he was told his mother's lineage was
English and his father's side was either French or Italian.
</P>
<P>
   If he hasn't seemed all that interested in his own ethnic
identity, conversations with the people he grew up with here in the
prairielands of southern Illinois offered a glimpse why.
</P>
<P>
   There are certainly identifiable ethnic groups in Christian
County, including the Italians who came here to mine coal before
the mines petered out after World War II, about when Corzine was
born in 1948. It's just that Italian-Americans and other groups,
including a dwindling number of Jews, don't stand out as much as
they once might have, said Jack Mazzotti, owner of Rene's drug
store on the courthouse square.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older group cared about that kind of thing, but they're
dying out,'' said Mazzotti, who remembers Corzine with fondness and
admiration from their days at Taylorville High School. ``We're all
pretty much all-American Americans now _ we don't have that class
and ethnic background thing that you see in the cities.'' (Or in
New Jersey, where one voter in four is of Italian descent.)
</P>
<P>
   Christian County's homogeneity might explain why Corzine would
be loose-tongued about ethnic jokes, Mazzotti went on, although he
winced when he heard of his old friend's recent gaffes about
Italian contractors making ``cement shoes'' and Jewish lawyers
getting them out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine grew up on a farm across the railroad tracks from the
highway at Willey's Station, a few miles up the road from
Taylorville toward Decatur. His father, Roy Allen Corzine, farmed
the fields around the house and sold insurance, while his mother,
Nancy, taught first and second grades at Memorial Elementary School
in Taylorville.
</P>
<P>
   As a Senate candidate, Corzine has liked to emphasize his humble
origins, partly as an antidote to a charge made by his opponent in
the primary, former Gov. Jim Florio, that Corzine was trying to buy
the Senate seat with an immense television campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Corzine's grandfather, also Roy, was a prosperous farmer who
was a Republican state assemblyman for four years and was chairman
of the important Agriculture Committee. Still, Corzine was not
pampered as a youth, said Carolyn Dorris, the sole surviving aunt
of Joanne Corzine, Corzine's wife, who also grew up here and who
has known Corzine since kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Florio said he never had to work hard, but he certainly
did,'' Dorris said in an interview at the big ranch house in
Taylorville's comfortable northeast section that the Corzines
bought for her and for Corzine's mother before she died. ``But he
worked the farm, and when he went to the U of I he got a union card
and worked as a hod carrier. He carried cement _ you think that
isn't hard?''
</P>
<P>
   Dorris was as unaware and as uninterested in the question of
Corzine's family background as he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of thing just doesn't come up very much around
here,'' she said, and apparently the Corzines are not alone. David
Herbert Donald opens his 1995 biography of Abraham Lincoln, who
settled less than 30 miles from here in Sangamon County, with the
words, ``Abraham Lincoln was not interested in his ancestry.''
Lincoln told a would-be biographer that it was ``a folly'' to
inquire into his roots.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 1893 edition of ``Portrait and Biographical Record of
Christian County, Illinois,'' offers a fragmentary look at a
Corzine family, like Lincoln's and the other pioneer families
around here, slowly making its way west out of New York and
Pennsylvania with the retreating frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Schaffer Corzine, who moved to Christian County from Ohio
in 1861, had a father named Allen _ Jon Corzine's father's middle
name _ born in Pennsylvania in 1816, according to the Record. And
Jacob's great-grandfather was John Corzine Sr., the book reports,
``who came to America from Holland and settled in Manhattan Island,
where he owned 60 acres of land on which Wall Street now stands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' said the librarian at the Decatur County
Genealogical Society, ``you can only go by what they told somebody
back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there were already plenty of Corzines in Illinois before
Jacob Schaffer Corzine. Twenty-one Corzines fought in the Civil War
in Illinois regiments, none of them from Christian County. Today,
Jon Corzine's nearest local relatives live around the prairie
village of Assumption, 15 miles east of Taylorville.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jon Corzine, the Assumption Corzines are all tall,
Methodist and nearsighted _ but Republican _ and they took an
interest in their distant cousin when he began to get his name in
the papers as a New York bond trader. But Jon Corzine apparently
had no more interest in pursuing the matter of his past with
long-lost relatives than he had with New Jersey political
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad wrote him once after someone sent us an article about
him in The Wall Street Journal,'' said Bob Corzine, a retired
Assumption farmer. ``It seems like it was six months before he
wrote back, and he said he had no knowledge of us here.'' Bob
Corzine let that sink in for a moment and added, ``He said he had
no interest in genealogy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorris was inclined to disbelieve any ties with the Assumption
Corzines, even though they lived less than a half-hour's drive
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're related it's like their yeller dog ran through our
yard once some ways back,'' Dorris said, suggesting that any
connection was brief and distant. ``That's about as close as you
can get to not being related.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jack Mazzotti, the owner of Rene's drug store, had a more
charitable interpretation, saying that rich and successful people
could be hard to approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``His friends step back because they don't know whether to call
him or not,'' Mazzetti said. ``He's in a different stratosphere
now, and how do you approach him without setting off signals that
you want something?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids,'' as Dorris called Jon and Joanne Corzine, have
hardly ignored their old town. They built a park in honor of
Dorris' late husband, Keith, behind the First United Methodist
Church here, and Tom Campbell, the principal of Taylorville High
School, pointed out that they had endowed two scholarships for
graduates of their alma mater. One, for $1,500 a year for four
years, is paid through the Bertram Hopper Memorial Foundation, the
same foundation, created by founders of the Georgia-Pacific Co.,
that gave Jon a scholarship to the University of Illinois. The
second, in Jon Corzine's father's name, is for $500, and goes to a
Methodist student.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has also been generous with his money to schools in the
East, and Dorris said he had a strong instinct to do the right
thing. Since her late husband had served four terms as Taylorville
city clerk before he quit in disgust at all the politicking, Dorris
tried to warn her favorite nephew about what he was getting into.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he said he wanted to run I said, `Jon, politics is a
dirty game.' And he said, `I know, but we have to get some good
guys in or we'll only have scum.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1052 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKO-BASKETBALL-TRAGED     04-08 1990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-BASKETBALL-TRAGEDY0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court time cut short
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the afternoon of Sept. 16, Travis Davenport lifted
weights and shot hoops in his old high school gymnasium. Echoing
the advice of his doctors, his pastor and his mother, his closest
friends discouraged him from joining their pickup game. This time,
Travis listened.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball was his passion. He had played it year-round _ at
Fairburn, Georgia's Creekside High, in AAU leagues, on any
playground _ until the first in a series of fainting spells. Even
then, he occasionally would slip onto the court and run one.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days earlier, a cardiologist had restated in no
uncertain terms that he must give up the game. So Travis, obedient,
only tossed up casual jumpshots in the gym before heading south,
back to college in Cochran.
</P>
<P>
   That night, he collapsed again and died. He didn't quite make it
to midnight of his 19th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE OF THE GAME
</P>
<P>
   Say the name Travis Davenport to people who were touched by him
and, subconsciously or not, their response eventually includes
heart.
</P>
<P>
   He put his heart and soul into it. Had a heart of gold. Played
half-heartedly sometimes. Did not take the warnings to heart. Was
heartbroken that his medical condition boxed out a life of
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Davenport died of heart failure. He isn't the first
athlete to brush aside signs of serious trouble and not live to
regret it.
</P>
<P>
   The media are revisiting the tragic tale of Hank Gathers, a
shooting star for Loyola-Marymount. His fame had the life-span of a
shooting star. Gathers dropped dead of a heart attack during a game
10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If Davenport heard those stories, he was hesitant to heed their
message.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball became his dying affection. ``He kept playing, even
after he experienced blackouts,'' said the Rev. Timothy McDonald,
pastor of Travis' church, First Iconium Baptist. ``He loved it
maybe a little too much. (Basketball) is the only thing he got
excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis was in elementary school when his divorced mother,
Sandra, had a basketball goal installed for her only child. It
lasted two years before toppling over from wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   So Travis and his posse took their ball elsewhere. They evolved
into the self-dubbed Penthouse Crew, an intentionally ironic tag.
Their hub was the basement of a member's home, where they mapped
out the weekend or shared their NBA dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, Travis stood out, if for no other reason that he was
rising toward 6 feet 7 and expanding to 250 pounds. If a person's
popularity can be measured by his number of nicknames, Travis was
the Crew chief: first Trap, then Baby Shaq, most recently Big Baby.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Little Giant'' is how Trea Reed remembers him, little
because he was still a kid, unwilling to flick off the TV in hotel
rooms on summer-league road trips for fear of the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Although well into his teens, Travis could connect with
youngsters, which made for enjoyable jobs as camp counselor or
teacher's student aide. ``Like a Pied Piper,'' said Al Outlaw, who
coached one of his AAU teams. ``The kids climbed all over him.''
</P>
<P>
   To his pals, he was a pillar. He drove them to the mall so they
could buy birthday presents for their moms. When A.J. Moye was
sneaker-less before a game, Travis unlaced his own and handed them
over. ``He taught me what friendship was all about,'' Moye said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis had shot up to 6 feet 5 as a ninth-grader and became an
instant starter at Creekside. The freshman led the
graduation-depleted Seminoles in rebounding and was second in
scoring. His coach, Kirby Lamb, described him as D-1, a player with
Division I college potential.
</P>
<P>
   Travis partly squandered his talents, Lamb said. ``By the time
he was a junior, I was ready to kick him off,'' said the coach,
since retired from Creekside. ``He didn't listen very well. He
regressed.'' His work ethic? ``Terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were no gripes from the AAU end. ``He was hard-working
for me,'' Outlaw said.
</P>
<P>
   As a senior, Travis paced Creekside in points and rebounds.
Colleges on the outer fringes of D-1 cast an eye. One was Winthrop,
which made this year's NCAA Tournament. Another was Norfolk State,
which invited Travis to its campus. In an impromptu game there, he
passed out.
</P>
<P>
   When his mother heard, she flashed back to her senior year in
high school. Her boyfriend Johnny _ later her husband and Travis'
father _ had to quit football because of seizures. Could Travis
have inherited the trait?
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to Mrs. Davenport, omens already had appeared.
Travis, pleading exhaustion, had asked out of one Creekside game.
On the bench, he had acted oddly and complained of
light-headedness, Lamb said.
</P>
<P>
   During an out-of-state AAU game, he had asked for water, sat
down and fainted. When the paramedics arrived, a recovered Travis
shooed them away.
</P>
<P>
   The scare at Norfolk triggered a whirlwind of doctors'
appointments and a four-day hospital stay for assorted tests. The
malady was traced to his heart. Medicine and rest were prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Travis' obligation to each was spotty. Friends had to remind,
even force, him to swallow his pills and to swear off ball.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Travis was in his bedroom, about to accompany Trea
Reed and Kerry Willis to the movies, when he collapsed. Again, he
was back to normal as the paramedics pulled up.
</P>
<P>
   D-1 DREAMS DASHED
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, Travis and his mother consulted as
many as five cardiologists. She was motivated to find a definitive
diagnosis. He was shopping for something else _ a doctor who would
approve of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But with each stop, the chorus grew louder: Put away the ball
and get a defibrillator or pacemaker implanted to rein in your
irregular heartbeat. He never did.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Davenport says doctors ultimately traced the cause to a
viral infection. Travis' primary cardiologist declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never wanted to go to the doctors. He didn't like them,''
Reed said. ``They told him what he didn't want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   His true homeboys banned him from their informal games. But many
heard of Travis sightings, of him huffing up and down courts here
and there.
</P>
<P>
   Outlaw barred him from AAU tournaments. ``He was determined to
play,'' Outlaw said. ``I really don't think he realized how serious
it was. You know how kids feel: `I'm invincible.'''
</P>
<P>
   Insufficient entrance-exam scores had dashed his D-1 dreams. Now
his precarious health was dooming him at any level of college ball.
So he chose to keep his condition a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Hatcher, coach at Middle Georgia Junior College, was
familiar with Travis by word of mouth. He came to the Davenports'
home to sign Travis on reputation alone. Only as the ink was drying
was he informed that there might be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it would be hard for him'' to quit, Kerry Willis said.
His mother said, ``I was worried about him having to sit and
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   As summer faded, Travis enrolled at Middle Georgia. Even if he
would never suit up, he was a college student _ the first among his
beaming relatives. ``Travis was like a beacon to them, a source of
pride,'' Outlaw said.
</P>
<P>
   In Cochran _ beyond the watch of his mother and concerned
acquaintances _ Travis could not resist basketball's lure. He
joined the team for pickup games before official practices began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played every day about 2:30,'' said his roommate, Marcus
Smith. ``Travis played for about a week.'' Smith said the coach got
word and put a halt to it.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was struck by how Travis labored in the games, needing
extended rests. Travis was hefty but hardly overweight.
</P>
<P>
   His roommate became a surrogate parent, worrying each night how
he would cope if Travis had a heart attack and forbidding him each
day from playing. ``Told him I'd kick his tail if he tried,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   BITTER ACCEPTANCE
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 11, Mrs. Davenport made her regular two-hour Saturday
morning drive to Cochran to fetch Travis. Customarily, she returned
him Sunday night, but he stayed over for a doctor's appointment on
Tuesday. There, Travis heard the hurtful words once more, louder
than before: Forget basketball. It's over. Get a pacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' she said, ``is when he came to the realization.'' They
prayed together, asking for guidance. They agreed that Travis could
find eventual solace in a teaching career.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a bitter acceptance. ``Mom, I can't understand
it,'' he told her. ``I get this far _ and this happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The next night, she stayed home from church to grant Travis'
wish of a pre-birthday meal with his favorite dishes _ short ribs,
macaroni and cheese, collard greens. Thursday afternoon, the gym at
Creekside was filled with friends, some home from colleges in South
Georgia that had closed because of Hurricane Floyd. Travis wanted
to run with them. ``We wouldn't let him,'' Willis said.
</P>
<P>
   So, he shot around and delivered his trademark bearhugs,
squeezing the breath out of his buddies. ``You made it to 19,''
A.J. Moye told him.
</P>
<P>
   Then he drove south, stopping by the dorm in Cochran to invite
his roommate out for a birthday celebration. Marcus Smith begged
off, citing studies, but Travis found an old Creekside crony to tag
along to a club in nearby Macon.
</P>
<P>
   They stayed a short time. Travis was walking to the car for the
ride back when he collapsed. Death came quickly.
</P>
<P>
   As the news spread north by telephone over the next 24 hours,
reactions ranged from disbelief to uncontrollable grief. Nobody was
more affected than Moye, who was expecting a guest _ Bob Knight.
The Indiana coach was paying his in-house visit to the junior from
Westlake High.
</P>
<P>
   When Knight arrived, Moye was in a back room, sobbing and
pounding the floor in helpless anger. The irascible, often
insensitive coach offered to return another time. Moye said he
could stay, and Knight comforted him with an embrace. The gesture
helped seal Moye's decision to sign with Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The Penthouse Crew's survivors hung together through the
weekend, reminiscing, going to the movies, smothering their
sadness. They searched their consciences to ask what more they
could have done for Travis.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knew the whole truth of his risky romance with
basketball, of his failing health. But some had braced themselves
for the worst. ``I knew he was going to keep playing,'' Outlaw
said. ``If he was going to go, he wanted it to be with a basketball
in his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Funeral-goers filled the 1,000 seats in the First Iconium
Baptist Church and spilled outside. Creekside let out so students
could attend. The Middle Georgia team arrived in a van.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral procession snaked along to Forest Lawn Memorial
Gardens, where Travis was buried under a tombstone decorated by his
longtime jersey number, 40. A half-year later, Mrs. Davenport is
reminded of Travis each time she walks by a large glass case in her
living room. The shrine includes photos, trophies, a diploma,
videotapes of Creekside games, a jersey donated by Lamb, a Bible, a
single rose, a toy white dove, a copy of the poem ``Heading Home''
and a gift from the neighborhood kids of an angel clutching a
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Davenport was not alone in missing Travis.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Bo Kimble carved out an enduring memory of any
NCAA Tournament when he awkwardly sank a free throw left-handed in
honor of his deceased friend, Hank Gathers. Travis' chums all
honored him on their various teams by writing his name, number or a
favorite nickname on their sneakers and wristbands. Trea Reed has
picked out a vacancy on his arm for a tattoo of a No. 40 with
angel's wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a family and we lost our link,'' said A.J. Moye, who
then repeated the word that seems unavoidable when the topic is
Travis Davenport. ``He had a heart as big as he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
