<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, April 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wintry weather will cover much of the upper Midwest and
Northeast in the wake of a potent low-pressure system moving into
eastern Canada. Rain will end Sunday morning in eastern New England
as a potent cold front sweeps offshore. In the wake of the front,
periods of snow will linger into the afternoon from the Adirondacks
to the Green and White Mountains. Winds from the northwest
averaging 20 to 30 miles an hour will draw much colder air from
central Canada into the interior Northeast and Middle Atlantic
states. Farther west, a fast-moving disturbance will promote snow
showers from the northern Great Lakes to the west slopes of the
central Appalachians. Overnight, temperatures will fall below
freezing from the Dakotas to the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   After a cold dawn, the Southeast will be sunny and rather cool.
The Western states will be mild, but some mountain showers will
occur from Oregon to the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: APRIL SNOW
</P>
<P>
   Unless it is falling very heavily, snow does not easily
accumulate on roads during the daytime in April. The strengthening
April sun penetrates the overcast, helping to keep pavements warm
and discouraging snow from accumulating. On Friday morning, it
began to snow rather heavily across parts of Iowa and Wisconsin.
Initially, the snow whitened grassy surfaces, which absorb less
solar energy than pavements. As heavy snow continued into the
evening, snow built up more rapidly on roads.
</P>
</TEXT>
