<SLUG> BC-EDIT-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: KOFI ANNAN'S MILLENNIAL VISION  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, April 9:
</P>
<P>
   Part of Kofi Annan's job as secretary-general of the United
Nations is to think big thoughts about the future of the planet.
Last week he made the most of that responsibility by outlining an
audacious vision for the world organization in the 21st century. It
would be easy to dismiss Annan's comprehensive vision as, in his
own words, ``absurdly ambitious.'' But it deserves a wide audience.
</P>
<P>
   In a report setting the agenda for a millennium assembly in New
York in September to which all the world's leaders are invited,
Annan reiterated his advocacy of environmental protection, military
interventions to stop genocide and mass murder, and curbs on
weapons proliferation. But his most intriguing appeals focused on
imaginative efforts among states, nongovernmental organizations and
the private sector to fight poverty and disease.
</P>
<P>
   Annan is right to suggest that the United Nations take the lead
in bringing the Internet and other information technologies to poor
nations. Throughout the developing world the Internet can greatly
enhance access to markets, government efficiency and education at
all levels.
</P>
<P>
   He announced plans to create an innovative volunteer corps, the
U.N. Information Technology Service, to train groups in developing
countries to use the Internet. He proposed an Internet health-care
network for 10,000 online terminals in hospitals and clinics to
provide access to medical information.
</P>
<P>
   Annan stakes out worthy goals for the next 15 years: to halve
the proportion of the world's people _ currently one in five _
whose income is less than a dollar a day, and to halve the
proportion of people _ also one in five _ without access to safe
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   He endorses a World Bank plan to improve the lives of 100
million slum dwellers by 2020. He proposes that the United Nations
work with the pharmaceutical industry and other partners to develop
an affordable vaccine against AIDS, and sets a goal of reducing HIV
infection rates among young adults by 25 percent in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the world will fall far short of these targets. Only a
day after Annan's report was released, the U.N. Development Program
concluded that there has been little progress in combating poverty
in the last five years. The main impediments, it found, were
corrupt and authoritarian governments.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States and other industrialized countries could
help by heeding Annan's call to drop their trade barriers against
exports from the least developed countries and lifting the debt of
poor countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-ANGLERS-NYT &LR;      04-08 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-ANGLERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: SALTY FLYRODDING COMES OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER KAMINSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a cold, rainy day in early spring, the idea of getting
together with a bunch of fellow anglers and swapping stories around
a warm fire was as close to fishing as I was going to get. At the
North Shore guest cottage of the light tackle guide and
restaurateur James Kang, the anglers were there but so, too, was
the chill, largely because the heat pipes had burst in the one cold
spell of winter. We warmed ourselves with plates of hot lasagna and
crabcakes and got down to business.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion of the meeting was more than an opportunity to
weave fish tales. The 17 guides on hand represented a vanguard of
the hundred or so flyrodder charter captains who have pioneered the
sport in metropolitan area waters. With fast growth, however, there
have come growing pains: guides who poach on each other's clients,
trash-talk about the competition, crowding at hot spots.
</P>
<P>
   These real-world difficulties are the kinds of things most of us
try to escape when we go off fly-fishing. But when you spend 150
days on the water in fair weather and foul and you have the kind of
kind of loner cowboy personality that makes you take up a career in
a little boat all by yourself, you are inevitably going to run into
elbow room problems.
</P>
<P>
   These nettlesome turf wars pale by comparison to the larger
environmental issues that confront all anglers. The great striper
comeback of the 1990s was caused in large part by enlightened (and
enforced) regulations and, notably, the ban on commercial fishing
in the greatest of all striper nurseries, Chesapeake Bay. In the
last few seasons, decreasing size limits, increased recreational
and commercial pressure and the opening of Chesapeake Bay to
netting mean that unless anglers organize and take important
conservation steps the hard-won resurgence of the striper may be
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not many businesses where you have only one supplier
and that supplier determines everything,'' said Frank Crescitelli,
a charter captain who was one of the prime movers behind the
guides' meeting and the professional association born of it. ``Our
only supplier is Mother Nature. If we mess up, she's gone and we're
out of business.'' This sentiment was echoed by others, including
the group's co-founders, Ernie French and Scott Holder.
</P>
<P>
   With conservation high on the agenda, the nascent group plans to
promote it both by example and by political pressure. Adopting the
catch-and-release ethic of trout fishing (out of which saltwater
fly-fishing developed), the organization will actively promote
no-kill striper fishing. By law, clients are allowed to keep two
fish, but all customers will be told that catch and release is the
goal and, in any case, no more than one striper may be kept.
</P>
<P>
   The guides also intend to keep less than their limit of
weakfish, flounder and bluefish. ``The law says you can keep 10
fish per day,'' Crescitelli said, ``but who ever needs, or uses, 10
bluefish?'' This is certainly the first time that charter captains
in our area (and to my knowledge, in the rest of the country as
well) have adopted a policy of taking less than the legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   The group also plans to band together to attend hearings and
pressure legislators who know well that one guide speaks for
hundreds of angler/voters. All fisherfolk need to exercising some
political muscle right now, Holder pointed out, as competing New
York state Senate and Assembly bills have languished, during which
time the Department of Environmental Conservation's legal ability
to regulate key aspects of striped bass fishing expired.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term effect of this inaction, according to Gordon
Colvin of the Department of Environmental Conservation, could be
that New York state will be found in violation of the rules of the
Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission, set up to oversee the
recovery of striped bass. That could lead to extreme restriction on
the fishery and, ultimately, its closure.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm raised by concerned angler/conservationists _
including the guides' group _ has roused legislators in Albany. The
Senate approved a compromise bill on April 5 and all that remains
to guarantee the opening of the striper season on May 8 is for the
Assembly to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   In a hands-on effort to promote conservation of pressured
resources, the guides plan to designate stewards for heavily fished
areas. Their job will be to inform others in the group when fishing
pressure on a particular spot is driving fish away. In that event,
all guides will agree to give the particular flat, shoal or rip a
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Here as elsewhere, the new association can suggest but not
enforce: nonetheless, the attendees unanimously agreed that these
are achievable goals. And the benefits of things like group
advertising, a collective Web presence and lower insurance rates
offer incentives beyond mere comity and good citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The first true test of the spirit at the recent meeting came
when the captains were asked to reach into their pockets. Jim
Levison, a retired New York City detective and East Hampton guide,
was appointed treasurer; he collected $50 apiece from the guides as
an initiation fee, with dues to be set later.
</P>
<P>
   We all ended the day agreeing that New York flyrodding had taken
an important first step.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
