<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      04-08 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE FATHER, LIKE SON 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of NASCAR's top drivers are aging gracefully, a testament
to the value of experience. But one tip-off that they are aging is
the budding proliferation of father-son drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring example: the Earnhardts, Dale Jr. and Sr. The
elder Earnhardt, who will be 49 this month, is a seven-time Winston
Cup series champion, and he stands fourth in this season's
standing. Junior, as his son is known, is a 25-year-old rookie who
just joined this season's list of winners.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with Junior's victory last week in Fort Worth, Texas,
the Earnhardts became the first father and son to win a Winston Cup
race in the same season since Bobby and Davey Allison in 1988.
Earnhardt Sr. won at Atlanta Motor Speedway last month.
</P>
<P>
   It took Junior just 12 races to make it to the winner's lane,
four fewer than his father required 21 years ago. ``Now we'll see
how big his head gets,'' Earnhardt Sr. said playfully after his
son's victory.
</P>
<P>
   As next week's racing shifts to storied Talladega, Ala., other
father-son drivers looking eventually to rival the Earnhardts
include the Pettys (Kyle and his son Adam), the Marlins (Sterling
and Steadman, who made his Busch series debut Saturday), the
Jarretts (Dale, the defending Winston Cup champion, and Jason), the
Labontes (Terry and Justin) and the Bodines (Geoffrey and Barry).
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting how Earnhardt Sr., stoic and gruff, approached
his son's slump before the breakthrough victory in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Right or wrong, Junior felt he needed some encouragement after
qualifying high but having trouble-filled finishes of 29th, 40th
and 38th. His father, working on his own car, gave no pep talks.
</P>
<P>
   At home after the poor finishes, Junior noticed that the phone
did not ring nearly as often as it had after his 10th-place in Las
Vegas. That bothered him because he figured this was going to be
his life's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can beat yourself up only so much,'' he said, ``before you
take a lot of confidence away from yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Gary Nelson, a former crew chief who is NASCAR's
Winston Cup director. Unsolicited, Nelson told Junior two days
before the Forth Worth race that he had a fine future. ``He said I
just needed to calm down,'' Junior said. ``It was good to hear. I
haven't heard that from anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior had come into the Winston Cup series as a two-time
champion of the Busch series, a fierce training ground for future
Winston Cup drivers. Still, he felt that Nelson gave him a
much-needed boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like being in a marriage,'' he said. ``Even though your
wife knows you love her, you've still got to tell her sometimes.
That was kind of the situation I was in. Like it'd be nice to get
patted on the back sometimes even though we had a bad weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he did think his father gave him some valuable advice after
the victory. ``He said to enjoy the moment and how it feels,'' and
then move on, Junior said. ``He knows that just as easily we could
have three more bad weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart established a benchmark for rookies last year when
he won three races and finished fourth in the point standing.
Earnhardt is ahead of him in one respect, though _ Stewart did not
win a race until his 25th start.
</P>
<P>
   Spreading the Wealth
</P>
<P>
   After seven Winston Cup races, there have been seven winners.
One more new winner and it will be a modern-era record to start a
season. Safety First  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the first Winston Cup race this year _ when one of Tony
Stewart's tire changers broke his leg when the car slammed into him
leaving the pit area in the Daytona 500 _ working on pit road has
proven more dangerous than steering a car at 180 miles an hour. And
losing control of right-side tires after they have been pulled from
a car has been a particularly troublesome safety hazard for both
crew and car.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sunday in Martinsville, Va., NASCAR officials will
penalize teams if they neglect to remove their right-side tires
from the pit box. It is a rule that may save a life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
