<SLUG> BC-NY-OFFICER-DEMOTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE OFFICIAL DEMOTED OVER RACIST REMARKS  
 BY JAYSON BLAIR  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The commander of a Queens police precinct was demoted
after participating in a conversation laced with racist jokes about
his supervisor, the Police Department's highest ranking
Asian-American, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The commander, Capt. Joseph T. Culbert, took part in the
conversation with a lieutenant and a police officer after he spoke
by cellular phone with the supervisor, Deputy Chief Dewey Fong.
Culbert thought he had hung up, but the call did not disconnect.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that Culbert then joined in ``an
inappropriate conversation'' that was inadvertently recovered on
Fong's cellular telephone's voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Culbert had made the call while driving to Brooklyn as part of
the crowd control unit for the funeral of Patrick Dorismond, an
unarmed man who was killed by an undercover officer last month.
</P>
<P>
   According to the officials, one of the other officers questioned
Fong's intelligence and then asked how Culbert could take orders
from someone who was not smart and ``looks like a Chinese takeout
deliveryman.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that the three men began laughing and that
Culbert then joined in for several minutes of what were described
as jokes about Fong. The police did not release specifics about
what the captain was accused of saying.
</P>
<P>
   Fong later heard the comments while listening to his voice mail,
officials said, and then reported them to the office of Deputy
Police Commissioner Neldra M. Zeigler, who oversees the
department's division that investigates complaints of
discrimination and harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Culbert and Fong did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
Police officials did not say whether the other officers involved
were disciplined or transferred.
</P>
<P>
   Culbert, who was the commander of the 104th Precinct in the
Ridgewood section of Queens, was transferred to a night position in
the Strategic and Tactical Command, which is responsible for
policing northern Brooklyn. His demotion was reported in Saturday's
editions of The New York Daily News and The New York Post.
</P>
</TEXT>
