<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-MESS-NYT &LR;      04-08 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-MESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRONG ANSWER TO THE BIG QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hockey's version of the worst team money could buy
ends its season in profound indifference at Madison Square Garden
Sunday afternoon, when the New York Rangers play host to the
Philadelphia Flyers on the final day of the National Hockey
League's regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers are going to the playoffs, perhaps as the top-seeded
team in the Eastern Conference. They have persevered even without
Eric Lindros, their former captain, who is suffering from yet
another of the concussions that threaten to end his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers? They are going home for the summer. Again.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden and Cablevision were not the only ones who did not
get their money's worth for a payroll in excess of $61 million, the
highest in the history of the league. Neither did the Rangers'
ticket holders, not this season nor either of the last two, as the
Rangers failed to qualify for the postseason for three consecutive
seasons for the first time since some of the franchise's darkest
days in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who realistically took themselves out of the
playoff picture three weeks ago, were officially eliminated from
playoff contention last weekend. They ended up with a major
house-cleaning, instead. With four games remaining in the season,
Dave Checketts, president of the Garden, fired Rangers General
Manager Neil Smith and Coach John Muckler on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the Rangers were looking back at Wayne Gretzky's
career and forward to an off-season spending spree. Then, over
seven underachieving, passionless, often agonizing months, the
Rangers provided an answer to this question: What difference does
$67 million worth of free-agent signings make?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: Not very much.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive season, the Rangers will finish with a
losing record at home. They have been pushed around by bigger teams
for years. They have not made the playoffs since Mark Messier
headed west for Vancouver in the summer of 1997 after a messy
divorce from the organization that he willed to its first Stanley
Cup title in 54 years.
</P>
<P>
   With Checketts' blessing, Smith, in his 11th season as general
manager, gobbled up every major free agent on the market last
summer. Smith was hoping to build a stopgap between the present and
a future built around prospects like Manny Malhotra, Pavel Brendl
and Jamie Lundmark.
</P>
<P>
   What Smith wound up with, however, was something very different,
more like the New York Mets of the early 1990s: an expensive
rotisserie team that stopped dead in its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the end of the 1992-93 season, when the Rangers lost
11 of their last 12 games, including the last seven, have the
Rangers stumbled this badly to the finish line. With one game
remaining in their season, the Rangers are 1-10-2 over their last
13 games. They are without a victory (0-7-1) in their last eight.
</P>
<P>
   As Rob DiMaio, whom the Rangers obtained just before the March
14 trading deadline, observed about his one-month stint with a team
bound for nowhere: ``There's no passion. There's no life. There's
no talking. There's no direction. I've never seen anything like it.
It's not hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   At least following the 1992-93 season, the Rangers went on to
win the Cup the next season. The foundation was already there,
however. In 1991-92, the Rangers had won the President's Trophy,
signifying the team with the league's best record. These current
Rangers have not had a winning season since Messier left.
</P>
<P>
   And they are built, as usual, around aging veterans, although
this season provided some bright spots for some younger players,
too. But the performances of Mike York, Jan Hlavac, Radek Dvorak
and Kim Johnsson were all too often dulled by the many failures of
the supposed stars: Theo Fleury, Valery Kamensky, Kevin Hatcher ...
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the changes start in the front office, as Checketts
heads a search for a new general manager. He hopes it will be
complete before the entry draft, which begins in Calgary on June
24. The new general manager will then pick the new coach. Both will
inherit a mess.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong? What didn't?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of a lot of things,'' said Tim Taylor,
one of last summer's free-agent signings, who became something
close to the conscience of the club this season. ``But if everyone
had played to their potential, we wouldn't be in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   Had any of the high-priced veterans even approached their normal
outputs of seasons past, there would never have been a full-scale
purge. They did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody getting used to each other and growing together,
that's something that took longer than a year as well,'' Taylor
said. ``We need to get a system that fits our team. You can't
pinpoint one thing. There are a couple of things that need to be
straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had been able to weather the 32 games they were
without their captain, Brian Leetch, who broke his right forearm on
Nov. 24. But once goaltender Mike Richter tore the anterior
cruciate ligament in his left knee during the All-Star skills
competition Feb. 5 _ the moment Muckler correctly termed the
season's turning point _ the Rangers' fortunes went into a
tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect metaphor for the season may have been Richter vainly
attempting to play the final two months on one good leg.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's worst fear was that he would be twinned with Muckler, if
and when the firings came. That is why Smith was believed to have
sought permission, without success, to have Muckler removed in
mid-November, a month and a half into a terrible season start.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's future was intertwined with Muckler's in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury, who has a measly 15 goals to show for a salary of
$8.5million this season, has acknowledged that the worst
performance of his career helped lead to the dual dismissals of
coach and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury said on the day of the firings: ``I don't think it's
entirely Muck's fault. I can take some of the blame. Obviously, I
haven't played as well as I wanted to. But in the end, it's always
the coach that takes the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   And by the end, Muckler had obviously tired of Fleury's act.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his mind, he felt I wasn't working as hard as I could or
playing as well as I could,'' Fleury said, adding that part of the
problem might have stemmed from Muckler's thinking that Fleury was
still the same ``hell-bent for leather'' type of player he had been
in Calgary a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my role at that time was a lot different then what it is
now,'' Fleury said. ``We just didn't see eye to eye on how I'm
supposed to play and what his expectations of me were.''
</P>
<P>
   That was precisely the Rangers' problem this season: Almost all
their expectations went unfulfilled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
