u e BC-OPERA-FLOYD0409A-COX     04-08 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-FLOYD0409A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Sassy Tree' composer lends Southern voice
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Like many folks, Carlisle Floyd confesses to a
love-hate relationship with the South. But he knows a rich,
melodramatic setting for opera when he sees it.
</P>
<P>
   The South has been the location for several works by the Latta,
S.C., native _ from Tennessee (``Susannah'') to South Carolina
(``The Passion of Jonathan Wade'') to Louisiana (``Willie Stark'').
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's newest opera, ``Cold Sassy Tree,'' is the
turn-of-the-century story of small-town life set in a North Georgia
town based on Commerce. Inspired by the 1984 novel by Atlanta
writer Olive Ann Burns, ``Cold Sassy Tree'' receives its world
premiere Friday at the Houston Grand Opera, which Floyd has been
associated with since 1976, when the college music professor moved
from Florida State University to the University of Houston. It's
being directed by filmmaker _ and opera enthusiast _ Bruce
Beresford (``Driving Miss Daisy'').
</P>
<P>
   The son of an itinerant Methodist minister, Floyd, 73, sat down
recently to discuss his Southern geography, and that of his operas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the South attracts the opera composer?
</P>
<P>
   A: The larger-than-life characters. The South tends to cherish
its eccentrics, and it has its own special kind of romance and
allure. And all of that was in the novel (``Cold Sassy Tree'').
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did ``Cold Sassy Tree'' come about?
</P>
<P>
   A: My sister, who lives in a little town called Holly Hills
(S.C.), gave it to me to read. I didn't know of its enormous
popularity, which I've since discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What attracted you to the material?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a curious book, such a mix of serious and comic, which
gave me a lot of trepidation. At first I thought, how can these
things co-exist side by side? And yet, that's the nature of
(Burns') work. It has very serious moments and then will turn
immediately very comic. I think that may be something pretty
specifically Southern, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The writing process took you home, didn't it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Writing the libretto, I felt like I had returned to my
childhood, in terms of hearing the language. (Burns) had an
incredible ear for dialogue. And that's something I think I'm
fairly skilled in recognizing. Her use of expressions, her
language, is absolutely stenographic.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did adapting the book pose problems?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. It's very episodic, like a series of vignettes rather
than anything narrative. The attractive thing was the vivid
characters. The locale, the color. That appealed to me very much.
My problem was to make some sort of dramatic narrative that can be
set to music.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was it like as a kid named Carlisle?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, my sister's name is Ermine, like the fur. You can
imagine as children growing up as Carlisle and Ermine. That's
pretty heavy; we wanted to be Betty Ann and Tom. But I quite like
Carlisle now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
