<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-FLAG0409-COX     04-08 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-FLAG0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia faces possible boycott over state flag
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When former Gov. Zell Miller decided to take the lead
on changing Georgia's flag seven years ago, he ran into a
Legislature deeply divided and unwilling to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Some things haven't changed in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be practical _ there are not the votes in the
General Assembly right now to change the flag,'' Gov. Roy Barnes
said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes promised only to ``continue to have dialogue'' over the
issue, but civil rights groups are pushing for more. They want
lawmakers to remove the Confederate battle emblem added to the
state flag during the height of the integration debates in 1956,
and they vow an economic boycott of the state next year if their
demands are ignored.
</P>
<P>
   That ultimatum by the Southern Christian Leadership Conference
last week, and growing protests over the Confederate banner flying
atop the capitol in neighboring South Carolina, have made the flag
flap an unavoidable controversy for lawmakers next January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a decision this session to forego it and wait until
2001,'' said Rep. Calvin Smyre (D-Columbus), an African-American
lawmaker who chairs both the powerful House Rules Committee and
House Democratic Caucus. ``I don't know if we could put our finger
in the dike again and keep the dam from breaking.''
</P>
<P>
   But how state officials will handle the explosive issue _ so
volatile that it polarized the state and jeopardized the
re-election of the last governor to touch it _ remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has refused so far to weigh in on the topic, even though
most political experts say he will have to take an active role if a
flag change occurs next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief and somewhat reluctant response to questions last
week, Barnes called the flag ``an important issue'' and discouraged
a boycott he said would punish African-American businesses as well
as the rest of the state. But he didn't comment on his role, and he
continued to focus on initiatives like his massive overhaul of the
education system as top priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, though, top Democrats like Smyre and former
Atlanta Mayor Maynard Jackson, who favor changing the flag, seem to
be trying to cool the rhetoric to keep it from bubbling over into
the 2000 elections, when all 236 seats of the Legislature are up
for a vote. At the same time, they're talking about building a
coalition of business, political and civic leaders to lead and give
political cover to flag-changing efforts in the 2001 General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to figure out a way to avoid a confrontation,''
said Rep. Tyrone Brooks (D-Atlanta), a leader in the anti-flag
movement. He said leaders have suggested he could expect ``more
dialogue, more jelling of support'' after the elections.
</P>
<P>
   The flag, which represents pride in heritage for some, and an
intense legacy of racism and the Old South for others, is still a
touchy subject in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of newcomers without the sentimental attachment to
the banner could dilute the controversy in the metro Atlanta
suburbs. But talk of removing the Confederate emblem is still
enough to rally stiff opposition in some rural districts in North
and South Georgia, as Miller's 1993 push demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who is perhaps the most popular in Georgia's
history for his HOPE scholarship and pre-kindergarten programs,
narrowly made it back for a second term after initiating the flag
fight a year before the 1994 elections. Miller has said his
persistence on the issue wasted a lot of political capital and
probably made the flag more difficult for future lawmakers to
address.
</P>
<P>
   Those lessons aren't lost on legislators reluctant to reopen the
fight. During his bid for governor in 1998, Barnes said he didn't
favor resurrecting the issue. Even though African-Americans are one
of the strongest and most reliable voting blocks for Democrats, it
was three Republican lawmakers from the state's urban areas got the
most attention for advocating a new flag this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hot issue you don't win on,'' House Majority Leader
Larry Walker (D-Perry) said this week , explaining that most
lawmakers don't have a clear mandate from their districts _ not
even the No. 2 Democrat in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on that,'' Walker said of his
position on the flag. ``I'll cross that bridge when I come to it.''
When may be the key question. Political experts differ on the
likely timing.
</P>
<P>
   Emory University political scientist Merle Black said 2001
offers perhaps the best opportunity for lawmakers to unfurl the
debate. Near the peak of his popularity, Barnes could leverage
substantial clout on the issue, with another year and legislative
session to buffer his re-election bid. And he may need to satisfy
black voters _ a key to his victory in 1998. ``The last thing he
wants is an open disagreement with black voters in Georgia,'' Black
said.
</P>
<P>
   But University of Georgia political scientist Charles Bullock
speculated that Democratic leaders will try to stave off a vote on
the flag for at least another couple of years, perhaps into Barnes'
second term, to keep from splintering their fragile alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a minimum they want to get through redistricting'' in late
2001. Redrawing districts for Congress and the Legislature
determines the balance of power in the state. With a racially
divisive battle over the flag, ``the leadership,'' Bullock said
``could easily lose control of redistricting _ or maybe lose
control'' of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BUFFALO-ECONOMY-ART-7     04-08 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFALO-ECONOMY-ART-710(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER ECONOMY: A CITY WHERE THE LIVING, AND THE LEAVING, IS
EASY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: This introductory note is publishable: Upstate New York, a
vast, diverse landscape of old cities, small towns, farms and
forests stretching from Buffalo to Albany and north to the Canadian
border, was once one of the most populous and prosperous regions of
the country. But the national economic boom that swept into New
York City and its suburbs passed it by. This is the first of an
occasional series on the region's quest for prosperity.) By LESLIE
EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ If this city wanted a ruefully honest bumper
sticker, it would read, ``Buffalo: Love It and Leave It.''
</P>
<P>
   The slogan sums up the conundrum that is Buffalo, a city that
people say they love to live in and yet are leaving in droves.
</P>
<P>
   Once a bustling home to 1.1 million people, Erie County, which
includes Buffalo and its suburbs, now has 926,000 and is shrinking
fast. Last year alone, more than 10,000 people moved away, leading
to one of the steepest population drops of any county in the
nation, according to new federal census estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The departees are not retirees seeking the sun. They are young
and middle-age people seeking better jobs _ or any job at all. And
despite a burst of better economic news in Buffalo, the exodus
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been leaving for 10, 20, 30 years,'' said Anthony
M. Masiello, the city's mayor. ``We're not going to see a
significant reversal of that for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it now has fewer residents than Staten Island, Buffalo
remains New York's second largest city, which helps explain why the
presidential candidates have been much in evidence. So have Hillary
Rodham Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani, the contenders for Senate.
Reigniting the economy is the biggest campaign issue upstate.
</P>
<P>
   But while politicians offer programs and policies, the reality
of Buffalo is not simply economic. It is historic, geographic,
demographic and psychological.
</P>
<P>
   Far more than in other parts of upstate New York that have also
lost residents, the shrinking of Buffalo seems to have seeped into
the city's soul and become part of its identity, as much as eating
spicy chicken wings and rooting for the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   You can see it in politics: The new county executive won an
upset victory with the campaign slogan ``Keep Our Kids.'' You see
it in home prices, which have scarcely budged in a decade. You see
it on the streets, built for heavier traffic (one of the joys of
Buffalo is being able to drive just about anywhere, including to
the airport, in less than 20 minutes). You see it in the local
sense of humor. One way to tell that you're from Buffalo, the joke
goes, is that half of your friends moved to Charlotte, N.C., and
the other half went to Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   And you can see it at Erie Community College's Williamsville
campus northeast of Buffalo. There, for years, a criminal justice
program has trained officers for local police departments and the
New York State Police. Now, it sends graduates to Virginia, Georgia
and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, it's good and it's sad,'' said Timothy J. Dwan, a local
judge who teaches at Erie. ``Our kids are getting darn good jobs,
but it's sad the South is plucking all the talent from the
Northeast.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pied Piper of Erie County may well be Rick Veit, the
employment manager for the government of Gwinnett County, Ga., just
north of Atlanta. Gwinnett is one of the fastest-growing counties
in the nation. This year, Veit needs to hire 30 to 50 police
officers, no easy task when unemployment is 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Veit grew up in Erie County, and a couple of years ago, he
got the bright idea of going home to recruit. He has hired 41
officers from western New York, 11 from Erie Community College
alone, and visited the college again last month to screen more than
200 potential recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Edward Smith, 29, who qualifies as a walking
piece of Buffalo history: He works at a grain elevator, as his
father and grandfather did. But the elevators, which were invented
in Buffalo in the 1840s, are now mostly abandoned, and there is
little to do at the few that remain. ``We drink a lot of coffee,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   His friend Jeff DeLair personifies a current trend in Buffalo _
underemployment, in which people take jobs for which they are
overqualified. Almost 127,000 workers in Buffalo have jobs but want
better ones, according to a recent study. The jobless rate in Erie
County is 6 percent, the highest of any major metropolitan area in
the United States (the national average is 4.4 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems tough to get a job up here,'' said DeLair, 25, who
has a bachelor's degree in criminal justice but works for a soda
distributor. ``The economy and the population; everybody's moving
south.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   People have been leaving New York City, too, but immigrants from
overseas have more than made up for the loss. Buffalo once was a
city of immigrants _ from Italy, Germany, Ireland, Poland _ but no
more.
</P>
<P>
   That means fewer workers. ``The shrinkage in the labor force can
create further pressures in terms of labor shortages,'' said
Richard Deitz, an economist for the Federal Reserve Bank in
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   So despite today's relatively high unemployment rate, companies
have to worry about finding enough workers in the future.
</P>
<P>
   That is definitely on the mind of Kevin J. Clarke, vice
president and general manager of Quebecor Printing Buffalo, which
embodies both the hope and the risk in Erie County today. Hope,
because business is booming at the printing plant, which is so big
that managers get around on bicycles. Presses the size of small
buildings run day and night, churning out paperback best sellers,
travel guides, even the drugstore coupon books that tumble out of
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Quebecor is one of several large manufacturers around Buffalo
with expansion plans, which for Clarke means hiring at least 300
people in the next two or three years. That is where the risk comes
in.
</P>
<P>
   Where is he going to find them?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at our work force, who they are, how old they
are, how many will leave and retire, and how to replace them,''
Clarke said. ``In eight years, there's a very, very frightening
amount of skilled workers we're going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   As he talked about his recruiting plans, Clarke raved about the
pleasures of living in Buffalo: good schools, affordable housing,
short drives to and from work. He can say these things, he
explained, because he is from Long Island. ``People who are local,
all they see is what it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   It used to be really something. At the turn of the 19th century,
Buffalo was the site of the Pan-American Exposition (where
President William McKinley was assassinated). Its steel mills once
lined Lake Erie. Grain elevators clustered along the Buffalo River.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lloyd Wright designed the first air-conditioned office
building here, as well as several homes; Louis Sullivan built an
early skyscraper, and McKim, Mead &AMP; White contributed mansions
along Delaware Avenue. City Hall is an Art Deco extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the beautiful buildings are still here, but the
prosperity that paid for them is gone. Development of the St.
Lawrence Seaway in the 1950s ended Buffalo's reign as a
transportation hub. In the 1970s, the steel mills began to close.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo still makes auto parts, but it is more than its economy
that makes the city part of the Rust Belt. Geographically closer to
Cleveland than to Queens, Buffalo looks like the Midwest, from the
huge bowl of sky over the flat country to the gravy that comes on a
turkey sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the niceness. To a degree few downstaters
understand, people really like living in Buffalo, which they say
has the advantages of a big city but feels like a small town.
Though parts of Erie County resemble Westchester County, ``you
don't have to be a big shot to have a house like the Clintons',''
said Daniel J. Ryan, director of career planning for the University
of Buffalo. ``And you know about the 6 degrees of separation? In
Buffalo, it's 2 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people believe the population problem will solve itself.
``Sure as day follows night, if jobs grow, the population will
grow,'' said Stephen Kagann, chief economist to Gov. George Pataki.
Last year, private-sector jobs in Buffalo increased by 1.8 percent,
he noted, less than the national average, but more than in the
previous three years put together.
</P>
<P>
   But Buffalo has clearly been slower than some of its Midwestern
counterparts to cope with the decline of its basic industries and
population.
</P>
<P>
   The area's advantages _ including that huge pool of
underemployed people _ ``have never been marketed to the outside
world,'' said Dennis Donovan of the Wadley-Donovan Group, which
advises companies on where to expand.
</P>
<P>
   Government is commonly seen as a culprit. Infighting among local
politicians is legendary; Joel Giambra, a Republican who is the new
county executive, has made waves simply because he is on speaking
terms with Masiello, the mayor, who is a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Giambra insists that the area's reputation as a snow magnet is
not the source of its population problem. He blames high taxes. So
do upstate residents in a new survey done by Harris Interactive for
M&AMP;T Bank, based in Buffalo. The survey found that 20 percent of
upstate residents planned to leave in the next five years, about
twice the average for other regions. Escaping high taxes was cited
even more often than the desire for better jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine found that
Buffalo residents were the most highly taxed of any citizens in the
nation. New York's combined state and local tax burden is the
second highest in the country, after Hawaii's. High taxes also
contribute to the region's high electricity prices.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But taxes are not the whole story, said George Palumbo, a
professor of economics at Canisius College in Buffalo. After all,
he said, New York City and its thriving suburbs have high taxes,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Another serious problem, in his view, is that the area's jobs
pay very low wages compared with similar jobs elsewhere. For
example, workers in finance-related jobs in Buffalo make 35 percent
less than the national average, Palumbo said; those in New York
City, of course, make far more. One possible explanation, he said,
is that ``a lot of back-office jobs have moved to Western New York
that don't pay a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   But some jobs Buffalo pay at least $50,000 a year _ and at least
225 are vacant. They are listed on an Internet site _
buffaloworks.net.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which has led to a couple of job placements since it
was set up in January, is sponsored by the New Millennium Group, a
volunteer organization that seems devoted to making Buffalo
residents buck up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it with the psychic malaise?'' asked Douglas W.
Dimitroff, a lawyer who is one of the group's founders. Dimitroff,
who worked in New York City before his first child was born, said
that maybe you had to leave the city to appreciate it. ``Folks who
think the grass is greener somewhere else probably should go
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas A. Kucharski did _ and ended up in Pennsylvania's Lehigh
Valley, the steel-making region that once seemed as downhearted as
Buffalo does today. As president of the Lehigh Valley Economic
Development Corp., Kucharski was involved in the area's successful
efforts to lure businesses from other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Now he hopes to work the same magic in his hometown. Kucharski
was recently named president of the Buffalo Niagara Enterprise,
which has a multimillion-dollar budget contributed by local
governments and businesses. He has moved in ``a couple of blocks
from Mom,'' he said (and worries about gaining weight from eating
her home-cooked dinners).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious challenges of selling Buffalo to people who
have seen it only snowed under on the TV news, Kucharski says he is
optimistic. As a local saying goes, he said, ``The second hardest
thing is to move to Buffalo. The first hardest thing is to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
