<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-LYNCHING-NYT &LR;      04-08 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LYNCHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: THE PERILS OF GROWING COMFORTABLE WITH EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Double parentheses should be set as brackets.) 
 By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most us have witnessed things that we would be better
off never having seen. The writer Susan Sontag applies this
distinction to the Holocaust photographs she stumbled upon in a
bookstore at the age of 12 in 1945, years before she could
conceptualize what the Holocaust even was. Writing of the
experience in her landmark book ``On Photography,'' Sontag recalled
that when she looked at those photographs ``Some limit had been
reached and not only that of horror ... something  &UR; in me  &LR; went
dead; something is still crying.''
</P>
<P>
   The modern era takes it on faith that images of suffering
stimulate sensitivity to that suffering. But Sontag argues that
little good comes of viewing photographic horrors that you can
barely imagine and have no power to relieve. A few photographs
retain their power to shock, becoming moral reference points, she
writes. But in general, repeated exposure to photographed horror
inures us to that horror, leading us to view even the most
grotesque images as ``just pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   This warning came immediately to mind recently as I toured the
New-York Historical Society's exhibition ``Without Sanctuary:
Lynching Photography in America,'' which opened last month and runs
through July 9. The photographs mainly depict black men with
hideously elongated necks, swinging sometimes in threes and fours
at the end of ropes tied to light poles, trees or gallows.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frightening pictures shows hundreds of
well-dressed men in a field, pressing forward for a better view of
a naked black man who has just been hanged and is now being
mutilated and burned on a pyre.
</P>
<P>
   Like the 12-year-old Susan Sontag in that bookstore, I reached
my ``limit'' quickly and left the room. I returned briefly to take
some notes and was on my way, never to return. There is an
unbearable measure of horror here that I have no interest in
learning to endure.
</P>
<P>
   Lynching scholars tell us that the scenes in this exhibition
were repeated thousands of times _ often before the entire
citizenry of a given town _ and were common throughout much of the
country until the 1940s. These ``lynching bees'' or ``Negro
barbecues'' were often cast as carnivals, to which the residents of
nearby towns brought picnic baskets and their children _ some of
whom are shown in these photographs posed and smiling next to
disfigured black corpses.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures in this show were mainly postcards that
commemorated the ``entertainment'' and were sent regularly through
the mail until it became illegal to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The show opened under the name ``Witness'' this winter at a
small gallery in Manhattan, and consisted mainly of photographs
without explanation, mounted on the gallery walls. The Historical
Society's version of the show includes lengthy descriptive captions
and an added section on the figures in the anti-lynching movement
who eventually brought this horror to an end, among them James
Weldon Johnson, W.E.B. Du Bois and the heroine of the movement, Ida
Wells-Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at this new section of the exhibition, I was reminded
that Wells-Barnett was sparing in her use of pictures or even
illustrations, understanding that likenesses of these events were a
form of brutality in themselves. Her first three works on lynching
_ ``Southern Horrors,'' ``A Red Record'' and ``Mob Rule in New
Orleans'' _ relied for their power on forensic descriptions of the
burnings and lynchings and shared only a single photograph among
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta collector James Allen, who found these photographs,
had hoped that they would provoke a discussion on the public nature
of racial brutality in the early 20th century and the role that era
played in shaping the racial attitudes of today.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Allen had hoped for a probing inquiry into the
nature of what he calls ``community violence,'' which leads to the
blood lust shown in the pictures. The written material that was
added to ``Without Sanctuary'' has given the exhibition some depth,
but not enough to produce the thoughtful meditation Allen had
wished for.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as he told me recently, ``White people feel guilty and
reticent; black people look at these pictures and just get angry.''
Having worked with these pictures for years, Allen is less
susceptible to their horror and was surprised when I told him that
I could not bear seeing them.
</P>
<P>
   A sober inquiry into racial violence has failed to materialize
not just in the galleries, but in much of the news coverage as
well. Some people were upset when news magazines reprinted the
photographs with too little historical context _ essentially
repeating the acts of those who took and distributed the pictures
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Allen had hoped to sensitize us to long-buried horrors of
America's racial past. But by choosing to do this through
photographs, he chose the most unwieldy method of all. With these
horrendous pictures loose in the culture, the ultimate effect could
easily be to normalize images that are in fact horrible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HOMELOAN-BIAS-590&AMP;     04-08 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELOAN-BIAS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS SHOWS RACIAL BIAS IN LENDING, SENATOR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A new study of nearly 240,000 home loan applications
from 1998 in New York City concludes that conventional banks have
largely ignored black neighborhoods, even those with above-average
incomes, creating a vacuum that has been filled by high-cost and
often abusive lenders.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis was done by the staff of Sen. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., who called the results the best evidence yet of racial
discrimination in loan decisions by banks and so-called subprime
lenders that charge high fees and interest for home equity loans to
borrowers with limited access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   During the year that was studied, banks denied loan applications
from blacks at nearly twice the rate for whites, even when they had
the same income, the study found. The rejection rates were 21.6
percent for blacks and 11.4 percent for whites. Even blacks with
incomes above $60,000 were rejected more often than whites with
incomes under $40,000, with 20 percent of the blacks turned down
compared with 17 percent of the whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever in the mortgage world a tale of two cities,
this is it,'' Schumer said. ``As far as New York's lending
institutions are concerned, blacks and whites may as well be living
on different planets. The disparity is shocking, and nothing good
explains the difference. The obvious answer is race.''
</P>
<P>
   While banks made most of their loans in New York City's white
neighborhoods, lenders catering to the subprime market dominated in
black areas, providing 55 percent of the home loans there but only
9 percent of the loans in white areas. The number of subprime loans
had tripled citywide and risen sevenfold in black neighborhoods
during the five years leading up to 1998, the most recent year for
which data was available to be studied. In the same period,
conventional bank loans in the city rose just 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Critics label many subprime lenders as ``predatory.'' Government
officials and consumer groups accuse them of using deceptive
practices and imposing exorbitant costs that force countless
victims into bankruptcy and foreclosure. The state's largest home
equity lender, Delta Financial Corp. of Woodbury, recently settled
state and federal lawsuits over its practices.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the citywide trends, the study also found stark racial
disparities in lending in neighborhood comparisons that paired six
mostly white areas with six mostly black areas of similar income in
the Bronx, Brooklyn and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the black upper-middle-class community of East
Flatbush, which has an average income of $60,010, banks rejected 25
percent of loan applications, and subprime lenders cornered 54
percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   But in a white neighborhood, Sheepshead Bay, with an average
income of $58,230, banks denied only 8 percent of the applications,
and subprime lenders did only 20 percent of the loan business
there.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, Schumer said, is for banks to make more loans to
blacks and for the government to crack down on subprime loans that
cheat homeowners. He said he would introduce legislation that would
ban many abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the banking industry were reluctant to
comment on the study, saying they had not had a chance to see it.
The president of the New York State Bankers Association, Michael P.
Smith, said that banks opposed discrimination and lending abuses
and that most banks had won outstanding ratings from state and
federal regulators for their reinvestment in minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   In past debates, defenders of lending practices have said that
other factors might explain racial disparities. Black and white
applicants with the same income may have different employment
histories, credit histories and savings for down payments, for
example. ``You have to look at the underwriting criteria,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the vice president of the Community Bankers
Association of New York State, Gary R. Brody, said, ``It's
difficult to make judgments based on raw data.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer's staff said that such explanations could not
account for all of the disparity and the consistent patterns they
found. Their study was based on census data on race and income, and
on income and racial statistics that lenders reported to the
federal government on 239,502 mortgage and refinancing applications
made in 1998. Of those, 132,293 resulted in loans, 40,856 were
denied and 66,353 were withdrawn.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Consumer advocates who have attacked lending practices praised
Schumer's study and his proposals. ``It validates what we've been
saying for some time,'' said Josh Zinner, who coordinates
foreclosure prevention efforts for the elderly for South Brooklyn
Legal Services.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's proposed Predatory Lending Deterrence Act would
require impartial credit counseling for borrowers and redefine
high-cost loans as those with an interest rate eight points above
the treasury rate (compared with 10 points now) or with points and
fees exceeding 4 percent of the total loan (compared with 8 percent
now). It would also bar penalties for prepaying a loan, refinancing
that fails to benefit borrowers, the financing of points and fees,
excessive balloon payments and lenders' demands for early payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad truth is that predatory lenders would never be able to
get a foot in the door if traditional banks made loans in minority
neighborhoods,'' Schumer said. ``Even in prosperous black
neighborhoods, money is sucked out of the community that could be
used for other things. There are so many sad tales of people who
have worked hard their whole lives and bought homes, but because
their lenders are predatory, have lost everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1088 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FREAKNIK0409-COX     04-08 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freaknik evolves into a non-event
 &HT;    By Rochelle Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By all indications, this year's Black College Spring
Break, aka Freaknik, will be a non-event. And other cities are
benefiting from the demise of the gathering, which once brought
hundreds of thousands of rowdy college students to Atlanta every
third weekend in April.
</P>
<P>
   At least one competing event _ Kappa Fest 2000 in Galveston,
Texas _ will be held during what has traditionally been the weekend
that Freaknik reigned. Another is going on this weekend on the
Mississippi coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently what's driving the party goers away has been
Atlanta's clampdown in recent years on the cruising, lewd behavior,
and public drunkenness that have characterized the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The fall-off was particularly apparent last year, when Atlanta
police, often outnumbering the revelers, made a show of enforcing a
no-tolerance policy. They instantly arrested anyone who, for
instance, caused a traffic tie-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, there were police officers everywhere,'' Elizabeth
Jackson, 19, a junior at North Carolina Central University in
Durham, said of her first and last Freaknik in 1998. ``When you see
that, you think they are just waiting for us to get out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson went to the Black College Reunion in Daytona Beach,
Fla., last weekend and planned to go to Black Entertainment
Television College Day at Paramount's Kings Dominion amusement park
near Richmond, Va., Saturday instead of coming to Freaknik again.
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik was ``a little too much for me,'' she recalled. ``I saw
a lot of flesh, a lot of girls ... taking off their clothes to take
pictures, guys pulling their pants down to take pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   CREATING A MANAGEABLE EVENT
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police and city officials began cracking down on
Freaknik revelers after more than 200,000 people converged on the
city in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Galveston is embracing the 250,000 young blacks
expected for Kappa Fest 2000 Beach Party next weekend. Like
Freaknik, Kappa Fest started several years ago as an informal
gathering and soon grew.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this year, event promoters have taken over
Kappa Fest and have paid the city $375,000 to cover police and
sanitation costs anticipated from the event. Big name rap, gospel
and hip-hop acts have been scheduled for the three-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston is putting out 350 trash barrels this year as opposed
to 100 last year and 210 portable toilets for the crowds to use _
four times more than last year. Nearly 50 sanitation workers will
be on duty throughout the weekend collecting garbage, and the city
will cordon off the city's beach area for the party. Free parking
and shuttle service to the entertainment district have been
provided to discourage cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston's goal is to make Kappa Fest ``a more manageable event
for us as a city and a more entertaining event for the students
that are coming down here,'' city spokesman Wes Swift said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistakes that other people have made is they don't embrace
these events,'' Swift said. ``We really don't think as a tourism
destination we should turn people away.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in Atlanta, college students were running
into problems that could have serious long-term consequences, said
Chris Smith, sales and operations director for Multi Image Resource
Group, the New Orleans company promoting Black Spring Break 2000 in
Biloxi, Miss., which ends today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids were getting arrest records, getting fined, and getting
hurt,'' Smith said. ``If you keep getting slapped in the face you
are going to learn. College kids are not going to continue taking
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Multi Image worked with Biloxi and Gulfport, Miss., officials to
make the event there run smoothly with as few arrests as possible,
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ... covered all bases so that everyone can be prepared
to have fun and go back to school,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   A SPONTANEOUS CONVERGENCE
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta officials say it is unfair to compare Atlanta and
Freaknik to the new black spring break events and the beach towns
where they are being held.
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik is an occurrence unlike almost all other major events:
a spontaneous convergence of young people who came to Atlanta with
no other purpose than cruising up and down Peachtree Street.
Besides the National Job Fair and the Sweet Auburn street festival,
there were no major events, such as the concerts and contests in
the other cities, nor were there attractions such as beaches and
rollercoasters. Also, Atlanta's business community isn't receptive
to the crowd, while Galveston, Daytona, and Biloxi rely on leisure
travelers for their economic survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of a city that comes to mind that is structured
like Atlanta that has an event like that,''said Bill Howard, vice
president of marketing, tourism and communications for Atlanta
Convention and Visitor's Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik has not been able to co-exist with the city because it
shuts down the city's operations, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta made every effort to accommodate Freaknik as much as
we could,'' Howard said. ``We made every effort to concede with
folks coming to Freaknik. (But) we have other events in the city at
the same time, and events that are hosted in Atlanta need to
coincide with other events. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any other city that was running into the problems we were
running into would employ the same'' methods to eliminate gridlock,
said DeWayne Martin, Mayor Bill Campbell's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   GOING, GOING, ...GONE?
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik is expected to continue its decline.
</P>
<P>
   Area club managers say that this year, they are hearing none of
buzz that normally precedes Freaknik. They'll be open as usual but
have little special planned besides adding extra disc jockeys and
staff during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be surprised if a lot of kids do come to Atlanta,'' said
Billy Pugh, a promotor who works with The Bounce nightclub on
Bankhead Highway.
</P>
<P>
   Students at the city's historically black colleges say they
aren't talking about it and few are planning to visit from out of
town. One Internet Web site dedicated to Freaknik _
www.freaknik.com _ appears to have died in the middle of
construction. E-mails to the developers are returned unread.
</P>
<P>
   ``IS THE ATLANTA FREAKNIK OVER?'' asks an article on the
blackbeachweek.com, a Web site and electronic newsletter that
tracks beach parties and other events geared toward young
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Police Department has prepared its traffic plan,
which focuses attention on downtown Atlanta streets, Special
Operations head Maj. Pete Andresen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we want to minimize problems of the citizens of
Atlanta,'' Andresen said. ``If we have Black College Spring Break
traffic, we'll reroute it if it's inconveniencing regular
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Another telling sign that Freaknik has been nixed is that,
unlike past year, it will be business as usual this weekend. The
Hawks will play two games at Phillips Arena. The rock band Kiss
will be in concert there, too. Even President Bill Clinton will be
in town Friday. In past years, most major events were shifted to
other weekends to avoid the potential for clashes with the Freaknik
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But the city is also bracing itself for Freaknik _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have a spontaneous event that's involving young
people, it's very difficult to assume no one will show up,'' Howard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
