<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-FORMULA-ONE-NYT &LR;      04-08 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FORMULA-ONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MATTER WHAT THE LIMITS, DRIVERS JUST KEEP PUSHING
</HEADLINE>
  By BRAD SPURGEON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While most sports are about trying to exceed the known limits,
the drivers and mechanics of Formula One are more aware than usual
this weekend as they begin the European leg of the season at the
San Marino Grand Prix at Imola, Italy, that car racing is about
trying to stay within the limits.
</P>
<P>
   This is not only because a McLaren-Mercedes car was disqualified
at the Brazilian Grand Prix two weeks ago for a front wing that was
two millimeters (eight-hundredths of an inch) outside the permitted
limit. This is also because it was at Imola that Ayrton Senna died
six years ago while trying to push his car beyond the limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes 90 percent is good enough to win,'' Senna once said,
``and sometimes 100 percent is not good enough. If it takes 200
percent to win, then I will put up with it. It's in my nature to
look for more. The challenge is to win and that is my great
motivation, even it if means going over the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   When a car is built a few millimeters beyond the limit, the race
stewards exclude the car, as has happened to cars in three of the
last four Formula One races. Drivers should exclude themselves when
they begin to go beyond the limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a high-tech sport where people are always going to go
to the limits to get maximum performance,'' said Max Mosley,
president of the International Automobile Federation, the sport's
governing body. ``When they go over those limits, then we have to
exclude them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Senna did not limit himself. Although his
Williams was not up to its world champion quality at the beginning
of the 1994 season, Senna managed to push the car into the pole
position in each of the first three races, including at Imola. He
also spun out in each race while being pushed by the young Michael
Schumacher, who was on the way to his first world title.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1993 autobiography, ``Vive Ma Vie'' (``Live My Life''),
Alain Prost, the four-time Formula One world champion and Senna's
greatest rival, tried to define what, aside from the desire to win,
makes drivers flirt with the limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we drive,'' he wrote, ``danger, speed and risk provoke an
increase in endorphins in the brain. We become `drugged' and fall
into a euphoric state. ... And we cannot control this state of
ecstasy. I occasionally found myself leading races on some of the
most dangerous tracks, and telling myself: `Slow down. You've got a
big enough lead.' But I went faster and faster, certain that I had
lifted my foot from the accelerator. It's a rare state of grace, an
extraordinary voluptuousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Prost had nevertheless decided after a serious accident in his
first year in Formula One in 1980 that he would drive at 90 percent
of his capacity and find the rest of his speed through the
development and setup of the car and adjustments of his racing
line.
</P>
<P>
   But drivers also develop, mature and undergo changes in their
appreciation of what constitutes their limits. Most young drivers
start out thinking nothing can happen to them. Even as they age and
become aware of the dangers, their confidence in their skill may
grow and in turn lead to driving ever closer to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Senna, a triple world champion, died at age 34. Both Jim Clark,
a two-time world champion, and Gilles Villeneuve, often considered
one of the greatest drivers, died in racing accidents at age 32.
Antonio Ascari, one of the best prewar drivers, and his son
Alberto, a two-time world champion, both died at age 36 _ Antonio
Ascari at the French Grand Prix in 1925, Alberto Ascari at Monza in
1955.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher, now 31, broke his leg last year at the British Grand
Prix at Silverstone and considered quitting. But in an interview
last Sunday with Welt am Sonntag, a German newspaper, Schumacher
said the accident ``opened my eyes about several things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more free in my head,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher has won three of the four races since his return in
Malaysia last October. But if he is more dangerous to his rivals,
is he also more dangerous to himself? In the first two races this
season he went off the track on several occasions during practice
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Although last month he said he did not fear dying in a crash, in
December Schumacher said he would consider quitting if some
talented young driver came along to push him too far. ``Because
then you may try to extend your limits to keep up with what he's
doing,'' he said. ``And that can be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when he won his second and last title, Schumacher said:
``In your whole body you must have senses to feel the limit and use
what the car is giving you, use this 100 percent. I think some
people may have more senses than others, and so have the ability to
drive the maximum time on the limit and use the maximum performance
the car can give you.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      04-08 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS NEEDING HOUSTON TO REGAIN HIS TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Fla.)  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ So often, it's as if Allan Houston needs his shooter's
touch as much as an artist needs his brush. He is helpless without
it, flustered when it disappears, crestfallen when a defender takes
it away.
</P>
<P>
   The moment it vanishes, his shoulders droop a little more, his
focus blurs a bit, and his defense usually suffers. Just after the
All-Star Game seemed to sap him, when his moves had the slur of a
record played a speed too slow, he hit a low in Miami on Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   He folded with his team. After being a part of a 20-point
second-quarter lead, the Knicks' resident All-Star fell off the
face of a game that marked the team's most humiliating collapse of
the year. He scored just 15 points around the effort of Dan Majerle
and the wingspan of Bruce Bowen and had the energy for only one
rebound. That was several shooting slumps ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Knicks prepare to meet Miami on Sunday, in a road
game crucial to the team's chances at catching the Heat for the No.
2 seeding in the playoffs, Houston is mired in yet another
discombobulated stretch during his season of inconsistency. Over
the last three games, Houston has made just 16 of 42 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anybody who is going to stop me from
scoring,'' Houston said after scoring just 10 points against
Orlando in the Knicks' victory Friday night. ``I just have to be
quicker to make adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston has had trouble lately in changing his game to adapt to
circumstances. With opponents like the Lakers, Wizards and Magic
trapping him and cutting off his path to an open jumper, Houston
has been taken out of the Knicks' set offense. Against the Lakers,
it was devastating to the Knicks, not because he did not score, but
because his defense was inactive.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few days, at the forceful prodding of Coach Jeff
Van Gundy, Houston has tried to change his behavior. Against the
Wizards, he kept Mitch Richmond (6 for 22) under control. On Friday
he held off the Magic's Ron Mercer (3 for 15).
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that he did other things even when he didn't shoot
well,'' Van Gundy said. ``It's like, do something else to help your
team win.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory is critical for the Knicks on Sunday. The Heat is on a
six-game winning streak and holds a two-game lead over the
third-seeded Knicks for the lead in the Atlantic Division. But
after two victories on back-to-back nights, supplied by Patrick
Ewing's indefatigable performances (30 and 28 points,
respectively), there is an arrogance about the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be, what, down a game when we win?'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   And then he was reminded, the Knicks would be down three games
with five left to play if they lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said we'll gain a game,'' Ewing said. ``We ain't losing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ewing bravado that had been so silent as the season began
has grown like a crescendo the better he has played. At the same
time, Houston has faded in the background. As Ewing has grown more
prominent in the offense, Houston has become more of a second or
third option than a first. Maybe Ewing is inhibiting him. Perhaps
Houston has just failed to fully recover from the drain of the
All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a psychologist,'' Houston said of his dip
in energy after the All-Star break, ``but if it lasted for more
than a week, I didn't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the break, the number of his attempted shots has fallen as
Ewing's has risen. But on Friday night, he ignored all the
statistics and took 17 shots. He made just 5. At one point, with
four fouls also weighing him down, Van Gundy took him out of the
game for eight minutes of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really frustrated,'' Houston said. ``What I've
learned since I've been here is to hang in there and stick with it.
My role on this team is to put the ball in the basket _ among other
things. If you're not doing that, you've got to do those other
things. And I knew I'd put it in eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned for the fourth quarter, he persisted instead of
disappearing. After starting 2 for 10, he continued to play defense
and sank three jumpers in three minutes. He slung his fist and
clapped his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the word is not confidence but cockiness,'' Houston
said. ``I think there's a difference. And that's something you got
to have, especially at my position.''
</P>
<P>
   For a 10-point game, Houston's face was uncommonly lit up with
excitement. He knew the Knicks needed the victory in Orlando to put
them in the right frame of mind going to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider the Miami game the one to get us to the No. 2 seed
and put us where we need to be,'' he said. ``It's good to have won
two games in a row going into that game. It's going to get us a
little more confident, but not false confidence. We know in the
back of our mind we can get it done. My father always said: `You
either get better or get worse. You don't stay the same.' I think
mentally we've kind of grown.''
</P>
<P>
   Mentally, Houston has not let his offensive hiccups leak into
his defense. Lately, he has been less of a one-trick player and
more of an overall force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff has just let me know that I can be as great a defensive
player as I can be an offensive one,'' Houston said. ``That's what
I want to be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
