<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VACATION-HOMES-REAL-1     04-08 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACATION-HOMES-REAL-1110(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: FOR VACATION HOMES, THE TREND IS BIGGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.H., Pa.)   By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The house rising on the corner of Jericho Lane and
Georgica Road in East Hampton may not be remarkable for its size _
at least by current Hamptons standards _ but it symbolizes a
direction that second homes are taking in many resort areas, to the
pleasure of their builders and the consternation of their critics.
</P>
<P>
   A children's playhouse, put up in the 1920s as part of the
estate next door, once stood on the 1.6-acre building site, which
was sold in August for $1,275,000. Three decades later, the
playhouse was transformed into a modest three-bedroom cottage that
in turn has been torn down to make way for what will be a residence
of 6,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger the better _ so goes the mantra these days for many
weekend and vacation retreat seekers, whether they are buying homes
they will occupy, tearing down existing structures or building on
vacant land. Though outsize houses are nothing new _ think of the
so-called ``cottages'' with ballrooms in Newport _ it has been a
while, brokers and planners say, since so many houses of more than
5,000, 10,000 and more square feet have gone up in resort areas.
</P>
<P>
   And the trend has generated everything from admiration to envy
to outright alarm.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hamptons, for example, which is having a boom year in
both resales and new construction of everything from quaint saltbox
cottages to geometric contemporary structures to farmhouses with
media rooms and Jacuzzis, the ongoing flashpoint for the debate
over size is the 57,000-square-foot, 25-bedroom, 39-bathroom Ira
Rennert mansion rising over the potato fields of Sagaponack.
</P>
<P>
   When zoning was introduced in the Town of Southampton in 1972,
the code mandated that one-story dwellings be at least 800 square
feet and those with two stories be 1,200 square feet, according to
Paul Houlihan, the chief building inspector. But despite
controversies ignited in the past by flamboyant structures, no one
imagined that a house could truly be too big until plans for the
Rennert house were divulged.
</P>
<P>
   As the result of unsuccessful efforts to scale back its
dimensions _ a lawsuit is pending even as the house rises _ the
town passed a law in 1998 limiting residential buildings to 20,000
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rennert house may be the extreme, but it is not unusual to
see a house of 10,000 to 12,000 square feet,'' said Frank Newbold,
senior vice president and brokerage manager for Sotheby's
International Realty in East Hampton. ``Speculators are doing
10,000-square-foot houses. Five years ago, half that size would
have been humongous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Builders of spec houses are trying to impress potential buyers
with square footage,'' he said, ``so they are building almost to
the limits of setbacks _ and if they can possibly squeeze a tennis
court onto the lot, they do.''
</P>
<P>
   With all that space to fill, there is plenty of room for the
amenities most in demand right now. ``They include one enormous
room or `great room,' with double-height ceiling and oversize
fireplace; a swanky master bathroom that could be the same size as
the bedroom, with oversize Jacuzzi, and steam shower,'' Newbold
said, adding that such houses are often sold before completion. In
keeping with the demand, prices are rising almost everywhere _ and
inventory is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the picturesque village of Truro, Mass., are also
watching larger and larger _ and of course more expensive _
vacation homes appear, although in this strip of Cape Cod near
Provincetown anything more than 5,000 square feet is considered by
some to be gargantuan.
</P>
<P>
   Even though 70 percent of the town falls under the domain of the
Cape Cod National Seashore and thus must remain undeveloped, some
residents, civic officials and conservationists fear that the
proliferation of what they scornfully deem ``trophy houses'' will
alter the unpretentious image of the Cape's smallest and most rural
town and strain its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Sferra, a planner with the Cape Cod Commission who worked
with the town to develop a local comprehensive plan adopted about
four years ago, said that the houses were cause for legitimate
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the traditional dwellings in Truro, it has
always had relatively modest cottages and Capes,'' she said. ``The
newer houses really dominate the landscape, and there is no sense
that the people building them are trying to fit them into the
landscape but want them to stand out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of time they are being built in places where people have
been able to walk or where open views of the ocean are being
blocked,'' she continued. ``Truro is a very small place where
people have traditionally gone to get away from civilization, from
government and from community, and suddenly civilization has found
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Williams, who resigned as the town's building
commissioner and zoning enforcement officer in February after
serving 15 years in the post, said he first sensed change in the
mid-1980s, when ``the two Laundromats in Truro closed down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One became an upscale gardening center and the other an
upscale delicatessen,'' Williams said. ``Neither could have
succeeded five years earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then about five years ago,'' he recalled, ``the first
million-dollar-plus house was built, followed by a series of
others. That marks a major demographic shift when on Memorial Day
there is an onslaught of Porsches, Jaguars and BMWs instead of the
usual wrecks of station wagons that people used to get to the store
or beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams views the future with some trepidation. ``If these
houses are an augury of what is to come, then they will change the
character of Truro,'' he said. ``There is something about Truro
that is practical, simple and functional. Trophy houses are a slap
in the face of the traditional. They belong in Newport. They don't
fit in here.'' He pointed to one house whose plans would have
violated height restrictions had it not been dug into a dune.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone agrees with him.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are some bigger houses than there were in the past,''
said Arthur Hultin, a builder who put up one of the houses subject
to criticism. ``If there are two dozen trophy houses in Truro I'd
be surprised. There are hundreds of small houses. I don't see it as
an aesthetic problem and I disagree that they will change the
character and tone of the place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Size alone is not what matters,'' he went on. ``It is not
necessarily bad to be big. There are just some poor architectural
choices being made across the board where houses don't fit their
environment because they don't have lasting architectural merit.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robert Weinstein, president of Roberts Associates Builders, who
does custom luxury construction and was responsible for one of the
first million-dollar homes in Truro, said: ``This is an interesting
issue because, on the one hand, people complain about sizes and on
the other we live in a society that puts pre-eminence on private
property and the right to exercise your right to build within the
constriction of any community's zoning laws. We don't all agree on
what is aesthetically appropriate or architecturally correct, but I
won't force my taste on someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Scale aside, prices on second homes, modest as well as lavish,
are escalating in Truro.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house sold in May 1999 for $185,000,'' Nick Brown,
president of Thomas D. Brown Real Estate Associates and a member of
the Truro planning board, said as he pointed to what he termed ``an
entry-level vacation house,'' a two-bedroom, one-bath Cape. ``Today
it would be $50,000 more. Till a year ago, the most expensive house
was $1,125,000; today we have a listing for $1,650,000.''
</P>
<P>
   That house sits high on a bluff overlooking the ocean in the
front and moors in the back, and has its own steep steps down to
the beach. Built in 1899, it is a typical uninsulated
turn-of-the-century cottage.
</P>
<P>
   Because of erosion that averages four feet a year, ``it has been
moved back as far as possible without going down the back of the
dune,'' Brown said, explaining that whoever acquires it will have
to be a risk taker. ``They will be buying a house where they can be
king of the mountain for a short period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacant land in Truro, as elsewhere, is commanding ever higher
prices as it becomes scarcer. There are 2,600 houses in the town,
with enough land remaining before reaching buildout, the point at
which every empty lot has been used, for 1,400 more.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Xavier Slivka, president for construction of
Geiger-Phillips, an architectural firm in Wellfleet, Mass., that
specializes in high-end design, said the price of land has gone up
about 35 percent in the last year. ``A 40,000-square-foot lot in
North Truro was the buy of the year last year at $105,000,'' he
said. ``It's simple supply and demand. People with money want to
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Truro reflects what is happening elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a banner year,'' said Joel Montgomery, a sales
associate with H.C.H. Real Estate in Harvey Cedars, N.J., on Long
Beach Island. ``What was $190,000 to $200,000 a year and a half ago
is now $275,000, and we are seeing properties that were $850,000 go
for more than $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   On Fire Island, where neighbors tend to be in viewing, if not
shouting, distance from one another, ``prices are higher than
ever,'' said Deborah B. Alter, who is in her 20th year as owner of
Fire Island Summer Space, which serves the mid-island communities
of Ocean Beach and Seaview and environs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales prices,'' she said, ``are up by 10 percent or more over
last year.'' In fact, she had a sale last week that far exceeded 10
percent. ``A house I sold last year for $183,000 is now reselling
for $295,000,'' she said. ``I can't believe it myself.'' The house,
in Ocean Beach, is a traditional two-story shingled cottage with
four bedrooms and an old-fashioned eat-in kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't have the million-dollar houses yet,'' she said.
``They tend to be in the high $500,000 to $700,000 range.'' These
homes are likely to be in the more expensive community of Seaview
and are often on double-size lots, making room for a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she noted, ``one street in Seaview now has six pools.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saltaire, the village with the largest houses on the western
end of the island, ``New homes are springing up all over,'' said
RoseAnn Larson, an associate with Larson Realty. ``They are maxing
out in size, 3,600 square feet, which is pretty big for Fire
Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Kenneth E. Larson, who has been a general
contractor on Fire Island for 25 years and now limits his business
to Saltaire, said, ``This is the busiest year we've had in 10
years.'' A four-bedroom house he put up last year ran the owner
$1,075,000, and a six-bedroom nearing completion will come in at
about $875,000, but it is on a smaller piece of property, 3,000
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   So far Larson has not noticed much escalation in resale prices
over last year, but, she said, ``they were up last year and they're
still up, $500,000 and more in the upper market.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bucks County, Pa., where listings range from $300,000 to $3
million, ``It looks as if we are seeing an 8 to 10 percent
increase, though given the heat of the market it is probably
slightly higher on choice properties,'' said Chris Beadling,
marketing manager for Kurfiss Real Estate in New Hope. ``We don't
keep weekend property for more than a few days. We had a converted
barn in the rural town of Ferndale that we listed on a Thursday in
February and sold on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   George C. Ballantyne, senior vice president and New England
regional manager of Sotheby's International Realty, also reported
sharp increases in prices. ``In Nantucket, Martha's Vineyard and
Northeast Harbor, Maine,'' he said, ``we have seen an increase of
20 percent, especially for waterfront property. Fifteen percent
appreciation over a year, which is substantial, is not unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Berkshires, ``the million-dollar house was virtually
unheard of a decade ago,'' said Joseph Carini, president of Wheeler
and Taylor, a Sotheby's affiliate that has offices in Great
Barrington and Stockbridge, Mass. ``Last year we had more than a
dozen million-dollar transactions and we already have two
properties on the books for more than that now, including a 16-room
colonial farmhouse with a contemporary wing on 31 acres that is due
to close in June for $2,450,000.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a report issued by Cook Pony Farm, a real estate
firm in the Hamptons, based on deeds recorded by Suffolk Profiles,
a biweekly listing of deeds, and two local newspapers, the number
of sales of $2 million-plus houses last year more than doubled
compared to 1998, rising from 39 to 89. ``With demand for larger,
more expensive homes growing, we anticipate ever stronger
appreciation in the foreseeable future,'' said Judi Desiderio, vice
president of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   But the report also pointed out that fewer than 10 percent of
the sales in the Hamptons were for transactions over $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think of the Hamptons as being East Hampton,
Southampton and Bridgehampton, where average prices are over $1
million,'' Desiderio said. ``If they would rediscover areas like
Westhampton, Hampton Bays, Quogue, Quiogue and Remsenberg, they
would find places that are beautiful and affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis Greenburger, the chairman and chief executive of Time
Equities, a real estate investment company and of Sanford J.
Greenburger Associates, a literary agency, bought a beach house
house on two and a half acres on the ocean in Quogue in September
and a country house on 30 acres in Old Chatham in Columbia County,
in January.
</P>
<P>
   He had looked at more than 50 listings in Quogue and more than
100 in Columbia County, searching for several years after
separating from his wife, with whom he had shared houses in both
communities.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying two houses in one year is a bit overwhelming,'' said
Greenburger, who would not divulge what he had paid for either.
``But since I had looked in both markets for quite a while without
finding anything that excited me, I felt that when I found
something that was right and I should act.''
</P>
<P>
   His saga of search is not unusual, given the shrinking inventory
everywhere. ``A year ago we had close to 700 properties for sale,''
said Cuthbert Train, owner of Train Properties on Mount Desert
Island, Maine ``Now we're down to 200. If you want to buy a house
in Northeast Harbor on the water, you would be put on a waiting
list.''
</P>
<P>
   He does have four condominiums available. ``They have filtered
views of the harbor,'' he said. ``You look past the tennis courts
and past boats and eventually your eyes get to water.''
</P>
<P>
   The units, which have two or three bedrooms, range from $225,000
to $295,000. In general, prices on the island range from about
$200,000 to more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a lot of availability anywhere on the island,''
Train said, pointing out the discrepancy between the old-line
old-moneyed Northeast Harbor and other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Southwest Harbor, separated from Northeast Harbor by 500
yards of Somes Sound, you would pay half as much,'' he said. ``We
recently sold something in Southwest Harbor for $1.5 million. In
Northeast Harbor it would have been $3 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Train always tries to own something in the community himself.
``I bought a third of an acre with a house on it last summer and
tore the house down,'' he said. ``I paid $75,000 for it and it is
on the market for $115,000 and is the only piece of land for sale
in the town.''
</P>
<P>
   With prices often dictated by the value of the land rather than
the condition, style or size of the house, demolition is becoming
increasingly common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teardowns are a big part of the market,'' Newbold said of East
Hampton. ``This area has been so carefully speculated that it is
harder and harder to find property, so we are doing cold calling,
saying, `You don't know how valuable your house has become.' A
ranch house with major mansions on either side is worth a great
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   In Columbia County, a thriving second-home market, ``There is
more building and a different kind of building than in the past,''
said Frances Schools, owner and principal broker of Old Ghent
Realty in Ghent, who has been in business 32 years and recently
sold her most expensive listing: a house for $2.1 million in
Hillsdale. Middle-range houses in the area go for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that people did not come up here for new
houses,'' she said. ``Now they have to because there are not enough
old houses, particularly not the kind of houses they want: the best
of whatever it is. If you're going to get an 1800s federal, you
want it to be exactly what it was intended when built plus have
modern bathrooms and kitchen. If you want a contemporary, it must
be a very good creative contemporary, and there are not a lot of
those up here. So people are starting to build the $1 million-plus
houses.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, ``It's not that many years ago that
builders refused to build with architects, and there was certainly
no such thing as a landscape architect. Now they're learning to
work with architects and becoming more modern and sophisticated. In
the past all people wanted were ponds; now they're putting in
swimming pools.''
</P>
<P>
   But the single most sought after commodity seems to be something
more ephemeral: privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest percentage of people who come up here want as much
quiet as they can get,'' she said. ``They work in the city, they
make money in the city, they require a city life, but they also
require a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Berkshires, Carini hears the same request from his
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really want privacy, we have a beautiful 345-acre
hilltop where you can land a helicopter and that has three-quarters
of a mile of frontage on a trout stream for $1,100,000,'' he said.
``The property has a simple farmhouse and several outbuildings, but
it is awaiting a house commensurate with its setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Carini was confident that there would be a buyer in the near
future. ``We are quite fascinated by the younger successful
entrepreneurs from Boston, Seattle, California who breeze into town
and absolutely have the resources to purchase their exact
fantasies,'' Carini said. ``Sometimes we have a tough job
satisfying their needs.'' What do they want? ``The same things as
everyone else,'' he said. ``They don't want to just look at the
lake; they want to buy the whole lake.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mix of clients in the Hamptons, Newbold said, ``We're
seeing younger and younger people, many of them in their mid-20s,
buying multimillion-dollar properties. They're not the captains of
industry but the lieutenants with substantial bonuses, along with
the dot-commers. A lot of them are new to New York, having come
from the Midwest or the West. They consider that part of the
package of New York City is a place in the country. It is part of
the New York experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave the prospective buyer on a budget, one
whose fortunes have not soared with stock options, who cannot
afford Versailles on the beach? There are, even as prices soar,
still houses to be had in lower and middle price ranges, though
what is considered reasonable in one community, say $400,000, may
be exorbitant in another. Buyers may just have to be a bit more
flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Burns, a broker with N.H. Colonials in Holderness, N.H.,
in the lake region of central New Hampshire, where houses are
listed for $225,000 to $3.9 million, said that ``depending on the
size of the house and the community, you could get a house for
under $100,000 and use the town beach.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bucks County, low-end prices start at around $300,000, said
Chris Beadling, marketing manager for Kurfiss Real Estate in New
Hope, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Hamptons, there is the occasional bargain. ``We just
sold a cottage in Noyac in the Town of Southampton for close to its
asking price of $159,500,'' said Aspasia G. Comnas, vice president
and brokerage manager in Sotheby's Bridgehampton office. ``It was a
single-story cottage with two bedrooms, two sun porches _ and it's
one block from the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is a house in Water Mill in the Hamptons that
could be considered a bargain _ depending on one's perspective. Its
listing price a year and a half ago, $5 million, was recently
dropped to $3,395,000.
</P>
<P>
   It is a medieval-style stone castle built four years ago by the
brothers Alan and Ivan Wilzig, bankers from Jersey City, N.J., that
includes among its amenities a disco, a gym with steam room and
sauna, a screening room, a pool with underwater speakers and a
fish-stocked freshwater pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a very specific buyer,'' said Tom Raffo, an
associate broker at Sotheby's International Realty in Southampton,
the exclusive agent for the property. ``It's almost like a
self-contained resort. You never have to leave the castle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
