<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-TEEN-STARTUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TEEN STARTUP, 18 AND WIRED FOR BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. _ The executives of the company running the
school district's computer system don't need to be told a thing
about the network or fiber-optic cables or even which teacher is
all thumbs on a mouse. All they need is a call every morning about
8 from the district secretary, Pat Raynor, to make sure they're
awake.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the district gets for hiring a couple of teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Sims and Sean Myrden, both 18 and 1999 Riverhead High
School graduates, are president and treasurer of Eastern Digital
Intranet Services. Last week the school board accepted their
$73,940 proposal to oversee the Long Island district's 600-computer
network for a year. And why not?
</P>
<P>
   They helped build the system as 16-year-old interns and
maintained it as technicians after graduating. When the school
board terminated the contract of its technology director earlier
this year, they bid against five companies, some boasting long
experience and millions in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to bid lower than two guys living with their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if either of them has a mortgage,'' said Bryon
Duffy, the adult president of Tech2Logic, which bid $170,000.
``They don't need the big bucks other people need.''
</P>
<P>
   Need is not in Kris and Sean's vocabulary. Boys in the
wonderland of technology, they followed a youthful fascination to
big prizes. They've forgone college and other trappings of an old
economy that, for them, might as well be an exhibit at the Museum
of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like the college experience,'' said Kris, who tried a
few months at Suffolk County Community College. ``But at 18, I feel
like I'm beyond that. Maybe I'll go to college when I'm 30, when
I'm retired.''
</P>
<P>
   They met in high school, both drawn to rock 'n' roll and
computers. Sean, whose father is a computer consultant, helped wire
computers as a child. Kris fell hard for them at 14. In their
working-class town, they were always scouting odd jobs. After
pestering school officials, they were hired as interns between
their sophomore and junior years and helped install hundreds of
computers.
</P>
<P>
   They became indispensable. Between classes they were pulled away
to solve computer problems. After graduating, they became
$50-an-hour technicians. Now, Kris said, ``we're situated.''
</P>
<P>
   Young and wired, the teen-agers' world view is all giddy
exuberance and serious money.
</P>
<P>
   They considered Silicon Valley after hearing of a school
employee's relative whose salary and stock options there made him
rich on paper. ``Thirteen million or $1.3 million,'' Kris said.
``Some big number.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kris mentioned a building they saw as a possible
headquarters one day, Sean interjected, ``Someone bought that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' Kris said, briefly disappointed. ``Oh well,
everything's always for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Kris, the exuberant partner, said: ``I would be personally happy
if I made $100,000. Well, probably $80,000 I'd be happy with.''
This year.
</P>
<P>
   Brash, perhaps, but in six months last year they made about
$80,000. Their contract allows for extra pay for additional school
projects. Opportunities elsewhere seem plentiful. Their competitors
for the contract hardly wrote them off. Some offered them jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Holmes, the Riverhead Central School District
superintendent, is thrilled that local boys made good, but said
they pose a challenge to educators: ``How do we accommodate the
kids who are very bright but say, `Sorry, I don't have time for the
traditional stuff'?''
</P>
<P>
   The boys are not fretting. Kris has a Corvette. Sean has a
Lexus. They're in a rock 'n' roll band. They're the hottest startup
in Riverhead. ``I wear khakis every day and eat at McDonalds,''
Kris said. ``It's a field like no other. It's run by young people.
It's not an institution yet. It's not run by suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean's father, John, said he told his son: ``Remember these
events. Remember these times. They don't happen that often.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean, working at his computer, ``looked at me like I was
crazy,'' Myrden said. ``I could see the 18-year-old in him saying:
`This is going to happen all the time. We're going to make this
happen.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
