<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FURNISHING-REAL-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: FURNISHING AN APARTMENT WITH THE CLICK OF A MOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y., N.H., Canada)   By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the old days, about five minutes ago, it was
enough to know which restaurant had just opened in the meat-packing
district, or which store on Elizabeth Street sold the best dresses.
Knowing where to get things has always been part of the currency
here, the mark of the sophisticated New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, there's a whole new world to master, and that
doesn't mean Queens and Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Its scouts are people like Brianna Lam, who lives in an elegant
Upper East Side apartment that is tastefully furnished with
antiques and early American oil paintings. She is friendly but not
effusive, perfectly dressed and as well-spoken as one would expect
from a woman who entered Columbia University at 16. When she
explains the row of liquor bottles in her kitchen by saying she
wanted to set up a ``bachelorette'' pad for herself, she seems as
Old World as her high-ceilinged apartment near Central Park in the
East 80s.
</P>
<P>
   But Lam, 28, is totally of her moment. The antique ottoman, the
secretary, the stereo system and the porcelain coasters didn't come
from little neighborhood shops. She found almost everything on the
Internet within two months of moving into her one-bedroom
apartment, and she spent only a fifth of what she had budgeted.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, Lam was separating from her husband and
was tired of the contemporary style they had cultivated. She wanted
antiques, she said, but nothing so expensive she couldn't give a
party without worrying that a $10,000 table would be teetering in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   By roaming through stores on the Upper East Side, she estimated
that it would cost her $50,000 to get the look she wanted, and so
she set aside that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when she started shopping, she was shocked to see that a
pair of chairs she liked cost $5,000. The big department stores
were no more appealing. ``A lot of time when you go to department
stores, you have to wait for six weeks,'' she said. ``When you're
starting from scratch, that seems like forever.''
</P>
<P>
   But being a technology consultant with her own company, Business
Solution Providers Inc., it was natural to her to check out Web
sites in her spare moments. She quickly found an Aubusson-style
needlepoint rug for $850; an upholstered antique footstool, which
doubles as a coffee table, for $190; a hand-painted tole tray table
with a stand for $130; and curved mahogany library steps for $100.
She even unearthed, for $175, a Lladro figurine of a Chinese woman,
which drew her, she said, ``because it looks a little like my
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she had to have help. Desperately wanting the library
steps _ which she found on eBay, the Internet auction site _ so she
could reach her collection of rare books on the top shelves of her
living room, she asked someone she works with to bid for her,
because at the crucial moment, just before the auction closed, she
was going to be at a meeting in London.
</P>
<P>
   With two chairs she had brought from her old life, and a chaise
lounge bought at Bloomingdale's and delivered quickly because it
was in stock, she completed her apartment with about $40,000 left
over. She took that money and began buying early American
paintings. Again she used the Internet, but usually went in person
to the galleries to see the work, after seeing online what was
available.
</P>
<P>
   In furnishing her apartment, she said, she used eBay a lot,
sometimes making the first contact there and then going off line to
negotiate when the auction minimum wasn't met. To protect herself,
she bought primarily from sellers who had garnered a lot of
positive feedback from previous buyers, comments that are posted on
the site. She always avoided buying anything that looked fuzzy in a
photo, and always asked a lot of questions about the object's
condition and shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 70 transactions, she said, she had only three
negative experiences. Twice, furniture was damaged because of poor
packing, but the pieces were insured. In the third case, china
arrived with two broken plates, but because it was insured, the
seller replaced them through www.replacements.com, a company that
sells individual pieces of china and glassware.
</P>
<P>
   Buying online, she said, saves time and broadens choices. ``It's
analogous to having a global amalgamation of stores right in front
of you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For paintings her favorite sites were www.sothebys.com and
www.artnet.com/questtroyal.html, a New York art dealer that
specializes in 19th and early 20th century art. Among her purchases
is an 1875 work by Jervis McEntee (1828-1891), a Hudson River
School painter, which she bought through a dealer she found on the
Internet _ who happened to be the person who lived in her apartment
before she did.
</P>
<P>
   She likes McEntee's work, she said, because it is not like the
``very bright, very sunny'' paintings typical of his time.
</P>
<P>
   He is often criticized for his darker pictures, she said, but
``he was someone I could relate to.'' She buys old art books partly
because they sometimes have personal information about painters
that isn't found in new books.
</P>
<P>
   She said she found eBay very time consuming because of the vast
number of items on sale. Mostly, she found the sellers very
helpful. When she saw the ottoman on eBay, offered by an antiques
dealer in the Hamptons, she made a bid, but when nobody met the
minimum, she contacted the dealer directly, said she had placed the
highest bid and asked for his best price.
</P>
<P>
   They struck a deal, and then came the best part. ``I said I
needed it for a cocktail party coming up,'' she said, ``and they
said, `We'll drop it off in the city for $25.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In her bedroom, the rug came from Home Depot, a store she really
admires. ``I'm pretty bullish on their stock,'' she said. ``It's
one of the only non-Internet, nonwireless-communication companies
in my portfolio.'' She found her digital camera by going to
www.shopper.com to find out who had the best prices.
</P>
<P>
   The beautiful duvet cover on the bed, however, came from a very
traditional source: her mother, who made it for her. ``When I was
little, she always wanted to make my clothes,'' said Lam, who was
born in Toronto and grew up in a small town in New Hampshire. ``I
wanted Levis.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that her apartment is finished, Lam is putting more time
into her other interests, including fiction writing and portrait
photography. She brings out a stunning photo of a woman she shot
during a race to Battery Park City, the woman's muscles glittering
like jewels in the light.
</P>
<P>
   She also likes handgun shooting, a hobby that startles anyone
who hears of it. ``People think it's violent,'' she said. But she
is not defensive. ``It's relaxing to me,'' she said. ``You're
focusing on the target.'' She shoots at a place in the West 20s,
where she likes meeting people she would never come across in her
work life, like police officers and FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work tons and tons of hours,'' she said. Then, ``I
thought, there's more to life than just working and making money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
