<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BABY-KIDNAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMBILICAL-CORD ALARM FAILED TO STOP HOSPITAL KIDNAPPING  
 BY TINA KELLEY  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police are investigating how a 2-day-old girl
could have been kidnapped from University Hospital at the Downstate
Medical Center in Brooklyn on Friday. She was returned safely that
evening, after the police arrested a teen-ager who they said had
taken the baby to a nearby apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Newborns at the hospital are fitted with a device on their
umbilical cords that activates an alarm whenever a baby is brought
near the doors to the ward. Immediately afterward, the doors are
supposed to lock.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm went off when the baby, Melanie Knight, was taken from
the ward, but her abductor apparently made it out of the hospital
before security officers near the hospital's exits were alerted.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, there were nine police officers and 20 security
officers on duty at the hospital, plus one investigator and three
administrators, said Brian Kell, a hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager, Angelique Lawrence, 17, was scheduled to be
charged with second-degree kidnapping Saturday, a felony that
carries a possible jail sentence of five to 25 years, said Teresa
General, a spokeswoman for the Brooklyn district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   According to a high-ranking police official close to the
investigation, Lawrence was most likely able to leave through the
doors because someone was coming into the maternity ward at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the only possible way,'' said the official. ``If
someone is walking in the door, the whole system is shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not think Lawrence had an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If downstairs is not notified, it's a clear way out,'' he
said. ``It seems inadequate. I guarantee it's going to be
upgraded.''
</P>
<P>
   Kell said that no similar incidents had occurred in the 10 years
he had worked at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence had been a patient at the hospital, where she had just
had surgery that would prevent her from having children. She had
told friends she was going into the hospital to have a baby, the
authorities said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
