<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FIDELITY-BOSTON-REAL-     04-08 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-BOSTON-REAL-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: FIDELITY IS A MAJOR INVESTOR IN REAL ESTATE, TOO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., R.I., N.H., Ohio, Texas, Ky., Utah, Calif., Hong
Kong, Britain, Canada.)  By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Financial District headquarters of Fidelity
Investments, the mutual-fund giant that manages $1 trillion,
couldn't be more modest. With no views, low ceilings and a rabbit
warren of corridors, the nine-story building where the company was
founded 54 years ago gives no hint of the real estate empire that
is rising from Fidelity's financial success.
</P>
<P>
   The family-owned and run company, long downtown Boston's biggest
office tenant, is now also poised to become one of its largest
commercial property investors and developers. In all, the FMR
Corp., Fidelity's parent, occupies almost 10 million square feet in
the United States and abroad, and it owns about 7 million square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, FMR owns 3.4 million square feet of downtown office
space. Of that, Fidelity Investments occupies 1.25 million square
feet, much of it in separate buildings surrounding its headquarters
at 82 Devonshire St. And it leases an additional 1.4 million square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Fidelity is probably Boston's only major office tenant
that is also a major investor and developer,'' said Thomas J.
Hynes, the chief executive of Meredith &AMP; Grew Inc./Oncor
International, a Boston real estate company.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's boldest investment here is the Seaport Center, part
of the real estate market emerging along the downtown waterfront.
The 2.5-million-square-foot complex includes a convention center
with office space that it redeveloped on an old fish pier in the
1980s, a two-year-old hotel and two office towers now under
construction. The east tower will open this fall, and the west this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Seaport Center hotel and towers are the first new buildings
that Fidelity has ever put up in Boston, and like most of its real
estate investments, is self-financed with company profits. It
obtained a 99-year lease on the 8.5-acre site from Massport, the
state port authority, and an option on a site for an adjacent third
tower.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its Devonshire Street headquarters, these three new
buildings have spectacular views of the harbor and downtown Boston.
In July, when the $140 million 16-story east tower opens, it will
be the first new office building in downtown Boston since the early
1990s. All told, there are nine projects valued at about $3 billion
being built or planned in the hot new Seaport District.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight percent of Fidelity's east tower has already been
leased, said Peter E. Masden, the managing director of Pembroke
Real Estate, the real estate investment unit of FMR. Given the
strength of the office market _ the vacancy rate is 2.9 percent and
rents are reaching into the $60-a-square-foot range _ Fidelity will
not itself occupy space there. ``The leasing is too good,'' Masden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hynes of Meredith &AMP; Grew said: ``Fidelity focuses on what's
cost-effective in deciding between leasing, owning and occupying.
And it has the in-house talent to do it all well.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the lure of substantial returns _ downtown Boston real
estate values went up about 70 percent in the last six years, city
assessors say _ Fidelity's rapid growth has made the accumulation
of real estate expertise imperative. It now has 30,162 employees,
about third of them working in Boston. In 1990, it had 7,000
employees, two-thirds of them in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real estate activity is driven by our jobs growth,'' said
David C. Weinstein, Fidelity's chief of administration. ``By the
mid-1990s, we were bursting at the seams.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, the company has bought, leased or built space in
Manhattan _ 230,000 square feet in the World Financial Center _ and
in Rhode Island, New Hampshire, Ohio, Kentucky, Texas, Utah and
California, and abroad, in Canada, Bermuda, Britain, Germany,
France, Japan and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing fears that Fidelity might someday abandon Boston,
Weinstein said, ``In an economy based on brainpower, we're in the
catbird seat here with all the colleges and universities.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic slowdown in the late '80s and early '90s presented
Fidelity some opportunities for cost-effective expansion.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, during the mid-1990s, it bought 1.6 million square
feet of space in Massachusetts and New Hampshire from the Digital
Equipment Corp. And it bought 350 acres to develop a campus in
Smithfield, R.I., where it built a 250,000-square-foot office
building and is now constructing another slightly larger building,
both for its own use.
</P>
<P>
   It is also building in office parks near Dallas and Cincinnati
and in Walnut Creek, Calif. In London, it will soon complete
construction of a $100 million six-story office building near St.
Paul's Cathedral. Masden said that about half of it was already
leased at rents that reach $140 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Boston, where Fidelity still rents the same amount
of space it did in 1990, it recently bought two buildings with a
total of about 1.1 million square feet for its own use. Last year,
it paid $187 million for 245 Summer St., an 850,000-square-foot
building where it now occupies some space and will soon have
another 350,000 square feet for expansion. It renovated the second
220,000-square-foot building, 255 State St., on the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity was a pioneer in the Seaport District. With lenders and
tenants still wary from the 1990s real estate crash, Fidelity's
ability to self-finance gave it an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're independent of the business cycle,'' Masden said,
explaining that Fidelity could move ahead with its own projects
when other office developers could not find financing.
</P>
<P>
   The company's heft is also helping the entire Seaport District
to emerge as a new downtown neighborhood, said William F. McCall
Jr., the chief executive of McCall &AMP; Almy Inc., a real estate
advisory company in Boston. ``Everyone knew that once they started
building they'd finish without going bankrupt,'' he said. ``Their
investment gave the area a huge boost in credibility.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Also helpful is $20 billion in publicly funded infrastructure
improvements now under way that have made the waterfront a prime
investment opportunity. The Seaport Center sits at what will be a
crossroads for a new transportation network. At its front door will
be a new tunnel under the harbor, to Logan International Airport;
an extension of the Massachusetts Turnpike; a rebuilt downtown
expressway; a truck road; and new rapid transit line.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, after Fidelity was stymied in building a new tower on
Devonshire Street, it teamed up with the John Drew Management Co.
on the Commonwealth Pier project. Together, they redeveloped the
fish pier into 700,000 square feet of offices that Fidelity
occupies and a 150,000-square-foot exhibition hall for trade shows.
At the same time, Fidelity started negotiating with Massport to
lease more adjacent land.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, as financially shaky developers were forced
to shelve plans, Fidelity continued its site planning and
ground-lease negotiations. By 1994, it started to focus on the
design of the 247-room Seaport Hotel and broke ground a year later.
In 1998, the hotel opened, and Fidelity started building the
505,000-square-foot east tower designed by Shepley Bulfinch
Richardson Abbott Architects of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its real estate activity, the company is still
modest about its holdings. The only public acknowledgment of its
impressive real estate portfolio is a demure 12-inch bronze plaque
with a grayish patina that fades into the masonry around the
entrance to its headquarters at 82 Devonshire St. The plaque is
simply engraved: Fidelity Building.
</P>
</TEXT>
