<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PLAINTIFF-DAVIDIANS04     04-08 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAINTIFF-DAVIDIANS0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Divisions visible among Davidian plaintiffs, attorneys
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There's been a shakeout in the number of
plaintiffs and the focus of their case in the last weeks before the
trial in the wrongful-death lawsuit against the government by
surviving Branch Davidians and relatives of those who died at Mount
Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   What's also becoming more evident is the differences among the
remaining plaintiffs as well as their attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   With a June 19 trial date looming, there are now fewer than 100
individual plaintiffs left in the lawsuit, according to the court
docket in the district clerk's office at the Western District of
Texas. That number doesn't include estates.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Mike Caddell easily has the most clients, 78
people. Many are referrals from attorneys Kirk Lyons of North
Carolina and Charles Grigson of Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey Clark, a former U.S. attorney general under President
Lyndon Johnson, has 19 clients.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco tossed out 125
plaintiffs last July when he dismissed most of the claims in the
case. The plaintiffs left are those suing the government for using
excessive force during the raid, allegedly shooting at the
Davidians on the day of the fire and not having fire-fighting
equipment present.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Davidians Kathryn Schroeder and Rita Riddle _ both of
whom were at Mount Carmel when the ATF raided it on Feb. 28, 1993
but left before the fire that led to the deaths of David Koresh and
75 followers _ were among those plaintiffs recently exiting the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Both women asked to be let out of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop Davidian Clive Doyle from angrily confronting
Caddell, who had been the attorney for Schroeder and Riddle, after
the Mount Carmel re-enactment.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange gave a rare glimpse into the feelings of longtime
Davidians going into the trial. Most of them are represented by
Clark. Doyle, Sheila Martin, Mary Belle Jones (the mother of
Koresh's legal wife, Rachel) and David Thibodeau are clients of
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle accused Caddell of asking people to drop out of the case,
a charge that Caddell denied.
</P>
<P>
   However, Doyle seemed most angry about reports that Caddell, the
lead plaintiffs' attorney, had criticized Koresh in interviews with
the news media covering the re-enactment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he represents the Branch Davidians anymore,''
Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell represents several Davidians, such as Misty Ferguson,
who was severely burned in the Mount Carmel fire, and Stan Sylvia,
a Davidian who was not at Mount Carmel during the siege. None,
however, were ever in the Davidians' upper echelon.
</P>
<P>
   That's given Caddell the leeway to be critical of Koresh's
actions at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you not be?'' Caddell asked. ``I don't make any
apologies for that. I wasn't at Mount Carmel. I don't know what was
going on, but I do know they should have surrendered after the
initial ATF assault and fought it out in court. The Davidians have
to take responsibility for their bad decisions just like the
government does. That doesn't mean if the FBI had handled things
differently that a lot more women and children wouldn't be alive
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Martin said Doyle was trying to make a point by
confronting Caddell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clive just wanted people to know he (Caddell) isn't our
lawyer,'' Martin said. ``He has nothing to do with our side.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Doyle, Martin doesn't appreciate hearing people blame
Koresh and the Davidians for what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government was the one who came to us,'' Martin said.
``It's not like we were in town making demands. What happened was
horrible and should never have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney refrained from assessing Caddell's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in the business of criticizing co-counsel,'' Clark
said. ``Never have been. Hope I never do.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Clark acknowledged he views the lawsuit differently
than Caddell.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell told the Waco Tribune-Herald that he no longer considers
it crucial to the wrongful-death lawsuit to prove the government
fired gunshots at the Davidians on April 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think the failure to have a plan to fight a fire may
be the most critical issue,'' Caddell said. ``Clearly, there was an
anticipation of a fire. But (Jeffrey) Jamar and (Richard) Rogers
said, 'We're not even going to try to fight one if it occurs.' They
understood that Janet Reno's instructions included having
firefighting equipment available. This is not a case where they
should have had a hook-and-ladder truck, and they only had a
pumper. They didn't have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, though, feels that history demands the plaintiffs try to
prove the government fired shots at the Davidians on the final day
of the siege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's essential to legal liability,'' Clark said.
``But whether the FBI fired shots or not is vastly important to the
American people and to history because they've so adamantly
insisted they didn't shoot. The meaning of that is enormous. How
can you hope for accountability if shooting occurred but the issue
remains unresolved?''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell attributes the two men's different trial philosophies to
personal history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been attorney general,'' Caddell said. ``I'm just a
trial lawyer. For me, a trial is about trying to win a lawsuit, not
make history. I'm not being critical of Ramsey. He has a different
perspective because of his own history. In my world, I measure
success or failure very simply. Did I make a recovery for my
client? If I make a recovery for my client, I will have succeeded
on their behalf. Let history pass its own judgment as to whether my
approach was effective or appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Clark, attorney James Brannon, who represents the estates
of Koresh's legal children (Cyrus, Star and Bobbie Lane, all of
whom died at Mount Carmel) wants to focus on proving shots were
fired at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Strategy, not history, guides his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can show the government was a bunch of liars on that
issue, their credibility on everything would be gone,'' Brannon
said. ``I know jurors would look at it that way. I don't know
whether Judge Smith would look at it that way. I don't know the
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Brannon said his relationship with Caddell has been cordial.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we walked out of the deposition of Janet Reno, he walked
up to the microphone and I got out of the way,'' Brannon said. ``I
didn't get stiff-armed. He is the lead counsel, and I let him
speak. I don't view our relationship as anything but cordial. If I
had his resources, I'm sure I would have done some things
differently, but I don't begrudge him for doing them. He's the one
advancing the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brannon said he may file a motion to remove Caddell as
lead attorney for the Holub plaintiffs (Jean Holub, Koresh's
grandmother, is the executor of the estates of his legal children).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we're getting down to trial, I don't want to be
arguing with him as to what's best for my clients,'' Brannon said.
``I'm not trying to be critical of Mr. Caddell or anything that he
has done. I just need to row my own boat when we get into court.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he expects that he'll still be the lead counsel in
the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Judge Smith will let three or four people plow
the same ground,'' Caddell said. ``I expect the court to designate
a lead counsel. He'll have responsibility for asking the general
questions. The other counsels will participate by asking questions
peculiar to the needs of their particular clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Although its raid led to the deadly siege, the ATF is likely to
take a backseat at the wrongful-death lawsuit trial. Caddell did
not depose a single official of the agency nor did he talk to any
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I didn't talk to any of them is that I knew what
they were going to say,'' Caddell said. ``It's not like any ATF
agent is going to admit firing his weapon indiscriminately without
having a target. But I think the evidence is clear that a lot of
the gunfire from the ATF was not directed at a specific target. As
a result, several people died.''
</P>
<P>
   Brannon agreed with Caddell's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to find out what those guys did,'' Brannon said.
``We already know.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the emphasis on the FBI is a matter of trying the
case by the numbers. Five Branch Davidians died on the first day of
the Mount Carmel siege. On the last day, 76 people died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just reflects the far greater number of deaths on April
19th,'' Clark said. ``We're basically suing for wrongful-death and
survivor claims, with a few people suing for their injuries. That
inherently means there's going to be more of a focus on the FBI
than on the ATF.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
