<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ELIAN09-COX     04-08 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN'S FATHER AVOIDS MEETING WITH RESCUERS
 &HT;    820&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN AND MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after publicly thanking the fishermen who
rescued his son, Juan Miguel Gonzalez avoided a meeting with them
Saturday and gave no indication he would agree to meet with the
Miami relatives who have taken care of 6-year-old Elian for the
past four months.
</P>
<P>
   The latest development came as the U.S. Justice Department and
immigration officials readied plans to transfer Elian to his father
_ by force if necessary _ later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's attorney, Gregory Craig, said his client would meet
Sunday with a panel of child psychiatrists appointed by the
government to help advise officials on the best way of transferring
Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The two fishermen, cousins Donato Darylrimple and Sam Ciancio,
flew at their own expense from Fort Lauderdale, Fla., to Washington
to urge Gonzalez to meet with the Miami relatives and to allow
Elian to remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   However, when they arrived at the suburban Bethesda, Md., home
of Cuba's chief diplomat here, they found that Gonzalez was
visiting the Cuban Interests Section in Washington, which serves as
an embassy in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The fishermen, who have been outspoken in their support for the
relatives' efforts to keep Elian in America, said they planned to
remain until Gonzalez consented to meet with them. They were joined
by Delphin Gonzalez, one of Elian's great-uncles from Miami, whose
efforts to meet with Juan Miguel on Friday were similarly rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to get on my knees, I'm going to get on my knees (to
have) this meeting because I love Elian,'' Darylrimple said. ``What
I'm pleading for is for him to communicate with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig said Juan Gonzalez would meet with the fishermen, perhaps
Sunday, but their appeals would not change Juan Gonzalez's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the efforts of the fishermen would be better
directed if they tried to persuade Lazaro Gonzalez to voluntarily
and promptly bring the boy to his father,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, has been caring for the
boy since shortly after he was found floating in an inner tube
three miles off Fort Lauderdale on Thanksgiving day. Elian's mother
and 10 others died after their small motorboat sank during the trip
from Cuba to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely Juan Miguel Gonzalez will agree to a meeting with
the Miami relatives, as has been urged by Florida's senators, Bob
Graham, a Democrat, and Connie Mack, a Republican, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Lazaro Gonzalez has filed suit in state court
against Juan Miguel Gonzalez, claiming he is unfit to have custody
of the child if he wants to return them to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing here is returning Elian soon to his father,''
Craig said. ``Lazaro has to take Elian by the hand and lead him to
(Juan Miguel) and say, 'here is your son.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Until that happens, there can be no reconciliation between the
family factions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting Sunday with the psychiatrists is the first of two
meetings that the government has sought to pave the way for the
transfer. Justice officials have urged the Miami relatives to meet
with the two psychiatrists and a psychologist on Monday to discuss
how to facilitate the transfer. It was unclear late Saturday
whether that meeting would take place.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, announcing the appointment of the
panel Friday, said their purpose was to help decide how and when _
not whether _ Elian would be returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post, quoting unidentified sources, reported
Saturday that Justice and immigration officials were developing a
plan for taking custody of Elian, perhaps as early as Wednesday, if
his Miami relatives do not agree to a voluntary transfer.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. marshals and immigration agents would approach the Miami
house during daylight hours, the newspaper said, and would rely on
local police to respond to any disturbances that might occur.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was calm Saturday, as leaders of the volatile Cuban exile
community called off any protests until Monday, when they scheduled
a prayer rally.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of angry vows that they would form a human chain to
protect the boy, some exiles seemed resigned to the likelihood of
losing the battle over the boy, which they have turned into a focal
point of their 40-year cold war against Cuban dictator Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid is the one who is going to lose,'' said Ramon
Hernandez, 74, who joined a small band of protestors outside the
Little Havana home of Lazaro Gonzalez. ``I don't understand how our
government can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez warned that some extremists might try to block any
effort to turn Elian over to his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people are crazy and they're going to do
something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A possible hitch to the government's plans could be a last-ditch
effort by the family to delay the reunion by going to court to ask
for an injunction to block Reno's order.
</P>
<P>
   They could ask for such an order from the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta, which is scheduled to hear their
appeal of a lawsuit stemming from the case on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   But the family might also try to going to a Florida family
court. They tried that strategy in January, arguing that Elian's
case is a child custody matter, but Reno brushed aside the
proceeding by saying the case is clearly an immigration matter and
solely the responsibility of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami federal judge upheld Reno on the issue, and has ordered
Elian returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   With the reunion appearing likely in the next few days, the
biggest unknown remained Miami's exiles. Miami erupted into two
days of protests in January after federal officials ordered that
Elian should go back to his father, with groups of demonstrators
blocking the entrance to Miami's seaport and tangling traffic
around Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas blasted federal
officials, saying their insistence on returning Elian to his father
despite the Miami relatives' objections was ``provoking'' the
community. Penelas was widely criticized for the comments, with
some observers saying he almost encouraged the protests.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Penelas called for calm and said police would make
arrests to stop any violence or disruptions of the public order. He
also praised exile leaders who cancelled a planned traffic
slow-down at Miami International Airport. Just when that might
happen remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives have insisted they will not break the law,
but have also said they will not take the boy to a neutral location
to meet his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't violate any laws,'' Delfin Gonzalez said Saturday at
a press conference in Maryland. ``But if the government needs to
come and pick him up, they know where we live.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.ins.usdoj.gov, libertyforelian.org
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com, Mike
William's e-mail address is mikew(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
