<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKC-OXFORD-CAMBRIDGE-     04-08 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-OXFORD-CAMBRIDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATCH STIRS SEVEN DECADES OF HOCKEY MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Vt., Pa., N.J., Mass., Canada)   By HUGH WHITNEY MORRISON  Hugh Whitney Morrison, a Rhodes scholar
from Canada, was a journalist on the Toronto Star and later with
the radio network of the Canadian Broadcasting Corp. 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As one of the few living members of the Oxford University ice
hockey team of 1931-32, I was invited to go from Toronto to attend
the 100th anniversary game between Oxford and Cambridge, which took
place at Oxford on March 5. So, at age 91, I and C. Herbert Little,
of Ottawa, went to England, as guests of honor of the current
Oxford team to represent our team, which not only beat Cambridge in
'31 but also went on to win the 1932 English and European
championships.
</P>
<P>
   The 100th anniversary game was played at the new Oxford ice rink
before a capacity crowd of just 1,200 spectators, mostly from the
two universities. Oxford residents were conspicuously absent.
</P>
<P>
   During the opening ceremonies, Little and I were presented with
special Oxford player jerseys with our names and the number ``31''
(for the year we played) emblazoned on the back. We also received
pewter mugs suitably engraved with the compliments of the Oxford
team's sponsor, the King's Arms, a well-known and ancient Oxford
hostelry. Seventy years ago, the Americans at Oxford dubbed it the
``Kappa Alpha House.''
</P>
<P>
   The official face-off was performed by the present Canadian high
commissioner (i.e., ambassador) to the United Kingdom, Roy
MacLaren, who, as a Cambridge postgrad, was booed politely by
Oxford adherents.
</P>
<P>
   The game that unfolded from there was a play of memory and
contrast for me.
</P>
<P>
   In my day, all the players on the 1931-32 Oxford team were
Rhodes scholars and all, except one, Canadians. The lone Yank on
the nine-player squad was Leland Watson from the University of
Minnesota. For the 100th anniversary game, there were only two
Rhodes scholars on the Oxford team.
</P>
<P>
   And while this year's team was predominantly Canadian, the two
stars for Oxford in the 100th anniversary game were the team's only
Americans: Jonathan Finer, from Norwich, Vt., by way of Harvard
'99, and Ian DeArdo, a four-year veteran from the University of
Pittsburgh and McGill.
</P>
<P>
   Finer, 24, had two goals and two assists and was named the
overall ``man of the match'' in a game won by Oxford, 4-2; DeArdo
was named Oxford's man of the match (each team had its own MVP as
well). So, these U.S. forwards were the top two skaters for Oxford,
leaving 15 Canadian teammates to look on, along with two Britons,
one German, one Australian and one Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge team showed a comparable complexity: two
Americans, Philip Coticelli, from Brick, N.J., and George
Whitesides, from Newton, Mass.; two Germans; two Britons; one
Swede; and 10 Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   That Finer was the only American Rhodes scholar in the Oxford
lineup would not in itself be noteworthy, but there was only one
other Rhodes scholar on Oxford's 22-man roster. He was Marc de
Rosnay, the lone Australian, a 6-foot, 182-pound defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   De Rosnay had the dubious distinction of receiving a match
penalty, halfway through the first period, for a head butt. It was
a late call, and by the linesman, not by the referee. So Oxford had
to play short-handed for five minutes, after which another Oxford
player took de Rosnay's place.
</P>
<P>
   This incident led me to reflections on the game today and as it
was 70 years ago when I was an Oxford left wing. In my time, all
teams were limited to a total of nine players, including one extra
forward line. We played on larger ice surfaces _ 200 feet long by
100 feet wide _ as against the standard rink today, which is only
85 feet wide. The result was much more of a wide-open,
passing-the-puck game with fewer penalties and thus less stoppage
of play and fewer short-handed situations.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties against boarding an opponent within 3 feet of the
boards were strictly enforced. Fighting was practically unknown.
Since there was less body contact, our equipment had no hip or
shoulder pads and, of course, no helmets. I can't recall a single
penalty (though there must have been a few) in our Oxford-Cambridge
match, which was played in London before several thousand.
</P>
<P>
   In our 25 other games that season in England and on the
Continent, I can recall very few penalties, all minor. In the 100th
anniversary match, Oxford had 11 penalties, which included 10
minors of two minutes each. Cambridge had only four minors. This is
not to imply that this anniversary match was a roughhouse affair
(it was not); only, as we used to say, chippy by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   In my day, there were no professional teams in England or
Western Europe (though some recruited special players disguised as
nationals). A new amateur English League with six teams, all in
major centers, was formed in 1931-32. My Oxford team played 12
games in it, about half of them at Oxford before 3,000 to 4,000
fans each game, and we were unbeaten and untied. At season's end
the city of Oxford (not the university) presented each of us with a
gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison today, the Oxford team has had to play in smaller
rinks and against inferior amateur teams, since it can't compete
with the two professional leagues that now exist in England.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, both the university and ice hockey had a different
emphasis. Today, Oxford University attracts a higher proportion of
older students taking postgraduate degrees. The Oxford captain,
Steven Smith, 30, has already earned a biochemistry Ph.D. in Canada
and is pursuing further research in that field. For Cambridge, last
year's captain, James Branch, 32, also a Canadian, who scored both
his team's goals and was Cambridge's man of the match, holds an
MBA.
</P>
<P>
   To judge only by this one anniversary match, though the game as
it is played today may be comparatively rougher than in my day, it
is not yet anywhere near that in the National Hockey League, with
its recent alarming, violent incidents. For this, all of us who
have been involved as players or spectators in or at this annual
Oxford-Cambridge match over these many, many years can be thankful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
