   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-FISHERMEN _ MIAMI _ Two of the fishermen who rescued Elian
Gonzalez at sea traveled to Washington on Saturday to try to
persuade his father to meet with the Cuban boy's Miami relatives.
(Williams, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LIPSTADT _ LONDON _ The parties prepare for the verdict
in the case of author David Irving, who is suing Emory University
professor Deborah Lipstadt and her publisher Penguin Books for
libel over assertions made about him in her 1994 book, ``Denying
the Holocaust: The Growing Assault on Truth and Memory.'' Lipstadt
portrayed Irving, 62, as a prominent and dangerous ``Holocaust
denier,'' who believes the systematic murder of 6 million Jews by
the Nazis during World War II never took place. She also depicts
him as an extremist who manipulates, distorts and falsifies history
for his own purposes. We re-cap the story to this point; and why it
is important. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., April 6, in (i) International and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-WORLDBANK _ WASHINGTON _ Advancing the spring meetings of
the International Monetary Fund and World Bank here to discuss
world economic issues. The groups that nearly shut down the World
Trade Organization meeting in Seattle are promising to the same
here ? an even bigger, brighter stage. This could either be a major
victory for the Clinton administration, or a serious black eye. The
first public battle lines over China's entry into the WTO may start
here. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday, April 7.
</P>
