<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   HANK-WILLIAMSIII _ Looking at 27-year-old Shelton Hank Williams
_ or Hank III as he's calling himself these days _ is like staring
into the face of a ghost. He is the spitting image of his famous
grandfather _ tall, skinny, almost woefully pale with thin lips and
chisled nose that could be reprinted straight from old black and
white publicity photos made in the 1940s. Deep in the back of a
mint green tour bus, the young legacy sits hunched over a beaten
guitar staring aimlessly at the worn carpet under his shredded
cowboy boots, waiting to go onstage in front of hundreds of pierced
and tattooed punk rockers at the cavernous Atlanta nightspot, The
Masquerade. As he launches a music career _ which started out
country and has now careened into thrash rock _ he seems keenly
aware of the inevitable comparisons that will be made to his family
tree. And Hank III has made a decision: He's going to uphold the
hard-living Family Tradition. (MLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 60. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-FLOYD _ HOUSTON _ A talk with Carlisle Floyd, the dean of
American opera composers, whose new work ``Cold Sassy Tree'' makes
its world premiere April 14 at Houston Grand Opera. The South
Carolina native talks about growing up in the South and why he sets
his operas there _ from Tennessee (``Susannah'') to Louisiana
(``Willie Stark'') to north Georgia (``Cold Sassy Tree'').
(Sabulis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TV-DONQUIXOTE _ A look at ``Don Quixote,'' a TNT movie. Long
before John Lithgow hit paydirt as a wacky alien on the NBC sitcom
3rd Rock from the Sun, I was a huge fan. The lanky, 6-foot-4-inch
Harvard trained actor was always able to morph into a stunning
array of meaty, although sometimes, over-the-top characters. I
remember well his Oscar-nominated turn as a lovable transsexual
football player in The World According to Garp. He was convincingly
intimidating as a psycho bad guy in Cliffhanger and Ricochet. I
shouldn't even have to mention his classic Saturday Night Live
skits with Jon Lovitz as a pompous actor. Theater. Film.
Television. The Emmy and Tony award-winning actor can do it all.
(Thompson, Palm Beach Post). 16.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PRESIDENT _ Review of TV show ``The American President,'' on
PBS Sunday. It's an interesting and often fascinating look at all
41 presidents. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
