<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-NO1-0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Penn State duo taking NFL draft by storm
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Penn State's players and coaches called Courtney Brown
the ``Quiet Storm,'' because of the defensive end's soft-spoken
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, LaVar Arrington stormed through Penn State like no
other player in the program's storied history. For three seasons,
the rebel linebacker butted heads with legendary coach Joe Paterno,
and even attacked an opposing kicker on national television.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their strikingly different personalities and
backgrounds, one of the Penn State stars will be the No. 1 pick in
Saturday's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Browns officials say they'll choose one of them with
the first choice, and the Washington Redskins could draft the other
player with the second or third pick.
</P>
<P>
   Both players visited with the Browns on Thursday, and the
outspoken Arrington told his potential employer who he'd take.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had the No. 1 pick, I would probably take (No.) 86,''
Arrington said, referring to Brown. ``But it would be nice if they
took (me).''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington and Brown would become only the sixth pair of college
teammates since 1967 to be selected within the first three picks of
the draft. Ohio State offensive tackle Orlando Pace (drafted No. 1
by the Rams) and cornerback Shawn Springs (No. 3 by the Seahawks)
were the most recent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And, although it seems like a remote possibility, both players
are holding out hope that the Browns will draft Florida State
receiver Peter Warrick with the No. 1 pick. That would leave
Arrington and Brown for the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's pretty exciting, the chance of Courtney and me
being on the same pro team,'' Arrington said. ``We're real close.
He's family to me. He's a heck of a guy. He might not always talk
and let people know, but he's a great person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We caused a lot of problems in college and we're only going to
get older and more mature. So that can cause more problems in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past few weeks, it was believed that Brown, 6 feet 5 and
269 pounds, jumped ahead of Arrington and Warrick after his
on-campus workout March 16. Brown ran the 40-yard dash in 4.55
seconds, which is faster than some running backs and receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't find many players coming into the draft who have
everything it takes like (Brown) does,'' Titans coach Jeff Fisher
said. ``He's got size, speed, great character. He can play either
side (of the line). He's just a great, great prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown grew up in the small town of Alvin, S.C., with his distant
cousin, Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton. Brown goes to Bible
reading once or twice a week, and asked his family members and
friends not to talk to the media about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They named Alvin the `Home of Joe Hamilton,' but I think that
was a little premature because Courtney's about to rebuild the
town,'' Hamilton said. ``He's going to be top dog in the county,
definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brown might not be the top dog in the draft. It is believed
that Arrington, 6 feet 3 and 250 pounds, could be gaining momentum.
He has apparently recovered from a lackluster workout, in which he
ran only slightly faster than Brown, despite being about 20 pounds
lighter than his teammate.
</P>
<P>
   That could be bad news for the Redskins, who reportedly covet
Arrington at outside linebacker. Washington really doesn't need
another defensive end after re-signing Marco Coleman in the
offseason, and also adding future Hall of Famer Bruce Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins reportedly will take Alabama offensive tackle Chris
Samuels with one of their first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Arrington) is driven,'' said Foge Fazio, the Redskins' new
linebackers coach. ``He's competitive. He loves the game and plays
with passion. He seems smart enough to come in and contribute right
away. There's no doubt in my mind this guy can come in and have a
positive impact for us. ... I hope we can get him. This guy can
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington, who grew up in Pittsburgh, said he'll be happy in
Cleveland or Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a ballplayer,'' he said, ``and whatever city welcomes me
with open arms will be the city I play my heart out for. You never
can tell what they're thinking. (The Browns) said they don't know.
At this point, I'm kind of confident that maybe I'll end up in
Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Browns coach Chris Palmer admits that it will be difficult to
choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Arrington and you say to yourself, `Here's a guy
that's going to play every down,''' Palmer said. ``I think both of
those guys are top picks because both guys are every-down players.
A lot of times there's a linebacker that can only play on first and
second down, or a guy's not fast enough and he's got to come off
the field on third down. But both of these guys can make a
difference on any down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
