<HEADLINE>
PENNINGTON'S THE ONE IN NFL QB DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes top prospects text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's quarterback crop won't capture the hype of last
year's, in fact, the focus in next Saturday's NFL draft will center
on just one man _ Marshall's Chad Pennington. But even Pennington
is not considered a top-five pick, with teams like Pittsburgh (8),
Denver (10), and San Francisco (12) pondering whether to use a pick
on him.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington is 6 feet 3 inches, 229 pounds, and an Academic
All-American. Tall, strong, and smart, attributes that endear him
to NFL general managers. But it's what he did with Marshall's
offense that has attracted NFL suitors. He threw for more than
3,500 yards in each of his three seasons, and over the past two
seasons he had a total of 76 touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior Bowl MVP has traits that coaches such as Denver's
Mike Shanahan appreciate in a quarterback. He has the ability to
recognize defenses at the line of scrimmage and audibilize; he runs
the clock well; and he is mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington has to prove he can throw the long ball in the NFL,
though a West Coast offense (Denver, San Francisco?) might suit him
well.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Pennington, the early round selections appear to be
Louisville's Chris Redman, Tennessee's Tee Martin, Florida's Doug
Johnson, Hofstra's Giovanni Carmazzi, Michigan's Tom Brady, and
Louisiana Tech's Tim Rattay.
</P>
<P>
   Redman is similar in size to Pennington _ 6-2, 222 pounds _ but
he doesn't run as well. The attraction he holds for scouts is his
toughness. He has a gritty nature, a la Phil Simms and Terry
Bradshaw, which is a positive and a negative. His reckless style
has made him injury-prone. Scouts like his accuracy and the way he
handles the ball (like Peyton Manning), especially on the
play-action fake.
</P>
<P>
   He threw for 3,614 yards last year.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who did not have a spectacular senior year _ hurting his
draft position _ is the most athletic quarterback in the draft. He
is Donovan McNabb-like in his mobility. One thing in Martin's favor
is that he won a national championship two years ago and displays
leadership qualities that coaches love.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is an excellent physical talent, but he is not at top of
QB class because of his past commitment to baseball. He was a Tampa
Bay Devil Rays farmhand until he hurt his rotator cuff. Despite the
injury, scouts like his arm strength and his ability to throw it
deep. Because of his inexperience, he has a tendency to make
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Carmazzi has been the rising star in the QB pool. He may be the
fastest of the lot, running 40 yards in 4.7 seconds at the combine.
The Academic All-American threw for 3,200 yards last season and is
capable of running with the ball. He's also considered a project,
but because of his intelligence and mobility, he may come along
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, nearly 6-5 and 210 pounds, is a dropback passer who
finally developed in his senior season. He was a bigtime player for
the Wolverines, making big plays when the team needed them. He was
not awed by any situation or event. Scouts like his calmness but
don't see him as a huge talent.
</P>
<P>
   Rattay comes from a run-and-shoot offense at Louisiana Tech, so
he will have to adapt his talents to the pro game. He's 6 feet and
mobile, best suited for an offense like the Tennessee Titans' where
Steve McNair throws a lot of short passes.
</P>
<P>
   The sleeper: Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton. He's 5-10, but he's a
superb athlete who belongs on an NFL roster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOP QUARTERBACK PROSPECTS
</P>
<P>
   (! used as column separator) &QL; 
