<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO MEET SEPARATELY WITH BARAK AND ARAFAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to reinvigorate the stalled Middle East
peace talks, President Clinton will meet here separately beginning
this week with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, the White House said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is due to come here on Tuesday. Arafat will come on April
20, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House restated the goal, embraced by the Israelis and
Palestinians, of reaching a final agreement by Sept. 13 on
questions like the future of Jerusalem, the shape of borders
between Israel and a Palestinian entity and the future of
Palestinian refugees. Arafat has said that if such an agreement is
not reached, he will unilaterally declare a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have been running well behind schedule. Teams of
midlevel officials representing Israel and the Palestinians began a
new round of talks on Friday in seclusion at Bolling Air Force Base
in suburban Maryland. The same negotiators met at Bolling for a
week last month, apparently without much progress.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said last week that the negotiators were not
likely to bridge their differences without direct participation by
their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   During their visits, Barak and Arafat will also meet with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Clinton and Barak would also discuss the
status of talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met for three hours with the Syrian leader, Hafez Assad
in Switzerland on March 26 in an unsuccessful attempt to persuade
Assad to moderate his differences with Israel and rejoin peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   That failure seemed to dash Clinton's hopes of presiding over a
comprehensive peace agreement among Syria, the Palestinians and
Israel before he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the United States, Clinton said it was up to
Assad to make the next move. Administration officials said Assad
had stuck to his view that Israel should return land seized from
Syria during the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Barak will also discuss Israel's decision to
withdraw from Lebanon by July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
