<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-GIANTS0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Coverage of Sat.'s game was not completed in time for story
- this is replacement.
 &HT;    Mulholland outing cause for concern
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A record 57 homers were hit in the major leagues
Friday night. Unfortunately, for the Braves, new fourth starter
Terry Mulholland gave up three of them.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds, Bobby Estalella and Jeff Kent hit home runs as the
San Francisco Giants opened a three-game weekend series with a 6-2
victory at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland didn't get out of the fourth inning against the
Giants, doing nothing to ease Braves concerns about the tail end of
their rotation without John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves don't need a fifth starter until April 22, but right
now they don't have a solid fourth behind Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine
and Kevin Millwood. Glavine pitches against the Giants today.
</P>
<P>
   Will the present plan suffice? Or will the Braves have to look
outside the organization, or at using young arms like Luis Rivera
and Bruce Chen? When might Steve Avery fit into the picture, or
John Burkett?
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Braves' luxury of four strong starters in a row
might be a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants needed only three-plus innings to catapult three
homers into the center-field seats off Mulholland, who hadn't given
up three in a game since 1996 with the Phillies. After the third
one, by Kent in the fourth inning, the Giants loaded the bases and
ended Mulholland's night on a base hit by pitcher Mark Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit the ball where our guys weren't, mainly on the other
side of the fence,'' Mulholland said. ``It's not the performance I
was looking for tonight. I don't think Bobby Cox or Leo Mazzone
were either.... I'd get guys where I wanted them in terms of
setting somebody up and I wasn't putting them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland, who had harnessed his control in his final two
starts of the spring, didn't have it Friday, leaving pitches up and
over the plate.
</P>
<P>
   He never got much help offensively. Andruw Jones and Javy Lopez
each homered with the bases empty, but otherwise the Braves
stranded nine runners in seven-plus innings against the 38-year-old
Gardner, who's trying to win a spot in the Giants' rotation while
Shawn Estes is on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hitting his spots and throwing on the corner,'' Lopez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
