<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LEARNING EXPERIENCE' FOR ODOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The payday for doomsday prophecy seemed to arrive
when the Clippers' prized rookie was introduced before a
season-opening scrimmage at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The public address employee referred to the gifted and
controversial messiah candidate as ``Larry Odom.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounded perfect. Odom, also known as ``Lamar'' to his friends
and almost everyone else on the planet, appeared to be in the
perfect place for the predicted, diabolical ruination of his mighty
skills.
</P>
<P>
   And he arrived with historical debris of his own. Even Southwest
Airlines couldn't lose all of this guy's baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Being drafted and hired by the Clippers - in the rolling eyes of
basketball observers - was as dangerous as plutonium in the mitts
of The Simpsons.
</P>
<P>
   So ... with less than two weeks before the Clips fire up their
TVs for the playoffs, let's take at look at their journey with
Odom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a learning experience ... it makes you appreciate
winning,'' said Odom of his first year in what's commonly judged as
NBA purgatory. ``But you can't let it affect your long-term mental
approach. You can't let losing become you.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice words, but what's he done to alter the perception, to help
produce victories? Try 16.7 points, 7.8 rebounds, 4.1 assists and
1.3 rebounds per game. The 20-year-old, 6-foot-10 multi-position
kid from NYC via Rhode Island and a fistful of AAU revivals can
fill a stat sheet.
</P>
<P>
   But, despite solemn oaths to make himself better, Odom hasn't
put in the extra work necessary to make the mid-range jumper, or
outwit wily defenders by occasionally using his right hand to avoid
a charging foul. He didn't move into the weight room to accrue the
necessary strength to finish plays. His habit of whining about
legitimately rotten calls has inspired officials to put him under
greater scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after a recent defeat at Houston, Odom returned to the
locker room and announced he was through for the rest of the
season. He also happened to have a severe calf strain, so Odom
seemed to be validating the content of this emotional outburst for
about a week. He's in uniform and back on the floor, but his game
is somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit that so-called rookie wall,'' he admitted last week.
``But I'm still looking forward to being the leader of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also a kid, who plays hard and hates losing. But until he
arrives early for workouts and stays late, the improvement won't
occur.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Lamar to quit blaming the team and begin looking
into the glass.
</P>
<P>
   If he sees Larry looking back at him, the Clippers are in real
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulls truly think the Clippers were tanking games as
draft strategy, they have more nerve than they can use. Didn't
Chicago GM Jerry Krause dump this season by trading Toni Kukoc
after Kukoc began leading the Bulls to the occasional victory?
Krause did receive another high pick and John Starks as
compensation, but then allowed the competent Starks to skip town.
... Grant Hill continues to assure at least one Detroit Pistons
crony that he's a free-agent goner this season. But think nothing
of soon-to-be-published revelations of the Hill house being put on
the market Mrs. Hill doesn't like the current crib and has
convinced the NBA's greatest small forward to purchase another one,
even if he changes his mind and remains with the Pistons. ... If
called to a vote, Seattle SuperSonics players might choose to play
for assistant coach Nate McMillan rather than Paul Westphal. One
source close to the Sonics said McMillan is no fan of Westphal, who
has yet to demand the George Karl-style defensive posture from his
players. McMillan, of course, is a Karl disciple. ...
</P>
<P>
   Seven-foot-five Chinese prospect Yao Ming wasn't allowed to
compete at last weekend's Nike Hoop Summit in Indy, put scouts did
get an eyeful of Olumide Oyedeji. Oyedeji, who played in the 1999
Summit, stunned NBA snoops with the results of what 12 months in
low-post lab study have done for his game. At 6-10, 240, the
high-flyin' Nigerian who plays for DJK Wurzburg, the same German
club team that presented Dirk Nowitzki to the NBA - could be a
mid-first-round pick. If he chooses to enter the draft. ``He
reminds me of Antonio McDyess with an accent,'' one scout said of
the 19-year-old Oyedeji, who submitted his name for the '99 draft,
then changed his mind. ... How serious is free-agent-candidate
Derek Anderson about hearing Clipper re-enlistment chatter? Here's
a clue: DA already moved out of his condo and is watching the clock
from an L.A. hotel. ... Last year, the pre-draft expo known as the
Portsmouth Invitational Tournament (PIT) produced a small-college
(NCAA Division III) dynamo named Devean George. The last four days,
Division II product Damon Reed, a 6-10 center from St. Rose (N.Y.),
may have played his way to the next level - an invitation to the
Phoenix pre-draft party. One Portsmouth invitee who didn't show is
Long Beach State's Mate Milisa. Milisa, the reigning Big West
Player of the Year, scratched due to a knee problem. ... Last
week's chat with Utah point guard Jacque Vaughn confirmed that the
expected free-agent departure of teammate Howard Eisley will not
guarantee Vaughn's Jazz return. ``It's been three years,'' said
Vaughn, who also will become a free agent July 1. ``It's time to
play.'' Earning starter's minutes in Utah is made impossible by
John Stockton, who seems fit for another season (or two). ...
</P>
<P>
   Etdrick Bohnannon started this campaign at Fort Wayne of the
CBA, but will end it having been photographed in two NBA team
pictures - those featuring the Knicks and the Clips, who signed the
defensive-minded ``four'' man through next season. ... More Clips?
Why not? The latest issue of ESPN The Magazine reported that
interim coach Todd and his two top assistants - some guys known as
Kareem and DJ - have a ``pact.'' If one of the three is hired for
the boss gig, he'll keep the other two around. According to
one-third of this triad, the report is fiction. ... Boston sharpie
Rick Pitino has promised to quit if his Celtics fail to make the
2001 playoffs. To keep him around, several Eastern Conference
coaches have made a pact to throw one game apiece to Boston next
year. ... Darius Miles, the ridiculously active 6-9 and
lottery-bound Flyer from Senior High in East St. Louis, Ill., made
just 51 percent of his free-throw attempts this season. ... Last
Sunday's scrap with Chris Childs demonstrated that Kobe Bryant is
extremely Jordanesque in his ability to swing and miss.
</P>
