u a BC-NY-BABY-KIDNAP-1STLD-     04-08 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BABY-KIDNAP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMBILICAL-CORD ALARM FAILED TO STOP HOSPITAL KIDNAPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Expands earlier story.) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police are investigating how a 2-day-old girl
could have been kidnapped from University Hospital at the Downstate
Medical Center in Brooklyn on Friday. She was returned safely that
evening, after the police arrested a teen-ager who they said had
taken the baby to a nearby apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Newborns at the hospital are fitted with a device on their
umbilical cords that activates an alarm whenever a baby is brought
near the doors to the ward. Immediately afterward, the doors are
supposed to lock. The alarm was activated when the baby, Melanie
Knight, was taken from the ward in a bassinet.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, there were nine police officers and 20 security
officers on duty at the hospital, plus one investigator and three
administrators, said Brian Kell, a hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager, Angelique Lawrence, 17, was scheduled to be
charged with second-degree kidnapping on Saturday, a felony that
carries a possible prison sentence of five to 25 years, said Teresa
General, a spokeswoman for the Brooklyn district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   According to a high-ranking police official close to the
investigation, Lawrence was most likely able to leave through the
doors because someone was coming into the maternity ward at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the only possible way,'' said the official. ``If
someone is walking in the door, the whole system is shot.''
</P>
<P>
   In such an event, if security officers near the entrances are
not alerted immediately, someone could leave the hospital with a
baby without being caught, the official said. He said he did not
think Lawrence had an accomplice. ``If downstairs is not notified,
it's a clear way out,'' he said. ``It seems inadequate. I guarantee
it's going to be upgraded.''
</P>
<P>
   Kell said it was possible that someone could have held the doors
open while the baby was taken out, or that the doors could have
been propped open. He said the police were investigating both
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   According to hospital procedures, when the alarm sounds, the
security office is notified immediately, and security and police
officers at the entrances are notified.
</P>
<P>
   The alarms are tested daily by nurses, and once a week by the
hospital police. Three times a day, nurses check to make sure that
numbers on the device on each baby match those on the mother's
identification bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue Hospital Center, in Manhattan, has a similar security
system. When the alarm is triggered by an infant's being taken from
the maternity ward, the doors to the stairways are locked, and any
elevators will bypass the floor so that no one can leave, said
Richard Pollas, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   At Downstate, where the maternity ward is on the third floor,
only the doors to the ward are locked when an alarm sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital police are not armed, though some carry batons.
Kell said that no similar incidents had occurred in the 10 years he
had worked at the hospital. The hospital uses the Pro-Sec security
system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lutz, president of Pro-Sec Protection Systems, based in
Lakewood, N.J., would not discuss how the system operated, citing
security concerns, but he said the system had prevented an
abduction a couple of years ago. He would not say where.
</P>
<P>
   Security systems in maternity wards have become more common,
with advancing technology and concerns about abductions and the
switching of infants. Some electronic scanning systems even play a
lullaby after verifying that the mother and infant are wearing tags
with matching identification numbers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the higher-profile cases of infant switching became news
in 1998, when Paula Johnson of Ruckersville, Va., discovered that
her biological daughter Rebecca, 3, had been switched at birth with
the child of two people who were killed in a car accident before
they could be told of the switch.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, a 16-year-old girl abducted a newborn from St.
Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center in Paterson, N.J. Ten years
ago, a 3-day-old boy was abducted from St. John's Episcopal
Hospital in Brooklyn by a woman who told the police she had had a
miscarriage two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that kidnappers are often women who have lost
children or are unable to have their own.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to earlier reports from the police, Lawrence had
visited a doctor at the hospital last week, and had been told she
had a condition that would prevent her from having children, a
law-enforcement spokeswoman said. Lawrence, who is overweight, had
told friends she was expecting a baby. On Friday, when she went to
the hospital to pick up some medication, she took Melanie, the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
