u s BC-BBC-GATECH-TEIXIERA04     04-08 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-GATECH-TEIXIERA0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teixeira's loss became Tech's gain
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech third baseman Mark Teixeira can smile now
when he recounts what he then considered the worst day of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's easy to look ahead instead of back when you are
one of the hottest hitters in college baseball and projected as the
likely first pick in the 2001 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure didn't think so at the time, but somebody must have
been looking out for me,'' Teixeira said. ``I couldn't be happier
the way things worked out. I just never planned it this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Teixeira thought he would go in the first round of the 1998
draft, bypass college baseball to sign a lucrative pro contract and
work his way quickly through the minors to realize his major-league
dream. If his hometown Baltimore Orioles drafted him, all the
better.
</P>
<P>
   Then reality hit.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before the draft, the Boston Red Sox said they would
select him with the 12th overall pick if he would agree to their
take-it-or-leave-it offer _ $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he wasn't taken in the first round or in any of
the next seven. By the time Boston finally selected him in the
ninth round, Teixeira had left his home in Severna Park, Md., to
work off some of his frustration at a gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so mad that I called Georgia Tech as soon as I got back
and told coach (Danny) Hall that I was coming,'' Teixeira said.
``No way was I going to sign with the Red Sox then.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall had signed Teixeira to a scholarship offer but never really
thought he would see the powerful switch-hitter in a Georgia Tech
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when he didn't go in the first round,'' Hall
said. ``I couldn't believe it. The Red Sox had called me the night
before and said they were taking him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he wasn't picked early, I thought we had a chance to
get him. Then, he became my ace recruiter, trying to convince our
other draftees not to sign and come here instead.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you fall from the first round to the ninth? Apparently by
having agent Scott Boras, a hard bargainer despised by many teams,
as your adviser and by initially rejecting the kind of money that
would have most people _ let alone an 18-year-old _ rushing for a
pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Red Sox told some teams things that weren't really
true,'' said Teixeira, who turns 20 on Tuesday. ``The money wasn't
the problem with Boston. I wasn't trying to be J.D. Drew. It was
the way it all was handled, with no chance to negotiate. It just
wasn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's loss was Georgia Tech's gain. The sophomore has been
terrorizing ACC pitchers for two years and has another season
before he is eligible for the draft again.
</P>
<P>
   Teixeira led Tech in average (.387), homers (13) and runs batted
in (65) in 58 games last year, and was selected freshman of the
year by Collegiate Baseball Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Teixeira has been even more dominating. Going into
Tech's weekend series at Maryland, he was hitting .447 in 31 games,
with eight home runs and 35 RBIs. Teixeira had eight multi-hit
games in a row and was batting .500 in ACC play.
</P>
<P>
   How good a hitter is Teixeira? He is putting up numbers that
Nomar Garciaparra could only have dreamed about during his first
two seasons at Tech. The All-Star shortstop for the Red Sox hit
.363 his freshman season and .297 as a sophomore, with a total of
seven home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sets Mark apart from the other top hitters I've had is
his power,'' Hall said. ``He can really hit the ball a long way.
Plus, he does it from both sides of the plate. Pitchers just don't
have much of a chance. He doesn't chase bad pitches and is willing
to go the other way when he has two strikes. You won't find a
better college hitter, and he showed last summer in the Cape Cod
League that he is just as good with a wood bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech has had six players taken in the first round of the
draft but never anyone first overall. Second baseman Ty Griffin was
the fourth player picked in 1988, going to the Chicago Cubs.
Pitcher Kevin Brown was taken by Texas with the seventh pick in
1986 and Garciaparra was the 12th pick by Boston in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A management major and dean's-list student, Teixeira says he
isn't even thinking about the 2001 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I care about is us getting to the College World Series
this year and next,'' Teixeira said. ``I can't control what happens
with the draft, so I'm not going to worry about it. I learned the
hard way that major-league baseball is business. Playing here is
the fun part, so I'm going to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
