<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-THIRD-RD0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods storms into picture
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Things were changing by the hour at Augusta
National Saturday. On the weather radar and on the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   The front blew in at midday, bringing rain, then winds strong
enough to bend towering hardwoods and blow putts away from the
hole.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Tiger Woods got a break from the weather and vaulted
into contention with a 4-under-par 68 and a 54-hole total of
1-under 215.
</P>
<P>
   Woods started the day at 3-over 147, but four straight birdies
put him back in the race. Although a rain delay of just over two
hours broke his momentum, he came back with birdies at 13 and 15
before taking a crucial bogey at the 17th, when his second shot
spun off the front and into the bunker. Although Woods played some
of the back nine in the rain, the rough winds did not arrive until
he was off the course.
</P>
<P>
   The thunderstorm and lightning delay, which caused the course to
be emptied of fans and players, prevented the leaders from
finishing their rounds until this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get back in this tournament,'' said Woods.
``I didn't want to feel as if I was completely out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III, who barely made the cut Friday at
3-over, also regrouped with a 68 to tie Woods at 215. Love said
that if conditions were windy and cold this morning, as expected,
his chances might improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very comfortable if I'm seven or eight back,'' Love
said. ``I'd like to be four or five at the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were very tough after skies cleared and the winds
picked up, making chipping and putting particularly treacherous on
the slick greens, which dried out quickly after the rain. Scores
soared accordingly, making those who played earlier feel all the
more fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jones hit disaster at the seventh hole, making a
triple-bogey 7, falling from 5-under to 2-under and finally off the
leaderboard. Phil Mickelson, who started the day one shot behind
leader David Duval, fell down the leaderboard with a front-nine 40.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus, the 60-year-old, six-time champion, started the
third round at even par, but lost his two-day magic, stumbling to
an 81. Duluth's Stewart Cink had a second consecutive 72 and is at
3-over 219. Larry Mize of Columbus slipped to a 73 and stands
2-over.
</P>
<P>
   Today's first prize will be $828,000, up from $720,000 last
year, from a purse of approximately $4.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
