<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Short tracks Wallace's metier
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Rusty Wallace is on another short-track tear
and the pole for today's Goody's Body Pain 500 at Martinsville
Speedway. His brother, Kenny, is starting beside him on the front
row.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty ought to be able to explain why drivers not named Wallace
have trouble at the half-mile Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know,'' Rusty said. ``It's the same thing when
people ask me why I run so good on short tracks. I tell them I
really don't know, I cut my teeth on (short tracks).''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace won two weeks ago at the short-track of Bristol. Here,
the drivers swap concrete for mostly asphalt and the high banks of
Bristol for the modest elevation of Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess on the short tracks I know what I want the car to
do,'' Wallace said. ``You have to have the car do what you want it
to do to maneuver and pass. ``Martinsville is the kind of place
where you could have a falling out with your own mother if she was
on the track with you,'' Rick Mast said. ``You know when you come
here that you're going to get mad at some people, and some people
are going to get mad at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mast won't have that worry: He didn't qualify the No. 14
Pontiac. But Mike Skinner, starting third in the No. 31 Chevy, can
relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I give people advice here,'' Skinner said, ``I say run
smooth. My son came up Friday morning and said Jeremy (Mayfield)
had the fastest car out there and he looks real smooth. He said,
`you look like you're up on the wheel with both hands and feet. Why
don't you just calm down and maybe you'll drive better?' In the
Winston Cup garage, it's hard to be as smooth as silk and be
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace seems to have mastered both functions. Now, he appears
poised to roll off a streak similar to one he began at Martinsville
in late 1992. In an eight-race stretch at Martinsville, he won five
times, was second twice and third once.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down and selected our test sessions really carefully,''
Wallace said. ``I said, `wait a minute guys, we haven't been
short-track testing because everybody thinks we're good. We'll end
the race nowadays and finish third or fourth. We used to dominate
those things. I think it's time to go back to the tracks that are
the very best for us and test at those tracks and really perfect
them and when we come back let's get some wins. These things all
pay 180 points to win.' So, we did that at Bristol and it worked
out. We came up (to Martinsville) and tested and it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
