<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS GET A KICK OUT OF HOFFMAN'S JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no coaching job like Steve Hoffman's coaching job. Not
around here, there isn't. Maybe not anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   With his 12th season coming up at Valley Ranch, Hoffman has
always worked under these kind of marching orders:
</P>
<P>
   Search the countryside for the best available kicker and punter,
meaning a couple of fine young men who will make the Cowboys proud,
and never put the head coach's head on the line because of wide
rights or shanks. Forget, of course, about obtaining such talent
through the draft or free agency. Punters and kickers are vital,
just not that ``vital.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to pay, both guys must be willing to work for
the bare minimum in salary, and not a dollar more. It's a
longstanding Valley Ranch tradition that punters and kickers are
cheap labor, therefore saving a few bucks to pay the stars.
</P>
<P>
   With those guidelines in place, Hoffman is given a go-get-'em
pat on the butt and a friendly reminder that the Cowboys are
counting on him to get it right. Who knows when the outcome of a
game will be riding on a kicker's toe.
</P>
<P>
   Several games did last season and Richie Cunningham suddenly
started failing on field goals. Although the entire offense was a
mess, only one player lost his job over it. Cunningham was released
in November after an all-pro season the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the coaches told me the team had lost confidence in
Richie,'' said Hoffman. ``My answer to him was that Richie had lost
confidence in the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Good point.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is a jovial sort with an excellent coaching reputation
for beating the bushes to locate gypsy kickers and punters who come
to the Cowboys as a nobody and eventually leave as a somebody. And
one way or the other, they all leave, although 95 percent of the
time it's because of better paying jobs elsewhere in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Gowin, the punter and kickoff man, did his job better over
the past couple of seasons than the likes of Aikman, Deion and Lett
combined. But when it comes time for financial reward, Gowin's came
last week from the New Orleans Saints. They swiped Gowin for a
$600,000 signing bonus and an average salary of over $600,000 for
three years. As good as Gowin was in both his areas, the Cowboys
would never think of investing that much money in him.
</P>
<P>
   What the heck, Jerry Jones just figures Hoffman will go out and
find another Toby Gowin who will work for the NFL rookie minimum of
$193,000. And while looking for a punter-kickoff man, Hoffman must
also find a new field goal kicker for the same price.
</P>
<P>
   These kind of players aren't important until they screw up _ and
then everyone is screaming, from the head coach, to the other
players, to the media, to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting concept,'' said Hoffman, smiling. ``But I
view it as a challenge. As much as I hated to lose a Toby Gowin,
I'm proud for him that he got that kind of money elsewhere. It's
like I've told all our guys for years about the money situation
here _ don't look at what's fair, just accept that's it this way,
and deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my standpoint, which comes from a team concept, I think
it's easier for us to find a punter or a kicker than it is to find
a \Rwide receiver\S Joey Galloway. So if we're saving money in my
area of the team, it's helping us elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving here with Jimmy Johnson in 1989, Hoffman has come
up with Ken Willis, Lin Elliott, Chris Boniol and Cunningham as
field goal kickers. All were untested and unknown in the NFL. All
made their marks. Punting-wise, his back-to-back duo of John Jett
and Gowin ranked among the league's best.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the new mystery men are Tim Seder and Jarret
Greaser (kickers) and Cory Collins and Barry Cantrell (punters).
They have all been signed, and others will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Where does Hoffman find these people? Seder is a high school
baseball coach in Ohio who showed up for a tryout wearing sneakers.
Cantrell is a Wall Street broker who was in camp with the Cowboys
two years ago. Collins is between jobs, having just been laid off
as a computer programmer. Greaser is a Texas Tech product who
didn't kick as a senior because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical things you can judge for yourself as you watch
these guys in tryouts, but the hard part is the guessing game on
can they handle the job mentally,'' said Hoffman, who can also
relate to the gypsy nature of free agent kickers and punters. He's
been there himself when it comes to holding on to an NFL dream long
after the college days.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the early '80s, a punter named Steve Hoffman was cut six
times in four years after being invited to training camps with NFL
and United States Football League clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spirit, I'm one of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Hoffman is a Cowboys' coach who is always asked to
do more with much less. Thus far, he's never failed, with yet
another challenge immediately awaiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
