<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGE OF QUALITY CHILD CARE HAS KANSAS CITY PARENTS SCRAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
 DAY CARE -- 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA McGUIRE and DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Last week the metropolitan area nearly lost
14 day-care centers run by the financially troubled YWCA of Greater
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   That situation, it turns out, is just the tip of the area's
child-care worries.
</P>
<P>
   As the economy booms, child-care employees are fleeing to better
jobs with better benefits, leaving many centers understaffed _ and
creating nightmares for working parents.
</P>
<P>
   Some centers have cut hours, which has intensified the shortage
of spaces available for children to a crisis level, said Abby
Baucom, director of the Metropolitan Council on Child Care, which
recently released a status report on early childhood care and
education in the area.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the shortage of teachers and slots for
children causes many parents to drive miles out of their way or
settle for mediocre care _ or in some cases, both.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious parents linger on waiting lists, especially if they want
infant or toddler care. Some parents now reserve slots months
before their babies are born.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting so bad, Baucom said, that one woman telephoned
several child-care centers to ask about waiting lists so she would
know when to get pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The economic woes have been labeled the ``child care trilemma'':
Parents can't afford to pay higher fees, which means centers can't
afford to hire and retain educated teachers, which means overall
quality of care is poor.
</P>
<P>
   And this is a problem not likely to be solved by parents paying
more. Many parents say they are paying the maximum they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles lurk from the Northland to southern Jackson County,
from the city to the suburbs. They are most intense in areas where
industrial growth is coupled with residential development. And they
affect the urban core, where welfare reform has put more mothers to
work and more children in need of child care. Child-care study
</P>
<P>
   The study, based on 1999 statistics, found:
</P>
<P>
   - The turnover rate for center staff is 42 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   - Only 4 percent of centers provide care during nontraditional
hours.
</P>
<P>
   - Forty percent of home providers and 60 percent of centers have
waiting lists for infants and toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   Some frustrated parents turn to nanny services, but those can
cost $10 or more an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she does not need child care until this summer, Ann
Brendle of Leawood began shopping for toddler care last August _
nearly a year in advance. She contacted six child-care providers
and ended up 19th, 27th and 40th on three different lists.
</P>
<P>
   Because siblings of children already attending centers have
first shot at many openings, Brendle's odds of finding quality
child care looked slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me I might get it, and I might not,'' said Brendle,
a former teacher who began thinking she might not be able to return
to work.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday she finally may have succeeded. She paid one center
a fee to hold a slot for her daughter, who turns 1 in June. If the
slot does not open as expected in July, the center will refund
Brendle's money.
</P>
<P>
   Infant and toddler care is more of a problem than for other ages
because of the high costs. Kansas requires one teacher for every
three infants, and Missouri requires one teacher for every four.
That is expensive, driving costs to $200 or more a week for
parents. Some centers do not provide care for these children,
because they lose money on them.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents nearly lost their day care when the YWCA said it is
considering filing for bankruptcy. Plans are being made for other
agencies to assume the responsibilities for 14 day-care sites if
the YWCA does file. Difficult issues
</P>
<P>
   Are there solutions to all these child-care problems?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of those things we haven't figured out,'' said
Karen Clayton, executive director of the Child Care Association of
Johnson County in Kansas, which is helping other agencies prepare
to inherit some of the YWCA's troubled sites. ``If I could answer
that question, I'd be doing speaking across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates say tobacco settlement money should be redirected
to child care. Others suggest a tax subsidy will be needed someday,
much like public schools are supported by taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Others say it's up to businesses to subsidize care for
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown centers of La Petite Academy in Tulsa, Okla., and
Wichita, Kan., have corporate support, which offsets expenses. A La
Petite center in downtown Kansas City at 10th Street and Baltimore
Avenue that will close this week did not have corporate support,
said Cindy Lehnhoff, La Petite's area vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents asked me, `What would it take (to keep the center
open)?' '' Lehnhoff said. ``I said, `Somebody's employer to step
up.' We can't lower our quality, and I think they respected that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Sprint Corp. announced it was eliminating a child-care
center from its Sprint campus in Overland Park, Kan., because too
many workers said they would need the service. The company did not
want a system in which they could be accused of playing favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week, however, executives said they were
considering building a center near the campus. Other options being
considered by Sprint include leasing a building or contracting with
existing day-care providers near the new headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp Credit Services provides day care for employees at
several sites across the country, including one near Kansas City
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (corporate officials) look at it as a benefit, and it's
promoted as an employee benefit,'' said Janice Clark, the site's
director.
</P>
<P>
   Employees pay fees often half what many other programs charge,
with the added benefit of having the center next door to work. They
can visit children during lunch in a 25,000-square-foot,
state-of-the-art, 3-year-old facility that earned national
accreditation a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say accreditation is key to improving the overall
quality of America's child-care system. Accredited centers must
meet curriculum, staffing and facility guidelines. These programs
deal with children's social, emotional and intellectual development
at a time children's brains are the most active.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
