r a BC-YWCACARE2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      04-08 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YWCA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CARE 2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ...the most active.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at Citi Family Center, take-home bags containing
developmental materials _ such as games, cooking activities and
books _ hang on racks near the lobby, each marked with a child's
name and color-coded by the children's ages. Parents check out the
bags for a week at a time, then return them for refills.
Accreditation
</P>
<P>
   There is a big push in the Kansas City area for child-care
providers to become accredited by the National Association for the
Education of Young Children. Indeed, accreditation was one of the
good-news items in the Child Care Council's report.
</P>
<P>
   So far 43 centers and three home providers in the metropolitan
area have earned accreditation. An additional 200 are working
toward the goal, Baucom said.
</P>
<P>
   However, staffing shortages can make it difficult to reach that
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any center where you are constantly worrying about staffing
issues, quality takes a back seat,'' Clayton said. ``If the
director has to worry about whether she is going to have to drive
the van or cook the meals, then she is not worrying about
accreditation issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Child-care workers _ despite awesome responsibility _
historically have been among the lowest paid of America's labor
force. According to the new study, the average starting wage for
child-care teachers in the Kansas City area is $6.50 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Goodcents around the corner from my house is offering to
hire delivery drivers at $10 to $15 an hour,'' Baucom said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehnhoff from La Petite has raised her staff salaries $2 per
hour in the last two years to encourage staffers to come and stay.
Her employees now earn from $8 to $10 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even then we have a labor shortage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, fewer than half of child-care centers
offer health insurance to teachers and assistant teachers.
</P>
<P>
   And the cost of child care for one infant and one toddler in a
center consumes, on average, about 25 percent of a family's income.
For poor families who earn too much for state-subsidized care,
child care can eat up 45 percent of family income.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of families, child care is the second-highest
monthly expense, after housing,'' Baucom said.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth, according to experts, is that parents have been
getting a break _ on the backs of child-care workers _ for a long
time. In a way, the traditional low pay of workers has served as an
unofficial subsidy for parents.
</P>
<P>
   Various studies show that parents pay between $3,000 and $4,000
annually in child-care expenses per child, Baucom said. But the
actual cost of quality care would be between $6,000 and $9,000 per
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Berta Sailer, director of St. Vincent's child-care center
in Midtown, predicts the problem will worsen until more money is
found for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get to the point where society and policy makers
recognize the work these people do,'' Sailer said, adding that
suburban centers have an advantage over day cares in the inner
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can raise rates, and their parents can probably afford
the increase,'' Sailer said.
</P>
<P>
   But most children who attend St. Vincent's do so on state
subsidy, which is tied to a funding formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could charge more, but it wouldn't do any good, because my
moms couldn't afford to pay it,'' Sailer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
