<HEADER>
A1145 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-FISHER-RADIO-KAN &LR;      04-08 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-RADIO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL RADIO STATIONS ARE BIG ON SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Kan. _ Nelson Rupard, owner of radio stations
KIND-AM and KIND-FM here, was talking about his sole foray into
talk radio, the rage in his business for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a syndicated show with two women,'' said Rupard, who,
being only 88, still handles the station's morning show, answers
the phone and performs light maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rupard didn't mind that the two were sassy and irreverent. As
the dean of Kansas broadcasters, he's been around long enough to
have heard absolutely, positively everything.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the two women started ruminating on bodily functions,
Rupard got on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd signed a contract,'' he said. ``But I told them this just
won't work here. They were nice. They let us out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rupard, inventor, mentor and a font of wondrous stories about
radio, is a disciple of that now-fading school of broadcasting
called ``full service'' _ meaning no automation, real people behind
the microphone, attention to the minutiae of the community, and
good taste,
</P>
<P>
   For KIND-AM and KIND-FM, which simulcast from an unembellished
studio on the edge of Elk City State Park, that equates to three
hours of news and markets in the morning, a variety of music (show
tunes and '70s and '80s hits) through the rest of the day, and then
sports (from high school to the Royals) until midnight. Plus a ton
of local stuff _ meetings, reunions, the city council, awards, you
name it.
</P>
<P>
   So bodily functions are out.
</P>
<P>
   Rupard allowed that his insistence on a certain propriety may
have roots in personal experience. Sixty-plus years ago, not long
out of high school, Rupard was working at station WHB up in Kansas
City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   One day an announcer nabbed him for a live commercial. Rupard,
healthy as a horse, was to play a satisfied customer of a certain
skin care product and offer a testimonial about its efficacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down in the copy I spotted this strange word,'' he said. ``I
tried to say it. But my tongue just got it all tangled. But they
were in a hurry, and I had to read it on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Psoriasis, as read by Rupard, came out minus the first, fifth,
and eighth letters.
</P>
<P>
   Rupard held onto his job. He worked as an engineer. He was on
the air. One of his jobs was to make sure a musician named Bill
Basie, later know as ``Count,'' was on time to do his weekly WHB
gig in the organ showroom of Jenkins Music Co. at 1217 Walnut St.
</P>
<P>
   He got to know other greats, such as Baby Lovett, Julia Hill,
and Bennie and Buster Moten. There were lots of live broadcasts,
not only from the old Northside Municipal Court, but also from the
Cherry Blossom Theater, where the ``Vine St. Varieties'' were held
and, oddly enough, whites sat in the balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Rupard, who joined WHB in 1932, had landed in what
was the most exciting town in the country working in a kinetic
industry that then was not unlike today's computer frontier.
</P>
<P>
   There was always something new _ improved equipment, innovative
means of transmission, original shows coming down the network line
from New York and Chicago _ and above all, the knowledge that
thousands upon thousands of people clustered around a box that sat
like a shrine in their living rooms, listening.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't really matter to what. Radio gave people what they'd
never had _ immediacy on a communal scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were just a handful of stations in Kansas City then,''
said Rupard, ``WDAF, KMBC, WHB and maybe a couple more. Everybody
knew each other. Everybody traded ideas. It was all new. How many
stations are there now _ 30 or more?''
</P>
<P>
   Rupard left WHB in 1942 and went to Emporia, Kan., taking part
ownership in KTSW (now KVOE). There he helped set up a Kansas
network, part of which was to bring educational programs to
isolated parts of the state
</P>
<P>
   One of Rupard's proudest memories is captured in a picture of a
teacher and several students crammed into a car with books,
notebooks and pencils. The caption said they were listening to one
of the network's school programs on the car's radio. Their school
lacked electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio was meant to serve people,'' he said. ``That picture was
all about that.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Rupard came to Independence and built KIND
from the ground up. The call letters, incidentally, were originally
assigned to a World War II Navy ship. Over the years, Rupard has
been approached with monetary offers to trade the letters to West
Coast radio stations, ones apparently looking for an altruistic
image or more melodic jingles. Rupard has scoffed at such offers.
</P>
<P>
   KIND-AM went on the air in 1947 at 1010 on the dial. KIND-FM, at
101.7, was one of the first FM stations in the state. It began
broadcasting in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   With Rupard running the station and his wife, Francis, keeping
up the business end, the station did well. There was a brief
controversy in the early 1950s when Rupard hired a black news
reader, Cy Keller, not because of his race but, as Rupard said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the Korean War going, and Cy was the only guy around
who could pronouce the names there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who earned their spurs at the station were Merle
Blair, now president and chief executive officer of the Topeka
Chamber of Commerce; Hoite Caston, a Los Angeles writer, producer
and director; and Bill Kurtis, who became a TV network newsman and
is now a producer and host of documentaries on the A&AMP;E cable
network.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said that the last time he and Kurtis were at the station,
Kurtis motioned him to take his picture against one of the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Rupard, ``bless his heart, has egg-crates for sound deadening,
and Bill wanted a picture,'' Blair said. ``I mean, who can believe
that? Then Bill...says, `OK, let's cut some spots,' and Bill did
some commercials for, I think, a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to encouraging young talent, Rupard, in the late
1950s, invented a device called the ``101 Spotter'' that replaced
discs and reel-to-reel tape. It was a forerunner of the audio
cartridge machine, which made ``Top-40'' radio possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nelson represents the epitome of community broadcasting,''
said Harriet Lange, executive director of the Kansas Association of
Broadcasters in Topeka. ``There's not many like him around
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Rupard said there had been some very informal talks with Kurtis,
Caston, Blair and other alumni of KIND about their buying the
station when he's no longer around ``so the widow Rupard can be
taken care of.'' But he has no plans to retire. Too busy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing. Would Rupard say ``psoriasis?''
</P>
<P>
   He did. Perfectly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
