<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1146 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-AWG-TEAMSTERS-KAN &LR;      04-08 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AWG-TEAMSTERS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 AWG, Teamsters battle to win over KC shoppers is escalating  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Monica Deleon last week pulled into the Price
Chopper parking lot in Roeland Park, Kan., but she quickly left
without shopping for groceries.
</P>
<P>
   A laid-off employee from Associated Wholesale Grocers had given
her a handbill describing the labor dispute between the food
wholesaler and 1,200 members of the Teamsters union in Kansas City
and Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Deleon said her father's experience as a union worker persuaded
her to shop elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family's gone through this before,'' she said Thursday as
she pulled onto 18th Street Expressway. ``We know what it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   While Deleon and others left without patronizing Price Chopper,
others ignored the ex-Associated workers and the leaflets in their
outstretched arms. Most drivers took the handbills but continued
into the store's parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for the hearts and minds of Kansas City grocery
shoppers is escalating.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters are engaged in a week-old conflict with Associated, a
grocery cooperative that laid off more than 600 warehouse and
transportation employees at its Kansas City, Kan., distribution
center. The company also did the same to nearly 700 employees in
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Citing mounting competition and a need to improve efficiencies
in its distribution system, Associated has outsourced its warehouse
and transportation operations to private companies. The Teamsters,
meanwhile, claim Associated is a growing wholesaler that wants to
boost profits for itself and its member owners by breaking the
union.
</P>
<P>
   The union has filed a charge with the National Labor Relations
Board, contending that Associated did not bargain in good faith and
requesting that the board rule that legal action be taken to
reinstate union members to their jobs. Associated said that it
followed federal guidelines, giving employees a two-month mass
layoff notice, and that those employees no longer work for
Associated.
</P>
<P>
   It could take four to six weeks for the board to decide whether
the union's complaint merits judicial action.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the outcome of the battle could be determined
by grocery shoppers in the Kansas City area, Springfield, Lawrence,
Kan., and Topeka, Kan. The union has identified those areas for a
boycott of stores that are supplied by Associated and are members
of its cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Associated continues to operate its outsourced distribution
centers. An executive said Friday that operations have not yet
returned to normal. But the company is satisfied with the progress
and expects to ship regular load amounts by today, said Jerry
Garland, the company's executive vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it wouldn't be back on schedule overnight,'' Garland
said. ``There have been delays, but we're right on track with where
we thought we'd be at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Associated is making its case through newspapers, radio and TV.
In the past two weeks the company has flooded Kansas City with
commercials and advertisements _ including full-page ads in The
Kansas City Star _ that ask consumers to support their locally
owned, independent grocers.
</P>
<P>
   The union has relied mostly on rallies and passing out
handbills. On Friday the union published an ad in The Star
disputing Associated's claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``These appeals to the public at large are common features of
many labor disputes,'' said Clete Daniel, professor of labor
history at Cornell University. ``Employers use whatever leverage
they have to convince customers they're right, and the unions try
to generate support from average, working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel said the advertising resources Associated has used to
counter the union's boycott are no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grocery business operates on a very thin profit margin,''
he said. ``If you launch a boycott and impact a relatively small
number of customers, you can still have a profound effect on the
store's bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to determine the effect of the labor dispute and
boycott.
</P>
<P>
   A Price Chopper spokesman said Thursday that operations are
normal at its area stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually takes three to four weeks before finding out if
sales are affected, but all indications are that it's business as
usual,'' said Alan Chapman of Wilson Chapman/SJS, spokesman for the
Price Chopper group. ``On the first day (of the outsourcing),
deliveries were delayed, but every day it's gotten better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, scattered reports of late deliveries continued
through the week. One truck was eight hours late on Wednesday to a
Kirksville store, according to one employee.
</P>
<P>
   It's also unclear whether grocers that compete with Associated's
stores, such as employee-owned Hy-Vee Food Stores Inc., are
benefiting from the dispute. A Hy-Vee store manager declined
comment Thursday, and a call to Hy-Vee's regional office in Lenexa,
Kan., was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area the union is distributing handbills at
more than 30 stores at various times, said Al Hoover, coordinator
of Local 955's activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not bullying anybody; we're just asking for support,''
said Troy Smith, an ex-Associated mechanic who had worked at the
company for more than nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Many customers are undecided. Among them is Mike DeJanes, a
Kansas City businessman who talked to ex-Associated workers
Thursday at the Northland Price Chopper.
</P>
<P>
   DeJanes runs a small deli and catering service that does some
business with Associated and other food suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know where I stand,'' he said after a 15-minute
discussion with the handbillers. ``I understand that businesses
have to be competitive and make decisions about labor costs, but
I've seen companies use the union issue as a smokescreen, too. The
other factor is that (as a business owner) I want to be able get my
products so I can sell things. This dispute could affect me, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
