<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA EXPECTS RESHUFFLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - When the season ends, it's likely Arizona's place in
the National League West will be gone as the Diamondbacks head to
the American League if realignment goes the way baseball executives
plan.
</P>
<P>
   But Diamondbacks managing general partner Jerry Colangelo, not
happy at all about his club's imminent move to the AL, isn't sold
on the fact that Arizona will never return to the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whatever happens for next year is going to be the
first step in major realignment,'' Colangelo said. ``That could
absolutely affect us. Where we go, if we go, doesn't mean that's
where we stay. That's where we would be for a few years, but that's
not necessarily where we end up.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners aren't expected to talk about realignment at the April 18
meeting in Houston, but it will be a topic at the June meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig has let it be known he wants the Texas
Rangers out of the AL West. No approval is needed to shift Arizona
and Tampa Bay before November 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But if Arizona jumps to the AL West, it could be only a
short-term move because Selig is interested in a major realignment
project that could split the AL and NL into sections of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, fans: A day that was supposed to be of celebration
turned confusing for the Florida Marlins thanks to some curious
timing from Florida Gov. Jeb Bush. He released an editorial in the
Miami Herald on opening day, stating that he would veto the
proposed $4-a-day cruise tax to help fund a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins were hoping to collect $320 million from the cruise
tax and owner John Henry was going to add $80 million for the new
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the timing of it,'' Marlins owner John
Boles said. ``I'm sure there were reasons for it, but it sure
shocked me to read the article _ opening day.... We've got enough
precipitation on us here without someone raining on our parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Rickey rhetoric: Since spring training, Mets left fielder Rickey
Henderson has been making noise about wanting a new contract. He
said he ``wasn't into'' playing. Henderson is upset he's making $2
million this season but thinks he was forced into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew they weren't going to do something with my contract,
we would have been fussing at the beginning of last season,''
Henderson said. ``I wouldn't have played for them. I would have
gone home. We probably would have gone to court to decide if I
accepted that contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout baseball, people are wondering about the situation.
Henderson is one of baseball's best leadoff hitters _ he hit .315
with 89 runs scored, 82 walks and 37 stolen bases last season _ but
the Mets are growing tired of his act.
</P>
<P>
   Woods vs. Valdes: The race is on in Chicago to see if Kerry Wood
makes it back into the Cubs rotation before former Dodger Ismael
Valdes. The Cubs are ecstatic that Wood, coming back from elbow
surgery, is making rapid progress and could pitch today for
Single-A Daytona, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cubs manager Don Baylor said Valdes, sent to the Cubs
along with Eric Young in the offseason, is at about the midway
point of spring and it could be two to three weeks before he's
ready to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, on the disabled list with shoulder tendinitis, had
trouble getting loose before his last throwing session.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Arizona made the playoffs a year ago and is the
favorite to win the NL West, but the folks in Greater Phoenix don't
seem to care. The Diamondbacks were 2,600 short of a sellout for
their home opener, and two nights later drew 15,007, the lowest
total at Bank One Ballpark. ``I don't know why,'' team president
Rich Dozer said. ``We've got Randy Johnson going, a perfect night,
the team wins the National League West.''... Ken Griffey Jr. made
his Cincinnati debut and was roundly cheered before the game by the
Cinergy Field record crowed of 55,595. And Griffey's mom, Birdie,
missed it. ``I was waiting for the elevator,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
