<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0409-COX     04-08 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore and Bush even, poll shows
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush are running
neck and neck in the presidential campaign, according to a Newsweek
poll released Saturday. The poll found that 44 percent of
registered voters favor each of the two major party candidates,
while 12 percent were undecided. Among independent voters, Bush had
a slight edge with 45 percent compared with 39 percent for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the likely Republican presidential nominee, scored 81
percent of Republican voters, while likely Democratic presidential
nominee Gore scored 76 percent of Democrats. Among minorities, Gore
got 63 percent compared with 23 percent for Bush, according to the
poll of 588 registered voters. The poll has a margin of error of 5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON REELS IN FUNDS FOR DNC
</P>
<P>
   Though continuing to trail Republicans in fund-raising overall,
the Democratic National Committee did manage to raise almost as
much money as the GOP during the first quarter of the year due to
President Clinton's help. Clinton helped raise half of the $26
million the DNC took in during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the president was again working to raise more money
by attending a fund-raising lunch that was expected to bring in
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gore attended a $5,000-per-person lunch in Broward
County, Fla., that was expected to bring in $1 million for the DNC.
Gore also announced an Internet partnership between the DNC and
Speakout.com, which he said will allow voters to read the party's
platform and propose changes.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC began April with more than $21 million in the bank _ its
largest amount ever _ according to General Chairman Ed Rendell.
This time four years ago, the party had $5 million in its account.
Since Jan. 1, 1999, the Republican National Committee has raised
more than $82 million; the Democrats $66 million.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH'S HEALTH CARE PLAN FOR POOR AMERICANS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is considering a $14 billion health care proposal
that would employ tax credits to pay health insurance premiums for
low-income Americans, the Wall Street Journal reported Friday. Bush
is leaning toward a plan that would grant $1,000 to each taxpayer
and $2,000 to families, according to the newspaper, although
advisers apparently disagree on the plan. These tax credits are
twice the size of credits that Bush formerly recommended. Some
Republicans back this plan as a way to increase the number of
Americans with health insurance without increasing the size of
government bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   GORE SILENT ON ELIAN WHILE IN FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   With Elian Gonzalez just 50 miles away, Vice President Al Gore _
who stunned the Clinton administration last week when he sided with
Miami's Cuban activists _ stayed silent on the issue Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As Elian's father met with Attorney General Janet Reno in an
effort to get back his son, Gore met with more than 100 voters in
Delray Beach, to talk health care and taxes _ not Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Gore hammered Bush's plan to allow people to invest part of
their Social Security taxes in the stock market. ``It may sound
like a small amount of speculation but it is really a large dose of
Social Security devastation,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett said Friday that ``during the last
eight years, Clinton-Gore failed to enact reforms to save and
strengthen Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   GRASS ROOTS IN THE PEWS
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell is set to step back onto the political
stage this week when he launches a voter registration and
mobilization campaign, ``People of Faith 2000.'' ABC News reports
that on Friday, Falwell will announce a plan to register an
additional 10 million religious people to vote, and to have them
carry ``I pray and I vote'' cards reminding them of their
commitment to turn out on Nov. 7. ABC says Falwell's folks also
plan to communicate with thousands of religious leaders to
encourage them to hold ``citizenship days''_ in effect, a
voter-registration drive in the pews.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
