<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIJAY SINGH IS THE MAN TO BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ A howling wind provided a stiff challenge for the
leaders, but Vijay Singh was too steady to be blown off course
Saturday during the third round of the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   With Tiger Woods and Davis Love III pulling themselves into
contention, the setup heading into Sunday's final-day action could
not get much better, considering the names near the top of the
leader board. But the pack will be chasing Vijay Singh, who seized
a three-stroke lead with a splendid ball-striking display despite
conditions fit more for flying a kite than for playing golf. Singh
nearly eagled No. 14 with a great approach shot that landed 2 feet
from the hole, then tapped in for a birdie that gave him his
biggest lead not long before play ended because of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   But a weird weather day at Augusta National Golf Club caused a
star-studded leader board to bunch like an accordion for most of
the day. Those who teed off early, like Woods and Love, played in
manageable conditions that allowed them to make a move. Those who
teed off late, like David Duval, Singh and Ernie Els, got a raw
deal and rugged conditions.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the final two groups teed off, Els and Mickelson
followed by Duval and Singh, there had already been a weather delay
of 2 hours 5 minutes that forced the third round to be suspended by
darkness before eight golfers could finish. And what a day they had
endured. In the late afternoon, there were 20 to 30-mile an hour
wind gusts, with the highest gust recorded at 42 mph. Those
conditions made golf balls do funny things, both in the air and on
the putting surface. Fans were losing their hats, but many players
were losing strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Singh and Loren Roberts played superbly considering the
conditions. Duval, despite a double-bogey at No.12, held his own,
as did Els and Mickelson. But Tom Lehman, Sergio Garcia and
Bernhard Langer lost precious ground that will make it difficult
for them to win, while Jack Nicklaus shot a difficult 81.
</P>
<P>
   After a day that was both exciting and unpredictable, Singh was
at seven under par through 14 holes when play was suspended. Duval
was in second place at four under through 14, and Roberts and Els
were tied at three under. Woods and Love, both of whom shot 68, and
Mike Weir, who shot 70, were tied at one under par.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely is a leader board that strong seen anywhere, and to see
it played out Sunday at Augusta will undoubtedly provide an outcome
of indelible memories. Some of Saturday's best moments were
provided by Woods and Love, who both did what it took to get back
into the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, who has never had a top-10 finish at the Masters, was
unflappable in the wind. Singh, the winner of the 1997 PGA
Championship, will be trying to win his second major Sunday. If he
does, he will have earned it.
</P>
<P>
   Woods entered the tournament as the favorite, but entered the
day in trouble, trailing Duval, the second-round leader, by nine
strokes. Woods had two choices Saturday, either make a move or see
his chance to win slip away. Woods chose the former.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up this morning, I knew what I had to do, which
was go out and get myself back in the tournament,'' said Woods, who
snapped a streak of 10 consecutive rounds of 70 or worse at the
Masters. ``I hit solid shots and controlled the flight of the ball.
To shoot 68 in those conditions, I'm pretty proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the elements conspired to aid his cause. While the
last groups were out on the course dealing with the elements, Woods
and Love were watching on television, getting closer to the lead
all the time. You could almost picture Woods and Love with their
feet up on couches somewhere, watching the afternoon proceedings
with grins on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flags were blowing so loud, it sounded like someone
shooting a gun out there,'' Love said of the afternoon conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys that got those late tee times didn't get the best of
it. But that's the way things go.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh and Roberts showed tremendous resiliency. Roberts, one of
the game's best putters but who has never won a major, made four
birdies on the front side, then hung tough on the back nine to
complete a strong day. Singh used his length and composure to build
his lead.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling with his putter Friday, Woods had dinner with
his father, Earl, who told his son that his hands were too low on
his putting stroke. Then Saturday morning, Woods's coach, Butch
Harmon, made a small correction.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Woods teed off, his stroke was corrected and his
attitude was determined. For the first time in the tournament,
Woods went on a strong run, making four consecutive birdies from
No. 7 through No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, play was called for the weather delay, which
temporarily broke Woods' momentum. But when play resumed, he made a
key up and down at No. 12, which featured a strange moment. As
Woods prepared for his chip shot at No. 12, a ball from the ninth
hole at the adjacent Augusta Country Club came flying over the
fence and landed on the 12th green. Startled, Woods backed away,
and a marshal retrieved the errant ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that scene from `Caddyshack 2,' where the ball just
went over the fence?'' Woods said. ``It was just splat, all over
the green. We never saw a cart, we never saw anybody. I guess he
was embarrassed and didn't want to come get his ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods kept moving forward, taking advantage of his length to
birdie both par-5's on the back nine, No. 13 and No. 15, to reach
two under par for the tournament, before a bogey at No. 17 dropped
him back a stroke when his day ended.
</P>
<P>
   Love also bogeyed No. 16 after reaching two under par, but
neither he nor Woods could complain too much. They were back on the
leader board. And they had plenty of elite company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't slept very good this week,'' Love said. ``It's very,
very hard to control your emotions out there. I want to win this
tournament just like any other major. But I want to win this one
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   So do many others. And after Saturday, many will still have a
chance.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
