u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-MARINERS-     04-08 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT MARINERS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Paul O'Neill bent at the knees in the Yankees'
clubhouse Saturday morning and the cracking sounds from his joints
were sharp and loud, like wishbones snapping. ``C'mon, body, get
going,'' O'Neill said, trying to shake off sluggishness.
</P>
<P>
   He felt the same way about the Yankees: they had lost two games
in a row and it felt like a lot more, O'Neill said before
Saturday's game, and he did his part to end the mini-slump, driving
a run-scoring double in the ninth inning to edge the Mariners, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The game had felt as if it were going against the Yankees,
however. They were not sharp, going 0 for 7 with runners in scoring
position in the first eight innings. The score was tied, 2-2, with
the Yankees' runs coming on homers by Tino Martinez and Alfonso
Soriano. Orlando Hernandez had pitched seven strong innings.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mesa retired the last two Yankees in the eighth inning and
the first two in the ninth inning, in the late-afternoon shadows
that crept from the home plate area toward the mound. Lou Piniella,
the Mariners' manager, stood in the dugout and waved his arms
dramatically for the lights to be turned on, knowing how difficult
it is to hit in such conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter singled with two outs, however, bringing O'Neill to
the plate for a matchup that he had dominated in the past. O'Neill
had faced Mesa nine times during the regular season and had six
hits and three walks, for a batting average of 1.000, an on-base
percentage of 1.000. With the count two balls and one strike, Jeter
broke for second, slid headfirst and barely beat the throw of
Seattle catcher Dan Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa might have pitched around O'Neill and gone after Bernie
Williams, who had one hit in nine at-bats against him with four
strikeouts. But Mesa attacked, and O'Neill swung at a 3-2 pitch and
rocketed the ball out of the shadows and into the sunlight of
right-center field, between the outfielders. Jeter scored and the
Yankees went ahead, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Soriano, the top shortstop prospect promoted from Class AAA
Columbus after Scott Brosius strained a rib cage muscle, made his
first start at third base Saturday. He made a nice play in the
first inning, diving to catch a looping line drive, but generally
looked uncomfortable; he has played only a handful of games at
third base. After second baseman Chuck Knoblauch misplayed Stan
Javier's ground ball in the fourth inning, Knoblauch's first error
of the season, Soriano charged awkwardly when Alex Rodriguez
grounded to third, and the ball bounced off Soriano and into the
air for another error.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud drew a walk, loading the bases with one out and John
Mabry coming to the plate, and El Duque was laughing. Hernandez
beckoned Jorge Posada to the mound and said something to him _
perhaps about how to pitch to Mabry, perhaps about something else _
but he smiled and tapped Posada on the back of the neck, chuckling
in what others might have construed as a tense situation.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez threw an inside fastball and jammed Mabry, who popped
up to second and then slammed his helmet after returning to the
dugout. El Duque was still smiling, still having fun. The count on
Mike Cameron reached two balls and two strikes and Hernandez shook
off the sign from Posada and called him out for a meeting.
Hernandez shook Posada off three more times and there was another
meeting on the mound, the crowd booing. Teammates say that El Duque
sometimes will shake off the signs merely to confuse the hitters,
and this may have been the case Saturday; after Hernandez and
Posada spoke, the catcher returned to the plate, looked at the home
plate umpire, Ed Montague, and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Hernandez must have had a plan, because two pitches
later he blew a fastball past Cameron, and raised his fist slightly
in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates were affording Hernandez almost no margin for
error, however, after Martinez lifted a solo homer to open the
second. The Yankees had runners at first and second and one out in
the second inning and could not score; Soriano's strikeout stunted
the rally. Martinez led off the fourth with a single and Ricky
Ledee lined a high drive to left. Thinking the ball would either
disappear over the fence or at least go over the head of Seattle
left fielder Raul Ibanez, Martinez rounded second and was on his
way to third when Ibanez caught the ball; the Mariners relayed the
ball to first for an easy double play.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer walked leading off the fifth and moved to second
on Soriano's bunt, but Jeter grounded to short and O'Neill flied to
right. The Yankees had another leadoff runner in the sixth when
Williams lined a single, but Martinez hit into a double play and,
with runners at first and second and two out, Spencer flied out.
The Yankees were 0 for 5 with runners in scoring position in the
first six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez finally relented. Ibanez pulled a home run just inside
the right-field foul pole in the fifth inning, tying the score, and
again the Mariners loaded the bases with one out in the sixth. El
Duque dominated Cameron, whiffing him easily for the second out,
and it appeared as if he would escape another jam. But Ibanez
dribbled a grounder along the first-base line, too far away for
Martinez to come in and make a play. Hernandez had the only chance
to get an out, rushing over and reaching _ and missing the ball as
he fell. Ibanez was safe, Javier scored and the Mariners were
ahead, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out Wilson, though, and Soriano erased the
difference quickly by lofting a breaking ball from Frank Rodriguez
over the left-field fence. Tie score, again, but the Yankees
squandered an opportunity for more. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
