<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DOHN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS STILL RECOVERING FROM PIAZZA TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - It doesn't rank with a show producer selling one of
his star players to finance a theater production, and it's not yet
time to parade a goat around Chavez Ravine to exorcise the demons
of past sins.
</P>
<P>
   But the fortunes of the Dodgers certainly took a dramatic turn
toward embarrassment and losing when Fox executive and baseball
novice Chase Carey traded Mike Piazza, and they haven't improved.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years after the fact, the Dodgers are still searching
for an answer at the catcher's position, and folks are still
talking about the impact of losing Piazza, not to mention the cloud
it created.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza can't play against the Dodgers without hearing whispers
of what might have been, or what his loss did to the organization,
but he doesn't wonder when the commotion will end.
</P>
<P>
   And there is an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans will let it go the moment we win,'' Dodgers first
baseman Eric Karros said. ``That's the whole thing. As long as
we're not winning, or as long as we're struggling and not playing
up to expectations....''
</P>
<P>
   While Piazza has moved on and prospered, by winning with the
Mets and by signing a seven-year, $91 million contract, the Dodgers
have continued to spiral downward.
</P>
<P>
   And it certainly doesn't help that Piazza has continued to
produce at his normal rate and the Mets are expected to contend for
a championship while the Dodgers wallowed last season and are
trying to answer questions about their catching.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to deal with the here and now, not the what-ifs,''
Piazza said. ``That's natural in life to do that sometimes, and I
know that's what people do, but you can't dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, many continue to do so because it is such a sore point.
</P>
<P>
   Because of how the Piazza situation concluded and the fallout
that followed, the Dodgers have changed how they deal with players
and negotiating contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Daly, managing general partner and CEO of the Dodgers, was
working with Hollywood when Piazza was dealt, but he understands
the breakdown of communication between management and player was
the biggest reason Piazza was traded.
</P>
<P>
   Daly vowed that he, personally, would talk to players so a lack
of communication wouldn't be the reason for a trade or for a player
leaving the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like that won't happen again,'' Daly said during
spring training. ``I will make sure of that.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that is of any concern to Piazza, who's distanced
himself from his Dodgers days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just concentrating on doing my job,'' Piazza said.
``That's what I'm supposed to do and that's the thing I have to
really dedicate myself to. I can't help (what happened). That's
just something that happened. As a player, you can't get wrapped up
into that stuff. It's tough enough to play baseball, let alone
playing with other circumstances or other things on your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   So Piazza just continues to produce. He batted .303 with 40
homers and 124 RBI last season with the Mets but caught flack from
the Shea faithful because he hit !ital!only!off! .293 with runners
in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the Dodgers, he has hit .318 with 64 homers and
208 RBI in 261 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about Dodger history, it's something
you're never going to be able to sweep under the carpet,'' Karros
said. ``It happened. Now, is it something that the decision makers
dwell on? Should we dwell on it as players? It's like saying, do we
go out there every day and worry we traded Pedro (Martinez) for
Delino (DeShields)?''
</P>
<P>
   Ahhhh, another idea for another time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
