<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-TIGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA MOTIVATE TIGER TO SHOOT 68
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Tiger Woods arrived yesterday at Augusta National
Golf Club with a point to prove.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by television reports that characterized his Masters
chances as over, Woods said he sought to change public opinion. A
round of 68 in blustery conditions, highlighted by four consecutive
birdies, accomplished that objective. It moved the world's
top-ranked golfer to 1 under par for the tournament and within six
strokes of the lead heading into today's final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out of it,'' said Woods, whose round was disrupted by
a two-hour rain delay. ``I watched a little TV \RFriday\S night,
and a lot of people were saying I was completely out of it. ... I
didn't appreciate it very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods declined to identify what station he was watching, but
multiple sports anchors in the Augusta area and on ESPN discounted
his chances after Woods finished his second round in a tie for 39th
place, nine strokes behind David Duval. Woods reeled in 33 players
with yesterday's effort, moving into a tie for sixth pending
today's completion of the suspended third round.
</P>
<P>
   Woods likened his motivational experience in front of the
television to a conversation Arnold Palmer held with Bob Drum, a
sportswriter from Pittsburgh, before the final round of the 1960
U.S. Open. Drum told Palmer he had ``no chance'' of erasing a
seven-stroke deficit heading in the final round. Palmer closed with
a 65, passed 14 players and won by two strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Palmer credited Drum with providing emotional fuel
for his comeback. Woods said he felt ``similar'' motivation after
watching Friday's telecast but declined to identify the
sportscaster who provided it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you that \Rtoday\S,'' said Woods, who played his way
back into contention by collecting six birdies and two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 24, collected four of those birdies in consecutive holes
(Nos. 7-10), with none of the birdie putts traveling farther than
10 feet. Woods' streak ended at No. 11, where he was forced to wait
out the two-hour rain delay before hitting his approach shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't very happy,'' Woods said of the timing of the delay.
``When you're into the round and you're playing well, you're in a
rhythm. You can feel it in your body. To all of a sudden have that
come to a stop was a little disconcerting.''
</P>
<P>
   After two pars, Woods rebounded to bag birdies at the back-nine
par-5 holes (Nos. 13 and 15) before missing the green and taking a
bogey at No. 17. By posting a 68, Woods ended a streak of 10
consecutive rounds without breaking 70 at the Masters. He
positioned himself to win his second consecutive major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning PGA champ also reinforced a lesson that golf
analysts, in Woods' opinion, should have learned while watching
Paul Lawrie rally to win the 1999 British Open despite beginning
the final round 10 strokes off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a major championship, if you go out and shoot in the
mid-60s, you're going to make up more than a couple of shots.
You're going to really move up in the field,'' Woods said. ``It's a
lot different than playing in a regular tour event. The conditions
are so much more severe that guys start thinking where they're at,
and it becomes more difficult to shoot a low round when you've got
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're 10 shots back going into the weekend and play some
great golf, you can really win.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're Tiger Woods, you also have a chance to silence some
second-guessers from the TV studio.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
