<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-DODGERS-METS-NYT &LR;      04-08 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT METS, 6-5 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Franco ambled toward the first-base line and
stared into the dugout after Devon White's three-run homer vanished
over the right-center-field fence Saturday. Franco's face was a
picture of disbelief. Had he really botched a four-run lead in the
ninth inning? Had he really turned a rewarding afternoon for Pat
Mahomes and Jay Payton and the rest of the plucky Mets into a
forgettable afternoon? He had.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Franco helped shove it toward being forgettable and
Armando Benitez, who was supposed to rest, cemented the grim
scenario by surrendering a two-out home run to Eric Karros that
enabled the Los Angeles Dodgers to steal a 6-5 victory in 10 dreary
innings at Shea Stadium. The former and current closer both
floundered and both were booed, and Franco was seriously lambasted
by the fans.
</P>
<P>
   What a waste of so many strong performances, what a disastrous
way to lose a game and what a way to make an afternoon forgettable.
This one-run loss felt much worse in the somber Mets clubhouse than
other one-run losses. This hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody did great,'' Franco said. ``Everybody did great, but
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have played only seven games this season, and they
proved in 1999 that they were a resilient club by coming from
behind to win 47 times. But, even if these Mets wind up having
similar qualities, they will not soon forget a game in which they
belted two homers off Kevin Brown, received a sturdy performance
from Mahomes _ a reliever filling in for the injured Al Leiter _
and then watched a 5-1 lead evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a ball game we should have won,'' said Payton, who
stroked his first major league homer. ``Everyone in here will tell
you that.''
</P>
<P>
   But they did not because Franco could not get three outs in the
ninth before the Dodgers scored four runs. Manager Bobby Valentine
mentioned before the game that Benitez was unavailable because he
had pitched in two straight games and it was too early in the
season for him to work in three straight. Since the Mets had a 5-1
bulge, the sight of Franco instead of Benitez in the ninth did not
seem puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   Franco immediately struggled as Karros led off with a homer.
After Adrian Beltre struck out, Franco walked Chad Kreuter and
allowed Kevin Elster's single. The tying run was at the plate and
Benitez received a call from Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said: `I need you. Can you pitch?' I said, `No big deal,'''
Benitez said.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez needs 7 to 10 minutes to get ready. While he warmed up,
Franco induced Jose Vizcaino to fly out. Two outs. Benitez was
still warming up and White was strolling to the plate. He was 1 for
5 in his career against Franco and 0 for 7 with five strikeouts
against Benitez, but Valentine wanted White, a switch-hitter, to
bat right-handed. Besides, Benitez, who dodged a question about
whether he needed a day off, said, ``I wasn't ready yet'' as White
batted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Johnny's ninth inning, whether it was a one-run game or
a four-run game,'' Valentine insisted. ``He just didn't have
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   White ripped Franco's outside fastball the opposite way for a
home run to tie the score, 5-5. Four of the first six batters
scored off Franco, negating Mahomes' five and two-thirds innings of
one-run pitching, Payton's homer, Edgardo Alfonzo's two-run shot
and Melvin Mora's three hits. Everything that could have made
Saturday special, from Valentine's reserve-dominated lineup to
Mahomes' searching for his first victory as a starter since Aug. 6,
1994, dramatically changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one stung after the effort Pat gave us,'' Franco said.
``It kind of got lost in all the other garbage that happened. It's
a tough one to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez replaced Franco for the 10th and was also victimized by
Karros. After recording the first two outs, Benitez said, he worked
too quickly, affecting his motion. He left a fastball high in the
strike zone and Karros hit it 425 feet to left-center. In the
dugout, the Mets were distraught. In the stands, the fans were
depressed.
</P>
<P>
   It was not that way all afternoon. Valentine rested Mike Piazza,
Derek Bell, Todd Zeile and Rey Ordonez and started Todd Pratt, Jon
Nunnally, Mora and Matt Franco in their places. Because Darryl
Hamilton is disabled with an arthritic left big toe, Payton started
in center field, meaning the Mets started three regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us were joking it was like a B game in spring
training,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Dodgers lost Brown when he broke his right pinkie
trying to bunt in the fifth inning. His manager, Davey Johnson,
said he would probably be out for three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It all worked for the Mets until the ninth. It worked until
Franco, who has 416 saves in his career, took the ball in a nonsave
situation and fizzled. Franco, his hands clasped behind his back,
was polite yet defiant as he spoke about the perilous territory he
knows so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't do your job, you get booed,'' he said. ``What am I
supposed to do? I'm not going to go home and worry about it. I've
been booed for 11 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
