r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-INJURIES( GAMERTK)-LADN   04-08 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-INJURIES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE BROWN, SHEFFIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (NO NOTEBOOK TONIGHT, GAMER TK)-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - One of the brightest moments in the past few years
for the Dodgers was overshadowed by injuries to ace right-hander
Kevin Brown and All-Star outfielder Gary Sheffield that have
brought uneasiness to the first week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is expected to miss three to four weeks with a fractured
pinkie on his right hand. Sheffield was on crutches after suffering
a high ankle sprain just above his right ankle. His status will be
re-evaluated today. While Brown appears headed for the disabled
list, Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said he's hopeful
Sheffield could return during the upcoming series at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Also, reliever Gregg Olson has a strained right forearm that
could send him to the disabled list and right-hander Mike Fetters
re-aggravated the left quadricep injury that plagued him early in
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   It made for a surreal clubhouse following an improbable win in
which the Dodgers rallied for four runs in the ninth and beat the
Mets 6-5 on Eric Karros' solo homer in the 10th inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad day, but it's a good day for the victory we had to
come back like we did,'' Sheffield said. ``We needed the win to get
back on the right track, but to lose two key players, we have to
have other guys pick us up until we get back. Hopefully, I'll be
back soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the lone given in the Dodgers' starting rotation, injured
his hand attempting to bunt in the top of the fifth inning. The
ball dipped below his bat and struck his hand. He doubled over in
pain but finished the at-bat. He also pitched the bottom of the
fifth inning before leaving the game.
</P>
<P>
   He will fly to Los Angeles today and be examined Monday by hand
specialist Dr. Norman Zemel. But he's not ruling out his Thursday
start in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can pitch around it, I'd like to do it,'' said Brown, who
also bruised his right ring finger on the bunt attempt. ``It's a
matter of what they say what would happen. If it heals up OK, or if
it heals up wrong, is it going to be a problem down the line? We'll
see what they think. You're not really using that finger. If it
heals up wrong, will it be a problem then? That's what I have to
talk to them and find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation where we'll see what they say and go from
there. As far as I'm concerned, I'm going to be out there as soon
as I can. Someone's going to have to convince me that I'm risking
having problems with it and causing problems with my pitching for a
while. I'm not interested in something that's going to cause a
season-long problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said the Dodgers wouldn't do anything
silly to jeopardize Brown's health or his career, and given he's in
the second year of a seven-year, $105 million contract it behooves
both parties to proceed cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's impossible to overstate Brown's importance to the
Dodgers, especially the starting rotation. For as much uncertainty
that surrounds the Dodgers' other starters, Brown is continually
counted on to pitch deep into games.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers trainer Stan Johnston said the fracture begins at the
base of the pinkie and travels up the finger to the first knuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to pitch with it, that's Brownie, but I don't see any
possibility of him pitching for three or four weeks,'' Johnson
said. ``We're not going to endanger a great career by bringing him
back too soon. That's just not going to happen. It's amazing he
could pitch another inning with the fracture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield suffered his ankle injury when he stumbled on the
warning track on Joe Nunnally's first-inning double. A long-term
injury would also have a heavy impact on the Dodgers' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, batting .400, has hit safely in all six games this
season. He also has two homers and two triples and sets up the
beefy part of the lineup with Shawn Green and Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got ready to plant my right foot and go back and get
the ball, my foot twisted, and I felt it, so I shifted my weight to
where I didn't break it,'' Sheffield said. ``This is not in a good
area because it's a high sprain. I hate that it's my right foot,
too. It's my push-off leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want a sprained ankle, but to do it on my right
foot, and to see what Mo Vaughn went through last year and the pain
he had to play through all season. Hopefully, it's nothing like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson was plagued by an elbow problem during the spring, but
Johnston said this injury is in another area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably going to take a little bit of time,'' Olson
said. ``Right now, I'd say I need some time. It seems like (a
strain). It's right in the bulk of the muscle. It's not in the area
that's serious. You felt it every pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Fetters said his quadricep problem shouldn't linger and he'd be
ready to go today, but the Dodgers still face enormous gaps to fill
if Brown, Sheffield and/or Olson are disabled.
</P>
<P>
   It's compounded by the fact the Dodgers still need to decide on
a starter for next Saturday's game against Cincinnati. Carlos Perez
was supposed to start against the Reds, but he was sent to Triple-A
Albuquerque before Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said every option would be looked at, but the Dodgers
are more likely to recall other pitchers. Eric Gagne, Jeff Williams
and Mike Judd are the leading candidates.
</P>
<P>
   What the Dodgers do to fill Sheffield's spot, if need be, is
more precarious. The Dodgers still have five healthy outfielders,
and they could call either an outfielder or an infielder into the
mix. Todd Hollandsworth is expected to start in Sheffield's
absence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
