<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-BBNOTES-SEATTLE-B     04-08 2662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-SEATTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD OF DIFFERENCE IN SEATTLE PEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have seen the face of baseball in Seattle without Junior, and
his name is . . . Daimajin?
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to the enormously gifted Alex Rodriguez,
who may follow Ken Griffey out of town after this season, the key
to whether the Mariners are contenders in September may well be
their new Japanese closer, Kazuhiro Sasaki, who already is a huge
star in the Pacific Rim and has the makings of one over here, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki's nickname is Daimajin, which is the name of a 60-foot
stone character in a Japanese folk tale who comes to life to save
his village from evil. Seattle general manager Pat Gillick is
paying Sasaki in excess of $8 million over the next two years to
spare Seattle the blown saves that were a staple during Griffey's
tenure with the team.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4-inch, 209-pound Sasaki, 32, is Japan's career
leader in saves with 229, and Thursday night he earned his first
save here against the Red Sox by striking out the side, showing off
a devastating forkball in the process. He also pitched the night
before against the Sox and threw a dozen fastballs, all for
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt he'd be good, we really did,'' said Seattle manager
Lou Piniella, who came into camp thinking Jose Mesa would return as
his closer, with Sasaki setting up, but changed his mind last
weekend. ``He threw the ball well this spring, and as spring
training progressed, he threw the ball better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Price, the Mariners' new pitching coach, played in the
Angels' minor league system with Bryan Harvey, the former All-Star
closer for the Angels and Marlins. Price says Sasaki's forkball
reminds him of the pitch Harvey learned from Joe Coleman, the
former Tigers pitcher. Sasaki doesn't throw it quite as hard as
Harvey did, but the paralyzing action is similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of guys who get ahead in the count and bury
it,'' Price said, ``but Kazu gets out ahead and throws strikes with
it, like he did against Jason (Varitek). The bottom falls out of
it, but it's still a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hideo Nomo, another Japanese pitcher, first came to the
Dodgers, his splitter was unhittable, but hitters eventually
learned to lay off the pitch because it usually dropped out of the
strike zone. That doesn't happen with Sasaki, Price says.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it was just one series, but is Sasaki as good as he
looked against the Sox?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is,'' Price said. ``I think he's not going into an
unfamiliar situation here. He was looked upon as the premier
pitcher in all of Japan, where I'm told he's preserved like a
national treasure, and he's working here in circumstances that he's
not unfamiliar with.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been doing it for 10 years. He knows what it's like to
pitch in the ninth inning. This is not the infancy stage of his
being a closer. And with his stuff, he doesn't have to back down to
anybody. He has great command of his fastball, and he's off the
charts with his forkball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization showed a real commitment to strengthening our
pitching. We were looking for a guy to step up and be that guy we
could rally around. No disrespect to Jose, but I see the public
really excited about Kazu. Not only for the way he pitches, but the
kid's personality. He's affable, always smiling, happy. He's
integrated himself with the club. He's a lot of fun to have
around.''
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 160 media members from Japan following
Sasaki during spring training in Arizona, and the Mariners' first
three games were televised back to Japan by NHK, a Japanese
television network, and broadcast by Jolf radio.
</P>
<P>
   When he came into the games in Safeco Field, the outfield panels
flashed ``Daimajin'' in giant letters while the center-field
scoreboard flashed the shortened version of his first name, Kazu,
in bright colors. He was greeted the first night with a standing
ovation, and he left to another one after earning his first save.
</P>
<P>
   The club, of course, understands the marketing possibilities
both home and abroad. He's already featured in a TV ad with club
broadcaster Dave Niehaus, supposedly learning English by repeating
some of Niehaus's pet phrases (``Grand salami'' for a grand slam).
Niehaus now has taken to uttering ``sashin,'' the Japanese word for
strikeout, when Sasaki rings someone up.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Hale, the Mariners' director of public information, told
of a reception held for Sasaki last weekend at Safeco Field in
response to a request from the Japanese-American chamber of
commerce. Five hundred people were in attendance, including many of
the top politicos in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The team's Japanese fans can now send messages to
Japan(at)Mariners.org and get a response from the team's Japan
liaison, Hide Sueyoshi, who also is the team's assistant to the
director for Pacific Rim scouting. And the team's press releases
are now available in Japanese on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Sox GM Dan Duquette liked Sasaki's skills but said his asking
price was too rich for the Sox, who gave $3.35 million to Korean
lefty Sang Hoon Lee instead. But it wouldn't have mattered if
Duquette were willing to cough over some of the Yawkey Trust's cash
for Sasaki. His agent, Tony Attanasio, is openly contemptuous of
Duquette and Boston's international scouting director, Ray
Poitevint.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella acknowledges there's a difference in these Mariners.
And it's not just Sasaki. Arthur Rhodes, the lefthander signed as a
free agent from Baltimore, was brought in twice to face Troy
O'Leary in the late innings and set down three Sox batters in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, in three-quarters of our games I didn't have a
lefty in the bullpen,'' Piniella said. ``You need matchups at the
end of the game. A manager basically uses what he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing how much smarter a manager becomes when he has a good
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we had a real good offense over here, but our
pitching was a struggle,'' Piniella said. ``We've fortified our
pitching, but now we're going to have to win with pitching and
defense. I knew that coming out of spring training. You're going to
see us play a lot of tight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the thunder we had in the past, but we're still
a home run hitting team, to be honest. You can talk all you want
about little ball, but we're still a home run hitting team.''
</P>
<P>
   A few long balls and one Daimajin, and the Mariners might still
be playing in October.
</P>
<P>
   A short triple
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bowa, the Mariners' third base coach, has been around pro
ball since 1966. As one of the greatest defensive shortstops in
history _ his lifetime fielding percentage of .980 is the National
League record for the position _ Bowa has an insider's view of the
Three Amigos, Nomar Garciaparra, Derek Jeter, and Alex Rodriguez.
He's coaching Rodriguez now _ A-Rod recommended him highly to
Gillick _ and he's a huge fan of Garciaparra and Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Bowa's thoughts last week, while first Nomar, then Jeter, went
head to head against A-Rod in Seattle:
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all great players. They'll get a hit, steal a base,
drive in a run, make plays. If you need a home run, they'll hit a
home run. If you need a double, they'll hit a double. You want all
three of them up at the plate with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of these guys comes along once every 50 years. We've got
three in one decade. I don't think we'll ever see anything like it
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing all three of them do is respect what has come
before them. Derek Jeter always says hello to me. Most guys don't
even know the names of the coaches and the managers. These guys
know the history of baseball. They respect the history of baseball,
and they all have work ethics second to none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched them from the other side, and they all work hard.
They don't take shortcuts. They're all on the top of their game.
Yes, they're all great athletes, but they work at it, too. Their
greatness is not easily achieved. I'd get to the clubhouse at 7 in
the morning during spring training, and A-Rod would be there,
working out.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that shocks me about Nomar? My arm hurts when he
throws. I've never seen somebody who throws that unorthodox get so
much on the ball in my life. He literally slings it over there,
with unbelievable velocity. You watch most guys who throw on the
run, they're just trying to get rid of it and get it to the bag. He
throws with great velocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a kid watching an instructional video of Nomar,
you'd say, `Don't throw like that or you'll blow your arm out.' (An
injury) would not surprise me, the way he throws. But I remember
talking to Jimy (Williams), and him saying, `I'm not saying a word
to this guy.' You can't. But I hope he doesn't blow out his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you compare the three of them, they all bring
everything to the party, but they all have different ways to get to
the party. A-Rod the other night, he hit a home run off his front
foot. Jeter inside-outs the ball unbelievably well. Nomar hits
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they do to each other is drive each other. They
all want to be the best, they all want a championship, and they all
respect one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking some heat
</P>
<P>
   Tim Spehr, the veteran catcher who opened the season in
Pawtucket, said 22-year-old Korean righthander Sunny Kim threw the
best bullpen session he caught in camp this spring. ``He's got a
great curve, a great split, and an excellent fastball,'' Spehr
said. ``He's going to come fast.'' Peabody's Steve Lomasney, who
caught Kim the last two years in Sarasota, Trenton, and the Arizona
Fall League, also has raves. Asked if Kim had a chance to become a
good pitcher, Lomasney looked disbelievingly at his questioner and
said, ``You mean he isn't one right now? He's got an above-average
fastball that he hits the black with on both sides of the plate, he
has a good breaking pitch that he can throw at any time in the
count, and his changeup (splitter), which is definitely his out
pitch, is one of the best around.'' Lomasney said Kim's fastball is
consistently 89-92 m.p.h. ``And there are certain times of the
game,'' he said, ``that he can hump it up to 95. His two-seamer is
as good a two-seamer as anybody. He's got real confidence in his
stuff, and he's not intimidated by anybody. He goes right after
hitters. And Sunny's real smart.'' Kim has picked up English
rapidly and carries around a portable computer translator . . .
It's a mystery why Donnie Sadler, who deserves to be on Boston's
big-league club, wasn't told until the day before the season
started in Pawtucket that the Sox planned to have him play center
field there. The decision was not made on Ben Mondor Way. It was
made on Yawkey Way. For Sadler, who would rather play second base,
center field is as much of a dead end as shortstop. Now, in
addition to having Garciaparra in front of him, he has Carl Everett
there, too, with Darren Lewis the obvious choice to play if Everett
goes down or needs a rest . . . Tough debut for Michael Coleman,
who was shifted to right field to make room for Sadler. He made an
error and whiffed three times in Pawtucket's 6-3 loss to Syracuse.
Tomo Ohka incurred his first minor league loss after going 15-0
between Trenton and Pawtucket last season, while Lee, in his
American pro debut, gave up four hits and four runs (one earned) in
1 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ex files
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Red Sox Player of the Week honors go to Carl Pavano. The
24-year-old Expos righthander, who is finally healthy and coming
off a great spring, gave up just one run on five hits and a walk in
eight innings of an 11-3 win over the Dodgers Thursday night.
Runners-up honors go to Orioles righthander Pat Rapp (6 IP, 5 H, 5
BB, 2 R) and Giants outfielder Ellis Burks (home runs in each of
his first two games, including an upper-deck shot at Miami's Pro
Player Stadium). Worst performance by an ex-Sox player? Tampa Bay
DH Jose Canseco, who struck out four times in four at-bats Thursday
against the Twins. Pavano, of course, went to Montreal in the Pedro
Martinez deal three Novembers ago. Tony Armas Jr., the highly-rated
pitching prospect who went with Pavano, is in extended spring
training because of stiffness in his throwing elbow . . . Blue Jays
second baseman Homer Bush tried out a cherry-red Garciaparra bat
during BP last week. The verdict? ``It's a keeper,'' he said . . .
Angels president Tony Tavares acknowledged Disney chairman Michael
Eisner is ``not passionate about having to own this team.'' Eisner
was noticeably absent from the Angels opener and was actively
trying to sell the team. Maybe it's an AL West thing. Mariners
officials say Hiroshi Yamauchi, who has owned 49 percent of the
club since '92, has yet to see a game in Seattle in person.
Yamauchi, chairman of Nintendo International, lives in Kyoto,
Japan. Compared with Eisner and Yamauchi, Sox boss John Harrington,
keeper of the Trust, is front and center . . . Arizona's Randy
Johnson threw more pitches (133) than any other Opening Day pitcher
last week. No surprise there. The Unit threw 4,206 pitches last
season, the most in the majors . . . It was an unnerving
development for the Dodgers when catcher Todd Hundley had to miss a
couple of games with a strained medial collateral ligament in his
right knee. Hundley came back and played Thursday, but he hit just
.207 last season after coming back from elbow surgery . . . Closer
Mike Jackson, passed over in the free agent market by teams worried
about his health, has sent up red flags in Philadelphia after
complaining of a sore shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel laboring
</P>
<P>
   A shaky debut for Charlie Manuel, the Indians' new manager, who
lost two out of three to the Orioles and Mike Hargrove, fired as
the Tribe's manager after their playoff elimination by the Sox. The
Indians already have lost more games against the Orioles this
season than they did all of last year under Hargrove, when they
went 9-1 against the Birds . . . Managers were showing short
tempers all over the circuit. Manuel made it through the opener, an
Indians win, but was tossed for arguing balls and strikes in the
next two games . . . Expos manager Felipe Alou cursed out Dodgers
pitcher Orel Hershiser for hitting slugger Vladimir Guerrero with a
pitch. Alou stood at the top of the dugout steps, bellowing at
Hershiser and saying the matter was ``between you and I.''
Hershiser, of course, denied he was throwing at Guerrero, who hit
two home runs in the series and had reached base three times in the
game when Hershiser nailed him. ``He's a big man, an honorable man,
a guy who might be in the Hall of Fame, and I might be lesser than
that,'' Alou said afterward. ``But I have a right to believe he hit
Guerrero purposely. If I'm wrong, I'll ask for forgiveness.''
Meanwhile, Milwaukee's new manager, Davey Lopes, yelled at Reds
shortstop Barry Larkin for stealing third in the ninth inning with
the Reds down four runs. The Brewers had left third base uncovered
while deploying a shift against Ken Griffey . . . You can be sure
Tigers fans took note of Gabe Kapler hitting two home runs in his
first game in Texas, while ex-Rangers slugger Juan Gonzalez already
is begging off games because of sore hamstrings. This is the fourth
season Gonzalez has missed games because of hamstring problems . .
. Brian McRae, released last week by the Cardinals, was in Seattle
last week working the Mariners-Sox game as an ESPN analyst . . .
While savoring the miracle of Andres Galarraga's return from cancer
and of Kenny Lofton's defying medical probability and returning
months ahead of schedule from elbow surgery, condolences go out to
the Aussie lefthander Graeme Lloyd, whose 26-year-old wife, Cindy,
died of complications from Crohn's disease on the eve of the Expos
opener. Said Expos catcher Chris Widger, ``It makes you think what
you do on the field is kind of stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
