<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     04-08 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMAR PUTTING FANS IN THE SEATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Edison Field, home of the Anaheim Angels, is
not far from York Field and Joe Miller Field in Whittier, Calif.,
where Ramon Garciaparra would hit millions of fungos to his young
son, Nomar.
</P>
<P>
   Edison is only a 20-minute drive from St. John Bosco in
Bellflower, Calif. _ a Catholic boys' school run by Salesian
priests _ from which Nomar graduated in 1991. It was at St. John
Bosco that he kicked a 47-yard field goal for the football team.
</P>
<P>
   Because of all this, Red Sox-Angels games in Southern California
are special for Nomar and his family. Mo Vaughn's parents, Leroy
and Shirley, attend almost every game, often sitting in a private
box Mo rents. Nomar, meanwhile, has more than 100 family and
friends scattered throughout the Edison stands, most on the first
base side behind the Red Sox dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him come over to the rail and kiss his sister before the
game,'' said an Edison usher Friday night. ``She was wearing a blue
Red Sox jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Garciaparras wear Nomar No. 5 jerseys. It was the
favorite number of dad Ramon (who grew up in Guadalajara, Mexico),
and it's been carried on by Ramon's kids, Nomar, Michael, Monique,
and Yvette. Red Sox garb is optional for mom Sylvia.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra visited Edison Field (then Anaheim Stadium) the day
he signed his Red Sox contract in 1994 (``I wasn't even 21 yet, I
was 20 years old''). The Red Sox were playing the Angels that night
and Garciaparra went on the radio with Joe Castiglione and made a
lasting impression on Sox fans listening back home. When he made
his first trip to California with the Sox two years later, his
personal cheering section was 300 strong. It's not quite that big
anymore, and the Garciaparras are a little more reserved these
days, but it's still a formidable support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see 'em,'' Nomar said. ``They're everywhere in the
stands. It's always great to feel the support and go out there and
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just good to see family. But I've got to go out there and
play another game. Unfortunately, I don't have a lot of time to
spend with them and stuff because we're playing a game every day.
To me, something special is being able to spend a lot of time with
the family and that I can't do while I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And the numbers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we had to do it through group sales,'' he said with a
smile. ``Now they're on their own and everybody gets them
themselves. I just take care of my immediate family now.''
</P>
<P>
   Other numbers were not so strong as the Sox prepared to play the
Angels in their fifth game of the season Saturday night. In the
Sox' first four games, Garciaparra was 3 for 16 (.188) with no
homers, no RBIs, and only one extra-base hit, a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be fine, he'll be fine, he will be fine,'' recited
manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting good swings,'' Garciaparra said. ``This happens.
It's part of it and you've got to go through it. The pitchers
aren't doing anything differently. I'm seeing balls I usually hit.
Right now it seems like we're a little out of synch. Our pitchers
are doing a good job, but we've got to go out and get some runs so
they feel more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night against Jason Dickson, Garciaparra came up with
Trot Nixon on third and one out in the fourth inning. He popped to
short _ an uncharacteristic failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy on third, one out _ popping up _ that's not our team,'' he
said, disgusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just missing balls. We've got to create more opportunities
and capitalize on 'em. It's still early and there's a lot, a lot of
baseball left. The key is keeping everybody healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any extra pressure on me. I just have to
go out there and do whatever it takes _ move the guy over or drive
guys in. I never set individual goals for myself. I just want to
win the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as he likes seeing family and friends, he looks forward to
getting back to Fenway Tuesday when the Red Sox open at home
against the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know our fans have expectations of us and we have high
expectations of ourselves as well,'' he said. ``We play hard and I
think they respect that we give 100 percent for nine innings. And
it shows because the fans stay and support us for all nine
innings.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be good for Nomar to get home, even if it's 3,000 miles
from home. At Fenway, there will be more No. 5 jerseys in the
stands _ folks who love Nomar like family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
