<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1171 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-WARRICK-     04-08 2559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-WARRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARRICK STILL THE REASONABLE CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brian Billick knows a few things about offense, having created
one at Minnesota that went wild and similar successful ones
elsewhere, so his opinion on matters offensive count, and his
opinion is clear on Peter Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   Take the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can measure him, weigh him, put him in shorts all you
want, but put the film on,'' said the Baltimore Ravens' coach last
week after Warrick had visited the team's training facility. ``He
is an impact player and will be one in this league. I don't think
anyone in this league will disagree with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Charley Armey won't. The St. Louis Rams' general
manager firmly believes Warrick is ``the only impact player in this
draft. The only player who can change a game with one play and
will.''
</P>
<P>
   So why isn't he going to be the first choice?
</P>
<P>
   How about because of paralysis from analysis?
</P>
<P>
   When the college football season ended in January, Warrick was
the No. 1 pick by acclamation. He was all but unstoppable through
his career at Florida State. He played best in the biggest games.
He threatened defenses constantly and burned them often. He changed
games by his mere presence.
</P>
<P>
   Then he ran a 4.67 40-yard dash in February at a private workout
and showed up to meet executives of the Cleveland Browns in
military fatigues, and the talk suddenly switched to Penn State's
two defensive stars, pass rusher Courtney Brown and linebacker
LaVar Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   What's up with that?
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's agent, Michael George, wonders himself. He says the
Browns changed their mind about Warrick about two weeks ago and
will go with defense, meaning Arrington or Brown, depending on
which one agrees to a contract before he's selected.
</P>
<P>
   Both are potential stars, but Warrick is the kind of player who
can do the things that another guy who was slip-sliding away in the
draft a couple of years ago does. He can do what Randy Moss can do,
which is force a defense to change the way it plays.
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently if he would take Vonnie Holliday again if he had
the chance, Green Bay Packers general manager Ron Wolf said, ``No,
I'd take Moss.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no knock on Holliday, it's a comment on what can happen
when teams look at a player they know is special and then go about
finding holes in him. In Moss's case, it was all off-the-field
problems, of which he had enough to legitimately concern teams. He
slid to No. 21 and has been in the Pro Bowl ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But Warrick has no such history. One bad 40 time run on an
indoor basketball court while wearing outdoor track shoes and
everything changed for him, which illustrates the weakness of many
NFL scouting operations.
</P>
<P>
   They spend millions to watch young men play football. They watch
film of them playing football. They go and watch them play football
live. They turn on the TV and watch them play football. Then
February comes when all the football games are over and they change
their minds based on a workout or a rumor.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the smartest guy in this entire process seems to be
young Warrick himself.
</P>
<P>
   He answered the questions about his speed by simply saying, ``To
be a great receiver, you don't have to have great speed. You have
to run great routes, then make yards after the catch. Teams aren't
drafting me to be a track star. If they want a track star, then
draft one. If they want a wide receiver, then I think I'm the best
in college football.''
</P>
<P>
   Which he is, but there is even a school of thought that says you
don't take a wide receiver No. 1 under any circumstances. It is a
position shared even by guys who should know better, guys who make
their living running offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at what Warrick did in his career and he was probably
the best player in college football the past three years,'' said
Washington coach Norv Turner at the recent owners meetings. ``I
think it's the position.''
</P>
<P>
   What Turner meant was that only five wide receivers have ever
been selected with the first overall pick. One was Irving Fryar,
who put together Hall of Fame numbers but not until he left the
team that gambled on him _ the Patriots. Another was Keyshawn
Johnson, and teams are talking about trading multiple picks to get
him away from the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel people will argue that it is easier to find great
receivers than great pass rushers, and that may be true, but you
can also miss far more easily on a pass rusher than on a great
receiver because the pass rushing game in the NFL is far different
from college, while route running and receiving skills are more
readily transferable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing with receivers is there are more of them, so the
differential from the top one to the fifth or sixth one isn't as
great as at some other positions,'' said Browns coach Chris Palmer.
``Peter Warrick is a great player. But the other two are
something.''
</P>
<P>
   They'd better be, because if the Browns and Redskins pass on
Warrick and he slips to No. 4 _ or even to Billick in the fifth
spot _ and turns into the same kind of player in the NFL that he
has been in college, somebody will have some explaining to do.
</P>
<P>
   As Warrick's agent loves to remind people, two years ago,
Arizona took Andre Wadsworth with the third pick, and Minnesota
took Moss with the 21st.
</P>
<P>
   Whom would you want today?
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Browns should remember what time of year this is.
It's a time when otherwise sane personnel men stop believing their
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There is still time for the Browns to avoid that. All they have
to do is what Billick suggested. All they have to do is put on some
film and see how many of these great defensive players they're
interested in ever tackled Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Rice, he's not the fastest man in the world, but when he
breaks out, isn't anybody going to catch him,'' Warrick said. ``It
all boils down to making plays when your number is called.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Warrick does that, which is why when his number is called
next, it should be the first one.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer still in demand
</P>
<P>
   If you don't understand how few NFL-caliber quarterbacks exist
today, consider the case of Rick Mirer. The former No. 1 pick of
the Seattle Seahawks has thrown 10 touchdown passes and 27
interceptions the last four years, with half the touchdowns and a
third of the interceptions coming last season when he went 2-4 as a
starter for the New York Jets before losing his job to a former
special teams player, Ray Lucas. Yet Mirer is being courted by the
49ers and Vikings and reportedly has a handshake agreement to sign
with San Francisco after June 1 when the Niners will have enough
cap room. As it stands, Mirer is set to have a two-day workout with
the 49ers during their April 28-30 minicamp. At the moment, the
49ers are $1.467 million under the cap but need to have $2 million
cleared to make their 10 draft selections . . . San Francisco is
not sure whether Steve Young will be back, but several close
friends believe he will not. Young always said he was unlikely to
get married until he was finished playing. He recently took that
step and has been on an extended honeymoon in the South Pacific. If
he does decide to play, the Denver Broncos hope to make a deal to
land him . . . Pity the league's assistant coaches. Not only are
Larry Kennan's efforts to get them medical insurance and other
benefits falling on deaf ears, but now the owners have done away
with the supervisory tag that allowed an assistant to break his
contract without permission if he was moving up to a coordinator's
job. Now no coach can take such a job without his old club's
permission if he is under contract. Do these guys coach in America
or the World League? . . . After a week of throwing, San Diego
quarterback Ryan Leaf says he has not gotten back the zip after two
arthroscopies on his shoulder in the last seven months. Leaf will
see well-known orthopedic surgeon James Andrews in Birmingham,
Ala., this week for a second opinion. The Chargers initially
claimed there was nothing wrong with his shoulder, but the young
quarterback remains convinced otherwise . . . The Rams will unveil
new uniforms at a fashion show in a St. Louis mall this week. They
have changed from royal blue to navy blue. Fortunately, the ram
horns remain on their helmets . . . Helmet trouble exists in New
York, however, after the Giants announced they were going back to
the old ``NY'' logo. This enraged politicians in New York and New
Jersey, many of whom work under the theory that if you train, play,
and practice in New Jersey all week, you shouldn't put ``NY'' on
your hat on Sunday afternoon. ``Calling them the New York Giants is
like Diana Ross going out on tour without Mary Wilson and trying to
say it's the Supremes,'' said New York Senate minority leader
Richard Codey. ``It's time for them to face it. They're the Jersey
Giants no matter what it says on their helmets. The closest they've
come to New York is when they look at it.'' Equally outraged was
New Jersey Gov. Christine Whitman, who probably should have more
important things on her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Tangled Web
</P>
<P>
   Only a week after NFL owners ``agreed'' not to do anything that
might jeopardize a leaguewide Internet deal, Dallas's Jerry Jones
did that when he signed a five-year deal to let Broadband Sports
operate the Cowboys' Web site. The owners had voted to unify
NFL.com with team Web sites but did allow individual clubs to
operate independently this year. Jones seemed to jump the gun,
though, with an ambitious plan that would include streaming video
of Cowboys practices, among other things. Technically, Jones did
nothing wrong because all clubs are free to make local deals this
year, but clearly he went further than expected . . . After meeting
with the Browns, Arrington feels he has a good chance to be the
draft's top selection. This comes only days after he advocated for
his teammate, Brown, to be the top selection. ``After conversing
with the owner and the coaching staff, I get the feeling they
really don't know,'' Arrington said. ``But at this point I'm kind
of confident that maybe I'll end up in Cleveland.'' Both Arrington
and Brown were in Cleveland Thursday. A day earlier, Arrington was
in Washington, saying the Redskins would be ``a perfect fit for
me.'' It probably didn't bode well for his interest in the Browns
that he claimed he spent most of his eight-minute interview trying
to convince them to take Brown . . . Speaking of draftees with
something on their mind, Michigan State wide receiver Plaxico
Burress has seen himself slide from a projected top-five pick to
more than halfway down the first round because of rumors that he
has attitude problems and is difficult to handle. Burress is
blaming most of the rumors on the Philadelphia Eagles, with whom he
failed to connect on several interview sessions. At the combine in
February, the Eagles claim, he blew them off to attend an Indiana
Pacers game. Burress says he knew nothing about the meeting. Then
last Monday, Burress said he wanted to go watch his school play for
the NCAA basketball title in Indianapolis rather than meet with
Philadelphia. Angered over a request from agent Leigh Steinberg's
office to reschedule, the Eagles simply canceled. The Jets, Bears,
Ravens, and Buccaneers all agreed to reschedule meetings with
Burress. Other unflattering (and Burress says unsubstantiated)
rumors are that he showed up for his private workout in a stretch
limo (he says it was a van) and that he is already more than
$200,000 in debt. It didn't help that when college teammate Gari
Scott came to visit the Eagles, he told reporters that many
teammates considered Burress arrogant and selfish. This happens
every year at this time to somebody. One year it happened to a guy
named Dan Marino. He seemd to survive it all right, and if Burress
can play, he will too.
</P>
<P>
   Minding his own business
</P>
<P>
   During the annual coaches breakfast at the owners' meetings in
Florida, Patriots coach Bill Belichick was asked if he was glad he
got out of the Jets' situation considering the problems new coach
Al Groh is already facing with Johnson and a tight salary cap. ``I
don't sit around and gloat about what everybody else's problems are
in the league,'' Belichick said. ``We've got about $400 under the
cap and no players, so I'm not really worried about the Jets. I've
got enough of my own problems.'' Unlike many of Belichick's
players, he understands the situation in New England . . . As
installment payments go, Barry Sanders made a big one last week
when he forked over $88,333 to the Lions as he began repaying the
portion of his signing bonus an arbitrator says he forfeited by
retiring two days before training camp last summer. Sanders paid
the first installment with a cashier's check, and the remaining
ones will be far bigger. If he stays retired, he has to come up
with $1.83 million a year for the next three years. He owed only
$83,333 this year because the Lions had withheld the final $1.75
million due him from his signing bonus last September. Right now
Sanders and the Lions are fighting over when the other payments are
due. Arbitrator Sam Kagel has yet to rule on that, but either way
it'll be a big installment . . . Jimmy Gould, agent for Terry
Glenn, should know better than to tell a reporter he is trying to
get the Patriots to renegotiate Glenn's contract, which has two
years to run. Glenn remains a special player, but his medical and
off-field problems have retarded his progress and made him less
than a fan favorite. The last thing he needs at the moment is talk
of a potential sit-down strike if he doesn't get the kind of deal
his draft day contemporary, Indianapolis's Marvin Harrison, just
landed. Harrison had 115 receptions for 1,663 yards and 12
touchdowns last year and was rewarded with a five-year, $25.4
million contract that included a $11.5 million signing bonus. This
has made Glenn and Johnson antsy. Johnson is demanding a new deal
or a trade from the Jets, couching it in a demand for ``respect.''
These days in sports, ``respect'' means only one thing: cash. The
difference is that Harrison put up far bigger numbers than Johnson
or Glenn and had only one year remaining on his contract, so his
new deal was extremely cap-friendly as well as good business for
the Colts. Glenn and Johnson have two years left, so there is no
pressure on the teams to do a thing. Fiscally, the smart thing is
for the Jets and Patriots to hold to their present deals. The smart
thing for Glenn is to be quiet and have the kind of season Harrison
had last year, when he had two years left on his contract. If Glenn
does anything near what Harrison did in 1999, he'll cash in next
year . . . Times have definitely changed in Tampa. The Bucs, who
once couldn't give away tickets, are within 2,000 sales of becoming
one of 11 NFL teams with a waiting list for season tickets. They
will try to sell those tickets at a pick-your-seat event this week
. . . Don't expect to see wide receiver Bert Emanuel in Raymond
James Stadium, though. The Bucs' wide receiver, who has been a
major disappointment the past two years, has been told not to
bother attending the team's offseason workouts because he'll be
gone by June, one way or another.
</P>
</TEXT>
