<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-AUGUSTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLAINTS, LIKE CHANGES, NOTHING NEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ So, many players were unhappy with the changes
made to Augusta National Golf Club? What a surprise. They are
usually such an agreeable group of gents.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw was aghast that the club would lay a shovel to
Bobby Jones's legacy. Jack Nicklaus couldn't use his tree lines.
Tiger Woods said the ninth hole was completely changed. And Phil
Mickelson, noted architect, said, ``I think Bobby Jones and Alister
Mackenzie were great designers. I don't think it's the place of
anybody, if you can't break 90, to be changing the golf course from
those original designs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, of course, shot a crisp 83 in the first round of The
Players Championship two weeks ago, so by six shots he apparently
is qualified _ to offer expertise on the subject. But when he tries
to do that, he makes it worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had the chance to play the same golf course that the
guys did in the '30s and '40s,'' he told reporters last week.
Apparently, he feels life was more fair for players back then. We
must assume, however, that while he'd like to play the Augusta
National of that era, he would not like the purses golfers played
for, the greens they putted on, the transportation they dealt with,
or their lack of TV exposure.
</P>
<P>
   And how about equipment? Why is it OK to improve equipment but
not to update golf courses? Simple. The equipment changes have
benefitted the players, while changes to courses usually don't.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta has long been one of the world's greatest courses, and
that hasn't changed one bit. Rough has been added to offset the
tremendous distance players now hit the ball. What remains the
heart and soul of this course, however, is its greens, which
require accurate shots to find the correct spots.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods shot 75 Thursday, it had nothing to do with narrow
fairways. He shanked a shot from the middle of the fairway at the
par-4 10th and made double bogey. He misjudged the wind at the
par-3 12th and went into the water. He missed a 2-foot putt at the
12th for a triple bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Stadler took a 9 at the par-5 15th. The rough? The
disrupted tree lines? The 1982 champ scoffed: ``The golf course
played the same as always. You have to hit good iron shots in
there, or you're struggling to make par.'' Stadler dumped his third
shot into the water on 15, took a drop, then got the next one wet.
Cheers to him for not blaming Tom Fazio, the famed architect who
oversaw the changes to this venerable course.
</P>
<P>
   And bravo to all those players who embrace logic on this
subject. Nick Price is among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy they are (making changes),'' said Price. ``There are
changes that needed to be done there over the years. It's nice to
see them do that, to make the course play longer and harder.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those folks who cringe at the thought of altering the
Mona Lisa of golf courses, check out the 2000 Masters media guide,
which chronicles 69 significant changes over time. Many are subtle,
some are not. There was, for instance, the switch from Bermuda to
bentgrass on the greens in 1980. There are still mumblings from the
old guard to go back to Bermuda to speed 'em up.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't today's pampered players love that?
</P>
<P>
   What's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind one thing about today's professional golfers: They
always find something to complain about. David Duval said exactly
that when asked about _ guess what? _ complaints that the TPC at
Sawgrass was too penalizing. Indeed, these players can't figure out
what the problem is, which makes you wonder whether there is a
problem. Go back to Pinehurst and last summer's US Open. John Daly,
after opening with a 68, spent an hour singing the praises of the
USGA for choosing such a site and exercising great judgment in its
setup. By Sunday, however, Daly had crashed, thanks in part to an
11 at the par-4 eighth hole. Suddenly Pinehurst was a goat farm and
officials were to blame. OK, so Daly is a bit irrational, but in
the final round, Price said the USGA had applied too much water to
the front of the greens, which prevented balls from releasing
toward the pin. Not an hour later, Craig Parry said the course was
too dry. ``Gentlemen, don't they use water in the US?'' he asked.
Paul Azinger said the Masters was the hardest tournament to win, as
it required all aspects of your game. Stuart Appleby opted for the
British Open. As difficult as Augusta National is, said Appleby,
``St. Andrews was a more complicated'' course . . . As the Masters
shapes its field in the mirror of the World Golf Championships
(using world rankings to determine exemptions), some PGA Tour
players have been left out. The decision to eliminate exemptions
for Tour winners was a hot topic last week. Many feel the greatest
prize for winning a Tour event has been a spot in the Masters. That
is no longer the case, as tournament officials invited the top 50
in the world rankings to make the event more competitive. The rule
adversely affected Olin Browne, Brad Faxon, Brian Henninger, Rich
Beem, J.L. Lewis, Tom Pernice Jr., and Jim Carter, all winners in
1999. Some players didn't know about the change. Gary Nicklaus was
in a playoff with Mickelson at the BellSouth last Sunday and
thought a victory would get him an invite to the Masters. While
many players don't like the new criteria, Jack Nicklaus and Arnold
Palmer did not have a problem with it. Hal Sutton was another.
``Overall, change is not easily accepted,'' said Sutton. ``It's
never popular the first time. But I think it's a good change.'' . .
. Padraig Harrington criss-crossed the globe before coming to the
Masters. The personable Irishman missed the cut at Bay Hill March
17 and did not have a berth in the following week's TPC. Since he
wasn't playing BellSouth, he was facing a 2 1/2-week layoff, so he
went to Rio de Janeiro and Sao Paulo for back-to-back European Tour
events. The travel was a gamble right before his Masters debut. But
in each event, Harrington had at least a share of the 54-hole lead;
he lost in Rio but won in Sao Paulo, which made the long trip to
Augusta more enjoyable _ and more tiring, too. He felt vindicated,
for many European Tour observers had questioned the move. ``It was
the right decision,'' he said . . . Jean Van de Velde is heading
back to Europe for the Seve Ballesteros Trophy April 14-16. He will
play for Continental Europe, coached by Seve Ballesteros, against
Great Britain and Ireland, captained by Colin Montgomerie. ``Seve
told me I would play more games than I did in the Ryder Cup,'' said
Van de Velde with a smile. In last September's Ryder Cup at
Brookline, Van de Velde played just one singles match . . . Part of
the charm of the Masters is that the course is not closed to
members until Monday. So Daly was in a foursome with Mid-Amateur
champion Danny Green and two members last Sunday. Daly was spotted
loading six boxes of shirts into his car for friends and relatives.
He loves everything about the Masters, but his five-year exemption
for winning the 1995 British Open is up, and who knows whether
he'll be back? Daly figured he ``had spent his prize money'' on the
gifts. Before he missed this year's cut his track record had been
decent at the Masters. Until this year, he had made the cut in all
seven appearances, his best finish a tie for third in 1993 . . .
Also playing Augusta last Sunday was Butch Harmon, who made two
treks around the fabled layout. He didn't break 80 either time; the
greens were too fast for him.
</P>
<P>
   Elder statesman
</P>
<P>
   Lee Elder has been a special guest with a distinguished presence
all week at Augusta. Twenty-five years ago, Elder was the first
black to play in this prestigious event. Wednesday night, Elder was
honored at a golf writers dinner, and he fielded questions at a
lengthy press conference Tuesday. While disappointed that more
blacks have not followed in his footsteps, Elder, 65, remains
committed to helping children find their way into golf. ``I think
we are going to be able to help more of the young kids,'' he said,
``and certainly it won't take so long before we can have other
black players be champions as well as Tiger Woods.'' . . . The
world's hottest golfer probably won't be seen again until April 28
at the Chick-fil-A Charity Championship in Stockbridge, Ga. We are,
of course, talking about Karrie Webb, who is 4 for 4 in 2000 . . .
Price, on the competition Woods brings to the Tour: ``It will be
really interesting to see how pro golf develops over the next five
years. Tiger has been out here for three years now, and the young
guys who were 12 or 13 when he started are now 15 and 16. He set
the bar at a certain level, and those young kids are practicing
very hard to hit the ball as far as he does. They know what they
have to do.'' . . . Mark O'Meara and Woods spent the week before
the Masters playing at Isleworth in Windermere, Fla. One member of
their group was Sergio Garcia, O'Meara's guest for a few days. ``He
figures, `These guys playing at Isleworth are winning all these
majors _ maybe I need to get there,' '' said O'Meara.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
