u s BC-GLF-WOODS-MASTERS-BOS     04-08 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-MASTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS COMES FROM OUT OF NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Tiger Woods was lining up his second shot on the
par-3 12th hole Saturday, a shot that even Woods called
``interesting,'' his left foot on grass, his right foot in a
bunker, and the ball on the lip.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden Woods's shot became even more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   A golf ball came flying onto that tiny 12th green. Dropped from
the heavens? Discarded by a Martian? Tossed overboard from a
wayward UFO?
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden you hear this `Splat!' . . . and there it was
on the right side of the green,'' said Woods. ``It'd be a great
shot for (Sunday's) pin placement'' on the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   The ball couldn't have come from another Masters golfer because
of the location of the green, nor could it have come from a
rambunctious fan because the gallery is kept at least 200 yards
away. It is the splendid isolation of the hole that made the sudden
appearance of the ball so much out of golf's Twilight Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was an earthly explanation for the golf ball from
the heavens. The Augusta Country Club adjoins the Augusta National
Golf Club, on which the Masters is held, and the ninth hole (a par
4) of the Augusta CC passes on a hillside above Augusta National's
12th hole, the middle jewel of Amen Corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guy from the Augusta Country Club sprayed one,'' said
Woods, `` . . . it was like Caddy Shack II . . . where one of the
balls just comes over a fence.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no shout of ``fore'' and no warning, said Woods. ``I
never saw a cart and I never saw anybody; I guess they were too
embarrassed to come and get it back,'' although high above Woods
and the 12th a cart kept scurrying back and forth, looking for the
errant ball.
</P>
<P>
   To no avail. A Masters marshal had picked it up and put it in
his pocket. ``I wasn't going to play that ball,'' said Woods.
``It's not my brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but another chapter of the Woods lore was about to be
written.
</P>
<P>
   A writer asked Woods if he could identify the brand of the ball
from the heavens, expecting a simple ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a Precept, but I'm not sure,'' said Woods. ``It
looked like . . . the dimple pattern from a distance looked like a
Precept.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams had unusually sharp eyesight, but Woods said he was
able to identify a golf ball by its dimple pattern, and from a
distance of 30 to 40 feet, although Woods would say he was about 20
feet from where the ball landed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My eyesight's 20/15,'' said Woods, trying to downplay his feat
of vision. ``Most pros, you throw a ball down, they can tell (the
ball's brand) just by the color of it, you can see the different
dimple pattern because each ball is uniquely different. You can
just tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods Saturday got himself back into contention with a 4-under
68 that left him 1-under after three rounds. His inspiration was
from his experience (``I knew if I could just get back under par,
anything can happen''), and from a late night sportscast Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching television, and a lot of people were saying I
was out of it,'' said Woods, who was a bland 3-over after two
rounds. ``I didn't appreciate it. I'm not out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Who said the dastardly words?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you that (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was also aided by a putting lesson from his father, Earl,
who did not walk the course but had watched his son on television
the first two rounds. His father suggested Tiger was holding his
hands too low before putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I took a look at it and, yeah, they were a little low,''
said Woods. ``The lower your hands the easier it is to hook the
ball. My dad has always been a believer in holding your hands up to
release your left hand with your right hand. I tried it (Friday
night), didn't like it, but I also felt it was probably better than
what I had.''
</P>
<P>
   It was. Woods made four straight birdies from the seventh
through the 10th holes, and even though they were set up by supreme
iron shots that left Woods with putts no longer than 7 feet, he
made them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm back, and I can release the blade properly,'' said
Woods, ``and get the ball rolling on line, and not . . . it felt
like I'd been skidding the putts a bit. But now the ball's rolling
end-over-end and the ball's not lipping out. That's when you know
you're really rolling it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was in the middle of his birdie run when a storm halted
play for two hours. His drive was in the middle of the 11th fairway
and he was ready for another birdie attempt. ``It was
disconcerting,'' said Woods, who spent the time ``eating and
listening to some great stories from the old guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was so anxious to resume play that he was standing by his
ball 10 minutes before the siren sounded. Woods went on to par the
11th, and then came the Twilight Zone of the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to taking a putting lesson from his father, then
going out to eat with him Friday night, Woods also spent a good
chunk of the night watching the Weather Channel. ``From what the
Weather Channel said, there's going to be some frost overnight and
freeze warnings,'' said Woods. ``Temperatures in the 30s and 40s
(Sunday), so it has to be colder when the leaders (who could not
complete their rounds Saturday because of darkness) play and it has
to be be warmer when I play.''
</P>
<P>
   He needed to get under par after Saturday's round, said Woods,
to get back in it. ``Now I feel I'm in striking distance, based on
what the forecast is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
