<HEADER>
A1174 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-ARRINGTONBROWN-NF     04-08 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARRINGTONBROWN-NFLDRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRINGTON, BROWN A PENN STATE DOUBLE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It should be a simple matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the first pick of the 2000 National Football League
draft, the Cleveland Browns select . . . Courtney Brown, defensive
end, Penn State,'' is the way NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue will
announce it next weekend in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Tagliabue will step up to the microphone
again and say, ``The Washington Redskins select . . . LaVar
Arrington, linebacker, Penn State.''
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, Brown and Arrington, arguably the two best
defensive players in college football last season, will move to the
next phase of their career.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there could be some last-minute maneuvering. The Browns
might deal the top pick to a team desperate for an offensive tackle
that moves up to take Alabama's Chris Samuels, or to a team needing
a wide receiver to be the last piece in its championship puzzle and
wants Florida State's Peter Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, then the Redskins, picking second and third,
could collect on a daily double and get both of the Penn State
players. The two wouldn't mind that, but it's probably better for
them to be separated so they can establish their own identities,
make their own footprints.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, anyone who has had to deal with Penn State's defense
the past couple of seasons knows about Arrington and Brown and how
much havoc they have created.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just unbelievable specimens,'' said Browns director of
football operations Dwight Clark, who will make the call on the
first pick. ``It's like somebody chiseled them out of granite.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as they are alike in the end product, they are almost
completely different in their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington is often over the line with his style of play and
personality. His teammates called him ``LA'' because he has some
Hollywood flash to him, whether it's leapfrogging blockers or
saying outrageous things.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in contrast, is a small-town kid from South Carolina who
will use the fewest words possible to express his opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington, at 6 feet 3 inches, 250 pounds, is a prototype NFL
linebacker, even though he'll tell you, ``I'm all mental. The
mental aspect of my game is the strongest part. I'm not the biggest
guy. If I am going up against somebody 300 pounds, I'm not going to
go over and nonchalantly knock him over. I have to envision what I
am going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington, who passed up his senior season, says he has no
preference as to where he goes, which is pretty much standard stuff
from top prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they need me to do, I will do,'' said Arrington. ``It
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington said he toyed with the idea of coming back for his
senior season but rejected it when longtime Penn State defensive
coordinator Jerry Sandusky retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the whole defensive line graduating and when Jerry
retired, it made my decision easier,'' said Arrington. ``I didn't
feel like starting over. There was no need for me to come back and
prove anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington understands the hype that has surrounded him and will
continue to surround him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can live up to the hype,'' he said. ``But I'm not
changing the way I play because of the hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he encourages it. He has been compared to New York
Giants Hall of Famer Lawrence Taylor, but he said, ``I don't think
I should be compared to Lawrence Taylor because I respect him too
much. I have a long way to go before I can be compared to Lawrence
Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Arrington kicks it up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I will get No. 56,'' he said with a laugh when asked
what number he would like to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has heard similar comparisons with men at his position and
shrugs them off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an honor to be characterized with such great
players,'' he said. ``But I haven't played one down in the league
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Arrington has looked every bit as intimidating as LT
in his prime. Take his performance in the Alamo Bowl this season.
Penn State, which had slid from a national championship contender
to a Big Ten also-ran with three consecutive losses, felt it had
something to prove. So did Arrington, in what he knew would be his
last college game. Fourteen tackles later _ three of which almost
certainly led to interceptions by Texas A&AMP;M quarterback Randy
McCown _ Arrington had proven his point.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington's playing style on the field matches his lifestyle off
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live life to the fullest,'' he said. ``My parents have
raised me to live life and not be afraid.'
</P>
<P>
   His father, Michael, served in Vietnam and nearly lost his legs
in a tank accident. Doctors told him he would never walk again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He proved them all wrong,'' said Arrington with a fierce sense
of pride.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's style is much more low-key, much less demonstrative.
Even his teammates wonder what's underneath the hood.
</P>
<P>
   His cousin, Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton, said,
``That's just him. He doesn't open up to guys that he really
doesn't know sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Brown about his future and he shows none of the confidence
that Arrington brandishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough coming to the NFL and understanding the
game at this level,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't back off when asked if he can do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think about the game,'' said the 6-5, 270-pound Brown,
who last season had 29 tackles for losses and 13 1/2 sacks (giving
him a school-record 33 for his career) and was Big Ten Defensive
Player of the Year and a unanimous All-American. ``Whatever needs
to be done, I try to take care of on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The negative part of Arrington's scouting report is that he
sometimes free-lances too much and will incur some dumb penalties
(for instance, an unsportsmanlike conduct infraction for hitting
Pittsburgh punter Greg DeBolt in the face mask).
</P>
<P>
   Some scouts wonder whether Brown will be too small to play
defensive line against the 300-pounders who now seem to dominate
NFL offensive lines.
</P>
<P>
   All of it seems picky right now. Come Saturday, both players
will be in New York, ready to take the next step.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it goes Brown, Arrington or Arrington, Brown, it really
doesn't matter that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to wait and see what happens,'' said Brown.
``We're going to have a job to do and we'll go out and do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
