<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1187 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-STEVENS-REHABILIT     04-08 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STEVENS-REHABILITATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS CLEANING UP HIS ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the things he has read, some of the looks his wife gets
from other parents when she drops their 3-year-old off at school,
they all serve to underscore to Kevin Stevens what he freely
admits, that he made a huge mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one to blame here but me, but some of what's out
there is so out of whack,'' said Stevens, speaking Saturday for the
first time since his Jan. 23 arrest for possession of an illegal
substance (crack cocaine). ``If you believed it all, you'd get the
impression that all I've been doing is drinkin' and druggin' my
life away. That's not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stuff you read, things the cops have said . . . at
times I've just wanted to put my head in my hands and cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Once one of the National Hockey League's most feared scorers and
most affable athletes, Stevens is a recovering binge drinker who
attends daily Alcoholics Anonymous meetings near his home in Rye,
N.Y., and who also intends to play again in the NHL one day. He
will attend the Rangers' final home game of the season Sunday at
Madison Square Garden, after which he will meet with the media and
present his side of the incidents surrounding his arrest in a
Collinsville, Ill., hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested that morning along with three others, including a
prostitute, Pamela Velia, Stevens in a Feb. 14 Sports Illustrated
article was described as a ``crack monster'' _ a characterization
provided by a Collinsville police officer who said he was quoting
Velia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what that means, `crack monster,' '' said
Stevens, speaking via telephone from the Rangers' workout facility
at Rye Playland. ``The article also had one of the cops making me
sound like I used crack cocaine for eight years. What I said was,
the first time I used cocaine was eight years ago, but that was the
powder, not crack. I don't have a drug problem. I never have. What
I've had is a drinking problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who will turn 35 Saturday, also maintains that Velia,
whom he said he had never met until after the Rangers' game hours
earlier in St. Louis, set him up for the arrest, deliberately or
unwittingly. He thinks she may have offered him up to police as a
means of getting charges dropped against her from a prior arrest.
Stevens's attorney, Neil Bruntrager, theorizes that Velia might
have been attempting to set up Stevens to be robbed. Stevens began
partying that night with some $3,000 in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd been arrested four or five other times, and she's been
arrested since,'' said Stevens. ``I mean, these are bad, bad people
we're talking about here. You wouldn't let your dog hang out with
them. But, hey, it just shows you some of the bad decisions I
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and Velia were arrested along with Darryl Crawford,
described by Stevens as Velia's boyfriend, and Alfred Triplett, the
cab driver hired by Stevens, for $100 an hour, after leaving a
nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stevens, the four of them were in a Collinsville
Travelodge motel room for only a short time that morning when Velia
said she wanted to make a phone call. In order to activate the
phone, Stevens had to make a $20 deposit, which he did by twice
making trips to the front desk and handing $10 to the clerk. By the
time Stevens returned to the room after the second deposit, Velia,
Triplett, and Crawford were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Collinsville police were knocking at his door, asking to
search the room. Velia, Stevens theorizes, set up the arrest
possibly by calling the police moments after that second trip to
the front desk. His attorney believes Velia might have called the
front desk and the clerk, in turn, called the police.
</P>
<P>
   The Sports Illustrated article reported that police, freely
granted permission to enter the room by Stevens, found the beds
still made. When an officer pulled back a pillow, a crack pipe
tumbled out. Bruntrager said police also found a small amount of
crack rolled up in a towel under the bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly,'' said Stevens, ``when they began lifting the
mattresses and stuff, and found that, I said, `You know what, that
must be from the people who were in the room before.' They found
stuff that I didn't know was there. But the room was in my name, so
I get charged. When they found the other three, they all had drugs
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Messages left at the Collinsville police department by the Globe
Saturday were not returned. A pretrial hearing is set for Thursday
in a Madison County courtroom in Edwardsville, Ill., but it's
possible only Stevens's counsel will have to appear. Stevens
already has pleaded not guilty to the possession charge, a felony.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since his arrest, Stevens has gone about trying to
reassemble his life and career. After his release from the
Collinsville jail, he reported directly to a Los Angeles drug
rehabilitation center and spent five days there before transferring
to another rehab in Connecticut for the next seven weeks, commuting
from his home in Rye, Tuesday through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling much better,'' said Stevens, who late last month
was placed back on the Rangers' payroll after being suspended in
January for violating the NHL/player union rehabilitation program.
``But anyone can stay sober in rehab. It's what happens to you,
what kind of support system you have, once you're out of rehab.
Luckily, I've got a great family and great friends who support me.
And the AA meetings help me a lot. That's been unbelievable. The
first time I went, I couldn't believe it, two guys I knew from
college were in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, Stevens's wife, the former Suzanne Pannuto
from Marshfield, Mass., gave birth to the couple's third child,
Ryan. Luke is 3 and Kylie is 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I really care about right now is my family,'' said
Stevens, who met his wife just before they began their freshman
years at Boston College in 1984. ``People read all this, about a
prostitute and crack, and they're going to draw their own
conclusions. But my wife knows the truth. She's the sweetest girl
in the world, and now when she takes our kid to school, people look
at her like she's married to some lunatic. I put myself in a bad
position here, but it's all related to my problem with alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, said Stevens, he made a decision to stop
drinking, voluntarily checking himself into a Los Angeles rehab in
conjuction with the league/union substance abuse program. He said
his drinking never got to the point where he put it before anything
else in his life, either his family or his career (``I never drank
before a game,'' he said), but he felt it was time to eliminate
booze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt it was better for my life that I not drink,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to entering a nightclub after the Jan. 22 game in St.
Louis, Stevens said, he had been without a drink for 18 months,
except for one time, a lapse that he said he promptly reported to
the rehab program's administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those months, I stayed sober,'' said Stevens. ``But I did
it the hard way _ no meetings. And I never cracked.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that night in January. Stevens hadn't played in four of
the five games leading up to the game in St. Louis. He wouldn't
have been in the lineup there if Adam Graves hadn't left the club
to be with his wife, in labor with twins. In his third year with
the Rangers, earning $3.2 million _ the end of a five-year deal he
signed in Boston _ Stevens had become a spare part in a struggling
offense. Neil Smith, then the club's general manager, was on the
verge of a deal that had Stevens going back to Pittsburgh, where he
played on two Cup winners at the start of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I was playing well,'' said Stevens,
describing the mindset that ultimately led him from first drink to
hotel room to jail cell after going without a point in St. Louis.
``I was taken back by that. I was thinking ahead, getting to
Pittsburgh and not playing well there, not being comfortable with
that. But my big mistake was having that first beer. I drank and
drank and drank. That's the way it is with me. I could drink for
two years and not have a problem. But it's that next day that I go
out of control, and you just never know when that next day will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is Stevens's final payday with the Rangers, although he
will not suit up against the Flyers. He's been working out
regularly in recent weeks, but hasn't skated. If the Rangers had
made the playoffs, he said, his intention was to play.
</P>
<P>
   As of July 1, Stevens will be a free agent. He would prefer to
return to the Rangers and will discuss that possibility soon with
club CEO Dave Checketts. Stevens is realistic enough to think that
his days on Broadway are finished and he'll have to look for work
elsewhere. He expects he'll place his home in Rye up for sale in
the next few weeks and move the family back to their home in
Duxbury, hoping to get employment offers over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, teams are going to be scared, I know that,'' he
said. ``But I'm clear-headed now, and I know I can play well, and I
don't mean as a third- or fourth-line guy. I can be on a first or
second line. I don't have that desire (to drink), that restlessness
in me. I'll be able to go somewhere and truly be able to give it my
best shot. I know, wherever it is, it's not going to be a good
contract, but I don't really care about that. I'll take an
invitation somewhere, no contract, and go in and earn it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to earn my way back. I just don't want it to end here,
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, Stevens also realizes his January escapade
could have led to a far different epitaph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm lucky to be alive,'' he said. ``I'm lucky in that I
put myself in a bad position, and now I'm grateful that I'm able to
be sitting here, with a great family, still able to play in the
league. If the cops didn't come, who knows, maybe I would have been
killed. That could be the blessing in disguise in this whole
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
