</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-LEAGUEWOES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATED PRICE FOR DILUTED PRODUCT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NHL is vastly more marketable than it was 10-15 years ago.
Its image, while hardly pristine, is far more civil than it was in
the bench-clearing, donnybrook days when even the sport's most
ardent supporters had trouble explaining the difference between
hockey and pro wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, this isn't John Ziegler's NHL anymore. It still has
its, shall we say, imperfections, its festering carbuncles. But
under the hand of commissioner Gary Bettman, now seven-plus years
on the job, the league cleaned up its image and was able to call
itself a 20th-century sport, even on the verge of the 21st century.
The same couldn't be said when Bettman took the wheel in February
1993.
</P>
<P>
   In a teleconference late last week, Bettman did what
commissioners do _ he extolled the virtues of his corporation, soon
to include 30 teams. He told the North American media that TV
ratings, attendance, and scoring all were on the upside in
1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Concussions, he noted, are actually down considerably from one
and two years ago. That's hard to believe when it seems every
roster has someone on the sidelines wondering what day it is, but
the Commish quoted numbers to support the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Bettman added that there are no plans ``on the radar
screen'' to add more teams to the playoff pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear from people in the league occasionally harkening back
to the good old days when four of six teams, two-thirds of the
teams, made the playoffs,'' said Bettman. ``But I believe that
where we are now, going to 16 out of 28 _ 16 of 30 (next season) _
is a whole lot better than 16 out of 21 (at the start of the
(1980s). I think it has made the regular season meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important to ticket-buying fans, Bettman quoted
evidence that the escalation of player salaries has begun to slow
down. If there is any hope for the NHL not shutting down in the
summer of 2004, when the collective bargaining agreement expires,
it will have to be found in the fine print of the players'
contracts, unless the league can find other revenues to keep ticket
prices from soaring out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said ``a bunch'' of the 28 teams will lose money this
year. For years, the Players' Association has regarded such
estimates as ownership scare tactics. Bettman and union boss Bob
Goodenow undoubtedly will chew over that interpretation ad
infinitum, but we do know this much: Ticket prices in most every
sport, and hockey in particular, are beyond the reach of a growing
portion of the public. If they don't at least level off, hockey is
on course for one whopper of a hangover.
</P>
<P>
   Not to sound like Alan Greenspan, but the growing bubble of the
economy has to burst one of these days. When it does, hockey could
be in for the biggest chill of all. I base that not on the
undergraduate Economics 101 course I took a quarter-century ago,
but simply on the number of rinks with $80, $90, and $100 loge
seats. Forget supply and demand and pie charts (we'll see enough of
those during the '04 lockout) and just look at the prices. A pair
of $80 loge seats for a full season would price out at $6,560. Now
add a playoff run, with higher prices. It begins to approach
$10,000. Long gone are the days when the local plumber or sub shop
owner maintained ownership of a pair of Bruins season tickets. And
if they have kept them, chances are the tab is split with three or
four other friends.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's not price that most threatens today's NHL. Far
more serious a problem is the entertainment value. This may seem
subjective, especially in light of how grim the Bruins played for
about 80 percent of this season. But take it from someone who
spends far too many hours clicking through countless games on the
satellite dish: There is simply a lot of bad hockey out there.
</P>
<P>
   Every commissioner has his plate full, Bettman more than most,
because the NHL is a league of ``old economy'' clubs (Boston,
Toronto, Montreal, Chicago, Detroit, and the Rangers) that
historically printed money no matter what the product, and an
assorted bunch in a ``new economy'' that included the well-heeled
Flyers as well as some truly struggling franchises such as Calgary,
Tampa Bay, and the Islanders. It's very difficult to get those two
groups on the same page in terms of growing the product.
</P>
<P>
   When Columbus and Minnesota enter the league in the fall, the
NHL will have 14 teams that don't make the playoffs. That's fine.
But the truth is, about half of those clubs will barely be
competitive October to April. In its ambition to broaden the
footprint of the league, in hopes of structuring a product with
nationwide broadcast allure, the NHL thinned out the North American
and international talent pool. If not for the Russians, Swedes,
Finns, and Czechs, there might not be enough talent to stock 15
teams. Their presence makes it about a 21- or 22-team league.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's stated mandate for the first decade of the 21st
century is to keep salaries down (ticket prices, too) and grow the
TV and Internet audience. The unstated mandate has to be to stop
the expansion lunacy. It's over. The player mines have been
stripped. The product already has outreached supply by 25-30
percent. Not enough good players. Too many bad games. If New York
doesn't understand that equation, none of the other numbers matter
one iota.
</P>
<P>
   Protective mechanism
</P>
<P>
   Grant Fuhr followed up the intention he stated more than a year
ago and announced his retirement, effective this weekend. But word
out of Calgary is that he already has agreed to a new deal, worth a
paltry $200,000, for 2000-01. Confused? Don't be. Fuhr's signature
on that deal will allow the Flames to expose him in the June
expansion draft and not risk losing Fred Brathwaite and
Jean-Sebastien Giguere. Fuhr gets a nice going-away present and the
Flames buy some cheap insurance . . . If Flames general manager Al
Coates sticks to the plan he made clear last fall, coach Brian
Sutter will get the gate now that the Flames have missed the
playoffs for a fourth straight season. Too bad. Sutter did a fine
job with the disjointed, inexperienced pieces he was handed. Word
around Calgary last week was that Coates also could be turfed . . .
Brave words from Bryan Berard last week (``I'm going to give this
the hardest fight of my life to get back on the ice''), his first
comments since his devastating eye injury a month ago and
subsequent surgery. He said he feels improvement in the eye and
dreams about returning. But it was shocking to hear the pride of
Woonsocket, R.I., say he won't consider wearing eye protection.
According to the Players' Association, 90 percent of NHLers don't
want to wear visors. Anyone who saw the video of Berard's accident,
blood streaming from his eye, has to be frightened by that
denouncement . . . Olympic update: Yes, the NHLers will be there in
2002, said Bettman, provided the IIHF and the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee can dot all the i's and cross the t's . . . The Kings
lost ex-Bruin Bryan Smolinski for up to six weeks with a wrenched
knee last Monday. No surgery necessary, but there may be no season
to return to, especially if the Kings draw the Avalanche in Round
1.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins' ax swift
</P>
<P>
   History shows that the Bruins waste little time dumping coaches
when Harry Sinden decides it's necessary. Some don't make it
through the season (Fred Creighton, Gerry Cheevers, Butch Goring).
Others generally have been lopped within two weeks of the end of
the season (Rick Bowness, Steve Kasper, Sutter). All signs point to
Pat Burns getting the heave-ho, and given the black cloud that has
hovered over the Hub's hockey team since early December, the dirty
deed likely will occur sooner than later. Again, two weeks is a
realistic barometer, allowing for some of the initial dust to
settle and the playoffs to begin. And who picks up the pieces in
Burns's wake? The ideal candidate would be ex-Bruin Dave Poulin,
now at Notre Dame, but sources close to him say Poulin wouldn't be
eager to return to Boston, not with spending always an issue and
the current player stock so thin. When the time comes, look for
Poulin to be back in Philly as the Flyers coach. Northeastern coach
Bruce Crowder, another ex-Bruin, should get a feeler, but sources
around the league generally believe he needs more experience. No
doubt Baby B's coach Peter Laviolette will end up in the mix here,
possibly as head coach. Remember: Management and Burns came to
loggerheads over the force-feeding of AHLers into the Boston
roster. That's not going to change in a hurry. Then why not hand it
to Laviolette, who has more experience with those kids than anyone
in the organization? . . . Cross Detroit power forward Brendan
Shanahan off the free agent shopping list. The Winged Wheels signed
him up last week, a four-year deal worth about $24 million (a Ray
Bourque-like $6 million a year), and language is in place for a
fifth season . . . Notice Dominik Hasek's shutout over the Devils
Thursday night? If the Sabres make the playoffs, it will be as the
last seed in the East. But with Hasek back in form, and Doug
Gilmour revived since his swap from Chicago, the Sabres easily
could win a round or two. The Sabres also didn't allow the Leafs a
single shot in the second period of a 3-2 win . . . John McMullen,
whose Devils soon will be sold to YankeeNet (possibly finalized in
June), could end up owning the Avalanche. Another possible suitor
in Denver: former Celtics owner Alan Cohen . . . Can someone
explain how the Ducks, with superstar strikers Teemu Selanne and
Paul Kariya, can't make the playoffs _ for the second time in three
seasons?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
