<HEADER>
A1250 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-ATTENDAN     04-08 1778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-ATTENDANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENDANCE PROBLEM OUT OF SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Celtics saw the new NBA last week. They went on the road to
play two playoff-bound teams in important games. In both cases, a
neutron bomb could have exploded in the arena without hurting a
soul.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets are trying to get an arena built downtown
amid pretty stark evidence that the people there don't care about
the team. There was an announced crowd of more than 16,000 against
the Celtics, but there were probably half that many people in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   This was a team on a winning streak, fighting for fourth place
and the alleged ``home-court'' advantage, and still the place was
dead. Already, the Hornets' visible co-owner, Ray Wooldridge (as
opposed to the one being kept out of sight in Jupiter, Fla.), is
trying to back off a proposal to have the public fund the $220
million arena.
</P>
<P>
   The following night, the Celtics played the Pistons in the
Palace of Auburn Hills, Mich., and the announced crowd was 14,581.
There may have been 10,000 people in the building.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons have Grant Hill, one of the league's few marquee
players. They, too, were on a roll of sorts under new coach George
Irvine. Once again, the building was lifeless.
</P>
<P>
   You want to know what's wrong with the league? People who bought
tickets don't bother going to the games. People who bought tickets
can't give them away, so the seats are unoccupied. You look at
games on the satellite dish and it is the same in every building,
though more noticeable in some (Cleveland, New Jersey, Miami).
</P>
<P>
   You might expect a dropoff in attendance in cities such as like
Boston, where there is no playoff chase. What's the excuse in
Charlotte? OK, the invisible owner has a bit of a public relations
problem, and the players get arrested now and then. But they've got
a good team.
</P>
<P>
   In their first 10 years, the Hornets sold out every game in a
24,000-seat building. This year, they've had three sellouts. They
once capped season tickets at 21,000. Now they've got 14,000. Their
average attendance last season was 19,232, sixth-highest in the
league. Two years ago, they were second to the Bulls at 23,405 a
game. This year, they're averaging 17,807 with what may be their
best team ever. But it's not uncommon for there to be fewer than
10,000 people at a game (the turnstile count can be unearthed
because Charlotte Coliseum is a public facility).
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons, like the Hornets, have a huge building that looks
empty when all the seats are not occupied. The Pistons were eighth
in the league in attendance last year at 17,783 a game. This year,
they're at 16,492. Then again, the Pistons had attendance problems
before the Bad Boys, have had them since the Bad Boys, and have a
history of first-round playoff exits. They've tasted two titles,
and making the playoffs apparently doesn't have the same cachet.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino saw all this and shook his head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have shot a cannon off in those buildings,'' he
said. He then noted that the Celtics have the fifth-best paid
attendance. But all you have to do is watch a game in the
FleetCenter and you can see the empty seats there, too.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? The Pistons had a four-hour meeting last week on
that very subject. How do you get people to sit in the seats they
bought? When that becomes a marketing nightmare, then you really
have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jones, the Hornets' free agent guard, already said he
might go elsewhere because of the sparse support in Charlotte. One
prominent landing spot: Orlando. Yet the Magic, who have as
exciting a team as any in the conference, can't fill their arena,
either.
</P>
<P>
   For a big game against San Antonio last week, the Magic drew
only 15,267, almost 2,000 shy of capacity. Two weeks ago, the Magic
drew only 13,505 for a Sunday afternoon game against Miami. Orlando
is averaging 13,281; it drew 16,444 last season. Yes, the Magic
started the year with a bleak forecast, but now they're probably
going to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It's not Charlotte's problem. Or Detroit's. Or Orlando's. It's
the league's. The NBA would be in for sticker shock if turnstile
count were used for attendance. That ludicrous capacity streak at
the United Center would be history (it was equally ludicrous at the
Boston Garden).
</P>
<P>
   They can note that the average attendance this season is about
the same as it was last year, but that misses the point. The
tickets may be sold, but the seats are empty. It's a problem. And
it will remain a problem until the product is worth the price.
Right now, it isn't even close.
</P>
<P>
   Fading fast
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Feb. 29, the 45-11 Portland Trail Blazers met
the 45-11 Los Angeles Lakers at the Rose Garden. The Lakers won,
90-87, and, as they say, the rest is history. That loss didn't just
stun the Blazers. It vaporized them. They're no longer watching the
Lakers. They're watching their backs as the Utah Jazz sneak up on
them for the conference's second-best record. Portland is
cooperating. It dropped back-to-back games last week to Houston and
Vancouver. Meanwhile, Monday night's game in Utah is huge for both
the Blazers and Jazz. After Portland's disturbing loss to the
Grizzlies, Scottie Pippen said, ``It's obvious we're not playing
well enough to beat anybody. We have to find something to motivate
us. I don't know if there's enough time for us to get what we need
back, to where we feel enough confidence to win a championship.''
Said coach Mike Dunleavy, ``We're in the worst situation you can be
in _ one of complacency. We've got to play harder.'' A Utah victory
would square the season series with Portland at 2-2 . . . Two names
you might want to watch as the NBA draft approaches are Ernest
Brown and Corey Hightower. They were teammates at Indian Hills
Community College in Ottumwa, Iowa, a Juco powerhouse. Both are
likely to come out and both appear to have ``first-round talent.''
Brown is a 7-footer from New York City, Hightower is a
6-foot-7-inch slasher from Flint, Mich. Yup, another Flintstone.
So, too, is Charlotte reserve Eddie Robinson, who offered these
thoughts on Hightower: ``I grew up with Corey. He lived down the
street. He's got what it takes to make it at this level. It's all a
matter of how hard he's willing to work. He asks me about the
league and I told him that his (predraft) workouts are the most
important thing. You have to have a good showing to make teams want
to pick you.'' As for Brown, the NBA lusts after athletic big men.
He has signed to play at Iowa State (Hightower has done the same at
TCU) but there's a potential headache; Iowa State hired one of
Brown's former Juco coaches. There's also what scouts
diplomatically call a ``stability issue'' with Brown. He left his
high school team (St. Raymond's), had some menial jobs (and also
fathered a child) and then went to Arizona to play Juco before
moving on to Indian Hills. Hightower, who attended the same school
as Tracy McGrady (Mt. Christian Zion in Durham, N.C.) before
heading the Juco route, is said to be the more highly regarded
right now (although scouts feel he's not as gifted as Darius Miles,
a top high school player). ``He's a good offensive player, very
athletic,'' says one GM. The two won't play before the assembled
NBA talent spotters until the June camp in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Riled up
</P>
<P>
   Since scoring 19 points in the second half of a fiasco in
Orlando, and after Pat Riley tore into critics of his team, the
Miami Heat have put together a nice little run. The Heat went into
the weekend having won five straight, all at home, including
victories over Phoenix, San Antonio, and Charlotte. The Hornets,
after losing to Miami, are 3-15 against teams that are in first or
second place in their division, with seven straight losses . . .
The Grizzlies finally stepped to the plate for coach Lionel
Hollins, who had not gotten a pay raise since replacing Brian Hill
last December. Neither Hollins nor GM Stu Jackson is under contract
past this season and both are believed to be on a slippery slope
because of an impending ownership change. Hill, meanwhile, has
moved back to Orlando and told the Vancouver Province that he has
not seen a Grizzlies game since he was let go . . . The suggestion
that taxpayers in North Carolina entirely fund a new arena for the
Hornets went over as you might think. In a letter to the Charlotte
Observer, Gina Cardinal of Charlotte called the proposal
``outrageous'' adding, ``our schools are struggling to pay teachers
even a below-living wage, children are trying to learn while
sitting in stifling trailers and some tall, mentally adolescent men
are being overpaid to throw a ball through a hoop. What is wrong
with our priorities?'' . . . The Warriors need three more wins to
avoid their worst season since the league went to an 82-game
schedule. The 1997-98 Warriors were 19-63 in P.J. Carlesimo's first
season. The 1964-65 San Francisco Warriors went 17-63 after winning
the division the year before. The reason: a midseason deal that
sent Wilt Chamberlain back to Philadelphia. Alas, the Warriors have
no more games with the Clippers, but that wouldn't do it anyway;
they're 1-3 against the Clips . . . Don Nelson has something to
shoot for down the stretch, even if his Mavericks don't. Nellie,
who says he's moving to the front office next season, is, according
to the Dallas Morning News, tied with Dick Motta for most career
ejections: 59 . . . Pitino now says he sees the Celtics, Nets,
Nuggets, and Mavericks at the same level. ``Whoever gets the one or
two players that gets them over the hump will be a
Philadelphia-type team. That's what we're trying to do.'' That's
reassuring . . . You may recall that Jalen Rose thought his
contract made him a free agent after last season. The Pacers
thought otherwise and prevailed when the matter went to
arbitration. Given the kind of year Rose has had, who looks like
the winner now as Rose enters free agency? Rose, who went to
Michigan, couldn't bring himself to root for Michigan State in the
NCAA final against Florida. He did say that he wasn't awed by the
talent, predicting that only three or four players from the Final
Four were NBA-caliber. ``When I was coming out of college,'' he
said, ``everyone could play.'' One of those four is Florida's Mike
Miller, who could be a top 10 pick if he leaves school. Pitino said
that Miller is not ready for the NBA and should return to school.
He added that he was not saying that to help his buddy, Florida
coach Billy Donovan. He simply thinks Miller is too raw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
