<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-SADERBY-LADN     04-08 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SADERBY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER SAHADI WINS WITH THE DEPUTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- The Deputy, bred in Ireland and raced as a 2-year-old
in Great Britain, eaned the opportunity Saturday to race in an
event that is as American as mom and apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Petardia put to rest the question of whether Jenine
Sahadi can train thoroughbreds, winning the $1 million Grade I
Santa Anita Derby by one length over the previously unbeaten War
Chant and stamping himself as one of the favorites for the Kentucky
Derby on May 6.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was vindication for Sahadi, who was needled by Bob
Baffert during Thursday's post-position draw and stormed away from
the media gathering before later returning to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   The first female trainer to win the Santa Anita Derby, she will
now have the opportunity to become the first woman to train a
Kentucky Derby champion if The Deputy remains healthy between now
and Derby Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been so proud of a horse before,'' Sahadi said of
The Deputy, third for much of the way before taking a short lead at
the top of the stretch. ``I know one thing -- he has a bigger heart
than any other 3-year-old out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi was asked if there had been any anxious moments during
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole race was anxious, are you kidding?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy, ridden by Chris McCarron, and War Chant, with Jerry
Bailey aboard, were the 2-1 co-favorites among an on-track crowd of
41,222 and raced through the stretch together before the winner
began to gradually pull away in the last sixteenth of a mile.
</P>
<P>
   It was McCarron's third Santa Anita Derby victory in 19 tries
and he will be looking for his third Kentucky Derby triumph after
winning with Alysheba in 1987 and Go For Gin in '94.
</P>
<P>
   Of his duel with War Chant and Bailey, McCarron said, ``It was a
matter of who was faster from the quarter pole to the wire. If I
get that same trip a month from now, man I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron said before the race he felt War Chant might be the
best 3-year-old in the country, better than Neil Drysdale's more
highly regarded Fusaichi Pegasus because he'd overcome adversity in
his last race (the Grade II San Rafael Stakes) and gone on to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's the second best now,'' McCarron quipped. ``Maybe
we have a better one now.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron has been aboard The Deputy, 4 for 9 lifetime with two
seconds and three thirds, in all four of his U.S. starts. He's come
away impressed, saying Sahadi has done a masterful job with the
colt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go back to my first experience with the horse and fast
forward to today,'' he said. ``He's been an A student from day one.
He's been an absolute professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``This colt pulls you to the race track, and I love that quality
in a horse. He just loves to be on the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning time of 1:49 for the 1 1/8 miles on the dirt was
well off the stakes record of 1:47, but the winning connections
couldn't have cared less.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Irwin, one of the colt's owners, said he believes Fusaichi
Pegasus is the best 3-year-old in the country but that his horse's
disposition will be an advantage in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he (Fusaichi Pegasus) will handle the festivites
at Churchill Downs,'' he said. ``Our horse won't have any problem
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, trained by Baffert, finished two lengths behind
War Chant in third. Anees was fourth, followed by pacesetter
Surfside and Cocky.
</P>
<P>
   Surfside's connections, who have touted the filly for the
Kentucky Derby all year, may have to reconsider after she finished
8 1/2 lengths behind the winner following slow early fractions of
:23 1/5, :47 1/5 and 1:11 2/5.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, Baffert and Anees' trainer, Alex Hassinger, all
indicated after the race that their horses are Kentucky
Derby-bound. The past three winners of the Derby -- Charismatic
last year, Real Quiet in '98 and Silver Charm in '97 -- ran fourth,
second and second, respectively, in the Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Said Baffert: ``He could never really get into his own deal.
We'll go on (to the Derby).''
</P>
<P>
   Hassinger bemoaned the lack of a faster pace. Anees trailed most
of the way before unleashing a late charge that left him six
lengths behind The Deputy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a great run to be where he was, and I think when we
change cities (to Louisville) we'll see a different horse, just
like last year. I'm not concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Anees ran third in last year's Norfolk Stakes at Oak Tree before
rebounding to win the Breeders' Cup Juvenile at Gulfstream Park in
Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2212EDT &QL; 
