<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-LADN </SLUG>
 
McENROE ANGRY AS U.S. FALLS BEHIND 2-1 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD -- The question to Jiri Novak: Is this a dream weekend
for you?
</P>
<P>
   Novak's response: ``This is not a dream. This is reality. We are
winning 2-1, and we are happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the U.S. Davis Cup dream team -- the top two singles
and top two doubles players -- finds itself in the middle of a
waking nightmare: One point away from defeat and its captain
expressing urgency, blasting his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're acting like spoiled children,'' John McEnroe said after
Novak and David Rikl swept Alex O'Brien and Jared Palmer 7-5, 6-4,
6-4 Saturday to take the lead in this Davis Cup quarterfinal at the
Great Western Forum. ``You have to work harder, you know. ...
Enough of being like, `Hey, these guys are playing well.' That's
not good enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should win every match. Novak's a good player. He's not as
good as our players. They're a good doubles team. I don't believe
they're as good as ours.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, McEnroe said, the Americans need to work harder. He
didn't think Pete Sampras worked enough, and Novak handed him his
worst Davis Cup defeat on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe didn't think O'Brien and Palmer did, either, and
Novak-Rikl swept them in 2 hours, 5 minutes after losing twice
previously to the Americans, including last week in Key Biscayne,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be extra effort,'' McEnroe said. ``If we're
guilty of anything, it's that we're not taking responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   He gets no argument from O'Brien and Palmer, who said the Czechs
never let them get into their game.
</P>
<P>
   And like the Novak-Sampras match on Friday, the Americans
weren't able to capitalize on early break chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Czechs broke in the first set to take a 6-5 lead, then
withstood two break points to close out the set.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. led 3-2 in the second set and had two break points,
only to have the Czechs fight back.
</P>
<P>
   By the time O'Brien and Palmer finally broke, tying the third
set at 3-3 on a Rikl double fault, it was too late. Novak and Rikl
broke again to go up 5-4, and Novak served the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played much better today than the other two times,''
Palmer said. ``Both served better, they returned better. They did
everything better. We had trouble getting anything going.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason: the Czechs listened to the advice of teammate Martin
Damm , who lost to O'Brien-Palmer last month in Indian Wells while
teamed with Robbie Koenig of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``One set goes to Martin Damm,'' Czech captain Jan Kukal said.
``We did exactly what they didn't like. Against them, you have to
return 90 percent of balls on line. You can't cross. You have to
stay on baseline.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is Novak. Many great Czech tennis players have
become American citizens, the most notable being Ivan Lendl and
Martina Navratilova.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps McEnroe might consider approaching Novak about switching
allegiances.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Novak said he wanted to become his country's
top Davis Cup player (he considers Lendl the top now). After
accounting for the last five of his country's Davis Cup points --
three against Great Britain and two here -- it's hard to argue he
isn't on his way. A victory today at noon against Andre Agassi
would further cement his reputation. It also gives the Czech
Republic the quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we are playing the team matches like a Davis Cup, there's
a special feeling because you are playing for the people that
support you and for the people in the city or the country,'' Novak
said. ``So we are playing for everybody, and that's such a nice
feeling for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sick feeling for the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
