A1387 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     04-08 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAHADI: NO MAN'S DEPUTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA - Who's training The Deputy?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert's infamous question of Santa Anita Derby Week was
answered in no uncertain terms Saturday. And Jenine Sahadi didn't
have to say a word.
</P>
<P>
   Who's training The Deputy?
</P>
<P>
   It was answered by the crowd, by the winning owners and by the
winning jockey.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy is trained by the popular new star - dare we say
starlet? - of this Kentucky Derby season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go get him (Baffert)! Show him who's boss!'' fans yelled from
behind the ropes as Sahadi walked behind The Deputy and Chris
McCarron from the saddling paddock to the track before the 63rd
Santa Anita Derby. Sahadi found herself acknowledging the unusually
raucous cheers with little waves of both hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt sort of like Julia Roberts, not that I look like her,''
Sahadi said of the red-carpet treatment. ``I felt like (begin
ital)somebody(end ital).''
</P>
<P>
   As Sahadi made her way from the winner's circle to the clubhouse
elevator after The Deputy and McCarron fought off War Chant and
Jerry Bailey to win by a length in the nation's deepest Kentucky
Derby prep, the crowd hanging over the horse tunnel shrieked its
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi, a 37-year-old USC graduate and former Hollywood Park
marketing- and publicity-department employee, had just became the
first woman trainer to win a Santa Anita Derby. She will go to
Louisville with a good chance to become the first woman trainer to
win the Kentucky Derby, set for May 6.
</P>
<P>
   For historians, as well as less-enlightened handicappers, the
issue of the next four weeks won't be whether The Deputy is up to
the challenge but whether Sahadi is up to it.
</P>
<P>
   Although she now has won three $1 million races, proving herself
at her sport's highest levels, Sahadi has been dogged by
insinuations she should share the credit with men.
</P>
<P>
   It started seven years ago when she got off to a fast start with
a barn made up largely of horses handed down from her boyfriend,
Julio Canani, the Santa Anita Handicap-winning trainer who was
temporarily out of business. It continued when she married fellow
trainer Ben Cecil.
</P>
<P>
   And it exploded in headlines when Baffert, at the Santa Anita
Derby post-position draw ceremony Thursday morning at Clockers'
Corner, took a verbal shot at Sahadi by asking McCarron, ``By the
way, who's training The Deputy, you or Jenine?''
</P>
<P>
   An unamused Sahadi responded, ``Thank God my horse has class,
because there's a lot of people who don't.'' Then she walked off
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, from the sounds of the on-site crowd of 41,222
Saturday, Sahadi won the brief debate in the public's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's colt, Captain Steve, finished an unthreatening third.
A wiseguy in the stands yelled at Baffert: ``Who trains Captain
Steve?''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, the Kentucky Derby winner in 1997 (Silver Charm) and
1998 (Real Quiet) and the perennial Churchill Downs scene-stealer,
might find he's no longer the public and media darling this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi sampled her new popularity Saturday morning when she met
with dozens of children from around the country who attended the
Santa Anita Derby with help from Kids to the Cup, a nonprofit
organization founded by California racehorse owner Trudy McCaffery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 12- and 13-year-old girls coming up to me and saying,
`I'd love to be just like you,' '' Sahadi said. ``That makes you
feel good, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   She has earned the adulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jenine Sahadi trained this colt to the minute and did it
absolutely perfectly,'' said McCarron, who has ridden The Deputy in
all four U.S. races and in workouts. ``It's been a while since I've
been on a horse of this class who's been perfectly happy every
single day he was on the track. He loves to be out on that
racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   Team Valor head Barry Irwin praised Sahadi's communications
skills - ask Baffert if she knows how to get her point across - and
her creativity as a trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Added Team Valor partner Jeff Siegel, who is also a popular
handicapper: ``I have no problem whatsoever in having her bring
this horse up to the race. Jenine is a Kentucky Derby (caliber)
trainer.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now isn't ``Who's training The Deputy?'' It's ``Who
better?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
