<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ME AND MORLEY AND SHERIFF JOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BY E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 
(PHOENIX) - A producer from 60 Min utes calls to say they're doing
a profile of Mari copa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio and would I talk
to them about it. Sure, I say. Then I hang up and call the REAL
producer of 60 Minutes, Sheriff Joe himself.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Paesano!'' he says. ``Did you get the last pizza I sent you _
with the anchovies?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``reward'' he ships over occasionally for ``blasting''
him.
</P>
<P>
   I tell him I just got off the telephone with a woman who works
with Morley Safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Arpaio says know ingly. ``We referred 60 Minutes to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   You referred them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' the sheriff says. ``I want you to get some national
publicity again. I got you on 20/20, didn't I?''
</P>
<P>
   I remind him that the seg ment I taped for that show was cut
from the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll get on this time,`` Arpaio says sincerely, adding,
``You've been hitting me so much, if they want the opposite view
they'll use you. You twist the words amazingly. And you're a
critic. And you don't like me.''
</P>
<P>
   To Sheriff Arpaio, these are good things:
</P>
<P>
   Blasting him in print. Twist ing words. Not liking him.
</P>
<P>
   They wouldn't be good things to a politician living in the real
world, but they are to Arpaio, who lives a fantasy of his own
creation.
</P>
<P>
   A movie.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio is the writer, pro ducer, director and star of an ongoing
production called ``The Toughest Sheriff in America.'' His show's
been on the air longer than Seinfeld. America can't get enough of
him. And neither can Europe and Asia and the other places who've
sent film crews to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Joe is accommodating. He built a custom-made movie set on jail
property and packed it with real-life inmate extras. The place is
called Tent City.
</P>
<P>
   He created the black and white striped costumes the bit players
wear, complete with pink underwear, and gave a few of them
recurring roles as members of carefully choreo graphed chain gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, apparently, he's taken on the responsibility of casting
director as well, putting the 60 Minutes folks in touch with a
local newspaper hack who'll trash Arpaio to Morley Safer and, in
doing so, make Ameri cans love the sheriff even more than they
already do.
</P>
<P>
   He can't miss.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wyatt Earp, Arpaio came to Arizona from some place far away
and reinvented himself. The Illinois born Earp spent the last years
of his life cultivating his own legend by working as an advisor to
Holly wood Westerns.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts bred Ar paio went one better. He's culti
vating his legend while still on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Politically Incor rect With Bill Maher will be in
Phoenix taping shows inside Tent City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a captive audience (in Tent City),'' Arpaio says. ``If
Maher treats me badly, he may stay there for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   People love it when Joe talks this way. It's the best part of
his shtick, the illusion he uses to obscure the real-life problems
with the jail. The lawsuits. The deaths. The charges of inhu mane
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, are you doing a column on this or are you just ticking me
off?'' Arpaio asks.
</P>
<P>
   It would only tick him off if I didn't do a column, didn't per
form my role in the movie of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio is the Francis Ford Coppola of his profession. The John
Ford. The Steven Spiel berg. Maybe that's why, on the collar of his
uniform shirt, the sheriff wears four stars.
</P>
<P>
   I figure he got them from Roger Ebert. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-00 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000408.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
