<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CREDIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL TAX CREDITS WIDE OPEN TO ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KARINA BLAND  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - School tax credits intended to help needy children
instead are paying for private school tuition and fancy trips for
kids whose parents can afford the expense.
</P>
<P>
   In all, almost $28 million was diverted from the state's general
fund in 1999, some of it covering middle-class kids' tuition and
public school jaunts to California's Catalina Island, The Arizona
Republic has found.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state doesn't regulate or even monitor the tax
credit program, leaving it open to abuse.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 law allows taxpayers to donate $200 to public schools and
$500 to private ones and take the same amount off their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said it would get needy students into private schools
and let more schools run extracurricular programs.
</P>
<P>
   But a review by The Republic found questionable practices the
framers of the legislation didn't anticipate or, if they did,
didn't publicly disclose:
</P>
<P>
   Many donations to private school scholarship funds are earmarked
for students already enrolled instead of new students, essentially
creating a state voucher system.
</P>
<P>
   Well-off public school parents pay for their kids' trips and
activities, then claim it as a tax credit, disappointing schools
hoping for a new source of cash.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Department of Revenue has questions about possible
abuse, but has no authority to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first time taxpayers gave freely to the
program, which had been entangled in an unsuccessful court battle
challenging whether it violated the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the Joint Legislative Budget Committee estimated the
program would cost the state's general fund $8.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1999, public schools and charters collected $13,992,979.
Private schools got $13,315,172.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's your money,'' said James DiCello, assistant
superintendent for business services for the Paradise Valley
Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, his district received $770,000 in tax credit
donations, but only $183,000 of that actually came to the school.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was written off by parents for their kids' activities,
most notably an annual school trip to the Catalina Island Marine
Institute where they study oceanography and scuba dive.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $183,000 the district did get, DiCello said it cost half
that in overtime for the school secretaries who stayed late to
write endless receipts for parents, to compile reports and for
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   DiCello is dismayed: ``We're not any better off than we were
before that legislation.'' &QL; 
SCHOLARSHIP FUNDS SET UP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the credit for private school scholarships,
including Rep. Mark Anderson, R-Mesa, who sponsored the
legislation, touted it as a way to send kids to private school who
otherwise couldn't afford to go.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what happens with most of the 32 scholarship funds
set up to pass out the money.
</P>
<P>
   Shanicka Brown, 9, and her sisters, 8-year-old Kiara Moore and
Ericka Rogers, 6, for example, now attend the Academy of Destiny in
Phoenix, on scholarships from the Arizona School Choice Trust.
</P>
<P>
   That fund, as well as the Catholic Tuition Organization of the
Diocese of Phoenix, for example, bases scholarships on income.
Neither lets donors earmark money for a child.
</P>
<P>
   But other funds do, and, in come cases, the money is going
almost exclusively to children already in private school,
regardless of financial need.
</P>
<P>
   The law only stipulates that 90 percent of what's collected go
to scholarships, not for who or why. Donors can name a child to
receive their money, though not their own. So, parents are writing
$500 checks for their friends' kids and asking them to do the same
for theirs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 96 percent of the $361,530 received by the Arizona
Scholarship Fund was earmarked for kids in private schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Director ChamBria Henderson said these are children whose
families struggle to pay their fees. She urges parents to solicit
donations for their children, asking relatives and friends to give
in their child's name.
</P>
<P>
   Trent Franks, a former lawmaker and conservative activist who
came up with the idea for the tax credit, readily admits that is
what parents do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would that be the worst thing that happened in the world?'' he
asks.
</P>
<P>
   He and other supporters admit the private school tax credit is
the next best thing to vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   For years, conservative lawmakers have tried to create a voucher
program to send kids to private schools with state money. Asking
for just $1 million or $2 million, the bills fail every time.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Franks asks, ``Why do we need vouchers at this point?''
Not with private schools raking in almost $14 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who rally enough people to write checks for their kids
can cover their entire tuition _ all with money that would have
been in state coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents contend the private school tax credits violate the
Arizona Constitution, which prohibits the use of public money to
aid parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most courts have ruled against vouchers, the tax
credit skirts the question of constitutionality by rerouting the
money before it gets to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has turned into something so close to vouchers you almost
can't tell the difference,'' said Sen. John Huppenthal, R-Chandler,
chairman of the Education Committee and a longtime voucher
supporter.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Education Association filed suit, but the Arizona
Supreme Court refused the case in late 1998, upholding the law.
</P>
<P>
   `It is a sham,'' said Penny Kotterman, the teachers group
president. ``It clearly subsidizes private and religious schools.''
</P>
<P>
   With 5,000 openings statewide in private schools, there is more
money for scholarships than space for new students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has turned out that people who already had their children
in private schools got a tax break,'' Kotterman said.
</P>
<P>
   Private school officials said the tax credit likely will create
such a demand that more private schools will open. Another Catholic
school, for example, is opening in Chandler in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Kotterman said the money would do more good, including
reducing class size and hiring more teachers, in the state's
general fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the program is working as it was intended and
getting additional resources to education,'' said Francie Noyes,
spokeswoman for Gov. Jane Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Noyes admits it is mostly middle-income families whose
kids already are in private schools who are taking advantage of the
program, not the poor kids supporters claimed it would help. &QL; 
IT MAKES A DIFFERENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Roosevelt Elementary School District in Phoenix, one of
the poorest in the state, money from tax credit donations has meant
after-school dance classes and keeping computer labs open late into
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The $102,000 donated to the district last year paid for a
student-run bakery and cafe at Lassen School and assorted field
trips, things the kids wouldn't otherwise have been able to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It truly does make a difference in the inner-city districts,''
said Mary Miller Crews, a Roosevelt teacher who coordinates the tax
credit program. ``We do honestly appreciate it. We are very, very
grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of her donations came from outside the district because few
of the people living there can afford to give away $200.
</P>
<P>
   She said she gets calls from taxpayers in richer districts,
saying they are sending her checks because their own schools don't
really need it.
</P>
<P>
   In the Deer Valley School District, students are raising money
to attend a mock trial debate contest through the tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   And Sun City residents came through for nearby Dysart schools,
which collected almost a half-million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   This is how school officials thought it would work.
</P>
<P>
   The public school tax credit always was intended for
extracurricular activities. School officials thought they would
spend the money on microscopes for the science club, sports
uniforms and music lessons for kids who can't afford them.
</P>
<P>
   That is happening in some districts, but in others, like
Paradise Valley and Scottsdale, schools record lots of donations
but actually get few checks. Instead, parents spend $200 on their
child's activities, then ask for a receipt to write it off.
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, Desert Canyon Middle School collected $150,242,
98 percent of which went back into parents' pockets, Principal Glen
Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   DiCello tells of parents using the tax credit to send band
students to Vancouver and New York, other kids to cheerleading and
wrestling camps. The annual California Catalina Island trip costs
parents $300 _ really, $100 after the tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of this money is going for tax relief,'' DiCello
said. ``It's not going to the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   And schools have to pay to administer the program.
</P>
<P>
   Huppenthal said he knows the tax credit is causing problems for
public schools, which, unlike the scholarship funds, don't get to
keep any of the money for administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``our parents like the situation as it stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, too, said he doesn't mind parents using the tax credit
to pay for their kids' activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people support extracurricular activities that
are good for kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Superintendent of Public Instruction Lisa Graham Keegan
used her tax credit to help pay for her son's trip to Catalina
Island.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit, Anderson said, means students who couldn't
afford to participate in school-related activities now can.
</P>
<P>
   That notion draws laughter from Roosevelt's Crews, who said few
of the parents in her district could afford to spend $200 on such
activities, tax credit or not. &QL;  CAN'T TRACE ALL
FUNDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Department of Revenue, chief economist Georganna Meyer
rubs her temples, perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   Most public schools and scholarship funds have reported how much
they collected, though they are not required to by law. She has few
concerns about them.
</P>
<P>
   But on her desk is a stack of forms from people who said they
made $500 donations to scholarship tuition funds she can't trace.
</P>
<P>
   Something queer is going on, and there's nothing she can do
about it. The tax credit legislation provided no oversight and no
muscle to investigate any suspected fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer is charged with compiling a report on the tax credits for
state lawmakers, a job made more difficult because the law doesn't
require schools or funds to report anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one audits them, and we're certainly not going to,'' Meyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The funds must file with the Internal Revenue Service. Still,
there are no rules about scholarship criteria or how long funds
have to give them out.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer puzzles over the scholarship fund of the Chabad Lubavitch
Orthodox Jewish Synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires that such funds provide money to at least two
separate schools. But this fund claims that its Phoenix Preparatory
High School, where boys and girls are taught separately in the
Orthodox Jewish tradition, is two schools even though they are
housed in the same building.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said that what they are doing is legal.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, far more people claim they wrote checks to
public schools than the schools actually report. Meyer won't have
exact numbers until after tax season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real concerned,'' she says. She pauses and then adds,
``At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers don't alarm me, but I see lots of possibilities
for abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   There are problems inherent with any new program, contends
Anderson, the law's sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will consider legislation next session to mandate
that schools and scholarship funds report to the state and possibly
do away with designating donations for a specific child.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson believes in the tax-credit program: ``You don't want
people misusing it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Karina.Bland(at)Arizona Republic.com or (602)
444-8614. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
