<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-WOODS-BOS     04-08 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS STORMS BACK INTO CONTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ They are in pursuit of a green jacket, but for
the wind-blown competitors in the 64th Masters, a winter parka
would be the choice of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   As the focus of this major championship took a chilling turn in
Saturday's third round, from treacherous greens to frostbite, there
was a confession from Vijay Singh that you perhaps may never hear
from someone playing so well in a major championship: ``We were all
just looking to get off the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in his right mind when he said it, too. The rest of his
body was frozen, however.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the third round was unlike anything this fabled event
has seen in a long time. When it began, the weather was relatively
calm, Tiger Woods was laboring nine shots out of the lead, and most
of the leaders were home in bed. When it mercifully came to an end
at 7:45 under moonlight, Augusta National GC may as well have been
in Iceland, Woods was very much a factor, standing 1-under after
shooting 68, and most of the leaders were wondering why they hadn't
pursued a warmer sport. Like ice fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the wind was coming,'' said Singh, ``and we could have
handled that. But I wasn't expecting the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't face this sort of weather _ temperatures in the 40s,
steady winds of 25 m.p.h. _ in his native Fiji, which makes what he
did even more remarkable. Singh, starting the day at 5-under, one
shot behind David Duval, tightened the straps to his ski boots . .
. er, golf shoes . . . and somehow made four birdies against two
bogeys to vault into a three-shot lead before the round was called
because of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   When play resumes at 8:15 this morning, eight players will
return to their positions to complete the third round. Singh
(7-under) and Duval (4-under) are standing over third shots to the
par 5 15th; Ernie Els (3-under) and Phil Mickelson (2-under) are on
16; Tom Lehman (1-over) and Steve Jones (1-over) will finish the
17th, as will Bernhard Langer (1-over) and Jeff Sluman (1-over).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Loren Roberts (71--213) has the clubhouse lead at
3-under and a couple of major threats _ Woods and Davis Love III _
got back into the hunt by sitting on their favorite couch in front
of their televisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say I hope these guys play terrible today,''
said Love after he, like Woods, went out early and shot a 4-under
68. ``I hope they get what I got (in Round 1 when he teed off late
in high winds). How's that for a political answer?''
</P>
<P>
   Cold-hearted, perhaps. But, then again, all other body parts
will have to thaw out, too. The forecast called for an overnight
frost, low temperatures this morning, and gusting winds. Only this
time, they'll all be in the same iceboat.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case in Round 3. Woods and Love got a good
portion of their rounds in before the horn sounded at 12:25 p.m. to
signal lightning in the area. The lightning never materialized, but
rain fell, and by the time play resumed two hours later, the
temperatures had dropped 20 degrees and the winds were whistling
through the pines.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who had shot 33 on the front, negotiated his remaining
eight holes with two birdies and a bogey to join Love at 1-under
and bid farewell for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Singh never showed such pleasure, though certainly he had to be
pleased. Paired with Duval in the final group, he teed off at 4
p.m. and was forced to walk in the path of golfers whose wheels had
been blown off. ``You could see the scoreboard, and everybody's
dropping off,'' said Singh. ``I just thought about concentrating on
what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, playing with Els just in front of Duval and Singh,
made five bogeys going out and dropped to 1-under. Els only made
one bogey on the front, but wasn't making anything happen. The
third-to-last pairing of Lehman (out in 38) and Jones (a
triple-bogey on the par 4 seventh after he skulled his shot from
the front bunker to the back bunker) was struggling, too.
</P>
<P>
   None of which flustered Singh. He tied Duval at 6-under with a
birdie at the par 5 second, assumed the lead when Duval
three-putted the par 4 third, but fell back into a tie with a bogey
at the fourth. When he birdied par 5 eighth, Singh was at 6-under
and in front by one.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, meanwhile, had gotten to 5-under with his fourth birdie
on the front, and though he gave two shots back when he went into
the wind on the backside, the man they call ``The Boss of the
Moss'' was content.
</P>
<P>
   Duval was looking at a red round until he got untracked by a
gust of wind at the par 3 12th. Delightful hole to watch,
infuriating one to play, it sits at the heart of Amen Corner where
the wind blows in every which direction. Only sometimes it waits
until after you have hit, which happened to Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the club as a lot of players did,'' said Duval of his
8-iron. ``It was just not favorable for me. It was bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   It was wet, the double-bogey knocking him to 3-under. Singh, who
had bogeyed the 11th with his worst swing of the day, hit next,
just as the wind settled down. His 8-iron came to rest 6 1/2 feet
behind the pin and he made the putt to complete a three-shot swing
on Duval and get to 6-under.
</P>
<P>
   Duval got within two shots with a birdie at the par 5 13th, but
Singh birdied 14 with a tap-in after a laser pitching wedge, such a
delightful turn of events he did the sensible thing _ he looked to
a tournament official to beg for mercy.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't come until he and Duval had driven off the 15th and
hit their lay-up shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of holes to be played,'' said Singh, who is
considered the hardest working player on the PGA Tour. But for the
first time ever, he was going not to the practice range, but to the
nearest fireplace for relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
