<HEADER>
A1410 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GROWTH-AZR &LR;      04-08 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPERS, WARY OF LIMITS ON GROWTH, PUSH PROJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - The scene is as rural as it gets: farmland stretching
for miles in the southeastern corner of the Phoenix area,
all-but-empty roads, the occasional crow of a rooster.
</P>
<P>
   But the sign along Arizona Farms Road tells another story: ``For
sale, 41 acres, 353 home sites permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   All along Phoenix's fringes, it's happening over and over:
Developers are racing to rezone fields and isolated desert for tens
of thousands of houses.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the rush, many say, is the Nov. 7 election, when
voters could pass the Citizens Growth Management Initiative and
slap restrictions on growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a deadline-beater,'' said John Kross, development
director for Queen Creek. ``These guys want to get their
development rights in under the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   So many subdivisions are in the pipeline that some say growth
limits, if passed, wouldn't be felt for years. Others worry that
planning is getting short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the view that all these houses will barely be
enough to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are adding up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, population 26,000, has 39,000 homes in the pipeline
and 6,000 to 7,000 more on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County has approved three master-planned communities in
the past year, the first since 1995. They have nearly 14,000 homes
in all, and the county is reviewing two other applications.
</P>
<P>
   Five developers in Buckeye are trying to get master plans
through by November, including more than 100,000 homes on the
western side of the White Tank Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Growth Management Initiative isn't on the ballot
yet, but the Sierra Club, which is leading the campaign, says it
has enough signatures.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative would require every Arizona community of more
than 2,500 people to adopt a growth-management plan that includes
an urban growth boundary. The boundary, drawn just large enough for
10 years of population growth, would limit where services could be
extended or densities increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of confusion'' over what steps are
needed now to make sure a project can be built later, said Elliott
Pollack, an economist and real estate investor. Is zoning enough,
or a development agreement? Or must the bulldozers be rolling?
</P>
<P>
   Housing analyst R.L. Brown is urging clients to get a five-year
stockpile of land with zoning and other approvals, known as
entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is out zoning and entitling anything they can think
of,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the headlong rush for zoning moving faster than the
Queen Creek area, where Kross is tracking 16 projects next door in
Pinal County, a total of 76,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The developments dwarf Queen Creek, with its 1,200 homes and
3,600 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The town itself has approved more than 10,000 homes within the
town limits while struggling to keep its agricultural roots and
rural lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Like many residents, Barry Jones, a former Mesa police
administrator, went there for the chance to live on a large lot and
keep horses. He's stunned at the development on the drawing boards.
Suburban neighborhoods with four homes per acre don't fit the
spread-out country living of Queen Creek, where densities are one
house per acre or less, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved to get away from it all,'' he said. ``We didn't think
it would grow this fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Martinez lives in town and prizes the tranquillity. She
said she'd like enough development to bring a supermarket and
pharmacy, sparing her a 15-mile drive, ``but not this explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of homes approved may be deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not all going to be here tomorrow,'' said Dennis Cady,
Pinal County planning director.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the larger projects will take five to 15 years to sell
out, he predicts, and will scale back in size. The pace of building
could slow, too, if the economy falters or interest rates rise
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Cady would much rather see coordinated development
in master-planned communities, rather than haphazard lot-splitting
with no requirements for water, sewers or access.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Creek Mayor Mark Schnepf worries that with so much haste,
``it sometimes means the project isn't as well-planned as it should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Ranch, nine miles southeast of Queen Creek, touched off
an avalanche of housing proposals. The mixed-use, golf-course
development is approved for 6,600 homes and construction is
steaming ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by farms and desert hills, Johnson Ranch demonstrates
how many home buyers are willing to put up with a remote location
to get a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't beat the housing prices out here,'' said Misty
Hidalgo, formerly of Mesa. She figures her $107,000, four-bedroom
house would go for $33,000 more in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   The downside, however, is her husband's 45-minute commute to
Chandler. Some of her neighbors make three-hour round-trips to jobs
in northwest Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo feels safer with her three sons, 3, 7 and 9, no longer
in a tough city neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better getting our kids out in the country,'' she said,
``not that it's going to stay country long.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of the surrounding land is already planned as homes
for thousands of other urban refugees. So many projects are
chugging through that some planners predict it will be years before
any growth boundaries would start to pinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many years of authorized development in place now,''
said Bill Mee, infrastructure financing coordinator for Phoenix.
``It would take a long time before people would start noticing.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the new applications, some enormous projects got the
green light years ago. Estrella Mountain Ranch, with 18,600 acres
at the southern end of Goodyear, is approved for 60,000 homes,
although that number won't be reached for years.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Bahr, a spokeswoman for the Citizens Growth Management
Initiative, realizes that developers are trying to get ahead of the
game but argues that the initiative is no less valuable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't buy into the argument that it's too late,'' she said.
``It can always get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   If the initiative passes, communities would take awhile to draw
growth boundaries, but interim restrictions would kick in right
away. New subdivisions or any increases in zoning intensity would
require a four-fifths approval of the local governing body.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Buckeye is one of those places where huge inventories
of home sites are being gathered. Driving into this town of 6,000,
you can still catch a whiff of manure, and you won't spot any large
housing developments. Yet seven master-planned communities are in
the wings.
</P>
<P>
   Projects are being revived that were floated in the go-go land
speculation of the 1980s. Town Manager Joe Blanton said Buckeye's
trump card is that development can tap the ample water supply that
now irrigates cotton and other crops.
</P>
<P>
   Maeve Johnson, executive director of Valley Partnership, a real
estate lobbying group, sees ``fear of the unknown'' at work.
Besides uncertainty over the initiative, there are questions about
how Growing Smarter Plus, a package of proposals passed by the
Legislature, will play out.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson says developers tell her that they're just
positioning themselves for the future.
</P>
<P>
   And some argue that the number of homes in the hopper isn't
large, considering the heated pace of growth in the 1990s. The
Phoenix area has been adding almost 25,000 houses and apartments a
year, said Stanley Paul Cook of Landiscor Aerial. A 10-year
inventory would be a quarter of a million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Brown says developers may be hustling for approval now,
but the Citizens Growth Management Initiative would likely throw on
the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting that prices would rise dramatically, he said, ``I
think major land sellers will be very slow to release their land
for development.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kathleen.Ingley(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8171. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
