<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-FISHERMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEN WHO RESCUED ELIAN PLAN TO TALK WITH BOY'S FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ The two fishermen who plucked Elian Gonzalez
from the sea flew to Washington on Saturday and, after an initial
attempt failed, appeared headed for a meeting with the boy's father
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The two fishermen, Sam Ciancio and Donato Dalrymple, both of
Fort Lauderdale, Fla., accompanied by two of the boy's Miami
relatives, had appeared midafternoon at the suburban home where the
boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, is staying. Gonzalez had left
the home, which belongs to the senior Cuban diplomat, about 20
minutes before the group arrived.
</P>
<P>
   A police officer serving as an emissary told the group Gonzalez
would not see them. So the fishermen and Elian's uncle Delfin
Gonzalez and cousin Alfredo Martell walked briskly before the 20
cameras set up on Millwood Road and voiced their frustration.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would return several times until Gonzalez agreed
to see them. The fishermen and representatives for Gonzalez met
Saturday night to work out a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Dalrymple said the fishermen wanted both to give Gonzalez, who
arrived on Thursday from Cuba, an opportunity to thank them in
person and to encourage him to meet with his Miami relatives and
work out a peaceful solution to the custody fight over the
6-year-old boy, who was found floating in an inner tube on Nov. 25
after his mother and 10 others drowned while fleeing Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've come to do is to reunite the Gonzalez family
together,'' said Dalrymple, who told interviewers in Florida he
would prefer that the boy stayed in the United States but said
outside the Bethesda home he would not attempt to sway the father.
</P>
<P>
   Ciancio said: ``This man owes us at least to meet with us. I
mean that's the bottom line. He owes us that respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
