<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-08 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1413 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-08 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER SENDS A MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. - The golf ball came from seemingly nowhere, sort
of like the epitaph that had been delivered the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods was standing over his ball at the 12th hole of
Augusta National Golf Course Saturday, preparing to hit a perilous
chip onto the par-3 green, when a golf ball fell out of the sky. It
landed on the putting surface but near enough to Woods that he
could read its dimple pattern and identify its maker.
</P>
<P>
   Woods got a good chuckle at what apparently was a duffer's
vagrant shot from the ninth hole of the Augusta Country Club course
that abuts Augusta National. On this day the fifth-year pro had the
luxury of laughing as he would launch no such aberrant shots in the
third round of the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   After the comic interlude, Wood would chip to within eight feet,
sink the putt and be on his merry way to a score of 68, a great
result on a day that was more like summer at St. Andrews than
spring at this plot of land golfers like to call heaven (but were
calling something entirely different by nightfall).
</P>
<P>
   Woods's third-round surge, achieved in cold and windy conditions
that turned ridiculous after a two-hour midday storm delay,
catapulted him from 39th place to tied for second in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Four golfers ahead of Woods on the scoreboard - V.J. Singh,
David Duval, Ernie Els, and Phil Mickelson - were stranded on the
course when darkness fell. Among them, only Singh, was under par
for the day.
</P>
<P>
   For Woods's 4-under-par effort, the other 56 golfers vying for
the Masters green jacket can curse whoever it was that Woods heard
writing him off on television Friday night after he survived the
cut by one stroke with opening rounds of 75 and 72.
</P>
<P>
   When will people learn to let a slumping Tiger lie?
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a little T.V. (Friday night) and a lot of the people
were saying I was completely out of it,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   He paused to let a smile cross his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he's right in the thick of it. My oh my, if Woods didn't
have a nickname we'd have to call him Lazarus.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year he has come back from seven strokes down with
seven holes to play to win. So why shouldn't Woods get woozy
visualizing the possibilities of teeing off today, six strokes
behind Singh, who has three-and-a-half holes of his third round to
negotiate before before tackling the final 18?
</P>
<P>
   When people say of Woods what was once said of Jack Nicklaus -
that he plays a game with which they're not familiar - it can mean
only one thing: They don't play chess.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old is always thinking a couple moves ahead.
Consider what he said when somebody asked him if he thought he'd
have an advantage over golfers forced by Mother Nature to complete
their third rounds today.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he believed he would, explaining, ``From what the
Weather Channel is saying, there's going to be some frost and
freeze warnings. Temperatures are supposed to go down to the 40s
and 30s tomorrow so it will be pretty cold for the players who have
to finish their third rounds in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, a few hours later the local news predicted cold
temperatures for this morning, with a chance of frost.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is meticulous in his preparation for every tournament but
especially the Grand Slams. The results can be so seamless it's
hard to fully appreciate his handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 he made a mockery of this tournament's storied history,
shooting four rounds of 70 or better here to run away with his
first major. That sublime week became Woods's cross to bear as
people expected him to hammer Augusta National every time out.
</P>
<P>
   But the golf course is no shrinking azalea. It dug in and got
the best of Woods for 10 consecutive rounds, his 68 representing
his first sub-70 round here since his final round of 69 three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   That his round Saturday looked relatively easy was a testament
to Woods's abilities. On the 205-yard, par-3 fourth hole, his tee
shot sailed left of the green, into the gallery. He got up and down
to save par with feathery shot that stopped two feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Ho hum, another par for Woods. That's surely what the scoreboard
watchers on the course were thinking. In fact, that flop shot he
fashioned was phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't an easy shot,'' Woods said, ``but I pulled it off.''
</P>
<P>
   He called it the key to what he considered a crucial round.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up (Saturday),'' Woods said, ``I knew what I had
to do, which was go out and get myself back in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   That he did. Then Woods sat back and watched from the warmth of
his rented house as the weather turned really rough and the leaders
came back to him as though they were in the clutches of some
mysterious magnetic field.
</P>
<P>
   Which they are, of course. It's called destiny and right now we
have to believe it pulls for Woods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
