<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALFFY WILL REST SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Ziggy Palffy was downright bubbly about playing
today for the first time in three weeks. But that was 36 hours ago.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy will not play against the Mighty Ducks, instead using the
additional five days before Game 1 of the playoffs in Detroit to
rehabilitate his right shoulder that was sprained in a Feb. 15 game
against the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy isn't ducking the Ducks' 19-year-old defenseman Vitaly
Vishnevski, who checked him into the board to cause the shoulder
injury. Vishnevski also is sidelined with a shoulder problem. It is
just a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Rob Blake, who has not played since last Saturday's
playoff clincher against the Ducks due to a badly bruised left
knee, will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The practices are harder than the game,'' Blake said after
Saturday's up-tempo, 45-minute workout. ``It's time to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings' leading scorer, Luc Robitaille (36 goals, 74
points), will be rested. Defenseman Garry Galley also has been
excused because his wife, Terry-Lynn, gave birth to the couple's
third child just hours after Friday's 3-2 victory over Dallas. The
baby, 9-pound, 4-ounce Blake Liam Galley, was named after Rob
Blake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty wiped out after staying up all night,'' coach Andy
Murray said of his defenseman. ``You don't want to put a guy out
there and risk injury.''
</P>
<P>
   With Galley out, Jaroslav Modry will play, giving him a chance
to extend his goal-scoring streak to three games. Modry, who has
played just 25 games this season, has impressed Murray despite the
limited playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the approach this year not to let the negative things
work against me,'' Modry said. ``When I wasn't playing, I continued
to work in practice. When I am in there, I want to make it
difficult to keep me out of the (defensive rotation).''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings go with three defensive pairings: Blake/Mattias
Norstrom, Galley/Sean O'Donnell, Jere Karalahti/Aki Berg. The last
two groups occasionally flip-flop, but it doesn't leave much time
for Modry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You love to see a guy push the others,'' Murray said. ``We
know this hasn't been easy. But it has made us a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: If the Kings win today, it will give them 94
points, the fourth-best record in club history. The Kings had 105
points under Bob Pulford during the 1974-75 season but lost to
Toronto in the first round. The Kings had 102 points in 1990-91
under Tom Webster. It was their only division title, but they lost
in the second round to Edmonton. In 1980-81, the Kings had 99
points under Bob Berry but lost in the first round to the New York
Rangers.... Stephane Fiset, who will start Thursday in Game 1
against Detroit, will play today against the Ducks. Fiset was 2-0
against the Red Wings during the regular season.... Forward Pierre
Boucher, who played his first game Friday after missing the entire
season because of a foot surgery, returned to minor-league Long
Beach and played in Saturday night's game against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   KINGS vs. DUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Time: Noon, the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Channel 7; KRLA-AM (1110).
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: The Kings are in, the Ducks are out and that won't
change today. But the game will mark the return of Kings captain
Rob Blake, who has not seen action since bruising his left knee
eight days ago, when the teams last played. In that game, the Kings
won 2-1 to qualify for the playoffs. Today could be a tough one
emotionally for the Ducks, who beat Nashville 5-1 on Friday but
were eliminated two hours later when Edmonton came back from a 3-1,
third-period deficit to beat Vancouver 4-3 in OT.
</P>
<P>
   - Matt McHale
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
